<HEADER>
A1340 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-ANGELS-MANAGERS-L     09-05 0476
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-MANAGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS LOOK FOR MANAGER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Now that the Anaheim Angels players
essentially forced Terry Collins out as manager, who's next? What
type of manager is needed to lead a team that has had so much
trouble getting along with each other?
</P>
<P>
   For starters, the list of candidates includes Don Baylor, Kevin
Kennedy, Chris Chambliss, Willie Randolph, Phil Garner and Davey
Lopes. Angels first baseman Mo Vaughn played for Kennedy in Boston
and the two are close, but Vaughn won't offer an endorsement to the
front office.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to be my decision,'' Vaughn said. ``(Kennedy's)
an intense guy. I don't believe in that East Coast/West Coast
thing. Kevin's a West Coast guy and he's as intense as Earl Weaver
was with the Baltimore Orioles.''
</P>
<P>
   But wasn't Collins intense? Is intensity the answer?
</P>
<P>
   ``What you need to have is a pact between the manager, coaching
staff and players,'' Vaughn said. ``It's like a written document.
If you as a player give everything you've got and have the right
attitude, the manager will lead you strategically on the field.
That's what you're looking for in a manager _ somebody who will
treat you like a man and in return you give him everything you've
got. If you don't prepare, you're letting down everybody who is
prepared.''
</P>
<P>
   For other Angels players, however, the question of who should
lead the team is none of their business.
</P>
<P>
   ``From any player's standpoint, nobody should be commenting on
what the team needs,'' right fielder Tim Salmon said. ``You should
take care of your own business and get yourself ready. We've got 30
games left, and that's what our focus should be. As far as who the
coaches are or who takes over, we shouldn't be thinking about that.
I do all I can to not think about those things.''
</P>
<P>
   Chambliss, a former Yankees player and now the club's hitting
coach, interviewed for the Angels' managerial job before the 1997
season that Collins eventually got.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm interested in any major-league managing job, there's no
secret about that,'' Chambliss said. ``When I interviewed with Bill
(Bavasi, the Angels GM) he said to me it was a very good interview.
He was very positive about it. But I wasn't asked back a second
time. That was really the extent of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Baylor, who is the hitting coach for the Atlanta Braves, said
he's interested but won't necessarily jump at the first
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The organization's philosophy of planning for the future is
something I'm more concerned with,'' he said recently. ``They have
to be an organization that is building toward winning. There are so
many young guys in the majors now that should be in Double-A or
Triple-A. There's no depth in the minor leagues.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-99 0016EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
