<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-BRAVES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DURZAO DOES IT AGAIN FOR D-BACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - For one night, at least, the Diamondbacks had enough
sand bags to keep San Francisco's rising river of momentum away.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona accomplished its objective by overcoming an early 3-0
deficit for a 5-4 victory over the Atlanta Braves on Saturday night
in front of 48,730 at Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie first baseman Erubiel Durazo continued his remarkable
development with a pair of home runs off right-hander John Smoltz,
and left-hander Greg Swindell and right-hander Matt Mantei held the
Braves hitless over the final three innings.
</P>
<P>
   After three straight losses, the Diamondbacks finally were able
to put their 80th victory on the board (80-56). They were able to
maintain their five-game lead in the National League West Division
despite the Giants' eighth straightvictory.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta (86-51) had won 10 in a row at home and 14 of its last
15. The Braves saw their lead in the NL East trimmed to 3{ games by
the New York Mets, who defeated the Colorado Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   When Ryan Klesko hit a three-run homer in the first inning off
right-hander Andy Benes, his second long shot in as many nights,
the Diamondbacks looked to be well on the way to dropping another
game to the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could go through the ``Here we go (again)'' routine, but
the guys here have a lot of confidence in the ability that allowed
themto get here, to finish the job,'' said Arizona Manager Buck
Showalter.
</P>
<P>
   Other than a solo homer by Randall Simon in the fourth inning,
Benes settled down and went on to pick up his 10th victory of the
season (10-11).
</P>
<P>
   ``Andy bent but didn't break, and gave us a key shutdown inning
in the sixth,'' Showalter said.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona had scored three times in the top of the sixth to take a
5-4lead.
</P>
<P>
   Luis Gonzalez doubled to lead off the inning and Steve Finley
drove him in with a double. Durazo, who had hit a solo homer with
two out in the fourth off Smoltz (9-7), hit one into the night that
landed 435 feet away for a two-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   Durazo put up big numbers at Double-A El Paso and Triple-A
Tucson, ``but doing it in the big leagues is a lot different,''
said Diamondbacks hitting coach Jim Presley.
</P>
<P>
   When Durazo first joined the big club on July 25, ``you could
see his potential. He was just `juicing it' in (batting
practice),'' Presley said.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-3, 225-pound Durazo is reminiscent of a
left-handed-hitting Andres ``Big Cat''Galarraga of the Braves,
turning easily on the fastball.
</P>
<P>
   Off-speed stuff has been another story, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's about a 10-day `grace period' before they (pitchers)
get a line on you (weakness),'' Presley said. ``But to his credit,
Erubiel has adjusted pretty well and is continuing to adjust.''
</P>
<P>
   Durazo, a 25-year-old native of Mexico, said he has been taking
a lot of early batting practice to work on off-speed pitches and
thinks he has improved.
</P>
<P>
   The extra work paid off on Saturday night. The first homer off
Smoltz was on a change-up, and the second was on a fastball.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my first time in a situation like this and I want to
learn as much as I can,'' he said. ``This is the last month of the
season. We want to keep winning and I wand to make a
contribution.''
</P>
<P>
   Swindell pitched the seventh and eighth. Walt Weiss, the leadoff
man in the seventh, reached base on an error by shortstop Hanley
Frias, but was erased on a double-play grounderby Chipper Jones to
end the inning. Swindell retired the side in order in the eighth
before Mantei took over in the ninth, striking out the side to earn
his 16th save with Arizona and 26th overall.
</P>
<P>
   In Swindell's last nine outings, opponents are hitting just .088
(3 for 34) off him. He appeared in his 50th game of the season and
lowered his ERA from 2.42 to 2.32. The more work he can get in, the
better. He appeared ina combined 81 games last season for Minnesota
and Boston.
</P>
<P>
   A starter early in his career, Swindell now feels comfortable in
hismiddle-relief role.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the time when you come in,the game is on the line and
I like that. It's a challenge for me,'' he said. ``And it
definitely helps to get as much work as you can,not just with one
or two hitters, but with five or six or seven.''
</P>
<P>
   Mantei mixed his curveball in more with his blazing fastball.
Askedif it was the best stuff he's had since coming to Arizona, he
said, ``Pretty close. I've never had this result. The guys busted
their butts to get the lead back and we were able to hold it.
Swindell got more of a save than I did.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
