<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-CASSTEVENS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
D-BACKS NOT WORRIED YET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Before the game, Chicken Little phoned Henny Penny who
called Cocky Locky. who told Ducky Lucky who told Goosey Loosey who
told Turkey Lurkey who faxed ``The Arizona Republic'' and called
every radio sports talk show in town.
</P>
<P>
   The sky is falling!
</P>
<P>
   Code red.
</P>
<P>
   Need the crisis hotline?
</P>
<P>
   Dial 1-800-UH-OH.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks had lost three in a row. And in the first
inning Saturday night _ look, the Giants are winning ``again'' _
gossip about the team's impending doom traveled almost as fast as
Ryan Klesko's three-run home run.
</P>
<P>
   But put down the phone. Now, take a deep breath. Do NOT panic.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks haven't.
</P>
<P>
   Here in tomahawk country, where the incessant
``boo''m-boom-boom-boom of tom-tom mixes with a mournful war chant
that can put a visitor on edge, the division-leading Diamondbacks
won a very important game.
</P>
<P>
   They showed some fortitude. Resiliency. Something Grandma called
gumption.
</P>
<P>
   Down 3-0 after Klesko's homer, his second in two nights, the
Diamondbacks beat the Atlanta Braves and pitcher John Smoltz who is
as tough as the stubble of his beard.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks chipped away, coming from behind, on the road
before a sellout crowd. They won the way they have won many games
during this magical season _ with the long ball. Erubiel Durazo
tagged Smoltz for two home runs.
</P>
<P>
   Does Durazo understand how big those two swings were? How much
his heric ccontribution in this 5-4 win means to this team?
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably not at this point in his life,'' Buck Showalter
deadpanned. ``And I'm not going to tell him.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory was especially big since San Francisco won in
Pittsburgh. Another Arizona loss would have cut the Diamondbacks
lead in the NL West to ``four'' games. Valley emergency crews would
be talking some fans down off high ledges.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our fans are a lot more worried than we are,'' Luis
Gonzalez said. The left fielder looked around the clubhouse.
``We've got veteran guys here. We're not panicking at all. You're
going to win a few in a row and lose a few in a row. That's part of
the life of a baseball season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a bunch of blue collar guys who play hard every game.
That's all you can ask for. Tonight, we showed the Braves and other
clubs that we're not going to give up at any time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks give no appearance that their esophagus is
constricted. They look and act like the same easy-going bunch that
that has won 80 games during this turnaround season.
</P>
<P>
   Three hours before the first pitch, players strolled into the
visitors clubhouse. They traded hellos. The room came alive with
playful banter. Several players gathered around a big-screen TV and
watched the first half of the Michigan-Notre Dame football game.
Decked out in a Michigan sweatshirt and cap, which he wore backward
like a catcher, Brian Butterfield jumped to his feet, as if
electrically stimulated. `'First down!'' he cried. The third base
coach signaled like a game official with his hand. ````That''
way!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey Butter,'' Gonzo called out. A grin spread across his long
angular face. ``You look a little intense. Loosen up!''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone else appeared relaxed. Seated on opposite couches, Todd
Stottlemyre and Greg Colbrunn tossed a baseball back and forth
during commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Gilkey played with his son. Showalter's face lights up
when he tells how Jaelen Gilkey walked up to him and said, ``Buck
Showalter, sign me up!''
</P>
<P>
   ``How much money do you want?''
</P>
<P>
   The 4-year-old thought a moment.
</P>
<P>
   `'Fifty dollars,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What position you want to play?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Pitcher.''
</P>
<P>
   Showalter said he would work on it. The problem, of course, is
finding a place for the kid in his staff. The manager has a
strikeout artist in Randy Johnson, who will start against Tom
Glavine Sunday. D-backs relievers shined again in this game. Greg
Swindell worked two hitless innings in relief of Andy Benes. And
Matt Mantei struck out the side in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Worry? You don't feel it in the clubhouse. You don't see it in
the youthful faces.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me? I'm pretty much the same every time I go out,'' Mantei
said. The closer grinned and put lyrics to the music of his pitch.
``Here's a fastball,'' he said. ``Hit it.'' &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at (602) 444-8635 or by e-mail at
david.casstevens(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
