<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-05 00:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1345 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s BC-FBC-ASU-40S-BLACKS-AZ     09-05 1288
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ASU-40S-BLACKS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THROWN FOR LOSS BY JIM CROW  
 IN '40S, BLACKS FROM ASU FELT PAIN OF RACISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, ARIZ. - The bumpy, three-hour flight to Kansas made
George Diggs and Morrison Warren feel like dice inside a
crapshooter's grip. They strolled near their Wichita hotel to clear
their heads.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona State football players knew something was wrong when
they returned to the lobby.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aren't those our bags?'' Diggs said.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, we already checked in,'' Warren said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're yours,'' the desk clerk said. ``We don't allow Negroes
in our hotel.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was humiliating,'' Warren said recently of the 1946 trip to
Wichita State. That evening, a hotel porter had to drive the two
players, who are now brothers-in-law, to a hotel for Blacks.
</P>
<P>
   More than a half-century later, he and Diggs remember it with
clarity.
</P>
<P>
   Baggage was a recurring theme during their careers at what was
then Arizona State College at Tempe, the baggage of being
African-American athletes when so few dotted college football's
landscape.
</P>
<P>
   Their memories of those days are stirred because of Monday's
first-ever meeting between ASU and Texas Tech at Sun Devil Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Although these teams shared Border Conference residency from
1933 to 1955, they never met. The Jim Crow laws that legalized
segregation between Blacks and Whites were one reason. And by the
1950s, when most color barriers fell, the schools lost interest in
playing one another. ASU has had Black football players since 1937,
when pioneer Emerson Harvey took the field, and the Sun Devils were
strongly encouraged by Texas schools to leave those athletes home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt terrible,'' Diggs said, ``to not be able to go with
your teammates.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue came to a head in a 1947 game against Texas College of
Mines, which is now Texas-El Paso. The school told Arizona State
that its two African-American players, standout running backs
Warren and Diggs, shouldn't come.
</P>
<P>
   ASU's administration debated the issue. If the two made the
trip, they would have been forced to eat and sleep apart from their
teammates. Safety was a concern.
</P>
<P>
   The ``El Paso Herald-Post'' quoted ASU Coach Eddie Doherty as
saying that if ``Morrison and his 200 pounds collided with a Mines
player and injured the Mines player, some of the more hot-headed
fans might stream out of the stands and attempt a lynching in
Southern style.''
</P>
<P>
   The players stayed home and their team lost, 21-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was devasted,'' Warren said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt bad,'' Diggs said. ``We were part of the team and
wanted to be there with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Their teammates were equally appalled. Both players were popular
on the team, not only because of their football skills but because
they were likable and classroom standouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really upset a lot of the guys that they couldn't go with
us,'' teammate Wilford (Whizzer) White said. ``They were really
great guys and great players. It hurt us on the field, too.
Morrison was our fullback, a good one, and Diggs was a good little
running back.''
</P>
<P>
   Al Onofrio, an assistant coach at the time, said: ``The team was
all for keeping everyone together. It didn't make sense.''
</P>
<P>
   It certainly didn't to Diggs and Warren, who had spent several
years fighting for their country in World War II. Ironically, a
pre-Armistice Day celebration was held at halftime of the Mines
game in memory of soldiers killed in the war.
</P>
<P>
   ASU takes stand &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Mines experience not only upset the team, but the ASU
student body. It was the driving force behind the Arizona State
College Athletic Council's 1947 declaration that the school would
schedule games only against opponents that allowed all of ASU's
players to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stand ASU took was ad vertised in the Black press
throughout the country and that reflected quite well on ASU,'' said
Warren, 75, who received a doctorate at ASU and was a professor of
school administration and supervision there for many years. ``It
was quite a move on the part of this little teachers college. This
was during a time when Eastern teams were told not to bring their
Black players to the Cotton Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   Warren has spent much of his life confronting racism. He moved
to Phoenix when he was 2 from Marlin, Texas, because his family
didn't want their children reared there.
</P>
<P>
   He attended a segregated school, Phoenix Union Colored High
School, and was forced to sit in the Negro sections of movie
theaters. He had been refused admittance at restaurants. When he
played football at Phoenix College in 1941 and 1942, before he
joined the service, he was not allowed to play against New Mexico
Military Institute at Roswell.
</P>
<P>
   He endured, he said, because of great support from both Phoenix
College and ASU. That wasn't always the case with opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd go to areas where there would be difficulty on the
field,'' he said. ``It was the first experience for many people. If
I would tackle them, sometimes I might hear `Nigger.' But I also
made some great friendships on the other side of the ball, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The attitude of the Texas schools worked against them when they
came to play in Tempe.
</P>
<P>
   White said: ``When those teams would come here, it was really a
boost for us. We didn't forget.''
</P>
<P>
   Even after the Texas schools began showing less resistance,
Texas Tech and ASU never scheduled games.
</P>
<P>
   ``When others were breaking the color barrier, Texas Tech
continued to hard line,'' said Bill Quinn, an ASU assistant coach
at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Kelley, an all-conference wide receiver from Texas Tech's
1948 team, said race was never an issue with his teammates and he
never heard an edict from the university.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never gave it a thought,'' he said. ``I really believe race
was never brought up by our administration. We competed against
Arizona State in other sports, and I remember running track against
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``To this day, I do believe a Black person is just as American
as Bill Kelley. I always thought the racial thing was blown out of
proportion.''
</P>
<P>
   Barrier broken in '37 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Race was first an issue with the ASU football team in 1937, when
Harvey, a standout athlete from Sacramento, became a member. Tom
Lillico, ASU's new graduate manager of athletics at the time, found
Harvey working at a Walgreen's in San Francisco and encouraged him
to come to Arizona State Teachers College.
</P>
<P>
   According to Dean Smith's book, ``The Sun Devils, Eight Decades
of'' ``Arizona State Football,'' his teammates initially had mixed
reactions about his presence.
</P>
<P>
   But after Coach Rudy Lavik promoted him to starting blocking
back and defensive end, his skills convinced everyone he belonged.
</P>
<P>
   The football team encountered isolated cases of discrimination
down the road. When the 1951 team traveled to Arkansas, it stopped
at several restaurants before finding one that would serve both its
White and Black athletes.
</P>
<P>
   That's how both group of athletes wanted it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both (Warren and Diggs) were very well-liked,'' Williams said.
``After college, when Morrison went to play professional football,
I wrote my family in Boston and said, `You've got to meet this guy
after a game and invite him to dinner. He's terrific.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Although the names of Diggs, Warren and Harvey may not be as
ensconced in ASU lore as firmly as some, one ASU player said they
shouldn't be forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think all athletes here, African-American or Caucasian,
should remember how fortunate we are that there were players like
that who paved the way,'' ASU senior cornerback Courtney Jackson
said. ``They stood for what they believed in. We should all be
proud.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-99 0021EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990905.0013 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-05 00:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1346 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s BC-FBN-CARDS-STADUIM?-AZ     09-05 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-STADUIM?-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE CALLING PLAYS ON STADIUM  
 CARDINALS HOPE `REGIONAL PARTNER SHIP' DEVELOPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LES POLK  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - When the Cardinals suffered a bitter election defeat
May 18 in Mesa's vote on a new stadium, team officials were
emphatic about one thing: They had no Plan B.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the team let the controversial Rio Salado Crossing
election debate die down, waiting for a glimmer of leadership from
somewhere in the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   That leadership quietly has emerged from the office of Gov. Jane
Hull, where officials have spent the summer evaluating information
from the Cardinals and the National Football League on the
public-private partnerships that have played a key role in
construction of more than 250 stadiums, arenas, performing arts
centers and convention centers built in North American this decade.
</P>
<P>
   The Cards, the NFL and the governor's office hope a creative
proposal can be crafted that soon would give the team hope of
leaving aged Sun Devil Stadium and the ranks of NFL economic
have-nots, and give the Valley hope of luring more Super Bowls,
keeping the Fiesta Bowl in the upper echelon of bowls and luring
other major sporting events.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dust is settled, and we look forward to progress over the
coming weeks,'' said Michael Bidwill, Cardinals vice president who
led the Rio Salado Crossing effort. ``It's becoming progressively
more difficult for the Cardinals to compete.''
</P>
<P>
   Because they lack the revenue streams being generated for NFL
teams in a wave of new stadiums across the land, the Cardinals are
conservative financially. And because they lack a
climate-controlled stadium, they have difficulty attracting fans to
Sun Devil Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the only team in the league that has trouble selling
half of our 50-yard line and 45-yard line seats,'' Bidwill said,
referring to the sunny, east side of the stadium. ``It's hard when
you can't move your inventory.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals want a retractable roof stadium with a grass
field, and Bidwill said he still likes the design of the $497
million stadium proposed for the Rio Salado Crossing.
</P>
<P>
   It featured 67,000 seats and was expandable for the Super Bowl.
A new stadium would open revenue streams for the Cardinals from
suites, club seats, advertising signs, scoreboards, naming rights
and concessions that are limited at Sun Devil Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Bidwill and others say the team learned a lesson in the Mesa
vote: An NFL stadium project is too much for one community to
handle.
</P>
<P>
   Mesa voters rejected, 60 percent to 40 percent, a proposed sales
tax increase for the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Horrow, an NFL stadium consultant, said what is needed now
is a ``regional partnership.'' That is what Bidwill and the state
hope to develop.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's now in the control of leadership in more of a larger
jurisdiction, the state,'' Bidwill said.
</P>
<P>
   George Weisz, an executive assistant to Hull, said state
officials are reviewing various concepts and hope to make progress
on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   No specific plan has emerged, but all the parties agree some
public participation will be necessary.
</P>
<P>
   None of the new or remodeled stadiums in the NFL has been built
without some public support _ be it infrastructure, land or a
financing mechanism.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Aiello, communications director for the NFL, said the
public can't expect the Cards to finance a stadium alone and run a
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's economically unfeasible for an NFL owner to both finance
a stadium and operate a team,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Aiello also reiterated that the NFL will put the Super Bowl back
in the Valley if a new stadium is built.
</P>
<P>
   As new stadiums pop up around the league, the rich get richer
and the Cardinals find it harder to compete.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland and Tennessee opened stadiums this season.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati, Detroit, Pittsburgh, New England, Seattle and Denver
will be in new stadiums in the coming years.
</P>
<P>
   Carolina, San Diego, St. Louis, Oakland, Tampa Bay, Atlanta and
Jacksonville already are in new or remodeled stadiums.
</P>
<P>
   None was built solely by the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``The league and the various NFL cities have a long track record
of public-private partnership,'' Bidwill said. ``There is a
recognition by communities that it is important.''
</P>
<P>
   Bidwill said the Cardinals will make a significant financial
contribution to whatever proposal comes forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've said all along that we want to remain in Arizona,'' he
said. ``We are working with the governor's office and are hopeful
that something can come together for the Cards, the Fiesta Bowl and
the community.'
</P>
<P>
   Horrow said the league is monitoring the situation and hoping
for a ``very creative solution.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Any of these deals in the '90s to some degree absolutely
requires a public-private partnership,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clearer than ever that the Cardinals need a new facility.
The league is following the situation closely and is dedicated to
working with the Cardinals and doing anything necessary to help.''
</P>
<P>
   Horrow said the Cardinals have become a ``have-not'' team
economically and are at a ``tremendous disadvantage competitively''
because of Sun Devil Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly this effort has to move forward in a meaningful way
consistent with every other community that has come up with a Plan
B,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That has happened in places such as Pittsburgh, where local tax
hikes were rejected by voters, but the state later stepped in and
devised a financing plan, Horrow said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Steelers will be on their way to playing in a new
stadium while the Cardinals still wait. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-99 0022EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
