r s BC-BKL-COMETS-LIBERTY-TE     09-05 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-COMETS-LIBERTY-TEX </SLUG>
 
Comets' coronation delayed New York's long shot 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MAC ENGEL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A little man wheeling the WNBA trophy was already on
the floor amid descending confetti when New York Liberty guard
Teresa Weatherspoon took her shot.
</P>
<P>
   With fourth-tenths of a second remaining, she put her practice
to the test when she let fly a desperation,
don't-even-bother-hailing-Mary 52-foot shot to win Game 2 of the
WNBA Finals, 68-67, over the Houston Comets. The victory forced a
decisive Game 3 at 2:30 p.m. today in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   After Houston's Tina Thompson hit the apparent
championship-winning shot with 2.3 seconds remaining, Weatherspoon
took the inbounds pass, dribbled twice and took two steps near
midcourt and the sideline. She arched a one-handed shot that banked
off the glass and through the net, leaving the sellout crowd of
16,285 silent and WNBA dignitaries stunned.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it left my hands I knew it was good,'' said Weatherspoon,
who finished with eight points, six rebounds and five assists. ``I
practice that shot after every practice, and every now and then I
hit it. I was just praying it would go in.'' .
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most heartbreaking loss I've been through,''
Houston coach Van Chancellor said. ``When Tina hit her shot I
thought we had a pretty good shot, but I didn't think she \R
Weatherspoon\S would hit a prayer. That shot wasn't the only thing
that beat us. Giving up 45 points in the second half did. We can't
give up 13 offensive rebounds.''
</P>
<P>
   The Liberty, which scored just two points in the first 10:24 of
the game, shot 30 percent and committed 10 turnovers in the first
half and trailed by 14 points at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't buy a basket, but I was getting shots,'' Liberty
guard Crystal Robinson said. ``Coach told me at halftime, `Keep
shooting, Crystal, you're a shooter and eventually they'll start to
fall.''' After shooting 1-for-6 in the first half, she scored
18-second half points on 5-of-5 shooting, including three
3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   Houston's Cynthia Cooper and Sheryl Swoopes, who combined for 44
points in the Game 1 victory, were all but shut down in the second
half, shooting a combined 2-for-14 and scoring 13 points. The
Liberty went on a 19-3 run to take their first lead with 11:33
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   The Comets regained the lead and led by nine before New York
answered with a 9-0 run. Houston led by four with 3:54 remaining
before Kym Hampton's personal 5-0 run made it a one-point game with
less than one minute remaining The lead changed hands several times
after that before the final seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have the intensity to win this game. We have to
match their intensity in the second half; that's our goal,'' Cooper
said. ``But, man, I can't believe she hit that shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither could the man wheeling out the trophy. \Nsubheds:Briefly
In losing their first home playoff game ever and only their eighth
home game in 53 games, the Big Three for the Comets _ Tina
Thompson, Cynthia Cooper and Sheryl Swoopes _ disappeared . In the
playoffs the trio had been averaging 48.1 points, more than 12
rebounds and 13 assists per game. In Game 2, they were limited to
41 points on 8-of-31 shooting with nine assists. ... Yesterday's
loss was Houston's first at home this season when leading at the
half. The Comets had been 15-0. ... Early in the second half,
Thompson caught an elbow near her right eye from New York's Sue
Wicks while going for a rebound. Thompson's right eye caught a
Wicks elbow, leaving Thompson on the floor for sometime. She
suffered a small bruise under her right eye that required a
bandage, but she returned to the game a few minutes later. ...
After losing Game 1, 73-60, New York coach Richie Adubato was
critical of one thing: officiating. The Comets went to the line 14
more times than the Liberty. He was fined $1,500 for his critiques.
In the news conference after yesterday's win, Adubato was reticent:
``I am not complaining about the foul line today ... even though it
was 42-22.'' That was the disparity between the number of foul
shots taken by the Comets compared to New York.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
