<SLUG> BC-BOX-DELAHOYA-TRINIDAD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DE LA HOYA STRATEGY: TELL ANYTHING BUT TRUTH  
 AIM IS TO KEEP TRINIDAD CLUELESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a business where deception is both an art form and a survival
skill, Oscar De La Hoya is an honest man.
</P>
<P>
   He lies.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya wasn't throwing any rhetorical feints last week when
he talked about his plans for Felix Trinidad on Sept. 18 in their
much-anticipated welterweight clash at Las Vegas' Mandalay Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody knows what I'm going to do inside the ring,'' De La
Hoya said in a conference call. ``I'm telling one person one thing,
another person another thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever comes out of my mouth about a strategy, it's all a
lie.''
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya's frank comment about an ancient, even honored
practice was yet another example of a personality that often
appears to be at odds with a code as old as a jagged scar. Fighters
were lying before the CIA launched its first disinformation
campaign. It's just that nobody ever admits it.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, De La Hoya always says and does things that
surprise, annoy, amuse and confuse. He's a mamma's boy with a mean
streak.
</P>
<P>
   With his Hollywood looks, he doesn't like to get hit, and pity
the fool who hits him. Ike Quartey discovered as much when a
seemingly beaten De La Hoya overwhelmed him late in their 12-round
fight with a last stand that was a mix of desperation and
determination.
</P>
<P>
   It's a dangerous combination, simply because nobody can ever be
certain when one or both will show up.
</P>
<P>
   As the opening bell for a fight with the potential to be among
the best in a decade approaches, the tide of ringside opinion is
swinging in favor of Trinidad, who last week predicted a
sixth-round knockout of De La Hoya as he broke camp in Puerto Rico
and headed for Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   It began to move in that direction a few weeks ago when
respected trainer Emanuel Steward, a former De La Hoya cornerman,
said Trinidad would win. Predictably, Steward created a bandwagon
that is getting very crowded. Steward said he told De La Hoya,
face-to-face, of his pick when the two had a chance encounter near
the fighter's training camp at Big Bear, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Steward explained his reasoning by saying that De La Hoya, the
World Boxing Council's unbeaten champion (31-0, 25 KOs), had too
many distractions. He plays golf, is getting married, just had a
child, fired a longtime adviser in Mike Hernandez and is trying to
become a mariachi singer.
</P>
<P>
   By Steward's way of thinking, Trinidad, the unbeaten
International Boxing Federation champion (35-0, 30 KOs), is more
devoted to his craft. While De La Hoya learns how to sing, Trinidad
is in the ring. That, at least, is the suggestion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has their own opinion,'' De La Hoya said. ``It's
just sad people who know who I am and know what I can do will go
with the other guy. It shows what kind of person that is.''
</P>
<P>
   But, in truth, Steward might have been doing De La Hoya a very
big favor. He sounded an alarm for a fighter who a year ago was
listed among ``Fortune'' magazine's top-earning athletes, with $37
million in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   By De La Hoya's own admission, there have been distractions.
Wealth buys a lot of them. He looked disinterested and often sloppy
in May before scoring an 11th-round stoppage of Oba Carr with a
sprained left hand that was virtually useless after the first
couple of rounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since this is a major fight, I'm hungry again,'' De La Hoya
said. ``After you've been through as much as I have been, you seem
to worry less about boxing. But this fight has made me re-focus. I
feel like the hungry fighter I was a few years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he had lost some of his passion for the sport
since victories in two confrontations with his boyhood idol, Julio
Cesar Chavez, De La Hoya said:
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely.''
</P>
<P>
   Reports of a re-dedicated De La Hoya can't be a source of much
comfort to the Trinidad camp.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, who really knows?
</P>
<P>
   ``For me to say different things is just a matter of confusing
my opponent,'' De La Hoya said. ``To me, that's playing it smart.''
</P>
<P>
   To everybody else, it's De La Hoya playing a role that, on Sept.
18, might be worth an Oscar. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
