<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ARIZONA-TCU-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UA TRIES TO BOUNCE BACK AGAINST TCU 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas - Arizona Coach Dick Tomey calls last week's
debacle at Penn State ``a measuring stick.'' For a man always in
search of progress, there wasn't much to measure. But Tomey clearly
used the stick.
</P>
<P>
   He used it on himself as a verbal lash in accepting
responsibility for the loss.
</P>
<P>
   And he used it on his team as he tried to prepare for today's
game against Texas Christian in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   There was an unmistakable sense of urgency in his tone
throughout practices in which he demanded that the Wildcats display
enthusiasm, energy and toughness. Tomey calls it heart, which is
something he also said was missing in Arizona's season opener.
</P>
<P>
   In the worst possible scenario, the Wildcats might discover
today that they lack more than just heart.
</P>
<P>
   The departure of cornerback Chris McAlister, offensive linemen
Yusuf Scott and Edwin Mulitalo, receiver Jeremy McDaniel, fullback
Kelvin Eafon and tight end Mike Lucky also might have stripped them
of more skill than they had realized.
</P>
<P>
   It probably would be premature to say all that after only one
game, no matter how one-sided.
</P>
<P>
   But overrated? Without a doubt. Penn State's whipping of Arizona
wiped away poll-created illusions that the Wildcats were one of the
nation's top five teams.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the question involves the very identity of this team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not very good right now, I do know that,'' said Bruce
Wiggins, the starting center. ``It's the truth. If I can't admit
it, we'll never get better.''
</P>
<P>
   So, who are these guys? Are they still a top 20 team? The
pollsters apparently think so. The Wildcats fell from No. 4 to No.
15 this week in the Associated Press. Are they still a favorite to
win the Pac-10? If you believe the polls, you have to think they
are. The Wildcats still are the highest-rated team in a conference
without contenders.
</P>
<P>
   For TCU, another date with a team from an apparently weak
conference has to be good news. The Horned Frogs ended last season
with an upset of Southern California in the Sun Bowl. TCU has to
hope it is picking up where it left off.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, it's safe to assume that TCU looked at the Penn State
game films and put together a plan that will test Arizona's weak
defensive corners.
</P>
<P>
   In receiver-turned-quarterback Patrick Batteaux and tailback
LaDainian Tomlinson, the Horned Frogs have an option attack with at
least two runners who can get to the corners quickly. It would seem
that Arizona has an ideal counter with a defense that stopped
Nebraska's option in December's Holiday Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we can quit looking at the highlights of last season,''
said Tomey, who might be looking for a shovel to replace that
measuring stick if the Wildcats stumble today. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
