<SLUG> BC-BKL-WNBA-CHAMPIONSHIP-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WNBA EXPANSION DRAFT TO COME EARLY THIS TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The all important details of the third WNBA expansion
draft remain a mystery, but not for long.
</P>
<P>
   League President Val Ackerman said Saturday that the draft to
begin stocking Seattle, Portland, Indianapolis and Miami will be
held in December.
</P>
<P>
   That's two months sooner than the 1998 expansion draft when
Detroit and Washington joined the league and four months before
Minnesota and Orlando selected players from the existing teams in
April. The '99 expansion draft was especially late because of
collective bargaining negotiations with the new players union.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything you read right now is speculation,'' regarding the
number of players teams will be allowed to protect from the
expansion teams, Ackerman said. ``We have to make a judgment as to
how do we best balance the need to make our expansion teams
reasonably competitive and yet give the exisiting teams the
benefits of all their efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you that we will try and be very fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Rumors are rampant that teams will be allowed to protect fewer
players than in the first two expansion drafts (six) and lose more
than one.
</P>
<P>
   Ackerman said she does not know if enough quality players will
sign with the league to allow it to stock the expansion teams with
at least one allocated player before the expansion draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some newcomers (Teresa Edwards, Katrina McClain,
Katy Steading among some of the former American Basketball League
players who did not immediately move to the WNBA) who weren't with
us and to some degree we have to figure out what their relationship
might be to the expansion teams,'' Ackerman said.
</P>
<P>
   Another group of ABL players who went unpicked in the WNBA draft
and some WNBA veterans who lost jobs, like the Mercury's Umeki
Webb, also could come into play with the expansion teams before the
annual draft in April.
</P>
<P>
   Briefly &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ackerman also said the 2000 season, to begin 10 days to two
weeks earlier because to accomodate the Sydney Olympics, will
conclude with eight teams (four per conference) in the playoffs
that will expand to best-of-3 in every round.
</P>
<P>
   This season, six of 12 teams (three per conference) made the
playoffs with each conference champion having a first-round bye and
the No. 2-3 teams meeting in a single game.
</P>
<P>
   A site for the 2000 All-Star Game will be named this fall,
Ackerman said, ``in a city that has the prospect of getting
incredible fan support.''
</P>
<P>
   New York hosted the first All-Star Game, and the leading
candidates for the sequel are Houston, Phoenix and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Ackerman rates the chances of franchise relocation for 2000 as
unlikely, meaning that teams lagging in attendance (Charlotte at
7,081 per game and Utah at 7,544 in particular) are safe for at
least another season. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
