<SLUG> BC-BKL-WNBA-CHAMPIONSHIP-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIRACLE SHOT KEEPS LIBERTY ALIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ If it takes a miracle to dethrone the Houston Comets,
the New York Liberty was the recipient of a major one Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   When a prayer from several steps beyond midcourt went in for
Teresa Weatherspoon as the buzzer sounded and premature celebration
of a Comets WNBA championship three-peat went off, delirium at the
sold-out Compaq Center turned to disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   Houston had never lost a home playoff game, much less one it
led, 17-2, at the outset and 37-23 at halftime. Or 67-65 with 2.4
seconds left after a tough nine-foot bank shot that Tina Thompson
stuck over Crystal Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   The banker that counted more, though, was the 47-foot heave by
Weatherspoon, perhaps the greatest shots in U.S. women's basketball
history.
</P>
<P>
   Only the 19-foot game winner by North Carolina's Charlotte Smith
in the 1994 NCAA Final compares, with bonus points for being in a
title game. The Liberty (21-16) only pulled even in the
best-of-three Finals. Game 3 is at 12:30 p.m. today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't going to look for anyone, I was going to live or die
with the shot,'' said Weatherspoon, New York's point guard and
spiritual leader known more for her defense. ``I'd rather put it on
my shoulders than to see one of my teammates have to take that
responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Knowing the Liberty had used all its timeouts, Weatherspoon
immediately took an inbounds from Becky Hammon and dribbled twice
vs. Thompson, who waved a hand at her as she let fly New York's
last chance to avenge its 1997 Finals loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``What?,'' Thompson screamed as the Liberty mobbed Weatherspoon
and the surreal finish sank in.
</P>
<P>
   Weatherspoon, 33, a native of Texas, said she never had made a
shot ``to this magnitude.'' New York's Richie Adubato, 60, said he
has lost a half-dozen games in his 38-year coaching career on such
buckets, but never had won one.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can say is we work on that shot every day and it finally
won a game for us,'' Adubato said. He wasn't kidding. Weatherspoon,
Hammon and others hang around after practice with the assistant
coaches to pretend and dream of winning games just the way it went
down on national television.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want them to go shower so we can get out of there,'' Adubato
said. ``Now I'm glad I told them not to shower.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston (29-8) couldn't wash off the second half fast enough
after losing at home for only the third time in two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps mentally the celebration began too soon for the Comets,
who were blitzed, 14-2, coming out of intermission, then rebuilt a
52-43 lead only to let that get away in the final 9:10.
</P>
<P>
   Liberty forward Crystal Robinson, 1 for 6 at halftime, bombed in
18 second-half points while Houston guard Cynthia Cooper went
strangely silent (0 for 6 in the second half with just three free
throws).
</P>
<P>
   Cooper, the three-time league scoring champion, had 29 points
Thursday in a 73-60 Game 1 win at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't play in the second half and when you don't play, you
don't win,'' Cooper said. ``But we are the two-time champions and
I'll tell you what, we know what it takes to win. We're going to
come back here (today) and have what it takes to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Comets' defense-driven, first-half dominance disguised some
problems: 37.5 percent shooting that dropped to 30 percent for the
game and a 21-15 rebound deficit that ended 34-28. Houston also
missed 10 free throws.
</P>
<P>
   New York received a stabilizing 10-point, 15-minute performance
from Hammon, a rookie guard. And 36-year-old Kym Hampton, in what
could have been her final game before retirement, came up with a
near double-double (10 points/nine rebounds).
</P>
<P>
   A Hampton three-pointer followed by a 15-footer gave the Liberty
a 63-62 lead at 1:24. Houston's Sheryl Swoopes drove to the basket,
was fouled by Hampton and made both free throws at 1:05.
</P>
<P>
   Off a Cooper steal, Thompson drove, was fouled by Sue Wicks and
made one free throw for a 65-63 lead with 28.4 seconds left. Then
after a timeout, Robinson pulled up to hit an 18-footer at 16.3.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson then answered that basket with her nine-footer, only
for Weatherspoon to have the final word. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-99 0034EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990905.0019 </DOCNO>
