<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STORY OF GIRL'S TURBULENT LIFE EMERGES IN INTERVIEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KARINA BLAND  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - From age 5, she would run back and forth outside her
family's mobile home in Litchfield Park. Faster and faster each
time, arms unfurled behind her, she seemed to believe if she ran
fast enough she could fly.
</P>
<P>
   She's been running ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Now 14, the hazel-eyed girl who has spent much of her life in
foster care has become a living symbol of the national debate over
abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, a Maricopa County Superior Court judge gave her
permission to travel to Kansas for a late-term abortion. She went
last week, and presumably had the procedure. She was 24 weeks
along.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone knows her decision. It was dissected and debated by
people who never knew her and likely never will.
</P>
<P>
   But no one knows the girl. She has been lost in the legal
maneuvering to block the abortion and the second-guessing over
whether she was old enough to make the choice.
</P>
<P>
   A picture of her turbulent life emerges through interviews with
family members, people who know her both now and as a younger
child, and from court and police records.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona Republic is not using her name because she is a
minor.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, the girl is very bright. Tests she took in
eighth grade indicated that she was smart enough to be in high
school, her family says. She loves to read and talks of being a
lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's no dummy,'' says Sandy Harper, the fiancee of James
Harkins, the girl's maternal uncle. ``She's far from it.''
</P>
<P>
   Harper has known the girl since the days she made those laps
alongside the trailer.
</P>
<P>
   When the girl was 7, she played with Barbie dolls that were
missing an arm, a leg or even a head, but she didn't seem to mind,
says Lori Murphy Lane, who was the girl's neighbor at the time.
</P>
<P>
   The girl has a thing for fairies and gnomes, say those who know
her. And she likes to dance.
</P>
<P>
   She wanted to be a normal kid with a normal family, says a
father whose children attended a West Valley charter school with
the girl.
</P>
<P>
   She went to the school while living in a Glendale group home
last year and part of this year. The girl quickly became a favorite
of parents and teachers, who said they worried about what she had
been through, and what was coming next.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, one couple from the school even filed for
guardianship of the girl, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   They want her to stop running. They want to give her a home. &QL; 
LIFETIME OF HARDSHIP &QL; 
The girl, just 14, has lived through enough hardship for a
lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   She's been moved from foster home to foster home since she was
8.
</P>
<P>
   Her father has never been around, rarely seeing the girl and not
paying any child support, family members say. She was taken from
her mother after she ran away from home and refused to return,
claiming abuse, they say.
</P>
<P>
   In January, her mother was found stabbed to death near Glendale
Municipal Airport, the first homicide of the new year in the
Phoenix area.
</P>
<P>
   The girl is the fourth of her mother's eight children. The
others are scattered. One was adopted, one is in prison, two live
with their father and two are in foster homes. One died of sudden
infant death syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   The girl was just a little thing, maybe 4 or 5, when Lane first
met her at their Litchfield Park trailer park.
</P>
<P>
   She says she watched what went on in the little girl's house
with horror.
</P>
<P>
   The girl's mother and the mother's boyfriend used drugs,
according to Lane, the mother's family and police reports.
</P>
<P>
   ``You name it, they done it,'' says Lane, who now lives in
Maryland with her husband and three sons.
</P>
<P>
   The home was unkempt and infested with roaches. The children
wore tattered secondhand clothes.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was always asking why my house was always clean and her
house looked like a pigpen,'' Lane says. ``I told her it was
because her mother was sick.''
</P>
<P>
   Lane says she would wash the girl's hair, carefully picking out
the lice and their eggs. She was constantly infected, and the
school sent notices warning other parents. Her classmates teased
her.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was humiliating for her,'' Lane says. `It broke my heart.''
</P>
<P>
   The girl would come to Lane's house when her mother wasn't at
home. Lane says the child was afraid of her mother's boyfriend.
</P>
<P>
   Lane says the mother's boyfriend often abused the kids, hitting
them often enough and hard enough that she and other neighbors
called state Child Protective Services and the police.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was petrified to go to that house,'' Lane says.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, the girl told police that was why she ran away from
home in early January: She didn't want another beating, according
to news reports at the time.
</P>
<P>
   She left on a Sunday afternoon, hiding out in a cardboard box in
the desert behind an apartment complex, news reports said.
</P>
<P>
   Lane went looking for the girl. She and her son found her lying
in the box, Lane says, her thin legs sticking out of the opening.
She had a blanket and candles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so tired of him doing what he is doing to me,'' Lane says
the girl told her.
</P>
<P>
   Lane persuaded her not to stay in the box, but the little girl
didn't go home, and her mother did not report her missing until she
was gone for 13{ hours, news reports said. Sheriff's deputies found
her at a friend's house on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Her mother and her mother's boyfriend were never charged with
child abuse, news reports said, though the girl has been in the
state's care ever since. &QL; 
REGULAR RUNAWAY &QL; 
This would not be the first time the girl ran away.
</P>
<P>
   She bolted regularly from the state's care, sometimes to look
for her mother, says Harper, her uncle's fiancee. At times, she got
as far as California, Oregon and Utah. Her flight record is such
that the judge ruled that she could be handcuffed on the way to get
- and even during _ the abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``She puts that little thumb out, and she's gone,'' Harper says.
</P>
<P>
   One place she didn't run from was the charter school she
attended while living in the Glendale group home. There, she
developed close relationships with kids and their parents, the
parents say.
</P>
<P>
   The girl went to church with one family, asking a lot of
questions about God and the Bible, the parents say. Her mother had
been a Wiccan, a group of self-titled ``witches'' who worship
nature, the parents and family members say.
</P>
<P>
   The girl had a Wicca book that belonged to her mother, according
to a police report. In June 1998, a staff member tried to take the
book from her.
</P>
<P>
   The staffer told police she was worried that the girl was
teaching other girls about witchcraft. During the confrontation,
the girl threw herself against a wall, punching a 10- by 10-inch
hole.
</P>
<P>
   She was charged with criminal damage and taken to Durango
Juvenile Detention Center in handcuffs, the police report says. She
was later released.
</P>
<P>
   The girl ran away from the same group home on Christmas Eve of
1998, the parents say, because staffers would not let her visit her
family. She went to see them anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Her relatives bought her a few CDs and some clothes and gave her
some cash, family members say, and then she disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   She didn't show back up at the group home until Jan. 4, about
two hours before her mother's body was found. &QL; 
MOM'S KILLER NOT FOUND &QL; 
Things had gotten worse for the girl's mother after her children
were taken by the state. Already pregnant with her youngest, she
tried to get her life together, her family says.
</P>
<P>
   She stayed sober for more than a year, turning in clean urine
samples to the state regularly, Harper says.
</P>
<P>
   But when she didn't get her kids back after some time, she went
back to her old ways, Harper says. Her killer has not been found.
</P>
<P>
   A CPS caseworker brought the girl to the funeral, where her
mother's body lay on a gurney, covered only by a sheet. Dried blood
was caked in her hair.
</P>
<P>
   ``That just horrified the whole family,'' Harper says. ``Even
the adults.''
</P>
<P>
   After the service, the girl was taken back to school.
</P>
<P>
   Not long after, she ran again.
</P>
<P>
   According to a Jan. 16 police report, staff at the group home
told police the girl was despondent over her mother's death and
threatening suicide when she left. The girl did not say where she
was going, only that ``I will know where I am when I get there.''
</P>
<P>
   She was picked up by police in early February and put in Durango
again. When she got out, she was moved to another group home.
</P>
<P>
   Both of the girl's maternal uncles, Bob Harkins and James
Harkins, want the girl to be allowed to live with them.
</P>
<P>
   James Harkins and his fiancee, Sandy Harper, manage an apartment
complex in Glendale. Bob Harkins lives with his girlfriend and
their 9-month-old baby in a four-bedroom house in the West Valley.
</P>
<P>
   For a time last year, the girl was allowed to visit her family
on the weekends. Then, in August of 1998, she was allowed to stay
with Bob Harkins for a week.
</P>
<P>
   But she ran again.
</P>
<P>
   She took off on Aug. 18, the first night of what was supposed to
be the weeklong visit. When Bob Harkins asked where she was going,
she said, ``I'm taking a boat to China.'' Her uncle called police
and CPS to report her missing, her family says.
</P>
<P>
   The girl needs close supervision, her family says. She lies
some. Last time Bob Harkins saw her _ about four or five months ago
_ she had short, purple hair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to whap her upside her head,'' he says. ``She's
a kid, but she thinks she's an adult.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Harkins thinks he can handle her, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has no choice but to behave around me or I'll whup on her
butt or set her in her room,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The girl was already pregnant the last time her family saw her,
Harper says. Her uncles wanted her to keep the baby.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told her, `If you want to keep this baby, we can do it
together as a family,' '' Harper says.
</P>
<P>
   But the girl didn't stick around.
</P>
<P>
   She was picked up on May 7 after giving false information about
who she was to a police officer, police reports say. Taken aside by
another officer, she confessed she was homeless and pregnant. She
was taken back to Durango.
</P>
<P>
   It was then that she first told state officials that she wanted
an abortion. She was granted permission but ran again and _ by the
time she returned late last month _ she was nearly six months
along. &QL; 
NEWS LEAKED TO MEDIA &QL; 
On Aug. 24, news of the court's order allowing the girl to travel
out of state to have a late-term abortion was leaked to the media.
It set off nearly two weeks of political and legal maneuvering to
stop the abortion.
</P>
<P>
   The judge's order was upheld by the Arizona Supreme Court, and
she traveled to Kansas last week, where she reportedly underwent
the two- to three-day procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Glendale police are attempting to determine the identity of the
father of the girl's fetus. Though the girl is not cooperating with
the investigation, investigators have requested a sample from the
fetus to establish paternity, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Police suspect the father is a man in his early 20s, so any
sexual contact with the girl _ who would have been 13 at the time _
would constitute a sexual assault under Arizona law, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to the alleged father, the girl wrote, ``I'm
pregnant. I mean, I'm really pregnant. You're the only person it
could have been.'' And she asks for $700 for an abortion. The
girl's family gave the letter and an address book belonging to the
girl to police.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's hungry for someone to take care of her and love her and
nurture her,'' Harper says. ``With their heart, not with any other
part of their body.''
</P>
<P>
   She is eager for the girl's return.
</P>
<P>
   Harper has the girl's Bible, the cover done in cross-stitch by
her grandmother, who died about five years ago. Inside is the
message, ``On the occasion of her third Christmas, December 25,
1987, My little ladybug, I love you very much. Grandma.''
</P>
<P>
   Harper keeps it by the girl's mother's ashes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to take her in my arms,'' Harper says, ``and tell
her we'll get through this together.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
