<HEADLINE>
CHOUINARD RELAXES, REGISTERS BIG YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Perhaps the biggest improvement among the Diamondbacks
over last season has been by right-handed middle reliever  &UR; Bobby
 &UR; Chouinard.
</P>
<P>
   Chouinard, 0-2 with a 4.23 ERA in 26 games for Arizona last
season, is 5-2 with a 2.10 ERA in 22 games in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I sound like a broken record, but it's all about
confidence, trusting myself,'' he said. ``Last year, my slider was
a little loopy, but now I have the confidence that I can throw it
in just about any count to a right-hander, or I can come back with
my sinker, change-up or curve to a lefty.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trick is to try not to get into a pattern. You don't want
the hitter to know what you're going to throw.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key is staying within yourself. I was overthrowing a lot
last year, trying to impress people with stuff I didn't have. I'd
like to throw 100 mph like  &UR; Randy Johnson, but I can't. So I have
to try to get the guy out with the best stuff I have. Just so long
as you get the out, that's what counts.'' &QL; 
Anderson on target &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After picking up a victory last Sunday and retiring all six men
he faced against the Braves on Friday night, left-hander  &UR; Brian
 &UR; Anderson seems to be settling into his role in the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference between now and the first time I was in the
bullpen is my mechanics. And I've got more innings under my belt,''
he said. ``Before, my mechanics were all over the place. Everything
seemed foreign to me. I'm more comfortable.'' &QL; 
Scouting search continues &QL;
</P>
<P>
   General Manager  &UR; Joe Garagiola  &UR; Jr. said the interview process
is near completion in the club's search for a new scouting
director.
</P>
<P>
   Nine candidates have been interviewed, some from within the
organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it's a matter of seeing if we want to bring anybody back,
or if we have enough information,'' Garagiola said.
</P>
<P>
   Garagiola hopes to have a person in place no later than the
first week of November, when the scouting directors have their
annual meetings, and so the new person can review and meet with his
staff. &QL; 
When the boss speaks . . . &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Garagiola, a graduate of Notre Dame, was asked whether he made
any wagers with a few members of the club who are Michigan fans on
Saturday's college football game.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I just walked through the clubhouse and said, `All of you
with one-year contracts, let's hear a little more enthusiasm (for
the Fighting Irish),' '' said Garagiola, whose alma mater put up a
good battle but lost. &QL; 
Short stop &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Though the Diamondbacks have struck out 18 times against the
Braves in the first two games of this series, they still will need
to average about 13 over their remaining 26 games to match last
season's 1,239, which led the major leagues. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
