<SLUG> BC-FBC-A&AMP;M-LA.-TECH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGGIES' OFFENSE SIZZLES, THEN SAGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHREVEPORT, La. _ Texas A&AMP;M coach R.C. Slocum was eager] to see
the 1999 debut of an offense that he felt had more capability than
at any time since Bucky Richardson ran 400-point attacks in
1990-91.
</P>
<P>
   In that respect, it's doubtful he'll find much more than a
quarter's worth of real pleasure in the sixth-ranked Aggies' 37-17
victory against Louisiana Tech last night before 40,328 at
Independence Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   For after posting a 24-point second quarter and rolling up 308
yards in the first half _ 4 yards fewer than last season's game
average _ the A&AMP;M offense sputtered and wheezed much like last
season's just-adequate unit that ranked 91st of 112 teams in NCAA
Division I-A.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, Louisiana Tech quarterback Tim Rattay (45-65-1,
331 yards) was able to spend way too much time on the field in the
second half. And that forced a weary Aggies defense into some
face-saving heroics after the Bulldogs closed to 30-17 on Rattay's
8-yard scoring pass to Delwyn Daigre six minutes into the second
half.
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Cornelius Anthony led a charge that dropped Bulldogs
tailback John Simon for a 1-yard loss on fourth-and-goal at the A&AMP;M
1 with 8:43 to play. Linebacker Brian Gamble thwarted the next
possession with a fumble recovery three minutes later, and
cornerback Jason Webster's interception with 3:47 left finally
sparked the offense into a late response.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Randy McCown found Bethel Johnson for a 12-yard
touchdown pass with 47 seconds left that capped an impressive debut
for the sophomore wide receiver.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't nervous,'' Anthony said. ``But a team with the type
passing attack they have, once you get them down you have to keep
driving at them. They're just like a boxer who staggers, but you
can't knock him down.''
</P>
<P>
   McCown finished a career-best 17-for-28 passing for 252 yards
and two touchdowns. Johnson caught four passes for 106 yards and a
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``The offense came out great in the first half,'' McCown said.
``We got a little complacent in the second half. We didn't come out
with the kind of fire we had in the \R30-point\S first half.''
</P>
<P>
   Slocum was more generic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a lot of good things out of this game tonight,'' Slocum
said. ``But we also have a lot of things to work on. A good opening
win.''
</P>
<P>
   In that 24-point second quarter, the Aggies scored 17 points
after drives of 73, 75 and 68 yards, and McCown threw a 23-yard
touchdown pass to Chris Taylor following Dante Hall's 42-yard punt
return.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson helped set up two scores with two leaping catches of
McCown passes. His first acrobatic reception went for 46 yards _
McCown's longest completion of a 12-of-16 half that produced 209
yards. Hall took it in from the 18 for A&AMP;M's initial touchdown and
a 13-3 lead four plays later at 10:28.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who practiced last season but was ineligible as a
partial academic qualifier, also went high to take in a 33-yard
gain with three seconds left in the half to open the door for
Terrence Kitchens' 26-yard field goal and a 30-10 lead on the last
play of the half.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was happy to have a good game, but I think I can do
better,'' Johnson said. ``I missed some balls I should have had.''
</P>
<P>
   Kitchens, a walk-on, opened his career as the replacement for
Russell Bynum by converting the first two field-goal attempts of
his career _ from 50 and 51 yards _ to open A&AMP;M scoring.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor's catch gave the Aggies a 20-3 lead at 8:38 of the second
quarter. Louisiana Tech answered with a 70-yard march that ended
with Rattay's 15-yard touchdown pass to Daigre to pull the Bulldogs
to 20-10. But the Aggies' 75-yard reply that featured two McCown
passes to Leroy Hodge for 34 yards re-extended the comfort zone
when fullback Ja'Mar Toombs bulled in from the one with 2:04 left
in the half.
\Nsubheds:EXTRA POINTS Before A&AMP;M kicker Terrance Kitchens kicked
field goals of 50 and 51 yards, the last Aggies field goal from
midfield was by Kyle Bryant against North Texas in 1997. ...
Officials delayed kickoff approximately 20 minutes because of
lightning in a nearby storm cloud, yet they permitted the Tech band
to perform pregame ceremonies while chatting on cell phones and
watching strikes off to the south. ... The Aggies' 30 first-half
points were the most since scoring 34 against Oklahoma in 1997.
Last season, the Aggies' highest halftime total was 14 points
(several times). The Aggies scored more than 30 in a game only
twice last season. ... Louisiana Tech's Tim Rattay has earned a
spot as one of college football's top passing quarterbacks, but he
might not even be the best quarterback in his family. Louisiana
Tech was the only school to offer Rattay a scholarship, but younger
brother, John, of Phoenix Desert Vista High School, recently
committed to Tennessee after being the subject of a national
recruiting battle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
