<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-GOMEZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROUBLE WITH ANGELS ON FIELD, NOT IN OF FICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just when it seemed the Anaheim Angels couldn't possibly sink
any lower, they did. The club that zoomed past Los Angeles and
Baltimore to gain the title of this year's most disappointing and
dysfunctional club watched its manager take the fall for its
players' failings.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Terry Collins put his head under the guillotine for the Angels,
who just two months earlier awarded Collins with a two-year
contract extension. Next up is probably General Manger  &UR; Bill
Bavasi, who accepted blame for putting together a bad ballclub.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people took as much responsibility as Terry Collins, if
they had one-quarter the integrity he has, this wouldn't have
happened,'' said Angels President  &UR; Tony Tavares, whose own job
security may be on shaky ground these days. ``I don't think (the
players) quit on Terry, they quit on themselves. I've never been
more disappointed in a team.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins, who guided the Angels to second-place finishes the past
two years, knew the end was near after Wednesday night's blown lead
and blown tempers when the Angels watched an eighth-inning,
eight-run lead evaporate in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   During the Indians' uprising, a brawl broke out when Anaheim
reliever  &UR; Troy Percival plunked  &UR; David Justice one pitch after
 &UR; Richie
 &UR; Sexson hit a massive three-run home run. All heck broke loose and
after the melee ended, Percival noted that  &UR; Mo Vaughn, who was in
the clubhouse, did not join his teammates during the mostly
uneventful fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got respect for my infielders, they were out there _
( &UR; Gary)
 &UR; DiSarcina, ( &UR; Darin)  &UR; Erstad, ( &UR; Troy)  &UR; Glaus,'' Percival said.
``That's where you learn who the people are on your team who are
standing behind you 100 percent. In the future, you know what guys
will go to battle with you and which ones won't.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn's name was conspicuously omitted. The next day, Vaughn
went into a pair of verbal tirades, filled with plenty of
expletives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want them to (expletive) hear me,'' Vaughn screamed in full
earshot of everyone in the clubhouse before Thursday's game. ``I've
been telling these (expletive) the same thing all year, keep that
(expletive) out of the papers. Be like a man.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins had a meeting with his players after the game and
realized not one of his concerns had anything to do with baseball,
but rather the petty bickering that has plagued this club all
season. That's when he knew it might be time to step aside.
</P>
<P>
   ``Speaking for the guys, we're pretty much embarrassed and
ashamed with the way we've conducted ourselves,'' said DiSarcina,
arguably the most stand-up of the Angels players. ``Terry deserved
better. You don't realize what your actions can do until something
like this happens.''
</P>
<P>
   This is one sad mess. &QL; 
Trivial question &QL; 
The Florida Marlins budged last week, giving in to first-round
pick &UR; Josh Beckett's demands of not only a major league contract,
but also a $7 million signing bonus, the highest ever for a high
school player. What are the top three signing bonuses ever given to
players in the June draft? &QL; 
Birds dropping &QL; 
Troubles in Southern California aren't the only serious problems
afflicting a major league club. The Baltimore Orioles took some of
their internal problem public last week when General Manager
 &UR; Frank &UR; Wren and Manager  &UR; Ray Miller aired some of their differences
toward each other.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said the Orioles roster was ``dysfunctional.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in baseball my whole life,'' Miller added. ``I'm a
realist. I know what I've got. I know what the situation is.''
</P>
<P>
   Presumably, Miller doesn't think much of the 1999 Orioles. But
Wren, who wanted to fire Miller in April, did not take the same
view of one of the highest-priced and lowest-achieving clubs in the
majors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a very difficult time justifying that,'' Wren said of
Miller's estimation of the club that leads the American League in
complete games.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore's offense ranks fifth in the league in average and the
staff ERA ranks sixth while the club's defense ranks first in the
AL. Orioles owner  &UR; Peter Angelos has not been shy about making
changes. If Miller and Wren are fired, distinct possibilities, it
will mark the fourth managerial change and third in the GM chair in
the past six years for Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Miller's contract has an option for next season that must be
exercised within 72 hours of the final game. Regardless of whether
he's fired, Miller has lost his team. Many pitchers regularly
ignore commands from the dugout. One position player recently
blasted Miller loudly as ``incompetent.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Orioles' problems don't just lie with management. Center
fielder  &UR; Brady Anderson was severely peeved last week when Miller
asked him to play left field for the first time since 1995, making
room for speedy rookie  &UR; Eugene Kingsale.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, who has lost a step or two on defense and has started
showing up later than any other player in the clubhouse recently,
has privately drawn the ire of Angelos. Of course, Anderson has
three years remaining on his five-year deal that includes a
no-trade clause.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not happy about it, but I've been told it's what's best
for the team,'' Anderson said.
</P>
<P>
   This entire situation is likely to get worse before it gets
better. &QL; 
Griffey in Gotham? &QL; 
Seattle's  &UR; Ken Griffey Jr. thought he was answering an innocent
question: Could he ever see himself in Yankees pinstripes?
</P>
<P>
   Little did the perennial All-Star center fielder know the
firestorm that was about to begin in the Big Apple. The back page
of one of the New York tabloids had a blaring headline that read
``Shea-Hey Kid'' about Griffey's possibly coming to the Mets as a
free agent after the 2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't talking about me playing for the Mets, but if I'd
ever play for the Yankees _ which is no, not as long as  &UR; George
Steinbrenner owns the team,'' Griffey said.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey's disdain for the Yankees boss stems from an incident
when he was 12 years old and his father had just become the club's
left fielder through free agency.
</P>
<P>
   It seems Steinbrenner once refused to allow Griffey Jr. on
Yankee Stadium's field during batting practice one day in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steinbrenner sent a security guard to tell my father (that)
George didn't want him on the field, meaning me,'' Griffey said.
``My father had to come and tell me that, but I had heard the guy
anyway. Dad said telling me was the toughest thing he ever had to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Making matters worse, Griffey Jr. remembers  &UR; Graig Nettles' son
was allowed to remain on the field during batting practice. Griffey
insists that even if Steinbrenner apologizes, his stance against
the Yankees will not change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never stepped on the field in the stadium until I was a
Mariner,'' he said. &QL; 
Trivial answer &QL; 
Right-handed pitcher  &UR; Matt White signed with Tampa Bay for a record
$10.2 million bonus after he became a loophole free agent shortly
after the 1996 June draft. Just weeks earlier, Diamondbacks first
baseman  &UR; Travis Lee, also a loophole free agent, had set the record
with a $10 million bonus.  &UR; Pat Burrell, top pick of the Phillies
last season, received an $8 million bonus, the largest ever awarded
by a club for a player it drafted. &QL; 
THE HIT LIST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By the way, October is looking very open: Visit the Web site
for the Los Angeles Dodgers and you learn how to rent Dodger
Stadium for weddings, class reunions, bar mitzvahs and bat mitzvahs
and, well, you get the picture.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Don't even get him started on Taco Bell: Chicago White Sox
pitcher  &UR; Carlos Castillo, whose girth continues to expand with each
passing month, may have given himself away with this comment about
the increasingly disenchanted fans at Comiskey Park: ``When we go
to Burger King or McDonald's, we don't yell at them if our burgers
are not cooked right.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Flashback: Von Joshua.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Right ERA, wrong Maddux: Entering the month,  &UR; Mike
 &UR; Maddux, not brother  &UR; Greg, had the lower ERA of the two siblings.
Mike Maddux, a Dodgers reliever, was 1-1 with 3.00 ERA.  &UR; Greg
Maddux, Atlanta's four-time Cy Young Award winner, was 17-6 with a
3.48 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; That's 22 down, three to go:  &UR; Craig Counsell becomes the last
of the former Marlins to return to Pro Player Stadium when the
Dodgers head to Miami later this week.  &UR; Alex Fernandez,  &UR; Antonio
 &UR; Alfonseca and  &UR; Cliff Floyd are the only remaining members from the
1997 championship club. &QL; 
EXTRA BASES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Cole Liniak, acquired from Boston in the Rod Beck deal, became
the 83rd third baseman to start a game for the Chicago Cubs since
 &UR; Ron Santo's retirement in 1974. That's an average of almost 3.5
third basemen per season.
</P>
<P>
   If history is an indication, then outfielder  &UR; Vernon
 &UR; Wells will have a fine major league career. Last week, Wells became
only the third Toronto player ever to start the season at Class A
and finish in the big leagues, joining  &UR; Dave Stieb and  &UR; Lloyd
Moseby.
</P>
<P>
   History was repeated last weekend when  &UR; Brian Bohanon became the
third Colorado pitcher to throw a complete-game shutout at Coors
Field, beating Philadelphia, 4-0. The others were thrown by  &UR; Mark
 &UR; Thompson in 1996 and  &UR; Roger Bailey in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The mighty Cleveland Indians might have six players reach 100
RBIs.  &UR; Manny Ramirez (139 through Saturday) and  &UR; Roberto
 &UR; Alomar (105) are already there. Next up are  &UR; Richie Sexson (96),
 &UR; Jim
 &UR; Thome (89),  &UR; Harold Baines (87) and  &UR; David Justice (78).
</P>
<P>
   The St. Louis Cardinals lead the majors in strikeouts. They have
nine players who have struck out at least 50 times. Leading that
list are  &UR; Mark McGwire (116) and  &UR; Fernando Tatis (110).
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago Cubs have six former members of the 1991 World
Series champion Minnesota Twins.  &UR; Mark Guthrie, who arrived last
week, joins  &UR; Rick Aguilera,  &UR; Gary Gaetti,  &UR; Jeff Reed,  &UR; Dan Serafini
and
 &UR; Kevin Tapani. Of course, Cubs President  &UR; Andy McPhail was the Twins
GM that year. &QL; 
THE RUMOR MILL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore owner  &UR; Peter Angelos has authorized serious
negotiations with ace pitcher  &UR; Mike Mussina. The right-handed
All-Star has one year remaining on a three-year, $20.45 million
deal. Expect Mussina to receive a  &UR; Pedro Martinez-type deal, worth
at least $75 million.
</P>
<P>
   Manager  &UR; Jerry Manuel does not want to see it happen, but the
Chicago White Sox will listen to offers for first
baseman/designated hitter  &UR; Frank Thomas this winter. Thomas has
only 15 home runs, a far cry from the slugger who averaged 38.8
home runs over a five-year span from 1993 through 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Willie McGee's 40-year-old legs still are spry enough to outrun
most major league players. But the one-time NL MVP and World Series
hero is sounding like someone who may be ready to call it a career.
``I'm not concentrating. . . . I know what I'm going to do. I've
answered a lot of questions in my mind this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Veteran  &UR; Frank Pulli, one of the 22 umpires whose resignations
were accepted last week, probably will not be out of a job very
long. Indications are strong that Pulli will be hired by Major
League Baseball in a supervisory capacity for umpires.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals right-hander  &UR; Alan Benes,  &UR; Andy's brother, was
scheduled to make his final rehabilitation assignment outing
Saturday. The Cardinals expect to activate the younger Benes this
week, placing him in the rotation for the final month. He hasn't
pitched in the bigs since July 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Former Pittsburgh Pirates General Manager  &UR; Ted
 &UR; Simmons is on the verge of being hired by San Diego. Simmons will
take over as vice president for scouting and player development.
The Padres have been through 10 years when few of their drafted
players have made it through the system.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado's  &UR; Jim Leyland already has told friends and family that
he will not return to manage the Rockies. This is the third time in
four years Leyland will walk in the middle of a multiyear contract.
Unlike the other times, don't expect him back next year. &QL; 
THE RANKINGS &QL; 
 &UR; TOP OF THE ORDER &QL; 
 &QL; 
