baseball game?  &QL; 
24. ColoradoA new ``help wanted'' sign is posted, this time for a
manager.  &QL; 
23. MilwaukeeComplete meltdown is under way in Brew City, where
leadership is lacking.  &QL; 
22. MontrealScrappy bunch that is playing very tight and tough of
late. ON THE RISE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; San Francisco Giants: The club that appeared all but out of the
NL West race two weeks ago has put it in high gear lately, having
won 14 of 17 entering a weekend series in Pittsburgh. The primary
reason for the surge has been left fielder  &UR; Barry Bonds, who has
been clubbing home runs at an amazing pace. During the 17-game
stretch, Bonds hit .353 with 14 home runs and 26 RBIs. ``It's why
he's got the title of superstar,'' Manager  &UR; Dusty Baker said. It
would take an incredible run by the Giants to overtake the
Diamondbacks, but this club has made miraculous comebacks in the
past two seasons. ``We understand these are the D-Day games that
will make us or break us,'' second baseman  &UR; Jeff Kent said. &QL; 
GOING SOUTH &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Philadelphia Phillies: Once on the fringe of the wild card
race, the Phillies have seen the bottom drop from their playoff
hopes. Philadelphia entered its weekend series against Cincinnati
having lost seven in a row and 18 of its previous 24 games. The
Phillies were once 13 games over .500 and entered the Reds series
two games over. ``We've got to keep battling,'' Manager  &UR; Terry
Francona said. ``There's no choice. We're still a much better team
than last year. I know the record doesn't reflect it lately, but we
are.'' The Phillies lost 10 games in the standings during August,
going 10-17. &QL; 
OVERHEARD &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Seattle Manager  &UR; Lou Piniella after he was asked to assess the
powerful New York Yankees, who had just finished a three-game sweep
over his Mariners: ``They're a good club. Let's leave it at that.
Beyond that, there's nothing to say _ zilch, zero, nada, whatever
language you want to use.'' &QL; 
OUT OF LEFT FIELD &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota pitcher  &UR; Jason Ryan, one of the many rookies on the
Twins, had an amazing revelation recently when the Twins sent him
to an eye doctor. Ryan discovered he had difficulty seeing the
catcher's signals. Fitted with his new glasses, Ryan fired a
two-hitter against Toronto. ``It was great to throw to something
you could see,'' Ryan said. Ryan was one of the two pitchers the
Cubs sent Minnesota in May in the  &UR; Rick Aguilera trade. How did
Ryan go through the Cubs system so long without an eye
examination? &QL; 
