<SLUG> BC-FBC-ARKANSAS-SMU-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAZORBACKS EASE THEIR WAY BY MUSTANGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ SMU opened its season against Arkansas in semi-grand
fashion last night, performing before their largest audience in the
Cotton Bowl in 21 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the Mustangs, the vast majority of the 51,019
attending were loudly yelping ``Sooey!'' most of the evening, as
the Razorbacks displayed a variety of awe-inspiring players in the
course of a 26-0 triumph.
</P>
<P>
   Topping the list was the pitch-and-catch combo of quarterback
Clint Stoerner and wide receiver Anthony Lucas, which produced
three touchdowns and needed little assistance. Nevertheless, the
18th-ranked Razorbacks also unveiled the tailback of the future,
incoming freshman Cedric Cobbs, who added a long, swift scoring
sprint.
</P>
<P>
   For the Mustangs, who had already lost four starters, it was a
long, frustrating ordeal. The game required 31/2 to complete, and
for most of that time, SMU _ playing in front of its largest Cotton
Bowl crowd since an engagement with Texas A&AMP;M in 1978 _ was in
distress. The Razorbacks held a 373-175 advantage in total yards
and had two scoring drives that moved a total of 123 yards in 20
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``They played like a top 10 team tonight and I think that's what
they are,'' SMU coach Mike Cavan said. ``That receiver of their's,
Lucas, he's real class. We couldn't do anything offensively, and we
just couldn't seem to do anything together.''
</P>
<P>
   Arkansas coach Houston Nutt said, ``We played well on defense,
and it's always good to win the opener and to win a shutout.
Overall, I think we're a better team than the way we played
tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   The evening's first blow was delivered by Arkansas return man
Fred Talley, who took a reverse handoff and went 37 yards on a punt
return to the SMU 49, where he was knocked out of bounds by his own
blocker, Orlando Green.
</P>
<P>
   Stoerner, 12-of-29 for 239 yards, launched the drive with a
first down by pulling the Mustangs offside with a long count and
finished it with a 28-yard pass to Lucas, who outmaneuvered Tracy
Hart in the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   The pair struck again early in the second period when Stoerner
executed a one-play, 11-second drive with a 70-yard flip to Lucas,
wide open behind two SMU defenders.
</P>
<P>
   The next drive went 53 yards in nine seconds, the time it took
Cobbs to spurt through the right side on a pitch, veer back to the
left past the linebackers, and outrun the secondary. Spelling
starter Chrys Chukwuma, Cobbs was Arkansas' leading rusher with 8
carries for 85 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Stoerner struck again in the third quarter with a 63-yard toss
to Lucas, who was again wide open and finished with 6 catches for
194 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a pretty good start on my goal for the season, which
was to just be Anthony Lucas again,'' said the Razorbacks wide
receiver who set school records last year for reception yardage and
touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Stoerner, who holds the school records for yardage and touchdown
passes, also got off to a good start, but for SMU it was a bitter
night. The Mustangs managed 35 rushing yards on 37 carries, and
quarterback Josh McCown hit only 9-of-25 passes for 72 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Tailback Rodnick Phillips, the top returning rusher in the WAC,
was held to 26 yards on 11 carries. Freshman Kris Briggs led SMU
rushers with 63 yards on 16 carries, all after the game was out of
reach. In their deepest penetration, the Mustangs reached the
Arkansas 30-yard line with eight minutes left, but could go no
further.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
