<SLUG> BC-REDISTRICT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. CHALLENGES ARIZONA'S PLAN FOR REDISTRICTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF BARKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON - Department says Arizona has failed to prove that
its plan for redrawing legislative district boundary lines after
the 2000 census wouldn't discriminate against minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's defense of its redistricting plan for legislative and
congressional seats is ``insufficient,'' the department's Civil
Rights Division said in a July 28 letter to the Arizona Attorney
General's Office that was obtained by ``The Arizona Republic''.
</P>
<P>
   The department gave Arizona two months to try again to show that
the plan wouldn't shortchange minorities by relying on census
figures that the department believes could undercount Native
Americans, Hispanics and other groups.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno has the authority to block the
plan if not satisfied with Arizona's response.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, which is also drawing criticism from national civil
rights groups, was approved by the Legislature and signed April 22
by Gov. Jane Hull.
</P>
<P>
   The plan restricts the sort of census data that may be used to
redraw state maps of legislative and congressional districts to
reflect population shifts during the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Under the state's approach, only numbers from the traditional
Census Bureau head count in 2000 would be employed. Citizens will
receive surveys in the mail, and census workers will be sent on
follow-up visits when there is no response. &QL; 
`SAMPLING' AN ISSUE &QL; 
The Census Bureau had hoped to augment that approach with a
scientific method known as ``statistical sampling,'' which is meant
to uncover the hardest-to-find Americans, particularly minorities
and the poor.
</P>
<P>
   Without sampling, many civil rights advocates believe, minority
groups will be denied an equal voice in government and lose out on
federal aid because the census won't accurately reflect their
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Hull does not believe Arizona's approach is discriminatory.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor wants to use a head count because she believes it
is the best way to make sure you do, in fact, get everybody,'' said
Francie Noyes, Hull's spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Conducted every 10 years, the census is an official snapshot of
America. The numbers are used not only to divvy up the 435 U.S.
House seats according to state populations, but also to allocate
billions of dollars in federal aid for schools, crime prevention,
transportation and other programs.
</P>
<P>
   The Census Bureau estimates that 8.4 million people, many of
them minorities, were missed in the 1990 head count. &QL; 
REPRESENTATION AT STAKE &QL; 
If minorities aren't sufficiently identified in the census,
according to civil rights advocates, then legislative districts may
be drawn in ways that split up certain groups arbitrarily, curbing
their clout in elections. Also, areas with large populations that
lack English-language proficiency may not qualify for voting
materials in their own language if they are not adequately counted.
</P>
<P>
   The bureau said Arizona tied with Montana for the fourth-worst
undercount in the nation, 2.4 percent. The only higher undercounts
were the District of Columbia (3.4 percent), New Mexico (3.1
percent) and California (2.7 percent).
</P>
<P>
   ``We are aware Arizona probably lost money because of an
undercount,'' Noyes said. ``No one prefers that. But she (Hull)
does believe that the most accurate way of getting everybody is to
count everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   In January, the U.S. Supreme Court ruled that the Constitution
prevented sampling from being used for allocating congressional
seats among the 50 states, but that states are free to decide for
themselves which numbers to use for drawing their district maps. &QL; 
4 STATES BAR SAMPLING &QL; 
So far, Arizona is one of just four states to shut the door on
sampling as a tool to redraw district lines. Alaska, Colorado and
Kansas are the others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our fear is that these will not be the only states that will
try to pass these types of measures,'' said Marisa Demeo, regional
counsel for the Mexican American Legal Defense and Educational
Fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concerns that MALDEF has, and many of the organizations
that support sampling, is that the partisan battle that began at
the national level is continuing at the state level now, and it's
at the expense of minorities, the poor, children and other
undercounted populations.''
</P>
<P>
   In Arizona, as well as the nation as a whole, sampling receives
more support from Democrats than Republicans. Sampling tends to
benefit population areas that more often _ although certainly not
always _ vote Democratic. The Clinton administration has been a
strong advocate for sampling.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's non-sampling bill was sponsored by state Rep. Wes
Marsh, a Republican from District 28. Marsh was on duty with the
Arizona Air National Guard and unavailable for comment. &QL; 
MINORITIES OPPOSED &QL; 
The state House voted 37-19 to approve the measure last spring.
Opponents included 10 Democrats who are either Hispanic,
African-American or Native American, according to an analysis by
the state Attorney General's Office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Realistically, we need to make sure not only that people know
about this, but know about the impact it's going to have,'' state
Rep. Ramon Valadez, a Democrat who voted against the bill, said
last week. ``Right now, we're fighting the fight.''
</P>
<P>
   The law needs to be approved by the Justice Department because
it represents a change in voting policy, the department said.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's initial defense of the law, submitted in June, said
the law was written ``without discriminatory intent and will have
no discriminatory effect on members of racial or language minority
groups.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Justice Department, not satisfied, has requested dozens
of documents from Arizona _ including years of election returns on
how minority candidates have fared in the state, and any studies on
``whether, or to what extent, voting in Arizona state legislative
or congressional elections since 1990 has been polarized by race.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona has also been asked to supply ``names, addresses,
telephone numbers, organizational affiliations'' of all minority
groups it consulted before enacting the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Napolitano's office is complying with the
request and will have it completed by the due date of Sept. 24,
spokeswoman Pati Urias said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
