<SLUG> BC-FBC-BAYLOR-BOSTON-COLLEGE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COACH'S BAYLOR DEBUT SAILS WIDE LEFT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHESTNUT HILL, Mass. _ Kyle Atteberry did not look like a man
who had just cost his team a football game.
</P>
<P>
   The senior kicker shanked his extra-point attempt to the left,
dooming the Baylor Bears to a 30-29, overtime loss to Boston
College and spoiling new coach Kevin Steele's first game at the
school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I totally muffed it,'' Atteberry said. ``It's a routine kick.
You should be axed for that in sports.''
</P>
<P>
   Atteberry said it with a smile on his face. He said it calmly.
He said it in a postgame format that some players about to be
fitted with goat's horns might have skipped.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps he was able to take it so well because his coach told
him he still loved him. Perhaps it was because his teammates
encouraged him.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it was because he has football in the right perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm fortunate to have a good relationship with the Lord,'' he
said. ``I look at this as a building block in character
development.''
</P>
<P>
   His missed kick was the most magnifed play.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor tied the game 23-23 on a 73-yard pass play from Jermaine
Alfred to Andra Fuller and Atteberry's extra point with 5:42 left
in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   In overtime, Boston College had the first possession. Running
back Cedric Washington scored on a 1-yard run and John Matich
kicked the extra point. Baylor then scored on a 1-yard run by
Alfred.
</P>
<P>
   While the missed kick cost the Bears a chance to tie, the loss
really wasn't Atteberry's fault. The Bears lost this one because of
a familiar problem.
</P>
<P>
   A defense that ranked 98th against the run last year in a 2-9
season couldn't stop an inexperienced Boston College offense, and
that proved to be the difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to find ways to help them stop the run,'' Steele
said. ``That was the key to the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles returned just three starters on offense. They lost
All-American running back Mike Cloud, who gained 1,726 yards in
'98. His replacement, Washington, was operating behind an
inexperienced offensive line.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't matter. Washington gained 177 yards and scored three
touchdowns. Overall, the Eagles rushed for 350 yards on 59 carries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to figure out how to get the run stopped,'' Steele
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bears had plenty of bright spots.
</P>
<P>
   Alfred, who beat out Odell James to become the starter,
completed 15 of 18 passes for 244 yards and two touchdowns. He
threw passes that were there for his receivers as they were coming
out of their breaks. His long touchdown to Fuller was made with a
blitzing linebacker in his face.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jermaine's a winner, he's a champion,'' Steele said.
``Probably his greatest strength is he's a calm, cool competitor.''
</P>
<P>
   The receiving corps, expected to be a weakness, came through
with some big catches. Fuller had six for 121 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker McKinley Bowie had an 83-yard interception return for
a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Special teams contributed a blocked punt by Samir Al-Amin that
led to a field goal.
</P>
<P>
   The Bears also made some big mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   Atteberry had a punt and an extra-point blocked by players who
came flying through the line. Running back Darrell Bush lost a
fumble with at the Boston College 25 early in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, though, the game came down to the inability to stop
the run.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles rallied from a 16-7 halftime deficit by running for
64 yards in a 68-yard drive for a field goal, and for all but three
yards in a 51-yard drive that gave them a 23-16 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we need to do is basic fundamentals, shedding blocks
better and all-out pursuit to the ball,'' defensive tackle Dwight
Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   If the Bears had done a better job of stopping the run, the game
might never have gone to overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Still, because it did, Atteberry took full responsibility. He
refused to blame a last-second change in holders from Alfred, who
had blurred vision after scoring what appeared to be a game-tying
touchdown on a quarterback sneak, to Ryan Chapdelaine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We practice with both holders, so that shouldn't be a
problem,'' he said. ``It was a great snap, a great hold. I just
missed it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Baylor defenders could have said the same thing about the
Boston College running backs.
Kyle Atteberry, the third-team all-Big 12 punter, is the kicker for
the first time since 1996 when, as a redshirt freshman, he made 35
of 36 PATs. He missed one yesterday and had another blocked. ...
The Bears were flagged for unsportsmanlike conduct when players
left the bench area to celebrate McKinley Bowie's interception
return for a touchdown. ``I told them we've had so little to
celebrate I'll take that one,'' coach Kevin Steele said. ``I won't
take the next one.'' ... Bowie said the touchdown was his first
since his junior year in high school, when he was a quarterback.
... Steele said he was more disappointed for his players than for
himself after losing his first game. ``I wanted this one personally
so bad for these guys,'' he said. ``They needed something good to
happen to them.'' ... Senior defensive tackle Dwight Johnson said
the new coaching staff has brought a new attitude. ``The coaches
were real motivated,'' he said. ``There weren't any negative vibes.
Last year after a loss everybody was down. These coaches were up. I
feel like we're on the right track. We can get it turned around.''
</P>
</TEXT>
