<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROTESTERS LEAVE, KIDS STILL THERE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Finally, it's quiet.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a week now, grown-ups all over town have been
shouting at one another over a girl.
</P>
<P>
   It's not unusual for adults to argue over children, of course.
This particular dis cussion got ugly because it concerned a
14-year-old who was pregnant and wanted to have an abortion.
</P>
<P>
   There were those who wanted to stop her and those who wanted to
let her go. Those who wanted the courts to handle things, and those
who wanted the govern ment to step in. Those who wanted to use
religious arguments to convince the girl not to have an abortion,
and those who tried to buy her off with cash.
</P>
<P>
   There was a candlelight vigil at the state Capitol and another
protest outside the Juvenile Court Center in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   There were promises from the Gover nor's Office to find out how
confidential information about the girl was made pub lic in the
first place, and promises from state legislators to tighten
procedures concerning juveniles and abortions.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Laura Schlessinger spoke about the girl on her nationally
syndicated radio show. Presidential candidate Steve Forbes
condemned the judge involved in the case for granting the girl
permission to leave the state to undergo the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   All the grown-ups involved, however, said again and again,
louder and louder, that their primary concern was the 14-year-old
girl _ a ward of the state since she was 5 _ along with all the
children like her. &QL; 
AFTER THE SPOTLIGHT
</P>
<P>
   But, that was before that the candles were blown out and the TV
cameras started pointing in other directions.
</P>
<P>
   It's peaceful, now.
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, I contacted the state De partment of Economic
Security, which handles adoption and foster care. With all the
people protesting and expressing their desire to help children, I
figured after more than a week there'd be no young sters left to
adopt in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are approximately 150 children right now who are legally
free for adop tion,'' said Lorraine Gordon of DES, ``and no one yet
stepping up to adopt.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the children have some diffi culties, like the
14-year-old everyone's been talking about. It could be they were
abused. Or maybe their mother used drugs. Or, simply, they're no
longer ba bies themselves.
</P>
<P>
   You can look at pictures of some of them.
</P>
<P>
   The DES maintains a Web site _ www.de.state.az.us. Or, you can
call for information at (602) 255-KIDS or 1-877-543-7633.
</P>
<P>
   ``The youngest on the Web site is about 8,'' Gordon said. ``Many
of them are kids with special needs, but we do of fer a lot of
support services and an adop tion subsidy. We do everything we can
to make adoptions work.''
</P>
<P>
   They must.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the 150 Arizona kids ready and waiting for
adoption, officials at DES say there are about 7,000 children in
foster care, with more entering the sys tem every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our foster parents are great,'' Gordon said. ``But we always
need more. In the ideal world, the foster homes would num ber five
times 7,000 so we could make sure we're getting the best possible
match between the children and the families.'' &QL; 
SO, WHERE ARE THEY NOW?
</P>
<P>
   Near as I can tell, Dr. Laura hasn't opened her home to any of
those kids. Neither has Steve Forbes, who probably has many homes.
Nor have Rep. Matt Salmon and the other the fellows who of fered
the 14-year-old scholarship money if she didn't have the abortion.
</P>
<P>
   I contacted Salmon's office last week to ask what he planned to
do with the money he pledged to the girl if she de cided to go
through with the abortion. Would he give it to another child? Or
use it to take in one of the 7,000 in foster homes? I never heard
back.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, I haven't heard much of anything lately from the
once loud-talking grown-ups.
</P>
<P>
   And neither have the kids.
</P>
<P>
   Stories come and go quickly in the news business, and I'd like
to say it's all over but the shouting. But, it turns out shouting
was all there was. &QL; 
 &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at (602) 444-8978 or at
ed.montini &LR; pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-99 0051EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
