<DOCNO> NYT19990905.0028 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-05 00:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1377 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l BC-TV-GOODY-AZR &LR;      09-05 1281
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GOODY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTING CHANCE FOR SUCCESS TAKEN AND ESPN WON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Nothing dusts up a good argument like sports. But no
one can dispute one thing: When they switched on the cameras for
the first time in Bristol, Conn., on Sept. 7, 1979, no one dreamed
that ESPN would change _ for better and for worse _ the face of
sports forever.
</P>
<P>
   The chances seemed especially slim if you were an insomniac
trying to understand the intricacies of Australian Rules Football
in the middle of the night. (If you remember the guys in the weird
white hats and overcoats, you know what I'm talking about.)
</P>
<P>
   The network, which celebrates its 20th anniversary with a
three-hour special Tuesday, got off to an admittedly slow start.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to understand, ESPN, in September of 1979, it was
like Gilligan,'' the ever-loquacious Chris Berman said earlier this
summer. (Berman actually signed on at ESPN about a month after it
began.) ``We were going on a three-hour tour. I mean, we really did
think the ``Minnow'' would be lost.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't. Now there is ESPN; ESPN2; ESPNEWS; ``ESPN: The
Magazin''e; ESPN Zone restaurants; the ESPYs; those funny,
self-deprecating commercials (``Charlie? Charlie? Come out and get
your whippin' ''). Professional football. Professional baseball.
ESPN broadcasts in every continent _ yes, even Antarctica, although
there has been no noticeable increase in dog-sledding coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Other networks have copied ESPN's style of sports coverage.
There's even a network series _ ABC's great ``Sports Night'' _
based on ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad for an outfit that used to televise darts tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ever do a replay on darts?'' Berman asked. `` `Ooh, nice wrist
action. Really good.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Rasmussen, the public-relations director of a hockey team
who started the network, took quite a gamble when he launched ESPN.
As ubiquitous as sports coverage is now, it's hard to remember what
an odd idea an all-sports network was in 1979. (Yes, ESPN
originally stood for Entertainment and Sports Network, but we knew
where the bread was buttered. The name was changed officially to
ESPN Inc. in 1984.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe it _ this is sports all the time,'' Berman
said.
</P>
<P>
   CONFIDENT BUT ALONE
</P>
<P>
   But he was confident that enough sports nuts existed to keep the
network afloat, Gilligan references notwithstanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, I can't predict if cable TV is going to make it in the
'80s, or are we going to have enough money, or are we going to get
sponsors other than Ginsu knives, you know, to pay for a couple of
things,'' he said. ``But I knew there were people out there like
us.''
</P>
<P>
   For a time, he was the only one who knew.
</P>
<P>
   ``In those early days, when you called and said, `Hi, we're
calling from ESPN' and asked for some information and press
credentials, they would say, `Could you spell that?' '' said Bob
Rauscher, ESPN's senior coordinating producer. ``And we told them,
`There's no word. It's just ESPN.' So we've come a long way since
then.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. ESPN is now in 76.2 million homes; ESPN2 is in 65.1
million. But the network's effect can be measured in more than
ratings numbers and advertising dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN's influence is so vast that it's almost impossible to watch
a local sportscast anywhere in the country without seeing the
anchors trying _ and failing, miserably _ to emulate the catchy,
witty delivery of the anchors on ESPN's flagship broadcast,
``Sport''s``''``Center.'' Thus, it's almost impossible to watch a
local sportscast.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of young people want to get to ESPN, and they do an
ESPN-esque sportscast,'' said Mark Curtis, sports anchor for
Channel 12 (KPNX) in Phoenix. ``You see these guys as kind of like
the demigods of sports.''
</P>
<P>
   NOT ANOTHER BERMAN
</P>
<P>
   Thankfully, Curtis, who said he once was offered a 2:30 a.m.
``Sport''s``''``Center'' spot (he declined), avoids aping the ESPN
anchors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Chris Berman is one of the best guys in the country,''
Curtis said. ``He's funny, he's glib. But you know what? I can't be
Chris Berman. And thank God I found that out a long time ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Many sports anchors still search for that knowledge. Here's
hoping they find it, soon. Because Curtis is right _ Berman is
Berman, just as Kenny Mayne is Kenny Mayne and Dan Patrick is Dan
Patrick. Imitation may be the sincerest form of flattery, but it's
not something you want to suffer through when you're looking for a
Diamondbacks score at 1 in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those (anchors) that are `me-first' are real easy to see, and
yes, I do shudder at that,'' Berman said.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick was more diplomatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are guys who do that, but they're young,'' he said.
``I'm 43. They're 25. When I was 25, I would have done the same
thing. So, I try to be fair to what they're doing. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``But they have enthusiasm. That's what I want. I want you
there, I want you enthused. And if you're enthused, and that's the
thing you can take to work every day, I'll take that.''
</P>
<P>
   Enthusiasm, he's got. Patrick was once one of those young
hopefuls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nineteen seventy-nine, I'm sitting in my off-campus housing at
the University of Dayton, and we didn't pay for heat that winter so
we could pay for cable,'' he said. ``And we used to sit on the
couch and we would huddle in blankets and you could actually see
your breath in the living room. And I was watching the first show I
ever saw _ and I remember to this day, (ESPN anchors) Bob Ley and
George Grande _ and I said, that's where I want to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Now it's where he is. Of course, popularity often brings a
price. In Patrick's case, it's the controversy stirred up by his
appearance in Coors commercials. Other popular
``Sport''s``''``Center'' anchors _ Keith Olbermann and Craig
Kilborn _ weathered their own storms before moving on to other
networks.
</P>
<P>
   Another danger of ESPN's popularity: athletes showboating just
so they can make ``Sport''s``''``Center'' highlights.
</P>
<P>
   ``It concerns me,'' Patrick said. ``It concerns me that we value
dunks _ that if you can dunk, you're a great player. And that's not
the way it should be. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``I love freedom of expression. I love spontaneity. But you have
to be careful. If you don't, you're just putting these guys onstage
and saying, `Go ahead and perform for you own benefit.' Then I
think we do a disservice.''
</P>
<P>
   TOP SPOT FOR WOMEN
</P>
<P>
   But the network has provided services, as well _ services more
important than just late-night hockey scores. For instance, ESPN
long has been home to what was once that most rare of sightings:
the woman sportscaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've worked with Robin Roberts, and Suzy Kolber is coming back
from Fox,'' Patrick said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Linda Cohn, I look at her like she's just another co-anchor.
She's knowledgeable. You don't look and say, `Oh, for a girl, she's
good.' You can't do that at ESPN. You can't hide your foibles.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are what you are, because it's live TV, and our women are
great because they know what they're talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   So do their men. That's why ESPN has lasted 20 years. That's why
it'll last at least 20 more.
</P>
<P>
   For a real sports fan, the local knock-offs and the commercial
tie-ins and the players goofing for the cameras are, in the end, an
easy price to pay for a good solid hour of
``Sport''s``''``Center''.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel we have the best news and information show in
sports,'' Berman said. ``I mean, we know. We don't feel, we know.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he's talking about sports. But it's hard to argue. &QL; 
Bill Goodykoontz can be reached at (602) 444-8974 or at
bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
