<HEADLINE>
BIG PLAYS ARE DELIVERED BY UNLIKELY GROUP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ With 12 suspended players, the Bruins were
counting on a slew of inexperienced players to contribute Saturday
night in the season opener against Boise State, and they did not
disappoint.
</P>
<P>
   _Sophomore tight end Bryan Fletcher, who played sparingly and
did not catch a pass last year, set up UCLA's first touchdown with
a spectacular 28-yard diving catch.
</P>
<P>
   !arrow! &UR; !off! &LR; Sophomore safety Julius Williams, a converted
cornerback, returned an interception 53 yards for the game-breaking
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   _Senior safety Joey Strycula, whose primary duty until this
season was as the holder, intercepted a pass that set up the
Bruins' final touchdown of the first half.
</P>
<P>
   _Junior tight end Gabe Crecion, who sat out last season because
of a crowded depth chart, caught a 5-yard touchdown pass from
quarterback Cory Paus to give the Bruins a 24-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   _Freshman cornerback Joe Hunter, who redshirted last season,
prevented a Boise State touchdown by intercepting a pass at the 6.
</P>
<P>
   _Receiver-turned-cornerback Paul Nelson, a freshman, recovered a
fumbled punt early in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   _Senior tight end Randy Hakes, who had one reception last year,
caught a 65-yard touchdown pass from Drew Bennett.
</P>
<P>
   Touching tribute: Before the game, UCLA honored former Boise
State player Paul Reyna, who died last month from injuries suffered
during practice. Reyna's parents, Carolyn Gusman and Art Reyna,
were honorary captains for Boise State.
</P>
<P>
   An old friend: At first glance, UCLA and Boise State might seem
an odd pairing. But the matchup actually makes perfect sense: Boise
State's athletic director, Gene Bleymaier, graduated from UCLA in
1975 and served as an assistant athletic director for five years.
</P>
<P>
   An old friend II: There are no Idahoans on UCLA's roster, but
offensive coordinator Al Borges spent two seasons in that position
at Boise State (1993-94) under the late coach Pokey Allen. In 1994,
Boise State was 13-2, won the Big Sky, and its offense was ranked
19th nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Borges was a finalist for the Broncos' head coaching job in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   Ready to hit: Arizona's poor tackling against Penn State last
week resulted from minimal contact during training camp. Were the
Bruins facing the same fate? They scrimmaged three times in spring
practice, but only once in training camp because the disabled
parking-suspensions created depth problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``You like to think you've done enough,'' coach Bob Toledo said.
``We do individual drills in practice, which is isolated tackling
as opposed to 11-on-11.''
</P>
<P>
   No show: Because of technical difficulties, the postgame
fireworks show was postponed until the Sept. 18 game against Fresno
State. Anyone holding a single-game ticket for Boise State can
redeem it for a general admission ticket on Sept. 18.
</P>
</TEXT>
