<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-05 01:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1384 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s BC-HKN-COYTOES-FRANCIS-Q     09-05 2412
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYTOES-FRANCIS-Q&AMP;A-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANCIS READY FOR CHALLENGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. - Today, former Boston Bruins assistant coach
Bob Francis will slip on his skates and begin coaching the Phoenix
Coyotes when veterans open training camp for the upcoming season at
the Cellular One Ice Den in Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   A few days ago, Francis, the 40-year-old son of former NHL
goalie great, coach and executive Emile Francis, sat down and
discussed at length his background, his philosophies and his many
views about the Valley's NHL team with Republic beat writer Bob
McManaman.
</P>
<P>
   The diminutive, mustachioed rookie head coach, who replaces the
fired Jim Schoenfeld after the Coyotes' second-best regular-season
finish in franchise history, appears to be many things: honest,
forthright, opinionated, provocative, humorous and modest. But more
than anything, perhaps, still unknown in Arizona. Until maybe now:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Question: What thoughts run through your mind as you prepare to
step onto the ice with your team for the first time?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer: Evaluating what the young guys can do and how many
strides they can take to make us a better team. . . . We're going
to take an approach here where we're going to put people in a lot
of different roles. If we're going to ask these guys to help create
more offense, we have to give them the opportunity to play with
different skill. We're not just going to look at a guy like Juha
Ylonen, for instance, and say, ``You've been on the checking line,
we know you can do that.'' I think Juha Ylonen has the skills and
ability to create more offense, so we've got to give him the
opportunity and the skills to show us what he can do. As well as
other guys, like Shane Doan, Tavis Hansen, Daniel Briere.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: So it's safe to assume then you'd have no problem
experimenting with splitting up Keith Tkachuk and Jeremy Roenick on
the team's first line?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: No. I know we'd be a lot more of a difficult team to play
against if we can have a more balanced attack. If it's the top two
lines, if it has to be the top three, then three. The chemistry of
our team? We don't know yet. We don't know if we're going to have
two high-powered scoring lines. If it means we have three, we're
going to take three if we can create it. I just know a team that
has one scoring line is easy to shut down. If you have two, it's a
little bit more difficult. If you have three, you're in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: You've had a considerable amount of time to study your
roster, analyze video and meet with team personnel since coming
aboard. Do you have a pretty good read on what kind of team and
what kind of players you have?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: Tapes can only tell you so much. Tapes have people in
particular positions and you know what the results were. So I think
if you want to try to improve, you have to try something different.
It may work, it may ``not'' work. The Phoenix Coyotes had a pretty
decent year. It didn't work out in the playoffs, but a lot of
things went well for them. They had a good start, then they had
some injuries and things tapered off. You have to ask yourself
``Why?'' Was it injuries? Or was it due to them not playing
conducive as a group?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: Actually, some would say it was due to a crappy power play
that finished next to last in the league.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: Well, yeah, that's an obvious one. But why ``was'' it so
crappy? That's where you have to find the answers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: On paper, is this team a contender if it stays healthy and
can buy into your system right away? Or is it just a good hockey
team that needs an awful lot of work?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: It's a good hockey team that can evolve into a legitimate
contender depending on the growth rate of some people I've already
mentioned. If we can bring along our younger people, help develop
them and get more production and more stock out of them, it's going
to make us a deeper team. Everybody knows what Keith Tkachuk,
Jeremy Roenick, Rick Tocchet, Greg Adams and Dallas Drake are
capable of doing. But we have to improve our second half up front.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: When you were introduced as the Coyotes' fourth coach in
five years, you talked about bringing more creativity and offensive
excitement, pumping more goals into the net. What are your basic
philosophies? What's going to be the Bob Francis coaching system?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: To score more than the opposition. If you ask me what type
of system, how we'd like to play, I can give you the same type of
system that every coach would dream of having. A high offensive
team that has the ability to score and the ability to shut down the
opposition, play tight defensively and the ability to adjust to any
type of game, whether it's physical, whether it's size or speed,
whether it's tight. I think we're open-minded as a coaching staff.
We have an idea of the way we want to play. But I think you have to
be careful. You have to build the system around your players, not
your players around your system.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: But every team has its own identity. Buffalo has its own. So
do Dallas and New Jersey and even Anaheim. What's going to be this
team's identity?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: I have no idea. But what was Buffalo's identity? Was it the
same at the start of the year as it was at the finish? No. Buffalo
played a very tight game, their defense did not even get involved
with the play, offensively, until they got a bunch of injuries up
front and they had to generate some offense. So then they activated
their D, they started pinching, their injured guys came back, and
they had some success by doing it so they remained with it. Then
they had more skill and depth up front and then they were an
effective hockey team. You go through some trials and errors before
you learn your identity and you establish your system.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: Systems change all the time. How about coaching in general?
Has the job changed significantly since you first broke in a decade
ago as a head coach with Salt Lake City in the International Hockey
League?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: Yeah, in a lot of ways. A ``lot'' of ways. I think nowadays,
you have to really communicate with the players. You can't use
threats, No. 1. Obviously with the salaries and the egos and
everything else that goes along with it, everybody is different and
communication is a priority. Coaching is a lot more involved than
it was years ago. You have the use of video, more scouts and staff.
As a result, you're better prepared for the opposition and I think
that's why you see the goals-against down compared to years ago.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: You said communication is key, but isn't ``survival'' really
the toughest aspect of being an NHL head coach these days,
considering the constant firings and hirings?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: Survival's pretty tough, yeah. I think there's a reason why
there isn't a lot of longevity as far as coaches are concerned
being in one place. I think the ability to change, be creative, to
keep the players' attention and respect is probably the biggest
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: Do soaring salaries undermine a coach's ability to run a
tight ship?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: I think if it's done properly, it can be done. But yes, it
is more difficult. You have things to take into consideration that
you aren't even aware of _ bonus structure, incentives _ and that's
something as a coach, I don't want to know. I have the ability to
operate and run the ship the way it should be done in my mind and
not take into consideration somebody's own personal interest.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: What did you learn about running a team from your father?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: More than anything, probably the morality part of it. You
treat players with honesty and respect, you'll get the same in
return. You don't have to make it complicated. When you start
playing head games and mind games, that's when you really start to
lose their respect.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: You earned your spurs on your own, coming up through the
ranks, but did you get a head start over other coaches because of
your dad?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: It certainly isn't my height, I'll tell you. I don't know,
maybe. . . . I learned some good things from him, that it's
imperative your team's in shape, to prepare, that you have to have
a system, how to go about it in practices. We discussed a lot over
the years and maybe subconsciously, it did. But I also learned a
lot from when I was player. I wasn't an elite player. I was small,
I was ugly and I had bad breath. I had to survive. It forced me to
read and compensate in other areas and I think it helped me improve
my hockey sense. I had to work pretty hard to stay and by doing
that, I think it gives you the intangibles to do what's necessary
without having it come naturally.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: What are your goals and expectations with the Coyotes your
first year?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: I think you have to be very careful with goals. I don't want
to discuss the history or the past here. All I'm concerned with is
our future and I think we need to simplify our goals right now and
that's just coming out of training camp strong. We want to set a
precedent. We want to build on it throughout the course of the year
and continue to improve. And if we're doing that, we're going to be
be playing our best at the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: You've mentioned the young players, but how important is it
that your top players carry the weight of the team?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: Well, your top guys have to take stock of the situation and
be accountable for it. I think we have the people here who want to
win. They're willing to cooperate and sacrifice to obtain that
goal. The ideal scenario for a coach, and this may sound
potentially scary, is to have a team that's self-governed, that are
accountable for each other and it's not just the coach. And I think
your top players have to initiate that. They have to set the
example. I sat down in training camp years ago and I was thinking,
``In 10 words or less, how would you identify the ideal team
player?'' And I came up with willingness and sacrifice, personal
risk for team success. Now that may have connotations of physical
play, but when you think about it, it covers the whole spectrum of
team play. Whether it means you get some power play time taken away
from you to help develop this guy, you just have to accept it and
not let it affect your play. If your top players can do that, it
just makes it easier for everyone else to follow.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: Sounds ideal, but can you honestly expect every player to
follow the rules?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: No. Some guys are going to buck the system. All this sounds
fine and dandy in the newspaper, but my job is to try and sell it.
That's why you're either going to be clapping or throwing darts at
me.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: What do think of Keith Tkachuk as a player and a leader?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: I think Keith is obviously one of the top players in the
league. I think the difference what Keith can add to his resume is
being associated with winning. . . . That's when you get the most
exposure. I think the market the team was in and is in now, the
fact we haven't gone a long way, a lot of people in the hockey
world aren't as aware of the skill level of Keith Tkachuk as there
can be. People in the NHL have a ton of respect for him. I think to
go along with that, Keith was put in a difficult role early in his
career by wearing the ``C.'' They give him a lot of responsibility
for a young man and more than most young athletes can handle. But I
think he's matured into the role. I hear from people around him
that he made tremendous strides last year. He's a warrior and his
fellow peers have the utmost respect for him. I think he's ready to
make that next step.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q. Do you have any concerns at all about this club's financial
situation or the fact Owner Richard Burke is reporting annual
losses of about $7 million? Or, about the uncertainty of getting a
new arena?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: No. None whatsoever. It's a deal I tell players a number of
times throughout the year, not about this particular scenario, but
I'm only concerned about things I can control.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: Fine. But if a tight budget prevents you from obtaining a
key player at the trading deadline to help push you over the top,
won't you become a little ticked off?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: That'll be something that has to be addressed at the time, I
suppose.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: The book on you, Coach, is that you've always been
ultra-competitive _ with a temper. Your teams back in the minors,
specifically the Golden Eagles, took on your demeanor. Especially
when you played the old Roadrunners.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: Well, when you play each other 14 to 16 times a year like we
did, you're not going to like each other. I think we even played
doubleheaders, for crying out loud.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: But did you have to tone down your personality and learn to
keep your temper in check?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: I've always felt I had to have a lot of intensity to
compensate for a lack of natural skills. But I did have to learn to
control it when I became a coach. . . . The biggest transition I've
had is maybe having a little more control behind the bench because
a team will react to what the coach does.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: What's your stance on payback and retribution? Derian
Hatcher's hit on Jeremy Roenick late last season, for instance?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: I think it's generally overplayed and created more through
the media than it is through the players themselves. That being
said, we will never get caught unprepared and we won't be naive.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: Tell us one thing about Bob Francis that nobody knows?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: I'm a pretty . . . bad golfer. But no, I'm just a pretty
simple guy. A simple guy who lives by his principles and doesn't
try to cause any trouble.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: The last coach here reportedly had an ultimatum hanging over
his head, that if the team didn't get out of the first round of the
playoffs, he would be history. Would you be bothered if the same
ultimatum was handed down to you, publicly?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: Something that comes with this profession is accountability.
I mean, it's no secret that when I chose to get into this position,
I put myself in a bit of predicament. I'm not naive to the fact
that if we don't produce, I'm not going to last. Why should I be
different than any other coach in professional sports? Yes, I'm
aware the Phoenix Coyotes had 90 points last year. Yes, I'm aware
they had home ice and fourth place in the conference. Yes, I'm
aware they got knocked out in the first round again. Yeah, I'm
aware of all that. Would it bother me? No, because the owner's
basically done that by not saying anything. Until I'm told, it's an
unwritten rule. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
