<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-05 01:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1385 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-HKN-STARS-CAMP-TEX     09-05 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-CAMP-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PARTY'S OVER, WORK BEGINS AGAIN FOR DALLAS STARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   So, what happens when you party like it's 1999?
</P>
<P>
   You get a heck of a hangover, that's what.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars celebrated their New Year a little early, taking home
the Stanley Cup in June and rolling through an endless stream of
silverware sleepovers since. But now it's time to take a
bromo-seltzer and get back to work. With training camp starting in
earnest today in Vail, Colo., the Stars face the challenge of
somehow shaking off the past two champagne-drenched months and
moving forward.
</P>
<P>
   And it won't be easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honestly, it's going to be tough,'' center Mike Modano said.
``After you win the Stanley Cup, it's hard to get excited about
training camp. I mean, it seems like we just finished. But, that's
part of the challenge for us. And once we get back out there, it'll
come back to us pretty quick.''
</P>
<P>
   Stars coach Ken Hitchcock agrees.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, he realizes that defending any championship creates
new ]challenges. With a six-day training camp leading into a
nine-game exhibition schedule leading into an 82-game
regular-season schedule leading into a four-round playoff, the
Stars have plenty of time to get things together before games start
to get serious. Then again, they've had less time to recover from
injuries, less time to condition and less time to mentally rest
than any team in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere in there, a balance must be struck.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you'd be hiding your head in the sand if you didn't
think there would be some debris,'' Hitchcock said. ``The thing is,
you can talk about the past and remember the past and even reflect
on the past to help the future. You just can't perform in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to guard against getting too far ahead of ourselves
trying to win a second Stanley Cup in October, and we have to guard
against falling too far behind and living in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock said he's determined to live in the moment, and
general manager Bob Gainey has given his coach a few tools to help
that cause. Since June, the Stars have traded backup goalie Roman
Turek and let go of five key veterans in Pat Verbeek, Craig Ludwig,
Dave Reid, Tony Hrkac and Brent Severyn. Enough of the roster has
been changed that Hitchcock expects to have a hungry group of
younger players fighting for the vacated jobs. But Gainey also left
intact a roster in which many of the players are in the prime of
their respective careers and a few key veterans are around who can
teach the new kids a thing or two.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, management is trying to build a roster to win in
the long run.
</P>
<P>
   Part of Gainey's plan has been to move in young talent when
young talent is ready, and the Stars have a ton of young talent.
They have drafted and trained top prospects such as Jon Sim, Juha
Lind, Richard Jackman, Pavel Patera, Jamie Wright and Marty Turco.
They have made moves to acquire prospects such as Blake Sloan,
Jamie Pushor, Brad Lukowich, Keith Aldridge and Alan Letang.
</P>
<P>
   In short, the cupboard is full. And that full cupboard creates
competition within the team, especially during training camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``The players can sense that there are openings, that there is a
chance for them to make the team. And that makes a difference,''
Hitchcock said. ``The hunger they have already is showing, and it
should make a big difference for the other players to see that
hunger.''
</P>
<P>
   That said, Hitchcock said he knows he doesn't need to push his
veterans. Particularly not after a grueling playoff run in which
eight of 23 games went into overtime and several players played
hurt. Brett Hull still is rehabilitating a torn medial collateral
ligament in his right knee. Mike Modano's fractured thumb is in
recovery, and Grant Marshall likely will not skate in Vail because
of a torn left groin.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might keep some of our players off the ice, but we can't be
too cautious, especially with the players who have been
rehabbing,'' Hitchcock said. ``Those players have missed a month of
conditioning, and now that month is sitting right in front of us
and we aim to take advantage of it. If they don't have that
conditioning base, they're going to fade and die in the second half
of the season. So this is a pretty crucial time.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, with open roster positions, a new chemistry to be built
in the absence of key veterans and the daunting challenge of
shaking off a Stanley Cup hangover, the bleary-eyed Stars might
consider September one of the more important months of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all know it was a short summer, and that presents a lot of
challenges,'' Hitchcock said. ``But if that's the price you pay for
being good, we're prepared to pay that price every year if we have
to.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
