<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YEAR TWO BEGINS TONIGHT AT TCU AND A LEGION OF DOUBTERS REMAINS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Confident that they have turned the eternal
college football corner, the TCU Horned Frogs launch a season
abounding in high hopes and fanciful dreams tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Stop me if you've read this before.
</P>
<P>
   You know you have. The same opening paragraph, if memory serves,
accompanied TCU season openers in, oh, 1971, 1985, 1992, 1995, and
several other years beginning with ``19'' that have been lost in
the flotsam of three decades of trying.
</P>
<P>
   And what happened? One season the coach died on the sidelines.
Another time, eight star players confessed they were on the take.
</P>
<P>
   If you're a TCU fan, your heart bears the Elmer's Glue lines
from all the times it's been broken. You want to believe ... you
want to be there tonight, when the Frogs host 15th-ranked Arizona
... but ...
</P>
<P>
   ``The first summer I was here, an elderly gentleman pulled me
aside after a speaking engagement,'' TCU athletic director Eric
Hyman said. ``And he told me, `Eric, I like what you're saying, but
you've got to earn your stripes to build any credibility around
here.'
</P>
<P>
   ``The man explained how for so many years, TCU had built people
up, only to let them down. He told me it was going to take a
minimum of three years to build our credibility again.''
</P>
<P>
   Year Two, for what it's worth, begins tonight, and the silent
legion of local TCU subway alums is apparently, indeed, determined
to wait and see what happens.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad. This could easily turn out to be the winningest TCU
team since the great Dan Jenkins carried a student ID. Under Dennis
Franchione, the Frogs should have a stout, gang-tackling defense
and a depth chart bolstered by its best recruiting class since ...
since ....
</P>
<P>
   Sorry. I forgot that you've heard that song before, too.
</P>
<P>
   A crowd of about 31,000 is expected to greet the Frogs when they
kick off at 6:30 p.m. against Arizona. That would leave empty about
one-third of the seats at Amon Carter Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   And with the Fox Sports Net Southwest cameras looking on and the
Conference USA presidents possibly watching, won't that look
special?
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Hyman and his staff seem neither anguished nor
suicidal about the modest opening-night audience. The gospel at TCU
these days is patience. Hyman points to the fact that season-ticket
sales are up 20 percent (to around 9,400) from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, you wonder. Is the TCU bandwagon that scary of a ride?
</P>
<P>
   If you've driven anywhere around Tarrant County, you have to
have seen the ``Power of Purple'' billboards. There have been TCU
commercials on Channel 5 and on area cable. Radio spots have been
running regularly on WBAP and The Ticket. Our own newspaper,
likewise, is about out of purple ink.
</P>
<P>
   As Hyman has learned, coming to a pro-infested sports area like
this, you have to market your product aggressively. The evidence
shows that he has.
</P>
<P>
   So where are you people? The Frogs-Wildcats encounter has the
makings of one of the weekend's marquee matchups. The Cowboys have
the day off. There is no school tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   At TCU, tailgating is legal and encouraged. Frog Alley again
will entertain early arrivals. And new this year is TCU Village,
the marketing department's version of Colonial's corporate tent.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, more than 10,000 empty seats figure to greet the Frogs and
Wildcats tonight. Go figure.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that TCU doesn't have a dowry of other assets to
display for the C-USA school presidents. But you never know. The
new conference, which will vote soon, doesn't need another Tulane,
where last year's 12-0 Greenies regularly played in front of 50,000
empty seats.
</P>
<P>
   Curiously, Frog fans are everywhere in this town, I'm convinced.
Some are even A&AMP;M and Texas grads, living in Fort Worth, who hold
dual allegiances. They will avidly root for TCU, and maybe even buy
tickets ... as long as the Frogs give them a reason to.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, though, winning a bowl game for the first time in 41
years wasn't enough.
</P>
<P>
   TCU opens tonight against a formidable Pac-10 foe, and Frog fans
are scared to death. They know what the ride home could be like.
They have read it all and seen it all. The TCU bandwagon, all too
often, has been like that exploding Pinto.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad. You're missing a Frogs team that deserves the
attention.
</P>
<P>
   They are quick. Talented. Brimming with a bright future.
</P>
<P>
   Oops. I know. You've heard that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-99 0110EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990905.0034 </DOCNO>
