<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-ARIZONA-OUTDOORS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLIDAY WEEKEND NO PARTY FOR LOCAL LAW ENFORCEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARRY BURKHART  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE HAVASU CITY - Saturday was a typical opening to the Labor
Day weekend on Lake Havasu: crowded with young adults and boats,
loud and full of beer. It was hard to tell whether there was more
brew in coolers than water in the lake.
</P>
<P>
   And, naturally, it was hot along the Colorado River, which
passes through Lake Havasu. Why else would anyone want so much
beer?
</P>
<P>
   This community has become known _ especially in California _ as
a place for the young to party during the three big summer
weekends.
</P>
<P>
   The community loves the business, but an army of law enforcement
agents isn't particularly happy about it.
</P>
<P>
   At the Lake Havasu Water Safety Center, known as Contact Point
to locals, two handcuffed 17-year-olds were being checked in. They
had no shoes so they ran on the short asphalt-covered trip from the
boat landing to the holding office. Both had a blood alcohol levels
near the legal intoxication limit. They were being tagged for
drinking as minors, not intoxication.
</P>
<P>
   ``All they could say was that everyone else was doing it, too,''
said one disgusted law enforcement officer. ``Why were we picking
on them? We just don't have enough people to check everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   The water safety center is a vast improvement over the old
barracks of Site Six that was the nerve center for law enforcement
in the early 1990s. It's a modern building that bunks officers and
offers office space to various agencies.
</P>
<P>
   There is another building nearer the water that has space for
the Mohave County Sheriff's Department, which is the lead agency in
enforcement on the Arizona side of the lake.
</P>
<P>
   But beer isn't the only problem here. The crush of boats itself
is a major one. On a major summer holiday, the U.S. Coast Guard
believes that more than 10,000 boats are on the water between
Bullhead City and Parker on the Lower Colorado River, said Don
Lindsay, a division captain for the U.S. Coast Guard Auxiliary.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's designated as one of the most dangerous waterways in the
nation _ a lot because of the partying,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, the auxiliary's enthusiastic and hard-working
volunteers tried to help set up communications among the 16 or so
agencies involved. That includes rescue, law enforcement, fire
fighting and injury treatment. City, county, state and federal
agencies are involved.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona State Parks, the Arizona Game and Fish Department, the
Coast Guard and the Mohave County Sheriff's Department all helped
finance the new buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Two U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service officers were leaving on
patrol late Saturday afternoon. They had worked on Friday evening.
Nothing special. They had arrested a DUI boat operator, and some
kids where were running personal watercraft in the darkness.
</P>
<P>
   With plenty of light left Saturday, several boats had sunk at
Havasu, and many more had gotten into trouble. Remember that old
statement: ``It's a war out there''? It looked like it. Boats were
coming down and across the lake in every direction, and the
personal watercraft operators were trying to jump their wakes. It's
an unbelievable scene of chaos. Then there was a group of
watercraft users riding up and down the lake. It appeared as if the
Hell's Angels had turned from motorcycles to boats.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Randy Johnson (no, he doesn't have long, stringy hair, a
6-10 frame and a wicked fastball) is in charge of search and rescue
coordination for the Mohave County Sheriff's Office.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been very fortunate this summer,'' he said. ``There
hasn't been that much trouble or that many accidents.''
</P>
<P>
   Lindsay believes that's because coordination has been so much
better than in years before.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson doesn't know, but he's still really concerned about
alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we curb that, we can save more lives,'' he said. ``There
are a lot of stressors out there. Water, wind and sun enhance the
effects of alcohol. It can get really rough.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that people seem to have different feelings about cars
and boats when it comes to alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone has a car,'' he said. ``They make their livelihoods
with them. Boating is just a recreation. A drinking boater is just
as dangerous. But we don't have the same laws. That kind of hinders
us. It's more difficult to enforce safety.''
</P>
<P>
   Officers need more help from the Legislature to fight this
growing problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing good is that we're seeing more boaters using
designated drivers.'' Johnson said. ``That helps.'' &QL; 
Barry Burkhart can be reached at 602 444-8454 or at barry.burkhart
(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
