<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-05 01:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1389 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s BC-FBN-FOX-BROWN-AZR &LR;      09-05 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FOX-BROWN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FOX NFL SUNDAY' HOST IS REFEREE ON SET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GINTONIO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It might be just a coincidence, but  &UR; James Brown is pumping iron
and getting down to his fighting weight _ just in time, as he tries
once again to control the opinionated and frequently off-the-wall
trio on ``Fox NFL Sunday''.
</P>
<P>
   Brown continually turns in top-flight work as the show's host.
Although he frequently takes a back seat to  &UR; Terry Bradshaw,  &UR; Howie
Long and  &UR; Chris Collinsworth, he's able to keep the program on an
even keel.
</P>
<P>
   The Fox shows usually had the upper hand against the competition
last season, and Brown was a big reason. He is smooth and
intelligent without coming across as patronizing, arrogant or
all-knowing, sins broadcasters have been committing since Day 1.
</P>
<P>
   Does he ever feel like a referee with the trio he faces every
week?
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely,'' he said. ``But it's a good position to be in.
The philosophy of the show is to dispense education and
information, and people will retain more if it's user-friendly.''
</P>
<P>
   At times, it seems as if Bradshaw, who for years has fostered
the notion that he remains a ``dumb quarterback,'' has had one too
many cups of black coffee without wearing a helmet. It's
entertaining, and it keeps Brown alert.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bradshaw is indeed kind of a class clown,'' the man they call
JB laughed. ``He knows it. My job is to make sure it doesn't go
overboard. You have to understand all the guys to know their
strengths and weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew Terry when he was at CBS, and we hit it off instantly.
I always tease him that I was never going to try to replace his
previous TV `husband,'  &UR; Greg Gumbel.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the dumb quarterback tales, ``nothing could be further
from the truth,'' Brown said. ``Unfortunately, so much emphasis is
placed on being articulate, and if in fact someone is not up to
perceived standards, he's said to be a stupid person or not bright.
Terry, being a country guy and being very proud of it, is as stupid
as a fox.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's hard for Brown not to take a couple of shots at the
old quarterback who led the Steelers to four Super Bowl
championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``He called his own plays, as he is fond of saying, even if he
had only five plays he could call,'' Brown said. ``He says it was
five right and five left, so that's 10.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who begins his sixth year with Fox, has proven his
versatility, from hosting the ``World's Funniest Videos'' and
boxing to moderating a worldwide discussion on PBS involving  &UR; Yanni
and music students. Currently, he is talking with network personnel
about hosting another type of show.
</P>
<P>
   He has come a long way since his days at CBS, when he and
analyst
 &UR; Dan Jiggetts were handed the fourth or fifth game of the day. ``We
used to laugh and say those games went to the 7-Eleven and the
local pub.''
</P>
<P>
   That was 1985, when Brown and his former Harvard classmate,
Jiggetts, were the first all-Black team to work NFL games for a
network.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Ed Goren, the executive producer of Fox Sports, worked with
Brown at CBS, and he made a strong bid to lure him to new
surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we started putting a team together here, there was some
sensitivity about bringing too many CBS people over, and the line
was we weren't going to become CBS Sports West,'' Goren said. ``At
that time, we already had  &UR; Pat Summerall,  &UR; John Madden, Bradshaw.
</P>
<P>
   ``But in the end, I was able to convince people that JB didn't
really have strong ties to CBS in the public mind like Greg Gumbel
did. In a certain way, JB has become the face and voice of Fox
Sports,'' Goren said.
</P>
<P>
   Goren said he thought Brown was underused at CBS.
</P>
<P>
   Brown sensed that, too, and one incident drove that home.
</P>
<P>
   Neither of two breakthrough opportunities presented to him by
CBS came to fruition regarding college basketball, and that's when
he started to question whether he was in the right career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I seriously thought about going back to corporate America, but
thanks to my future wife and brother, I stuck with it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said the desire to go to Harvard was sparked by  &UR; Bill
Bradley, one of his early heroes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He impressed me, along with  &UR; Jimmy McMillen, an All-American
at Columbia,'' he said. ``I felt if I could go to Harvard, an Ivy
League school, I could defuse that myth of a dumb jock. I told my
mom that . . . I could be like Bill Bradley.'' &QL; 
Jim Gintonio covers sports media. He can be reached at (602)
444-8380 or at jim.gintonio(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-99 0117EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
