r s BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-SCHOENFE     09-05 1243
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-SCHOENFELD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAIT TALKS RATED R FOR RANCOROUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   All was quiet in  &UR; John Tait's Tempe neighborhood on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Chiefs General Manager  &UR; Carl Peterson didn't knock on the front
door of the Tait house and make a peace offering.
</P>
<P>
   Chiefs first-year Coach  &UR; Gunther Cunningham didn't call the
Brigham Young offensive tackle a ``jellyfish.''
</P>
<P>
   And a Kansas City TV station finally left the Valley, so that
Tait's dad,  &UR; Alan, could do yard work or go out for pizza without
being followed.
</P>
<P>
   ``John said, `He felt like  &UR; Princess Diana running from the
paparazzi,' '' Alan Tait said.
</P>
<P>
   John Tait's world forever changed Tuesday when he and his
Phoenix-based agents,  &UR; Ethan Lock and  &UR; Vance Malinovic, received
national publicity for walking out of an obscenity-laced meeting
with Peterson in Kansas City. Tait and his agents then flew back to
the Valley, but not before holding a news conference in which they
explained what happened in the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Lock said Peterson ``lunged across the (negotiating) table and
said, `Sit the (expletive) down.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Tait, a devout Mormon, said he then told Peterson, ``That's
it,'' and they left.
</P>
<P>
   Tait's camp maintains Peterson used the ``F word'' 12 times
during the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson has apologized twice for his use of profanity, but that
hasn't helped get the deal done.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides can't even agree on why Tait, a Tempe McClintock
High School graduate, was in the meeting with Peterson.
</P>
<P>
   The Chiefs said Tait was there because his camp insisted on it.
</P>
<P>
   Tait's representatives said the player attended the meeting at
the Chiefs' request.
</P>
<P>
   The sides agree on one thing: Cunningham's comments have done
nothing but make the situation worse.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham made several snide remarks about Tait before
referring to him as a jellyfish because he had missed camp.
Cunningham added that he was ``sure those defensive guys are
drooling to take a smack at (Tait).''
</P>
<P>
   Lock was incensed and called Cunningham a ``foot-shuffling
porter,'' intimating that the coach was nothing more than
Peterson's puppet.
</P>
<P>
   By criticizing the player, Cunningham already has flunked Head
Coaching 101, that coaches stay out of negotiations and never rip
an unsigned player.
</P>
<P>
   ``You haven't heard  &UR; Vince Tobin say one bad thing about  &UR; L.J.
 &UR; Shelton,'' a Tait confidante said Saturday of the Cardinals head
coach and unsigned first-round draft pick. ``I'm beginning to
wonder if this is a marriage that can't be saved.''
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham made things even worse when he said Lock should have
the guts to call him names face to face.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question was: `Would I play John Tait?' and I said, `He
would look like a jellyfish,' and that's obvious,'' Cunningham
said. ``Any normal human being could figure out that you can't sign
a contract four weeks after the preseason and go out and try to
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``For all this to happen is beyond me, and the talk shows (in
Kansas City) are having fun with it. That's how they sell their
advertising. Any human being can take so much of a personal attack,
but if you really want to know, I have a hard time with them.'' &QL; 
Three of a kind &QL; 
Cowboys owner  &UR; Jerry Jones, arrested last week and charged with
fleeing the scene of a traffic stop, isn't the first league owner
to have a brush with the law.
</P>
<P>
   But NFL historians, after exhaustive research, have decided that
Jones' arrest gives the team an unprecedented trifecta: first team
to have a star player (wide receiver  &UR; Michael Irvin), head coach
 &UR; (Barry
 &UR; Switzer) and owner arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin went to trial on drug charges and former Coach Switzer was
charged with possession of a gun at an airport security check. &QL; 
Honeymoon is over &QL; 
Even before the Eagles play a regular season game, fans want
first-year Coach  &UR; Andy Reid to dump starting quarterback  &UR; Doug
Pederson for rookie  &UR; Donovan McNabb, the second pick overall in
April's draft.
</P>
<P>
   Reid said Pederson remains his starter for next Sunday's season
opener against the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to change on that,'' Reid said. ``It's a
subjective decision on my part. I have to have a feel for (when
McNabb is ready).''
</P>
<P>
   Pederson, an off-season free agent acquisition who played for
Reid in Green Bay, failed to lead the Eagles to a touchdown in the
preseason.
</P>
<P>
   McNabb, meanwhile, came off the bench to throw for three
touchdowns Thursday night to lead the Eagles past the Browns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Am I ready?''' McNabb said. ``I'm confident. But there are
still questions I need answered. I'm not exactly where I want to
be.'' &QL; 
Losing streak &QL; 
Giants Coach  &UR; Jim Fassel is not a big fan of the league's new and
improved instant replay.
</P>
<P>
   He challenged four calls in the preseason and lost each,
including two in Friday's game against Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   ``With my luck right now, you might never see another replay out
of me,'' said Fassel, former offensive coordinator of the
Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   Shocking the world &QL; 
Patriots officials apparently saw something in former Arizona State
cornerback  &UR; J'Juan Cherry that no one else in the league did.
</P>
<P>
   They took Cherry, dismissed from this year's ASU team, in the
fourth round of last week's supplemental draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw him work out, I immediately thought, `Free agent,
nothing more than that,' '' said an NFC Central scout. ``I didn't
think he'd get taken by anyone, believe me.'' &QL; 
Stump the band &QL; 
Glendale Cactus High School graduate  &UR; Ryan Christopherson, cut by
the Broncos last week, knows he forever will be part of the answer
to a trivia question: Name the 20 running backs drafted ahead of
All-Pro &UR; Terrell Davis in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Christopherson, formerly of the Cardinals, was the 169th
selection overall, taken in the fifth round, 27 spots ahead of
Davis, a sixth-round pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I want to mention that to my grandkids one day
because they'll ask what happened with me,'' Christopherson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were talking about that the other day, that 20 years from
now, we're going to be looking at T.D. like  &UR; O.J. (Simpson), the
best running back ever. And you're sitting right there in the same
room, so it's amazing. And it's amazing because he's such a
down-to-earth guy with all the things he's accomplished.'' &QL; 
Short shots &QL; 
 &UR; Charlie Garner, the former Scottsdale Community College running
back, appears to have beaten out  &UR; Lawrence Phillips with the 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   ``'' ``Muscle and Fitness Magazine'' lists Colts offensive
tackle  &UR; Tarik Glenn, 6 feet 5, 335 pounds, as having the worst
physique in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   A Delta employee, watching the long-awaited arrival of rookie
defensive end  &UR; Demetrius Underwood, at Fort Lauderdale Airport:
``All I've got to say is I hope he doesn't miss tackles like he
misses flights.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants rode the train to their preseason game in Baltimore,
the first time they have taken a train to a game in 40 years. It
saved them $75,000, which is why they'll take the train to
Washington later this season.
</P>
<P>
   Carolina Panthers Coach  &UR; George Seifert, on why he's considering
keeping four quarterbacks, including former NAU star
 &UR; Jeff Lewis: ``We've got one per quarter. That would foul
(opponents) up. Who knows? Why not be innovative? I mean,  &UR; Knute
Rockne had to start somewhere.'' &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Steve Schoenfeld can
be reached at 444-8334 or by e-mail at steve.schoenfeld(at)pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
