<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-05 01:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1391 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s BC-BBN-DBACKS-WOMACK-AZR     09-05 1727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-WOMACK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMACK STILL ADJUSTING TO OUTFIELD  
 THINGS LOOKING UP FOR D-BACK AFTER EARLY UNCERTAINTIES, INJURY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - If the Diamondbacks are fortunate enough to reach the
playoffs and advance to the World Series, perhaps no player will
appreciate it more than Tony Womack.
</P>
<P>
   He has endured as much or more this season than many players do
in their careers.
</P>
<P>
   First, there was the saga of the trade with the Pittsburgh
Pirates. It was on. It was off. It was on. It was off. His emotions
were caught in the middle. The Pirates were his original and only
organization. He wasn't sure what to think anymore.
</P>
<P>
   When the trade finally went through on Feb. 26, he arrived in
Arizona amid more uncertainty: The Diamondbacks wanted him to move
from second base to the outfield. His wife, Janet, also was
pregnant with their second child.
</P>
<P>
   Then, a little more than a week later, on March 7, Womack was
hit in the right wrist by a pitch from the Chicago White Sox's Jim
Parque and the resulting fracture kept him out until the second
week of the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   Once the injury healed, Womack was inserted into the leadoff
spot in Manager Buck Showalter's batting order and has become a
permanent fixture.
</P>
<P>
   He also has developed into an above-average outfielder, although
his attention has been diverted again of late by stints at
shortstop and second base.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony's been taking ground balls in the infield since spring
training, so it isn't that difficult for him,'' Showalter said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Womack says he would prefer to play one position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked my butt off to be a middle infielder, then I found a
home at second base'' (with the Pirates, with whom he was a
National League All-Star in 1997), Womack said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going to a new position was a tough time for me. My family
prayed for me. I'm thankful my wife is strong, for the things she
said and did for me during the trade and transition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really didn't have a choice in the matter. I didn't ask to
come here. That's not meant to say that I don't want to be here,
it's just that you get traded and you don't have any say in the
matter. It was the first time and it was hard to accept and it took
a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still adjusting. I'm not going to say that I'm there (as
an outfielder). I'm working day in, day out.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest difference in the outfield and infield is the
throws, he says. Outfielders throw more over the top on a
consistent basis, while infielders throw at all sorts of arm
angles. &QL; 
Finders keepers &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Womack, who turns 30 on Sept. 26, said he didn't necessarily
choose to play baseball _ ``it may have chosen me.''
</P>
<P>
   Growing up in Gretna, Va., he was a basketball freak. Played
baseball in high school, too, but basketball was it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, they (colleges) are looking more for 6-foot-6
guards and I'm not quite that tall,'' said the 5-foot-9, 160-pound
Womack. ``You have to be at the right school in the right situation
just to get a tryout.''
</P>
<P>
   So he went to college (Guilford, N.C.) without a scholarship. He
worked at fast-food restaurants and worked for his father, Thomas,
building mobile homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to work for everything I got, school, everything.
Perhaps that's why it meant and means more to me to get where I am
from where I've come,'' Womack said.
</P>
<P>
   The Pirates drafted him his junior year in the seventh round in
1991. He got his share of money, but he wanted it in the contract
that the main part of what he received to go toward his final years
of school. He went on to finish his degree in sports management at
Guilford and later earned his master's in sports management at
North Carolina-Greensboro.
</P>
<P>
   He worked his way through the ranks with the Pirates, playing
parts of the 1993, 1994 and 1996 seasons with the big club. His
first full season was 1997 and he followed that up with another in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks drew a lot of attention for wanting Womack to
switch to the outfield, but the fact is, the Pirates also were
going to move him to the outfield. They had a promising second
baseman in the minor leagues, Warren Morris, who now starts most of
the big club's games at second.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted Tony to play the outfield,'' Pirates Manager Gene
Lamont said. ``I thought we had to be better in the middle
(infield). His agent told us that he didn't want to play the
outfield. Tony had already done everything we had asked, so it was
a tough situation all the way around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy for him that he was able to go to a club that has a
chance to be in a pennant race. He's the best at stealing bases. He
knows when to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Womack renewed acquaintances with the Pirates when the
Diamondbacks played in Pittsburgh a few weeks ago. He still misses
some of his former teammates, but he also had something to prove to
the Pirates' front office. He helped the Diamondbacks win three of
four games. &QL; 
The switch &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dwayne Murphy, the Diamondbacks' outfield instructor who was a
six-time Gold Glove winner, said Womack ``is capable of playing any
position he wants and playing it well.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the move to right field, Murphy said, ``He's turned into
a quality outfielder. He makes it look easy. His speed is always a
plus, but he gets a good jump on the ball. He has good instincts.
You can have all the speed in the world, but if you don't have the
instincts, you end up getting bad angles on the ball. He charges
the ball well and plays the wall well.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I think having Steve Finley out there (in center field)
helps him out a lot. They seem to work pretty well together.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Finley: ``It didn't take long for us to feel comfortable. I
think he trusts the decisions I make and I trust him. He's a great
athlete.'' &QL; 
The speed &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Womack's on-base percentage was .336 entering this weekend, not
as productive as some leadoff men, yet better than he has been in
his career. In his two full seasons with the Pirates, he was .326
and .319.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting on base is what it's all about,'' he said. ``I know I
need to improve, but I think I ``have'' improved.''
</P>
<P>
   He had 46 walks with a month to go in the season, three more
than in 1997. He had 23 doubles, three off his career best, seven
triples, which put him among the National League leaders, and three
home runs, including an inside-the-park grand slam against Houston
in the Astrodome on July 21.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people wonder why I don't bunt more than I do,'' he said.
``I bunt when I feel the time is right, when I feel I have the best
chance to make it. I don't really get caught up in what people
write or say. Unless you're in my shoes, you don't know. You can
make a perfect bunt and still get thrown out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to try to hit the ball over the place, get them
(defenders) off me. That way, they aren't sure what's going to
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   When Womack does reach first, something is almost sure to
happen, and that is a stolen base. He led the league with a
career-high 61 entering Friday's play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't study pitchers on tape that much,'' he said. ``I pick
up things as I go along and I see things I don't forget. Pitchers
change their demeanor, at least they do around me. You try to pick
up something, anything to give you an advantage. But sometimes you
can do too much thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Butterfield, the Diamondbacks' baserunning instructor,
said Womack's speed is a disruptive influence.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not the best baserunner we have, but he's getting better.
He's still a young player in terms of major league experience,''
Butterfield said. ``He gets the big stolen base for you. Some guys
run just to run, but he knows when and when not to do it. He's more
interested in doing it to get in position to score runs.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the most impressive things about Womack, Butterfield
says, is how he works with veteran Jay Bell, the No. 2 hitter in
the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being disruptive on the bases means Jay will get more
fastballs and therefore get a chance to drive in more runs or put
runners in scoring position,'' Butterfield said. ``Jay is
unselfish, having taken extra strikes to allow Tony to try to steal
second and third. This year, Jay is doing the best job of a
two-hole hitter I've seen, and a lot of that is because of Tony.''
</P>
<P>
   Butterfield said that the club times how fast a pitcher releases
the ball on his delivery to the plate.
</P>
<P>
   If it's 1.3-1.4 seconds, the runner has a good chance. If it's
1.1-1.2, the odds decrease considerably. And there are some
rarities below 1.1, like 1.07 or 1.09, but Butterfield said Womack
has stolen on those arms a few times.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's pretty amazing,'' Butterfield said. &QL; 
The man &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many of Womack's Diamondbacks teammates are more outgoing and
boisterous. He prefers the quiet route most of the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I can fit in anywhere, and I fit in here,'' he said.
``I stay to myself a lot, but I'm not afraid to interact. I'm
quiet, but I can joke around and have a good time.''
</P>
<P>
   On the field, he is all business.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad, when he was telling my brother and me about playing
and how to act, always said, `Don't do stupid stuff. Don't
embarrass the family,' '' Womack said. ``I'm human, and I'm not
always going to agree (with a call). But yelling, all that stuff,
looks real bad. For the young people learning the game, that's not
cool. There's nothing cool about that. You try not to cuss, because
that's not going to change the call. I prefer to keep it inside. It
doesn't work that way for everybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always try to stay on an even keel, never get too high or
too low. That way, you have more of a chance to be successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing is, I don't take it home. The trade
and the injury were tough, but I've received great support from my
family. I get everything from my family. They're No. 2, besides the
man upstairs. You need your family.''
</P>
<P>
   Womack's family includes his wife, daughter, Jessica, who turns
4 on Sept. 12, and son Alsander, born in mid-March.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know how hard I've worked to prove to myself I belong
here,'' he said.``It's going to be interesting the rest of the
season for them and the fans here. I want the fans to see what I'm
all about and what the team is all about. We've done well so far.
We just have to keep it going.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
