<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-BOISESTATE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA ROLLS TO VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ From the FBI investigation to the disabled
parking scandal and his son-in-law's successful battle with a brain
tumor, it was a grueling offseason for Bruins coach Bob Toledo. He
was as exhausted when training camp began as he usually is in
November.
</P>
<P>
   But Toledo couldn't have scripted a better start to his fourth
regular season _ with or without 12 suspended players and injured
receiver Danny Farmer.
</P>
<P>
   In the Bruins' 38-7 victory over Boise State on Saturday night
at the Rose Bowl, the kicking game held, the defense was superb,
and the quarterback quagmire lurched toward a resolution as
second-stringer Cory Paus outplayed starter Drew Bennett.
</P>
<P>
   A redshirt freshman from New Lenox, Ill., Paus completed 7 of 9
passes for 78 yards and directed two touchdown drives in the first
half. The second _ a five-yard pass to tight-end Gabe Crecion _
gave the Bruins a 24-0 lead before halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett recovered from a 2-of-9 start and looked sharp in the
second half _ he could start next week's game at Ohio State _ but
it was clearly Paus' night.
</P>
<P>
   Accurate and savvy, his performance was reminiscent of Cade
McNown's uncanny play as a true freshman in 1995. In fact, it was
better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cade was not ready to play,'' Toledo said. ``He made a lot of
mistakes, but he learned and got better. Cory has been here (a
year). He's learned the system. He's done things Cade couldn't do.
In that sense, he's ahead. Whether he finishes ahead remains to be
seen.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA's defense, maligned last season, was equally impressive.
Despite missing five suspended starters, the Bruins held Boise
State to 123 yards in the decisive first half and intercepted
Broncos quarterback Bart Hendricks twice.
</P>
<P>
   Julius Williams' 53-yard interception-return touchdown gave the
Bruins a 17-0 lead, and Joey Strycula's interception on the ensuing
play set up the Paus-to-Crecion touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   In attitude and execution, it was a dramatically different UCLA
defense than the inept version of last year. Of course, Boise State
didn't provide much resistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``UCLA should never be 99th in the nation,'' Toledo said of last
year's defensive ranking. ``There's much less confusion (this
year), and they're better fundamentally. They're playing hard and
confidently. I have a better feeling than I did a year ago.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory negated any effects of the two-game disabled
parking-suspensions. Now, the Bruins can do no worse than split
their first two games _ the same fate most expected with a full
roster.
</P>
<P>
   Following Toledo's pregame strategy, Bennett played three series
before Paus entered with 5:18 left in the first quarter. He
completed his first pass, a screen to tight-end Bryan Fletcher,
then hit Brad Melsby for a first down near midfield. The drive
sputtered a few minutes later, but UCLA's defense forced a punt,
and Paus returned to lead the first touchdown drive of the season.
</P>
<P>
   It began with a screen to tailback DeShaun Foster, who scooted
for 23 yards to Boise State's 45. Six plays later, facing
third-and-12, Paus lofted a delicate pass to the 6-foot-5 Fletcher,
who made a fabulous diving catch at the Broncos' 4.
</P>
<P>
   Two plays later, Foster plowed over linebacker Bryan Johnson for
a 10-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins' defense took command on the following series. On
third-and-6, Hendricks tried to hit his tight end, Dave Stachelski,
who was battling Williams for position near midfield. Before the
ball arrived, Stachelski stumbled, giving Williams an uncontested
interception.
</P>
<P>
   A converted cornerback playing his first game at safety,
Williams looked like a tailback as he raced 53 yards down the right
sideline for a touchdown that gave the Bruins a 17-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Boise State's next play _ i.e., Hendricks' next mistake _ broke
the game open. With Kenyon Coleman charging hard, Hendricks threw a
screen pass to Strycula, giving the Bruins possession at Boise
State's 32.
</P>
<P>
   After three tough runs by Jermaine Lewis, Paus rolled right and
connected with Crecion for a touchdown and a 24-0 lead five minutes
before halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the third quarter, Bennett tossed his first career
touchdown, a 65-yard pass to tight end Randy Hakes.
</P>
</TEXT>
