<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-05 01:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1393 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBC-BASEBALL-REPORT-T     09-05 1488
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BASEBALL-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GM JOBS PROVIDE CHANCE TO RIGHT WRONGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Major League Baseball has a dismal record when it
comes to hiring African-Americans and/or Hispanics as general
managers. There are none of either and there haven't been since Bob
Watson, fed up with George Steinbrenner, resigned from the New York
Yankees in February 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Mets assistant general manager Omar Minaya is aware of this, and
there are some in baseball who think he's the right person to
change it. National League president Leonard Coleman is among those
pushing him for the Milwaukee Brewers opening.
</P>
<P>
   But Minaya, who interviewed with the Los Angeles Dodgers last
year, is also wary of becoming the ``official minority candidate''
of general manager searches, somewhat in the same way Davey Lopes
has been unfairly used in manager situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope this,'' Minaya said. ``I hope that I would be
considered a good baseball man. I hope my association with the
Texas Rangers and the team that is there now, and my association
with the New York Mets winning this year are my credentials ... not
my race.''
</P>
<P>
   The Brewers' job is being watched carefully. Club president
Wendy Selig-Prieb is in a difficult position. Obviously, she wants
to hire the right person for a franchise that is moving into a new
ballpark next year. But her father is Bud Selig, the commissioner
of baseball, who is under pressure to increase the number of
African-Americans and Hispanics in key positions.
</P>
<P>
   Minaya already has interviewed with the Brewers. So has Toronto
Blue Jays assistant Dave Stewart. Reds assistant general manager
Doc Rodgers is another possibility. That's a pretty good pool to
pick from right there, but Selig-Prieb has also interviewed several
white candidates, including White Sox assistant Dan Evans and
former Indians assistant Dan O'Dowd. Former Dodgers general manager
Fred Claire could get an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Minaya said the important thing is for African-Americans and
Hispanics to continue to get opportunities one level below general
manager: scouting director, farm director and assistant general
manager. The more those jobs are filled without regard to race, the
better chance baseball has of correcting a bad situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think baseball has acknowledged they want to do better,''
Minaya said. ``Baseball wants to improve how it goes about the
interview process for jobs that are considered the heads of
departments. There are qualified people in baseball that can do
those jobs and there's been improvement in those hirings the past
couple of years.''
</P>
<P>
   Minaya, who started with the Rangers as an area scout, got his
break in 1994, when general manager Doug Melvin promoted him to
director of professional scouting. The Rangers were the first to
have such a department, and now half the teams in baseball have
split their professional and amateur scouting.
</P>
<P>
   Minaya is known in baseball as the man who signed Sammy Sosa,
almost like Jimmy Stewart's character was known as the Man Who Shot
Liberty Valance. But he also signed Kevin Elster for the Rangers in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   Minaya wants baseball people to take an unbiased look at the
record and the person. If they do that, he said he is confident the
disgraceful past inequalities can be rectified.
</P>
<P>
   SPOTLIGHT on
</P>
<P>
   Henderson providing rare leadership for Mets Rickey Henderson
has been called the greatest leadoff hitter of all-time and there's
little doubt he's the greatest base stealer of all-time. He's also
been called, at various times of his career, an All-Star, most
valuable player, superstar, malingerer, malcontent and royal pain
in the neck.
</P>
<P>
   Now the New York Mets are calling him something else in his 21st
season in the major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Team leader.
</P>
<P>
   Who would have believed it?
</P>
<P>
   ``I might be the sparkplug,'' Henderson said. ``I'm just trying
to create something out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Henderson has always been able to do that when he's healthy. His
career on-base percentage is over .400, he's fifth all-time in runs
scored and he has almost 400 more stolen bases than anybody in
history.
</P>
<P>
   But what impresses the Mets is the way he has conducted himself
in the clubhouse as a mentor to their younger players, especially
right fielder Roger Cedeno.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has been an inspiration,'' Mets manager Bobby Valentine.
``I didn't know what to expect from him, but by observing him
across the field, I didn't expect him to be a positive person on
the team. But he has given us positive leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Henderson still has injury problems. He has missed time this
season because of a sprained ankle and a strained thigh, and
there's still some doubt he'll get the 500 plate appearances needed
to automatically kick in a $2 million option for next season.
</P>
<P>
   But he is hitting .337 after three years of .241, .248 and a
career-low .236 last season.
</P>
<P>
   \Nsubheds:QUICK HITS
</P>
<P>
   Among the Kansas City Royals' September callups was shortstop
Felix Martinez. Martinez was the Royals' Opening Day shortstop in
1998 but was involved in a major brawl with the Anaheim Angels on
June 2 and was sent down the next day. When the Royals recalled him
this week, he had to immediately begin serving a five-day
suspension resulting from the brawl.
</P>
<P>
   The St. Louis Cardinals have made re-signing pitcher Darren
Oliver a priority this off-season. They will also look for a
closer. Rick Croushore, Ricky Bottalico and Juan Acevedo have
flopped in the role.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago Cubs were thrilled to dump Rod Beck on the Red Sox.
He's signed for next season at $3.5 million with a club option for
$4.5 million in 2001. The Red Sox were doing fine with Derek Lowe
as closer, but they wanted Beck's experience down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Seven times this season, the Diamondbacks have been shut out or
held to one run in a game Randy Johnson started. He has a 2.38
earned-run average in those games, with 89 strikeouts in 53
innings. In his other 23 starts, Johnson is 14-2.
</P>
<P>
   Greece, as host country for the 2004 Olympics, is required to
field a team in every sport, including baseball. So they've asked
Orioles owner Peter Angelos for his assistance in developing a
national baseball program. Lesson 1: Hire good people (Johnny
Oates, Pat Gillick, Davey Johnson, Frank Wren) tell them how to do
their jobs, then run them off as quickly as possible.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees insist Darryl Strawberry will not play left field.
They insist that job has been won by Ricky Ledee. So Strawberry
will pinch-hit and spell Chili Davis at designated hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Mets second baseman Edgardo Alfonzo had six hits, including
three home runs, in Monday's 17-1 victory. The next day, he showed
up at the Astrodome for early batting practice.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' infield, including shortstop Rey Ordonez, showed up on
the cover of ``Sports Illustrated'' with the question being raised,
is this the best defensive infield in history? If it is, the Mets
would still like to break it up by trading for Alex Rodriguez next
year.
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies were 6-17 while Curt Schilling was on the disabled
list. The rotation was 3-12 with a 6.35 ERA and the team went from
51/2 games to 151/2 out in the standings. One casualty was Chad
Ogea, who was finally yanked out of the rotation after going 6-12
with a 5.71 earned-run average.
</P>
<P>
   There are two teams that need general managers: Milwaukee and
Colorado. Baseball people say Milwaukee is the much better
position, even though the Rockies sell out every night. There are
many who believe the Rockies will never be able to assemble a
decent pitching staff, mainly because the top free agents will
never want to pitch there.
</P>
<P>
   After Wednesday's game with the Astros, Mets pitcher Orel
Hershiser went over and shook hands with umpire Bob Davidson, one
of 22 whose resignation was accepted. Said Hershiser: ``He was the
only guy on the field whose last day of work it was. That's a
lonely place to be. Players and umpires are never going to see
eye-to-eye. All you can do is give your best and I thought Bob was
one of those who always did that.''
</P>
<P>
   When Atlanta's Bret Boone and Cincinnati's Aaron Boone homered
Wednesday, it marked the first time since Sept. 14, 1974, at Tiger
Stadium (Graig Nettles of the Yankees, Jim Nettles of the Tigers)
that brothers from opposing teams homered in the same day.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Jays starter Joey Hamilton, who is 7-8 with a 6.52 ERA,
won't pitch again this season and will probably undergo shoulder
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Astros second baseman Craig Biggio on the Cincinnati Reds:
``They have a good team. They're strong up the middle, they do
little things right, they have good pitching and an outstanding
bullpen. I don't think anybody is surprised by what they've done.
It's like Barry Larkin said. Nobody is doing more than what they
expected. No one is having a career year. Everybody is just doing
their jobs.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
