<HEADLINE>
CARDINALS FACE A DAUNTING FIRST 4 WEEKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Check back in a month.
</P>
<P>
   It won't be the Cardinals' won-lost record that reveals whether
they are for real. The measuring stick will be how their young
players, coming off a taste of playoff success, handle the
aftermath of an opening four-game stretch that has the potential to
rock their world.
</P>
<P>
   That's the key to their season.
</P>
<P>
   Take inventory of the splints and soft casts. The holdouts. Walk
past the lockers that have names above them but no corresponding
bodies dressing in front of them. Look at the nasty schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is hard to put a team together when you've got some key
parts missing,'' Coach Vince Tobin said.
</P>
<P>
   Throw in the league's fourth-toughest schedule and it would be
easy to believe that the Cardinals will not approach their
breakthrough accom plishments of last season.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals will be fortunate to have more than one win coming
out of September after visiting Miami and playing San Francisco at
home. Then they open October by visiting Dallas, the team they
nearly shut out in the first round of the playoffs. The soft spot
is the opener against Philadelphia. But that's on the road.
</P>
<P>
   The players can't let go mentally.
</P>
<P>
   Being in the hole early is not new. The league routinely
front-loads Cardinals' schedules with road games to avoid the
desert heat. The team is accustomed to playing catch up, and almost
always has played it badly.
</P>
<P>
   The difference is this team is better equipped to handle it. The
Cardinals now know the feeling of winning (9-7), of having pulled
out the close ones (NFL-record seven wins by three points or
fewer), and of having nearly shut out a bigtime franchise in the
playoffs (20-7 at Dallas). They have moved past considerable
negativism.
</P>
<P>
   What they aren't accustomed to is playing from the lead, of
performing when expectations are high. This season will be a new
experience.
</P>
<P>
   And it more than likely will begin on a down note, testing their
developing maturity.
</P>
<P>
   Their potentially high-scoring offense will not be in rhythm.
Quarterback Jake Plummer and most of the line are injured, and
first-round pick L.J. Shelton and receiver Rob Moore are unsigned.
</P>
<P>
   The run-stopping ability of the defense will be in question
because tackles Eric Swann (knee surgery) and Mark Smith (unsigned)
aren't on the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Several locker room leaders _ Jamir Miller, Lomas Brown, Larry
Centers _ have left as free agents.
</P>
<P>
   If they can weather the storm, watch out.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals don't have to win the division, although they
could win the weak NFC East even with a slow start. They need only
make the playoff field. By postseason, they should be at full
strength and confident.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got some credibility last year, although we really didn't
until we beat Dallas,'' Plummer said. ``If we had just gotten to
the playoffs and lost, I'm sure people would have said we were 9-7
against a weak schedule and we were not that good. But we beat
Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we've got the (New York) Jets, Miami, San Francisco,
Atlanta, Green Bay _ quality playoff teams from last year. If we
beat them and go 9-7, we will have accomplished something in
everyone's eyes. Then no one can doubt that we have a good team.''
</P>
<P>
   The players believe. For every Lomas Brown or Larry Centers that
have departed there is a Plummer or an Adrian Murrell stepping
forward to lead. For every departed Jamir Miller there is an Andre
Wadsworth to encourage the defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can see a big change from when I got here last year in the
way we practice, in the attitude of everyone in here,'' Wadsworth
said. ``Once you have tasted what you want, then you work even
harder to get more of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Center Aaron Graham took it a step further.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're starting to learn how to practice in a way that is
required of a playoff team,'' he said. ``We're not out there
wasting time.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem has been transferring it from the practice field to
the game field.
</P>
<P>
   That Plummer comes from Arizona State, Graham from Nebraska and
Wadsworth from Florida State is typical of the young Cardinals.
They have drafted players from large winning college programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a correlation,'' Wadsworth said. ``If you don't know
how to lose, that's a big key right there.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Graham: ``We expect to make the playoffs. The thing in the
back of everyone's mind now is what we're going to do when we get
there. We don't take getting there for granted, but now we know how
to get there, we know what is expected of us, and I think we'll be
there. Then when we get that opportunity, it's what we do with it
that matters.''
</P>
<P>
   That starts with Plummer, an instinctive playmaker and leader
who in his first 26 pro appearances has taken the Cardinals to nine
comeback wins. Plummer must improve his tendency to start slowly in
games and make the killer turnover.
</P>
<P>
   He has to show that his technical skills equal his scrambling
ability.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to get Jake to an even broader level of perfection,''
said Marc Trestman, the Cardinals' offensive coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first time in seven seasons that Plummer will be
coached by the same coordinator in sucessive seasons, and Trestman
said that is apparent already.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're probably 70 percent better than we were a year ago at
this time,'' Trestman said. ``We understand each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Plummer didn't fully understand the nuances of
Trestman's West Coast offense. During the bye week, it was
simplified. The result: After averaging 15.6 points and 246.1 yards
in the first eight games, the Cardinals improved to 25.0 points and
392.5 yards in the final eight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a whole different ballgame out here this year,'' Plummer
said. ``I know the plays, so I can concentrate on reading the
defenses. . . . That will help our offense keep moving the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   So would another 1,000-yard rushing year from Murrell, whose
cutback skills are well suited to a developing line that can create
a crack but won't always blow a foe off the ball.
</P>
<P>
   So would another NFC-leading receiving year from Frank Sanders,
with help from rookie wideout David Boston and Moore _ if the
team's designated frachise player signs.
</P>
<P>
   Wadsworth, a holdout through preseason last year, had four
sacks. He should more than double that, according to Tobin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Andre is going have a breakout year,'' Tobin said.
</P>
<P>
   So should end Simeon Rice, who is in the final year of his
contract.
</P>
<P>
   What happens at the defensive tackles will be critical. Swann
continues to work to rehabilitate his knee. There has been little
progress in Smith's contract talks. The linebacking corps is
average at best.
</P>
<P>
   The secondary has been upgraded with Corey Chavous, Kwamie
Lassiter, Tommy Bennett and Tom Knight improving to complement
Aeneas Williams. It now is a strength of the team.
</P>
<P>
   The return game should be strong with Boston running back punts
and Michael Pittman and Mario Bates splitting kickoffs. Either
kicker _ Joe Nedney or Chris Jacke _ can win. Punter Scott Player
is getting steadily better.
</P>
<P>
   It's a team that by season's end should be a threat, if it
doesn't let the season get away from it early.
</P>
<P>
   ``There certainly is a lot more light at the end of the tunnel
going into this year than a year ago, when we were coming off a
4-12 season,'' Tobin said. ``This year we have accomplished
something and the players know they've accomplished something. They
realize they can play at the level they need to play at. That's a
big step for them. That's something you can talk about, but you
have to experience it to truly believe it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
