</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BRONCOS-PREVIEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRIESE WILL FIGHT GHOST, PRESSURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER - Green Bay's Bart Starr couldn't do it. Didn't even come
close.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh's Terry Bradshaw also failed to three-peat. So did
Joe Montana with San Francisco, Troy Aikman with Dallas and Bob
Griese with Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Griese, Bob's son, wasn't even born when the Dolphins,
trying to win three consecutive Super Bowls, were knocked out in
the first round of the 1974 playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   But now it's up to Brian Griese to try to take the Denver
Broncos, back-to-back Super Bowl champions, where no other NFL team
has been. Sure, Griese, 24, led a 1997 Michigan team to a share of
its first national championship in 49 years. But he's also the same
guy who has thrown three passes _ one was intercepted _ for a minus
2 yards in the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I didn't think Brian could take us all the way, I wouldn't
have made this decision,'' Broncos Coach Mike Shanahan said last
Monday in promoting Griese to be a starter ahead of veteran Bubby
Brister.
</P>
<P>
   But when the Broncos open the regular season Sept. 13 on
``Monday Night'' ``Football,'' Griese won't be lining up across the
line of scrimmage from Indiana. He'll be playing his father's old
team, the Dolphins, considered by many an AFC title contender.
</P>
<P>
   Dolphins Coach Jimmy Johnson, a defensive specialist, would like
nothing better than to knock Griese out of his first start.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been here one year, so I can't pretend to know everything
that's going on,'' Griese said. ``But I have confidence in this
team and the people that run this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Griese is confident because he knows he has All-Pro running back
Terrell Davis playing alongside him. Davis will try to become the
first running back in league history to rush for 2,000 yards in
back-to-back seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't measure myself in terms of numbers,'' Davis said. ``I
never have. Numbers don't dictate to me whether I've had a good
season or not.''
</P>
<P>
   How far the Broncos go this season could be up to Griese, who
not only will be the first quarterback in NFL history to make his
starting debut with the defending Super Bowl champions, but it will
be on the same night future Hall of Famer John Elway is inducted
into the Broncos' Ring of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, there is a five-year waiting period for Broncos players
to get that honor. A Broncos official said that with Elway, a Rocky
Mountain majesty who also will have his number retired, there was a
``five-second'' waiting period.
</P>
<P>
   The ghost of Elway can be haunting. Brister found that out in
the three months it appeared he was the heir apparent. The same
Denver newspapers that used to report what Elway gave
trick-or-treaters on Halloween thought football-crazed, inquiring
minds would want to know that Brister got his daughter, Madeline, a
Barbie doll and clothes for her third birthday.
</P>
<P>
   ``After John retired (in May), things changed for me,'' Brister
said. ``My wife has started going to the grocery store a little bit
more. I put the ball cap on when I go. It's not that bad. It's not
like John. I feel bad for John. He can't go anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   That hasn't changed for Elway, even in retirement. It was big
news when Elway took his family last month to the motorcycle rally
in Sturgis, S.D. It was even bigger news when Elway purchased a 50
percent share of a Web site and an 8 percent share of a financial
services company.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pressure to replace a guy like John Elway is tremendous,''
Shanahan said. ``I think the scrutiny by the media is
overwhelming.''
</P>
<P>
   Griese is about to find out what it's like to be Elway's
successor.
</P>
<P>
   Before Shanahan made his quarterback move, promoting Griese,
Denver radio talk shows were split on who should be the starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``(This decision) will be popular as long as Brian's winning
games,'' Broncos owner Pat Bowlen said. ``As soon as he loses a
few, he'll have the same amount of pressure on him that Bubby
did.'' &QL; 
Great supporting cast
</P>
<P>
   Nobody feels worse for Brister than Broncos linebacker Bill
Romanowski, a former teammate of Brister's with the Philadelphia
Eagles who talked Shanahan into signing him two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But Romanowski also thinks the Broncos have enough talent to be
successful regardless of the quarterback. They are one of the
deepest teams in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Brister was 4-0 as Elway's replacement a year ago, mainly
because of Davis, who last season became the fourth player in
league history to rush for more than 2,000 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel the burden,'' Davis said. ``When I was in games
with Bubby last year, I didn't feel like I had to go out and carry
the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Also last season, the Broncos set team records for touchdowns
(62), touchdown passes (32), points (501), rushing yardage (2,468)
and total offense (6,092).
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a great football team,'' Romanowski said. ``We have a
much-improved football team. Look at our depth. Look at our
cornerback situation, now that we've added Dale Carter (in free
agency). I don't know if anybody can compare to our secondary.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we used to play (Carter) in Kansas City, people usually
didn't throw his way. Now, we know why.''
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos' defense was already good before Carter was added.
</P>
<P>
   The team's defense allowed 65 points in three playoff games in
1997. Last season, the defense allowed only 32 points in their
three playoff wins.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who know football know the defense was responsible for
us getting to the playoffs and winning it,'' Romanowski said.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos also have one of the NFL's best offensive minds in
Shanahan.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a step ahead of everyone else in the league,'' tight end
Shannon Sharpe said last month before deciding to no longer talk to
the media. ``We can survive without John (Elway) or me or maybe
even Terrell. But we might not get by without him.''
</P>
<P>
   So if the Broncos have so much confidence they can win it all in
the post-Elway era, how come they still haven't field his official
retirement papers with the NFL office?
</P>
<P>
   Imagine the magnitude of the story if Elway makes a comeback
this season to help the Broncos try to three-peat.
</P>
<P>
   Don't count on it. He never once showed up at training camp.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos are confident they can get to Super Bowl XXXIV in
Atlanta without them, which is why they served Southern cuisine at
camp, dishes they might eat the week of the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Griese, raised in south Florida, knows all about Cajun food. &QL; 
The Denver Post and Rocky Mountain News contributed to this story. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-99 0126EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990905.0043 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-05 01:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1397 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-CSUN-LADN     09-05 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CSUN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHRIDGE WINS AFTER SLOW START
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRAHAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It was an uneven performance, sometimes mediocre
and sometimes crisp. Cal State Northridge football surely can't go
on this way.
</P>
<P>
   Cut this team some slack, though.
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors, outplayed in the first 30 minutes of their season
opener against an unknown opponent, slowly showed their superiority
and beat Western Oregon 38-19 on Saturday afternoon at North Campus
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The victory might not have been impressive enough for most of
the 3,142 fans who entered the gate, who knew the Matadors were one
minute away from winning the Big Sky Conference championship last
year.
</P>
<P>
   After enduring a crazy summer that saw Ron Ponciano fired as
head coach, offensive coordinator Rob Phenice forced to resign and
an internal report released detailing the program's numerous NCAA
violations, just playing the game was enough.
</P>
<P>
   That showed in a first half in which the Matadors sputtered and
made mistake after mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the things in the summer, people can say they didn't think
about (them) and they had no effect,'' senior running back Jaumal
Bradley said, ``but it was in the back of my mind. We have a whole
new look. I know a lot of people who watched us play (Saturday)
noticed that we seemed a little different in the things we do. Our
attitude ... we came out a little lax and tentative.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were just not mentally focused.''
</P>
<P>
   CSUN (1-0) didn't seem bothered when Western Oregon scored the
first touchdown of the game _ a 26-yard pass from quarterback Erik
Davis to Derrick Miles with three minutes left in the first
quarter. The players didn't look worried when the Division II
Wolves (0-1) took a 13-3 lead on a 51-yard scoring pass from Davis
to Miles six minutes before halftime.
</P>
<P>
   The Division I-AA Matadors hadn't lost to a Division II team in
four years. The idea, however, crept into CSUN interim head coach
Jeff Kearin's mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thought? How about complete panic and fear?'' Kearin quipped
after the game. ``But I believe in these kids. (At halftime) I saw
no fear in their eyes. There was no doubt in their eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Arnold, who became the school's all-time leading receiver
in the first half, set the tone in opening the second with a
58-yard kickoff return.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN wore down the Wolves, not only with quick passes but a
newfound running game. The Matadors, who were last in the Big Sky
in rushing yards last year, averaging 84 per game, had 249 on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley had 90 yards and two touchdowns, and redshirt freshman
Alan Taylor had a team-leading 94 on only 10 carries.
</P>
<P>
   ``A big improvement,'' Bradley said. ``(Now) we give an imposing
threat to a lot of people.''
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors might look a little tougher, choosing to run the
ball in short-yardage situations where they once would have thrown.
But CSUN isn't Michigan or Ohio State.
</P>
<P>
   Sophomore quarterback Marcus Brady had 45 attempts, completing
28 for 321 yards and two touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Senior wide receiver Aaron Arnold had 12 catches for 138 yards
and set the school record for receptions in a career late in the
second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   After a slow start, Brady completed passes to eight different
receivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to make things happen,'' Brady said. ``I just had
to get into the flow of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   So did the CSUN secondary, which was thrown in the first quarter
when starting safety Hassan Abdul-Malik re-injured his right
hamstring and left the game. Davis's three touchdown passes were
from 26, 51 and 41 yards, and they all came when a receiver was
open in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   ``They weren't really fooling us,'' said safety Rahman Sparks,
``but there were a couple mistakes I made in coverage. (They) were
just blown assignments.''
</P>
<P>
   Sparks intercepted Davis with 11 minutes left in the game. CSUN
cornerback Karalus Doyle picked off Davis on Western Oregon's next
possession, as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got us a couple times up the middle,'' Kearin said. ``We
were a little bit hurt when Hassan went out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-99 0126EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
