<HEADER>
A1399 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-PRO-FOOTBALL-REPO     09-05 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PRO-FOOTBALL-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRONCOS FIGHTING OFF-FIELD DISTRACTIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the Cowboys tried to keep their dynasty afloat in the
mid-1990s, they fought through myriad off-field distractions.
</P>
<P>
   The Denver Broncos want to join the Cowboys as the only
three-time Super Bowl winners of the decade. And if the past few
weeks count for anything, the Broncos have the Cowboys' mid-1990s
act down pat.
</P>
<P>
   Retirement, free-agent defections, injuries, a coaching change,
and too many run-ins with the police ate away at a Cowboys
franchise that won an unprecedented three Super Bowls in four
years.
</P>
<P>
   Retirement, free-agent defections, a quarterback controversy,
and now a drug charge threaten to eat away at a Broncos franchise
attempting to win an unprecedented three consecutive Super Bowl
titles.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos chances of making history in 1999 have been slowly
unraveling since they won Super Bowl XXXIII. Quarterback John Elway
retired. Starting defensive backs Steve Atwater and Darrien Gordon
were not re-signed and accepted free-agent contracts from other
teams.
</P>
<P>
   Broncos coach Mike Shanahan all but promised Bubby Brister the
job Elway had for 16 years. But Brister played so poorly during the
preseason that Shanahan last week replaced him with second-year
quarterback Brian Griese. Brister was so upset that he stormed out
of camp and said he would have left the team if the only person who
mattered was Shanahan.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, reports surfaced that starting linebacker Bill
Romanowski faces drug charges on account that he used fraud to get
access to the drug Phenetermine, which is usually prescribed for
severely obese people, but also acts as a stimulant to the central
nervous system.
</P>
<P>
   Yet as the Broncos walked out of Texas Stadium last week, beaten
handily by the Cowboys, wide receiver Rod Smith said, ``Don't worry
about us, man, we're going to be OK _ I can promise you that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos even have the mid-1990s Cowboys denial down pat,
too.
</P>
<P>
   Shanahan's bunch might get over the free-agent defections, but
you don't lose one of the greatest quarterbacks of all-time and not
be affected. The Broncos have looked awful this summer, and Brister
was a big part of the problem, throwing over or under his receiver
or to the wrong jersey altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Shanahan was smart to name Griese the starter. He looks so much
more comfortable in the pocket than Brister, and he made better
decisions.But sooner or later, opposing teams will have figured out
how to play Griese, and the second-year player will certainly
struggle. Then what? Shanahan has said he will play Brister. But
will Brister be willing to play for a coach whom he publicly said
``misled,'' him into believing the starting job was his?
</P>
<P>
   Brister met privately with Shanahan four days after his war of
words with the coach and said there will not be a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him that I was just mad at him,'' Brister said. ``But
he is still the boss. ... I feel like I earned the right to start,
but that's not the case right now. I have to swallow my pride and
move on and just be bigger than the situation and be ready when
they need me.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as Romanowski is concerned, one of attorneys, Jeffrey
Springer, says his client is not guilty. But until the matter is
settled, the Broncos and Romanowski will have to answer questions
from a media with the right to know. That can take some of the edge
off of your mental preparation for games.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   SPOTLIGHT: Packers coach Ray Rhodes
Rhodes `real fortunate' to land in Green Bay
</P>
<P>
   Like a homeless person who wins the lottery, Ray Rhodes is a new
man in Green Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Nine months ago, Rhodes was one of eight NFL head coaches out of
a job, having been fired from Philadelphia after four seasons in
which his club went from a 10-6 playoff team in 1995 to 3-13 last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Today, he is head coach of a Green Bay Packers team that has
been to two of the past three Super Bowls, and is one of the NFC
favorites to reach Super Bowl XXXIV in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been real fortunate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After Mike Holmgren left Green Bay to take the head
coach//general manager job in Seattle, the first thing Packers
general manager Ron Wolf did was call Rhodes, who had been the
Packers' defensive coordinator in 1992-93. Despite Rhodes' 29-34-1
record in Philadelphia, Wolf said Rhodes, ``was my first choice,
the logical guy to hire.''
</P>
<P>
   Rhodes led the Eagles to the playoffs in his first two years
there, but ownership's refusal to be a big player in free agency
led to an evaporation in talent. And after the club posted its
worst record in 30 years, Rhodes got the ax. But he refuses to
point fingers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They \REagles ownership\S gave me my 11, and the other team
had its 11 out there and a lot of times, their 11 beat my 11,''
Rhodes said after a practice last month. ``That's on me. I'm going
to leave it at that.''
</P>
<P>
   Rhodes' laid back style has been well-received by Packers
players whose careers began under the fiery approach of Holmgren.
</P>
<P>
   ``He rarely yells at you and that's important when you are at
practice in front of a lot of people, that makes you feel like a
man, like you'd run through a wall for him,'' defensive tackle
Santana Dotson said. ``But I've told the young guys, just because
coach is nice, he won't be too happy with you come Sunday and you
are not doing what you are supposed to do.''
</P>
<P>
   \Nsubheds:QUICK HITS \Nsubheds:Chargers DB on thin ice San Diego
Chargers safety Rodney Harrison is on thin ice with the NFL.
Harrison, who was fined $15,000 Wednesday for twice using his
helmet as a weapon to hit St. Louis Rams wide receiver Isaac Bruce
in a preseason game on Friday, was told by Gene Washington, the
NFL's behavior policeman, that one more illegal hit could mean
suspension.
</P>
<P>
   The 26-year-old Pro Bowl strong safety was fined $10,000 in 1997
for an illegal hit on Kansas City wide receiver Andre Rison and
$10,000 for a hit on San Francisco 49ers wide receiver and current
CBS analyst Brent Jones, which was later appealed and rescinded. He
was also fined $5,000 for a forearm to the face of Carolina wide
receiver Michael Bates.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been fined for unnecessary roughness, for hitting players
in the head and neck with his forearm and the last two were for
unnecessary roughness and impermissible use of the helmet,''
Washington said. ``The fines don't seem to be changing his
behavior.''
</P>
</TEXT>
