<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-BREAKDOWN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDICINE BALL TO BOWLING BALL  
 A LIGHT-HEARTED LOOK AT CARDS' DEPTH CHART 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - There are several ways to analyze a two-deep
roster.
</P>
<P>
   One is with statistics, which often are boring and begin to read
like some kind of mathematical computer printout, which only those
who truly know their icons from their bytes own the patience to
slog through.
</P>
<P>
   It can be presented straight! ZZZZzzzzzzzzzz.
</P>
<P>
   Another way is to present it through Cardinals defensive end
Simeon Rice, who has developed his own language, ``Simeon Speak,''
which only he and his closest friends seemingly understand.
</P>
<P>
   However, in our never-ending desire to serve the masses, the
option here is merely to present it in a slightly off-the-wall
manner: &QL; 
Offense &QL; 
 &UR; Wide receiver: Incompatibility could hurt here. The job is Rob
Moore's, but unless his income is increased soon, the Cardinals
won't find him ``pattable.'' Top draft pick David Boston backs him
up, but he'll also be the third receiver and deep threat when the
Cardinals go to three wideouts.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Left tackle: Coaches often punish mental mistakes by ordering
offenders to run three laps around Anthony Clement, 6 feet 8, 325
pounds. Opposing players have found it hard to get around him.
All-purpose Matt Joyce also will play here if Clement's balky back
acts up. Say, has anyone heard from or seen rookie L.J. Shelton?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Left guard: He might look like a giant medicine ball, but Chris
Dishman proved he actually does have joints when he missed the last
three weeks of camp after elbow surgery. Joyce will play here when
Dishman doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Center: Aaron Graham, Dishman's teammate at Nebraska, has
beefed up to 301 pounds and now has the weight to go along with his
cerebral approach to the game. Veteran Mike Devlin provides
dependable backup.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Right guard: Lester Holmes is the man here, as soon as he
recovers from injuries he received in the one-car rollover with
teammates Ernest Dye and Carl Simpson. Former Arizona Wildcat Yusuf
Scott will be the listed backup, but Joyce, whose legs could be
worn to stubs by the season's end, will start if Holmes isn't
ready.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Right tackle: James Dexter was Mr. Reliable last year and Jon
Clark is his listed backup. But if Dexter goes down, Joyce will
likely fill in. Do you get the feeling that maybe Joyce is
underpaid?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Wide receiver: Frank Sanders has 285 career catches for 3,858
yards and 13 touchdowns. He came up big in the playoff drive last
year and has come up even bigger as a role model to younger
players. Backups here could be either Andy McCullough or Tony
Hamler . . . or someone the waiver wire offers up.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Quarterback: Jake Plummer, the cereal mogul, is this team's
heart and soul. He is somewhat weak at thumb, though. Dave Brown
will be the man if Plummer goes down, which would be your basic
disaster. No. 3 Chris Greisen will have people asking, ``Stoney
who?'' OK, so they were already asking that.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Running back: Adrian Murrell was the sixth NFL player in
history to rush for 1,000 yard for different teams in successive
years. He'll be utilized more as a receiver this year, too. Mario
Bates will be the short-yardage man, with the walking muscle called
Michael Pittman used as a third-down back to replace Larry Centers.
Make it in place of Centers, who's tough to replace.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Fullback: If Dishman is a medicine ball, then rookie
fourth-round pick Joel Makovicka is a bowling ball with arms.
That's what Dish, who obviously doesn't have a mirror, calls him.
His backup will be either Rod Brown or rookie Dennis McKinley,
neither of whom has Makovicka's grasp of the offense.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Place kicking: Nedney Jacke, or is it Joe Chris? It's a battle
yet to be decided. Joe Nedney has more range. Chris Jacke probably
is more accurate. Either can do the job. &QL; 
Defense &QL; 
 &UR; Left end: Andre Wadsworth was slowed because of a tender knee in
camp, but at least he was there this year, and will better show his
talents. He'll be backed up by Brad Ottis, who can also play
inside. Ottis missed last season because of a broken foot, and was
missed greatly. Jomo Cousins, captain of the All-NFL Name Team, is
still a work in progress.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Left tackle: Will Eric Swann's arthritic surgically repaired
knee allow him to play? If it doesn't, circle the wagons.
Otherwise, it's life with journeymen Bernard Wilson, Rashod Swinger
and Jerry Drake. Whoa. Mike Moten is on injured reserve for the
season.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Right tackle: The Cardinals better back up the armored truck
and sign Mark Smith or . . . well, its life with journeymen
Simpson, Wilson, Swinger and Drake. Also, a life of misery for the
linebacking corps.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Right end: Simeon Rice has looked so good that people are
starting to understand what he says. Rice didn't miss a practice in
his first full camp and looks to be better than his All-Rookie form
three years ago. He's even showing signs of playing the run! Ottis
plays behind him.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Left linebacker: Jamir Miller is gone and now hates the world
from Cleveland, so the Cardinals signed Detroit's Rob Fredrickson.
He is better vs. the pass than Miller, but not nearly the run
supporter. Florida rookie Johnny Rutledge will likely back him up.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Middle linebacker: Pound for pound, Ron McKinnon is great.
Unfortunately, there aren't that many pounds, and if Swann and
Smith are missing, he could be standing in the middle of a freeway.
Mark Maddox was an adequate backup last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Right linebacker: Starter Patrick Sapp, a standout
special-teams player, is an inflated college quarterback who, in
his fourth season, has better learned the nuances of the position.
Sapp started during the playoff drive last season, after taking the
job from Tony McCombs, who again will provide backup.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Left cornerback: Aeneas Williams is All-Pro and the defense's
answer to Plummer on offense. Alas, he doesn't have a cereal to
call his own. Williams was played sparingly in preseason because of
a head and neck injury. Ty Howard, locked in a battle for roster
survival with rookie Coby Rhinehart, is listed as the backup, but
Tommy Knight would move from a right corner backup role to start if
Aeneas goes down.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Right cornerback: Corey Chavous, the walking encyclopedia of
football lore, moved from safety to this position last year. Opened
eyes. If he continues to improve, the Cardinals' corners could be
among best in the league. Knight hopefully has put slap lesions and
injuries behind and will see a lot of action in nickel and dime
packages.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Free safety: Kwamie Lassiter took the job late in the season
and finished as the NFC's leader in interceptions. That's
reasonably strong. J.J. McCleskey, who had a few starts at corner
last year, is Lassiter's backup at 5-8 (can you buy elevator
cleats?).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Strong safety: Solid position with Tommy Bennett and Pat
Tillman, who moves from free safety. Bennett, an unrestricted free
agent at year's end, is looking to have a big year for obvious
rea$on$. Tillman enjoys running full tilt into solid objects and is
better suited for this position.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Punter: Scott Player, who showed in preseason that he's no
threat as a running back or quarterback, will be fine when he
learns to take his practice field punting to the arena on Sundays.
No guarantees, however. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
