<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-SCHEDULE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOUGH SCHEDULE GIVES  ARIZONA FEW BREAKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - The New York Giants and Tampa Bay Buccaneers were
the feel-good stories of 1997 when soft schedules helped propel
them into the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, both were out of the playoffs, their fans
questioning whether they were one-year wonders.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals could be in the same boat this year after using a
fifth-place schedule to help them end the league's longest playoff
drought.
</P>
<P>
   They finished the 1998 regular season at 9-7, earning a playoff
berth in a non-strike year for the first time since 1975. Then, the
Cardinals upset NFC East champion Dallas in the first round, their
first playoff victory in 51 years.
</P>
<P>
   This season, the Cardinals will be minus their all-time leading
receiver (Larry Centers), their top tackler of a year ago (Jamir
Miller) and a seven-time Pro Bowl left offensive tackle (Lomas
Brown).
</P>
<P>
   They also play the league's fourth-toughest schedule and the
second-toughest in the NFC, behind only the Buccaneers, whose
opponents were 138-118 last season, a .539 winning percentage.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals' opponents were 137-119 last season, a .535
winning percentage, a tougher schedule than even Super Bowl
champion Denver will play.
</P>
<P>
   On the Cardinals' schedule are three division champions _
Atlanta, 14-2 in winning the NFC West; the New York Jets, 12-4 in
winning the AFC East; and Dallas, 10-6 in winning the NFC East.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, playoff teams Miami, Buffalo, New England, Green
Bay and San Francisco are on the Cardinals' schedule.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals even got a bad break in their interconference
games against AFC East foes. They play everyone in the division
except last-place Indianapolis as part of the NFL's rotating
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Other than divisional foes Philadelphia and Washington, the only
team on the Cardinals' schedule that had a losing record year ago
is Detroit, which was 5-11.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, the Cardinals won five games against last-place
teams _ Chicago, St. Louis, San Diego and Philadelphia twice.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants can relate. They went from worst-to-first in winning
the 1997 NFC East crown. But they lost last season to Tampa Bay,
Atlanta, Green Bay, San Francisco and Dallas, all playoff teams, in
finishing 8-8 and out of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay, playing a second-place schedule last year, began the
season with two losses and never recovered. The Buccaneers lost
three consecutive games in midseason to Tennessee, Jacksonville and
Detroit to fall out of the playoff race.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
