<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FANTASY-MULLLER-ADV-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T BE TAKEN ABACK, DRAFT ONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL MULLER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   To draft a winning fantasy football team this year, you'll have
to avoid the crowds.
</P>
<P>
   Quite a few NFL backfields are overstocked with running backs,
all fighting for starting jobs. Other teams are overflowing with
quarterbacks, meaning starters can turn into backups faster than
you can say  &UR; Scott Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, the first priority is running back. The position is
as thin as ever, and  &UR; Barry Sanders' retirement doesn't help
matters. Grab a steady back early in the draft, and stay away from
teams that are leaving voice mail messages for  &UR; Eddie Lee Ivory.
</P>
<P>
   Denver's  &UR; Terrell Davis should be the first pick in any draft.
There's a precipitous drop in talent after that.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most muddled situations is in Miami, where Coach
 &UR; Jimmy
 &UR; Johnson realizes he is two players away from a championship.
Unfortunately, those two players are  &UR; Troy Aikman and  &UR; Emmitt
Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's not one to give up easily. He brought three running
backs to camp, all with an equal chance of starting.
</P>
<P>
   There's incumbent  &UR; Karim Abdul- &QL; 
 &UR; Jabbar, Mississippi State rookie  &UR; James Johnson and Louisiana
State/McNeese State rookie  &UR; Cecil (``Fought Law, Law Won'')
Collins.
</P>
<P>
   Collins has looked good early, while James Johnson has been
dinged up in camp. I expect Collins to win the starting job, but we
could see big doses of all three, meaning rotten stats for fantasy
owners.
</P>
<P>
   In Oakland, the Raiders aren't sold on  &UR; Napoleon Kaufman, so
they've brought in a slew of other running backs _ all bad.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, maybe  &UR; Al Davis thinks he's Dr. Frankenstein and can
build a decent back from the likes of  &UR; Zack Crockett, Rashaan
Salaam,
 &UR; Tyrone Wheatley and  &UR; Randy Jordan. Methinks not.
</P>
<P>
   In Baltimore,  &UR; Errict Rhett will handle the goal-line duties for
 &UR; Priest Holmes, who was inconsistent last year.  &UR; Charles Evans
lurks, and you know how painful that can be.
</P>
<P>
   The Ravens also will play the quarterback shuffle, with
fumble-prone  &UR; Tony Banks pressing Mitchell, who at one time was an
actual NFL quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, everybody thought  &UR; Skip Hicks would be the
starting running back. Everybody except Coach  &UR; Norv Turner, who
said  &UR; Stephen
 &UR; Davis might push for the job.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, Redskins receiver  &UR; Michael Westbrook says he's
aiming for the Pro Bowl this year. As long as he's not aiming for
Stephen Davis.
</P>
<P>
   In Arizona, Ohio State standout  &UR; David Boston will probably take
some receptions away from  &UR; Frank Sanders and  &UR; Rob Moore.
</P>
<P>
   There's also the question of  &UR; Jake Plummer's health with the
departure of left tackle  &UR; Lomas Brown. Should Plummer go down, the
Cardinals will turn to the always underwhelming  &UR; Dave Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona running back  &UR; Adrian Murrell remains a middle-round
pick, mostly because he's too small (215 pounds) to handle the ball
at the goal line. This season, he'll again be lifted for  &UR; Mario
Bates or
 &UR; Michael Pittman.
</P>
<P>
   Some sleepers and busts for draft day: &QL; 
Sleepers &QL; 
Both the Steelers and the Rams grabbed talented wide receivers in
the draft.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh picked Louisiana Tech star  &UR; Troy Edwards, who scored
27 touchdowns his senior year and lit up Nebraska for a record 405
yards and three scores. The Steelers don't have much depth at wide
receiver, so Edwards should play early and often.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams picked  &UR; Torry Holt, a North Carolina State receiver who
looked good in the preseason. He was more valuable, however, before
the season-ending injury to St. Louis quarterback  &UR; Trent Green.
</P>
<P>
   I also like rookie running back  &UR; Kevin Faulk, who may start for
the Patriots, and  &UR; Bill Schroeder, who will play across from
 &UR; Antonio
 &UR; Freeman at wide receiver for the Packers.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, a late-round pick: receiver  &UR; E.G. Green of
Indianapolis. &QL; 
Potential busts &QL; 
Every year, we hear how New England wide receiver  &UR; Terry Glenn is
poised to burn up the league. Every year, Glenn succumbs to a
series of minor injuries and plays poorly. This time, it's a sore
toe. Draft him at your own risk.
</P>
<P>
   Carolina running back  &UR; Tim Biakabutuka has the starting job, but
it's doubtful he will keep it. Despite off-field problems,  &UR; Fred
 &UR; (``Missed the Plane'') Lane will probably see significant action
for the Panthers. If not him, then  &UR; William Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   There's a reason Denver quarterback  &UR; Bubby Brister has been a
career backup. After watching Brister flail about in preseason,
Denver will go with  &UR; Brian Griese. Once Bubby, twice shy. &QL; 
Bill Muller's Fantasy Football notebook appears every Friday. He
can be reached at (602) 444-8178 or at bill.muller(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-99 0133EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990905.0048 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-05 01:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
