<HEADLINE>
UCLA DEFENSE IMPROVES ITS IMAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ And for the role of college football's most
dramatic turnaround, the early 1999 nominee is:
</P>
<P>
   The UCLA defense.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, those arm-tackling, yards-giving, season-ruining matadors
of yesteryear, showed up in their opening game of the new season
and made like the Steel Curtain.
</P>
<P>
   So it came Saturday night against that former junior college
power Boise State, it still bordered on impressive.
</P>
<P>
   When the Bruins opened slowly, leading 3-0 at the end of the
first quarter, it was the UCLA defense that stepped up big.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, the defense gave up the big plays. On this night, it
made them.
</P>
<P>
   All those new starters, all those stand-ins and backups to the
backups, put together a marvelous effort and flirted with recording
UCLA's first shutout in three years in the 38-7 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been looking forward to this since last January,''
said UCLA's new defensive coordinator, Bob Field. ``They have
something to prove. I think they took a step towards that
tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   After struggling most of last year and ending the season with
two embarrassing losses when a national title was within reach, the
UCLA defense came into the Rose Bowl on Saturday with six new
starters and plenty more questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't play well last year, and then those last two games
put our season in perspective,'' said sophomore strong safety
Julius Williams. ``We didn't tackle well. We lined up in wrong
positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight we just wanted to swarm to the ball and show the UCLA
defense is tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Their defense started to take control early in the second
quarter. With the Bruins leading 10-0, Williams stepped in front of
a Bart Hendricks pass and returned it 53 yards for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   On the Broncos' next possession, free safety Joey Strycula _ who
had been the holder for the past three years and one of the new
starters _ read a screen pass and intercepted it at the Boise State
23, returning it 7 yards to set up a short UCLA touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``All week long I was excited,'' Strycula said. ``I couldn't
sleep. I felt like I was going to throw up before the game. But
then after the first snap, it all came back.''
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos tried it again, but this time it was freshman
cornerback Joe Hunter who picked off Hendricks. If the team were
not riddled by suspensions over the disabled-parking pass fiasco,
Field said, none of the three who pulled down interceptions
probably would have started.
</P>
<P>
   These new, and seemingly improved, Bruins went in at the half in
command, up 24-0.
</P>
<P>
   It would never get much better for the Broncos. A UCLA team that
allowed more than 28 points per game last season, had opened its
new campaign under Field in impressive fashion.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were tired of reading all those bad things about
themselves in the papers,'' Field said.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, no one is mistaking the Broncos for some national
powerhouse. This oh-so-young defense could get a glimpse of both
ends of the collegiate spectrum next week when the Bruins travel to
Ohio State.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not taking anything away from Boise State, they're
tough,'' Strycula said. ``But we know there will be tougher games
ahead.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
