<HEADLINE>
`OLD PRO' KNOWS WHAT IT TAKES TO BE READY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, ARIZ. - The old pro will awaken in a Philadelphia hotel
room, without the aid of an alarm clock.
</P>
<P>
   It is Sunday, 5:30 a.m. In 7{ hours, the Cardinals play the
Eagles in the opener.
</P>
<P>
   Time to put on his game face.
</P>
<P>
   Trey Junkin inspects his fingers. He trimmed his nails the night
before, collected the clippings and flushed them down the toilet.
</P>
<P>
   At 5:30 a.m., he showers. He stretches.
</P>
<P>
   Then he crawls back in bed and ``pretends'' to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   At 7 a.m., when Cardinals players receive a wake-up call, the
17-year NFL veteran and oldest player on the team, takes
``another'' hot shower. He splashes on cologne. The brand he wears
only on game day.
</P>
<P>
   Breakfast is at 9 a.m. The Cardinals' long snapper always
arrives 45 minutes early. He pours a cup of coffee. Reads the
paper. Reviews the special-teams report.
</P>
<P>
   His pre-game meal ``never'' varies. Baked potato, topped with
spaghetti and tomato sauce. A bowl of oatmeal sprinkled with brown
sugar. A protein bar.
</P>
<P>
   At the table, he shakes salt into his palm and tosses the grains
over his left shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   He rides with the trainers to the game. He wants to be the first
player to arrive at the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   In that quiet hour, he sits on a table in the visiting team's
locker room. Assistant trainer Jeff Herndon tapes his ankles,
always the left one first. Junkin's left knee _ the one scarred
from six surgeries _ the old pro tapes himself.
</P>
<P>
   He smears petroleum jelly on his toes ``to prevent blisters.''
Next, the ritual of dressing for battle begins. Left under-sock,
right under-sock. Left game sock, then the right one. He pulls on
an elastic girdle and his game pants. Left shoe. Right shoe.
Assistant trainer Jim Shearer ``spats'' both with a spool of
adhesive tape.
</P>
<P>
   A linebacker from Louisiana Tech, Junkin broke into the NFL in
1983. He played for the Bills, the Redskins, the Raiders, the
Seahawks. The Cardinals, needing someone who could deliver the ball
on target to the punter, signed him during the 1996 season.
</P>
<P>
   Next Sunday's opener in Veterans Stadium will mark his 233rd NFL
game. He is 38 years old. He was 17 when rookie David Boston was
born.
</P>
<P>
   He folds two sticks of Big Red gum into his mouth. Two other
pieces (for later) go into his cubicle. Game program in hand, he
enters the nearly empty stadium. Alone, he walks along the chalked
hash marks, goal line to goal line, carefully inspecting the field.
</P>
<P>
   He stretches out in one end zone. He loosens up. Looking around,
he takes it all in.
</P>
<P>
   ``The greatest time for me is Sunday morning when I'm in the
stadium by myself,'' the old pro says. ``I'm lying on the turf.
Smelling the grass. Hopefully, the sun is shining. It's hard to
explain, but for thoses 15 or 20 minutes, it's the best feeling.
It's what I live for. When I finish playing, that's the one thing I
will miss the most.''
</P>
<P>
   He thumbs through the program and tosses it to a fan in the
stands.
</P>
<P>
   As teammates begin drifting into the arena, he tosses a football
with punter Scott Player. Standing at the 20-yard line, he turns
and takes aim at the nearest goal post and fires. Five throws. ``If
I hit (the crossbar) the first time,'' he says, ``we're going to
have a great day.''
</P>
<P>
   Returning to the locker room, on goes the armor, shoulder pads
first. Then the wristbands, left then right. He tapes his fingers
on his left hand, then his right. And both thumbs.
</P>
<P>
   Then he sits near the door and waits, alone with his thoughts,
feeling the excitement build. He knows his superstitions seem silly
to others. But there is a rhythm to the reassuring rituals he
performs. The old pro is ``getting ready.'' Each quirky habit, one
built upon the next, tells him, ``This is it. . . this is it.''
</P>
<P>
   When the game begins, he isn't nervous. But he knows what
happens the first time the Cardinals have to punt. As he jogs onto
the field, ``suddenly I can't breathe.'' The distance from the
sideline to the ball isn't far. ``It takes _ what? _ three or four
seconds, but I feel like I'm running underwater. It's the longest
run of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he is over the ball. He hears the count.
</P>
<P>
   From his hands, through his legs, the snap a tight spiral. Then,
the thud as foot meets ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at it as just a job,'' the old pro says. ``I'm here to
snap the ball.'' He laughs. ``And be the weirdest guy on the
team.'' &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at (602) 444-8635 or at
david.casstevens(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
