<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDINALS IN A STATE OF GRACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'm sitting in the dugout at Wrigley Field. A face emerges from
the clubhouse, and just like that, Cubs star Mark Grace is standing
in front of me. He has a very serious look on his face.
</P>
<P>
   ``So,'' he says, ``what's happening with the Cardinals?''
</P>
<P>
   It is the first week in August, and suddenly, I'm wondering if
Mark McGwire has been traded or if the Gateway Arch has collapsed
on Busch Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cardinals?'' I ask.
</P>
<P>
   Grace is getting impatient.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, the Cardinals,'' Grace said. ``You know I live in
Arizona, right?''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, that I knew.
</P>
<P>
   ``And you know I'm a season ticket holder?'' Grace said.
</P>
<P>
   That I did not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, yeah,'' Grace said. ``I rarely miss a game.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, you'll find Cardinals fans everywhere. Last year, an
adult-film director named Seymour Butts showed up at training camp,
with one of his starlets in tow. I ran into him in a Flagstaff bar,
and after the chance meeting, I was somewhat curious to discuss his
line of work. Sorry, he only wanted to talk about the Big Red.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks' Luis Gonzalez is purchasing season tickets.
E-mail from across the country fills my computer every time the
Cardinals are in the news. Jake Plummer is doing national
television commercials.
</P>
<P>
   There is no doubt that this franchise is hot.
</P>
<P>
   Now, if only they can remember how to win football games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm worried about that,'' Grace said. ``They've got San
Francisco, Green Bay, Atlanta and the AFC East (as non-conference
opponents). They're playing a witch of a schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   Like so many other Cardinals fans across the nation, Grace grew
up in St. Louis. But he left the Midwest before Cardinals owner
Bill Bidwill did, so much of the natural anger is missing from
Grace's perspective.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, I'm curious what he thinks of Bidwill. After all,
Bidwill never hides his deep disdain for the Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a Bidwill basher by any means,'' Grace said. ``During
the lean years, he could've put a better product out there on the
field. But now he's starting to open his pocketbook a little more
often. I think he realizes the times are changing, football is
changing and, in the end, you get what you pay for. And I'm glad to
see he's doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, Grace has never met Mark Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Like any self-respecting millionaire, Grace does not sit on the
aluminum bleachers frying in the desert sun. For the sake of
comfort, he has a loge box. But he is not a dispassionate fan or a
bandwagon type who shows up for the chilled shrimp.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, he missed only the game against the New Orleans
Saints, and that one he watched at a sports book in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, Grace remains largely unnoticed at Sun Devil
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm much more recognizable in Chicago,'' Grace said. ``When
I'm at Cardinals games, all I ever hear is, `Hey, Travis Lee is
better than you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Chances are, that won't happen this season, either.
</P>
<P>
   What ``will'' happen, nobody knows. Grace is somewhat leery,
somewhat apprehensive, somewhat giddy over the swift turnaround the
franchise pulled off in 1998. That combination of emotions makes
him the prototypical Cardinals fan. And like everyone else, his
focus starts with the quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew Jake (Plummer) when he was at ASU,'' Grace said. ``He's
a good guy, a fun-loving guy, a guy who likes to get out a little
bit. And in that respect, he's a young Mark Grace.
</P>
<P>
   ``But for a guy who is not very big, he's tough. He takes a lot
of hits, he gets the (expletive) beat out of him, he gets back up.
And then he beats you. I love a guy who will go out there every day
and take his lumps.''
</P>
<P>
   As a member of the Cubs, taking your lumps is something Grace
knows a lot about. And as The Sequel gets ready to unfold in the
Valley, Grace only hopes the magic at Sun Devil Stadium lasts a bit
longer than it does at Wrigley Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't I know it,'' he said. ``But I'll be there. I'm the
biggest Cardinals fan around.'' &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at (602) 444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
