<HEADLINE>
BRADY DELIVERS WHEN IT COUNTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VINCENT BONSIGNORE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As first-game performances go, there were the
typical mistakes, misreads and stretches of uneven play. But every
so often, Cal State Northridge quarterback Marcus Brady converted
one of those magical plays that obliges Matadors coach Jeff Kearin
to proclaim him the one of the best quarterbacks in the country.
</P>
<P>
   The sort of play that earned Brady the Big Sky Conference
Newcomer of the Year honor in 1998, and the kind the Matadors must
have this year if they are to challenge for the conference title.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to get us out of a lot of trouble this year, and
he's going to make us coaches look a lot better and a lot
smarter,'' Kearin said Saturday after CSUN opened 1999 with a 38-19
win over gritty Western Oregon. ``And he's only going to get
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Brady was brilliant at times on Saturday, rescuing the Matadors
from a potentially devastating loss against an NCAA Division II
team.
</P>
<P>
   And he was at his best when Northridge absolutely needed him to
be.
</P>
<P>
   With the Matadors trailing 13-10 in the third quarter, he
completed two long passes to preserve a drive that eventually
enabled the Matadors to take a 17-13 lead.
</P>
<P>
   First he side-stepped a Western Oregon tackler in the end zone
on third and long at the Matadors five-yard line, then danced a few
steps to his right and threw 26 yards to Aaron Arnold for the first
down. Seven plays later on a fourth-and-3 at the Wolves' 30-yard
line, Brady checked off at the line of scrimmage when he noticed
Western Oregon was about to blitz, then threw 28 yards to Drew
Amerson, his boyhood friend from San Diego, for another first down.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the type of the thing he can do,'' Kearin said.
``That's what makes him one of the best NCAA Division I-AA
quarterbacks in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   The two plays were vintage Brady, showing off his athletic
ability, resourcefulness and throwing arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt the (tackler) at my feet in the end zone, but I knew I
was strong enough to break out of that,'' Brady said. ``Then I just
did what I was supposed to do, make the play.''
</P>
<P>
   Brady threw an interception in the second quarter and finished
with 321 yards and two touchdowns on 28 of 48 passes, but wasn't
satisfied with his performance. Neither was Kearin, who said Brady
seemed tentative at times.
</P>
<P>
   ``He even said afterward that he wasn't real happy with the way
he played,'' Kearin said. ``But I think it was just first-game
jitters.''
</P>
<P>
   Brady, who passed for 2,974 yards and 25 touchdowns a year ago,
agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking too much and I wasn't relaxed,'' he said. ``But
once I got into the flow of the game I started to relax and have
fun. I always play better when I'm having fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Brady was more upset than worried when Western Oregon led 13-10
at halftime. He knew the Matadors were physically superior to the
Wolves, so there was no panic in the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really didn't make any adjustments other than mental
ones,'' Brady said. ``We knew that once we calmed down, we'd be
fine.''
</P>
<P>
   And with Brady at quarterback, that should be the case all year
for Northridge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
