<DOCNO> NYT19990905.0053 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-05 01:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1412 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-EXPOS-HNS &LR;      09-05 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-EXPOS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
MONTREAL _ The Montreal Expos did everything possible to give away
Saturday's game. The Astros gave it right back.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Then in the 10th inning, plate umpire Tim Timmons handed it back
to the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Bagwell scored the go-ahead run on a controversial call at
home plate, the first run in a three-run outburst that allowed the
Astros to steal a 5-2 victory from the Expos before another
smallish crowd (8,471) at Olympic Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   A terrific pitching duel between Shane Reynolds and Javier
Vazquez was overshadowed by an error-infested game by the Expos,
then by the Houston bullpen's inability to hold a two-run lead, and
finally by the questionable call in the 10th.
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell hit a two-out double off Ugueth Urbina in the 10th
inning. Bagwell stole third on a 3-1 wild pitch to Russ Johnson and
headed for home as the ball got away from catcher Chris Widger.
</P>
<P>
   Widger threw to Urbina (6-6), who juggled the ball in his arms
while he blocked the plate. With his view blocked, Timmons, one of
22 newly hired umpires, made a safe call before Bagwell pushed his
foot between Urbina's legs to touch the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Bell followed with a two-run homer to right as the Astros
remained 2{ games ahead of Cincinnati in the National League
Central.
</P>
<P>
   ``I touched it late, whatever that means,'' Bagwell said. ``I'm
pretty much out there (running the bases) on my own. I was stealing
third, and as I got to third I knew the ball had gotten away. All
of our guys were yelling and screaming, so I said, `Heck, I'll give
it a shot.'
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't plan on getting too many hits off Urbina. He's one
of the best closers in the league. I took a chance, and fortunately
it paid off.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros nearly wasted an impressive pitching performance by
Reynolds, who tossed seven shutout innings but was forced to leave
the game in the eighth after hurting his left knee sliding into
second base on a pickoff attempt.
</P>
<P>
   The injury was not believed to be serious, and manager Larry
Dierker said he took Reynolds out of the game as a precaution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just happy to get out of here with a win the way things
turned out,'' Dierker said. ``Shane was pitching his best game of
the whole year. I don't think they would have scored off him the
way he was throwing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has six or seven more starts for us, and I didn't want to
jeopardize the rest of his starts by trying to send him out there
with a sore knee.''
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds, who is without a victory since Aug. 5, gave up four
hits. Vazquez allowed just three and struck out seven in eight
innings, at one point retiring 11 in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Montreal made four errors, three in the eighth as the Astros
took a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds opened the eighth with a ground ball that third baseman
Shane Andrews threw past first for a two-base error. After Craig
Biggio sacrificed, second baseman Jose Vidro misplayed Stan
Javier's grounder to allow the game's first run to score.
</P>
<P>
   The ball then got by Vladimir Guerrero _ his 17th error _ and
Bagwell followed with a sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   Montreal leads the major leagues with 138 errors and has
committed six in the first two games of the series.
</P>
<P>
   But the 2-0 lead lasted just minutes as the Expos rallied for
two runs in the bottom of the eighth off Jay Powell and Billy
Wagner.
</P>
<P>
   Powell allowed hits to both batters he faced, and Wagner walked
Geoff Blum to load the bases with no outs.
</P>
<P>
   Rondell White's sacrifice fly and Wilton Guerrero's RBI single
made it 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   Bell's throw from right pulled catcher Tony Eusebio off the
plate, and Orlando Merced slid past the tag for the tying run. It
was only the third blown save for Wagner in 36 chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hated it for Shane. I was terrible,'' Powell said. ``I fell
behind both hitters. I had to give them fastballs. I put everybody
in a tough situation. It's my job, and I just didn't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jose Cabrera (4-0) picked up the win, allowing one hit in two
innings.
</P>
<P>
   With runs scarce, the Astros failed to cash in on their
opportunities early in the game.
</P>
<P>
   In the seventh, Ken Caminiti led off with a double to center
field and Bell reached on an error by shortstop Mike Mordecai. Matt
Mieske could not execute the bunt and struck out, and Eusebio flied
to right field.
</P>
<P>
   Then Ricky Gutierrez sent a deep drive to right field but was
robbed when Guerrero made a running, over-the-shoulder catch near
the wall.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros had two runners on base in the ninth, but Gutierrez
flied out to center and pinch hitter Bill Spiers popped out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-99 0138EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
