<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-05 01:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1413 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     09-05 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A QUIET ROAR COMES FROM KEARIN'S WAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A couple of nights before his Cal State Northridge
head-coaching debut, Jeff Kearin met a few old law-school friends
at a beachfront restaurant. He was the one in a T-shirt, a whistle
hanging out of his pocket.
</P>
<P>
   Since he's a football coach and they're attorneys, he was bound
to hear some unsolicited advice.
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob Davie is a wuss! John Robinson is a wuss!'' a woman, a
Notre Dame fan, told him. ``You've gotta be hard on those guys
(players)!''
</P>
<P>
   Kearin, a Robinson protege, could only laugh. He is not and
never will be the drill sergeant some fans like to see on the
sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a real hard-ass, not a real screamer and yeller,'' he
said this week. ``I'm not into the Knute Rockne-Vince Lombardi
stereotype.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kearin's laid-back self-image was tested early and often in
Northridge's 38-19 victory over Western Oregon on a sunny Saturday
afternoon at North Campus Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors committed 15 penalties, including two for
``unsportsmanlike'' excessive celebrating and one for a late hit.
They were offsides on a kickoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not about that,'' Kearin said later of the personal
fouls. ``We are not going to be a cheap-shot team. Guys are not
going to play if they do those things.''
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors fumbled away a scoring chance on their first
possession, had to settle for a field goal on their second after a
botched pitchout, and threw an interception that led to a Western
Oregon touchdown. The fumble might have been the result of an
official's bad call.
</P>
<P>
   ``That got me a little hot,'' Kearin said, taking his emotional
temperature after the game.
</P>
<P>
   Yet none of the frustrations of the season's first 30 minutes,
in which the Matadors trailed 13-3 against a Division II team,
produced the kind of fire-and-brimstone halftime speech that
Kearin's friend from the restaurant would have preferred.
</P>
<P>
   There was no exhortation to win one for the Gipper, or for Ron
Ponciano, or for the neighborly homeowners of the Lindley West
Coalition, or for whomever the young Matadors are playing this
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just, `Stop making mistakes,''' Kearin said, relaxing
with a Diet Pepsi later.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a grilling or yelling or anything like that,''
running back Jaumal Bradley said. ``It was, `Calm down. Settle
down.'''
</P>
<P>
   That, for better or worse, is the coach Northridge hired six
weeks ago, at least on an interim basis, after the popular Ponciano
was fired because the administration believed he'd violated NCAA
and university rules.
</P>
<P>
   Kearin, 39, comes off as a thoroughly nice individual _
self-deprecating (``I'm a little unprepared'') but confident (he
predicts a Big Sky Conference championship), just enough of a
Pollyanna to call this ``the best job in college football'' but
just enough of a realist to add ``for me, not for everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Someone described him as a real person who happens to be a
football coach. If you've met many football coaches, you know
that's saying a lot.
</P>
<P>
   Kearin's refreshingly non-confrontational personality is one
reason he was hired. His knowledge of NCAA athletic-department
rules _ after dealing with compliance and eligibility issues as a
Northridge assistant _ is another.
</P>
<P>
   But removing his ``interim'' label will require a measure of
success on the field after the Matadors' improved, 7-4 season under
Ponciano in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't get the job in January,'' Kearin said, ``if I don't
win and/or I cheat.''
</P>
<P>
   Northridge should win by more than 19 points against a school
like Western Oregon, the softest opponent on the schedule.
</P>
<P>
   The sloppy first half could be laid at the feet of the
first-time head coach. Maybe a Rockne-style pre-game pep talk would
have helped.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were a couple of series into the game before I thought,
`Hey, the season's started!''' Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley blamed himself and other seniors for that, saying if
anybody is responsible for firing up the team, it's them, not the
coach.
</P>
<P>
   Can a nice guy find happiness in the head coach's office? The
guess here is while Kearin won't win the Big Sky championship, he
won't finish last either.
</P>
<P>
   The next game on the Matadors' schedule is at Kansas, and if
they had Rockne and Lombardi, that would be too much to overcome.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-99 0138EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
