<HEADLINE>
NFC WEST CAPSULES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; 1. Atlanta Falcons &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; 1998 ISSUE: 14-2, first. &QL; 
 &UR; FEARLESS LEADER: Dan Reeves (172-125-1). &QL; 
 &UR; HALL OF JUSTICE: Georgia Dome (71,228). &QL; 
 &UR; THE NEW AVENGERS: Free agents WR Chris Calloway, G Greg Bishop, S
Marty Carter; rookie DE Patrick Kerney. &QL; 
 &UR; STILL A GOOD  &UR; GUY: RB Jamal Anderson, QB Chris Chandler, WR Terence
Mathis, TE O.J. Santiago, LE Lester Archambeaux, CB Ray Buchanan,
LB Jessie Tuggle, S Eugene Robinson. &QL; 
 &UR; GONE TO EVIL FORCES: WR Tony Martin, LB Cornelius Bennett. &QL; 
 &UR; TEST OF WILL: The Falcons could all but have the division title
wrapped up before hitting a torturous season-ending four-game
stretch (at San Francisco, at Tennessee, Arizona, San Francisco). &QL; 
 &UR; WILL PREVAIL IF: The secondary that appears on paper to be improved
actually is improved on the field. &QL; 
 &UR; WILL PERISH IF: The players are too taken with themselves after
their stunning run to the division title and Super Bowl last year. &QL; 
 &UR; CYBERSPACE HOME: www.atlantafalcons.com. &QL; 
 &UR; 2. San Francisco 49ers &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; 1998 ISSUE: 12-4, second. &QL; 
 &UR; FEARLESS LEADER: Steve Mariucci (27-9). &QL; 
 &UR; HALL OF JUSTICE: 3Com Park at Candlestick Point (70,270). &QL; 
 &UR; THE NEW AVENGERS: Free agents RB Lawrence Phillips, RB Travis
Jervey, RB Charlie Garner, DE Charles Haley, DE Marvin Washington;
rookie DT Reggie McGrew. &QL; 
 &UR; STILL A GOOD  &UR; GUY: WR Jerry Rice, QB Steve Young, CB R.W.
McQuarters, LB Ken Norton, S Tim McDonald. &QL; 
 &UR; GONE TO EVIL FORCES: RG Kevin Gogan, DE Ray Barker, OT Jamie Brown,
TE Irv Smith, CB Marquez Pope. &QL; 
 &UR; TEST OF WILL: It's not a strong schedule but three of the first
five are on the road, including a Monday night game at Arizona. An
aging core group could be out of gas for two games in the closing
four weeks with chief nemesis Atlanta. &QL; 
 &UR; WILL PREVAIL IF: The defense tightens and stops foes in key
situations, which it did not do last season. &QL; 
 &UR; WILL PERISH IF: RB Lawrence Phillips breaks their hearts with his
personality and lifestyle flaws after the club puts it fate in his
hands following season-ending injury to RB Garrison Hearst. &QL; 
 &UR; CYBERSPACE HOME: www.sf49ers.com. &QL; 
 &UR; 3. New Orleans Saints &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; 1998 ISSUE: 6-10, third. &QL; 
 &UR; FEARLESS LEADER: Mike Ditka (124-88). &QL; 
 &UR; HALL OF JUSTICE: Louisiana Superdome (70,200). &QL; 
 &UR; THE NEW AVENGERS: Free agents WR Eddie Kennison, G Wally Williams;
rookie RB Ricky Williams. &QL; 
 &UR; STILL A GOOD  &UR; GUY: OT Willie Roaf, OT Kyle Turley, TE Cam Cleeland,
QB Billy Joe Hobart, La'Roi Glover, LB Mark Fields, S Rob Kelly, S
Sammy Knight. &QL; 
 &UR; GONE TO EVIL FORCES: QB Kerry Collins, WR Eric Guiliford, OT
Clarence Jones, WR Sean Dawkins. &QL; 
 &UR; TEST OF WILL: A rookie back, Ricky Williams, will get off to a slow
start because of an injury. That will hamper Ditka's effort to put
more spark into the league's 28th-ranked offense. So will an
average quarterback. Patience is the word. But then, the
26th-ranked defense is tested by a stronger schedule, as well. &QL; 
 &UR; WILL PREVAIL IF: Nobody can touch RB Williams. &QL; 
 &UR; WILL PERISH IF: Ditka's volatile temper short-circuits the efforts
of those who are trying to improve. &QL; 
 &UR; CYBERSPACE HOME: www.nfl.com/saints. &QL; 
 &UR; 4. St. Louis Rams &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; 1998 ISSUE: 4-12, fourth. &QL; 
 &UR; FEARLESS LEADER: Dick Vermeil (66-74). &QL; 
 &UR; HALL OF JUSTICE: Trans World Dome (66,000). &QL; 
 &UR; THE NEW AVENGERS: Traded for RB Marshall Faulk, free agents QB
Trent Green, G Adam Timmerman, LB Todd Collins, S Devin Bush;
rookies WR Torry Holt, CB Dre' Bly. &QL; 
 &UR; STILL A GOOD  &UR; GUY: WR Isaac Bruce, OT Orlando Pace, DT D'Marco
Farr, DE Kevin Carter. &QL; 
 &UR; GONE TO EVIL FORCES: QB Tony Banks, OT Wayne Gandy, WR Eddie
Kennison, LB Roman Phifer, G Zack Weigert. &QL; 
 &UR; TEST OF WILL: In a division full of old coaches with big names,
Dick Vermeil is challenged to take a revamped team back to
respectability or enter into retirement _ again. The league's
second-easiest schedule should help break in a new running back. &QL; 
 &UR; WILL PREVAIL IF: RB Marshall Faulk revitalize a punchless attack. &QL; 
 &UR; WILL PERISH IF: They really do miss Green, out for the season
because of a knee injury. &QL; 
 &UR; CYBERSPACE HOME: www.stlouisrams.com. &QL; 
 &UR; 5. Carolina Panthers &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; 1998 ISSUE: 4-12, fourth. &QL; 
 &UR; FEARLESS LEADER: George Seifert (108-35). &QL; 
 &UR; HALL OF JUSTICE: Ericsson Stadium (72,250). &QL; 
 &UR; THE NEW AVENGERS: Free agents WR Patrick Jeffers, LB Steve Tovar,
DE Antonio Edwards, LB Dean Wells, LB Donta Jones, QB Jeff Lewis, G
Nate Newton; rookies OT Chris Terry, DE Mike Rucker. &QL; 
 &UR; STILL A GOOD  &UR; GUY: WR Rae Carruth, DT Sean Gilbert, DE Jason Peter,
LB Kevin Greene, S Brent Alexander, QB Steve Beuerlein. &QL; 
 &UR; GONE TO EVIL FORCES: WR Rocket Ismail, OT Blake Brockermeyer, LB
Jeff Brady, LB Greg Lloyd, WR Mark Carrier. &QL; 
 &UR; TEST OF WILL: The players have to be patient while the new coach
rebuilds, starting with the league's worst defense. Seifert didn't
stand pat, making wholesale roster changes immediately. It will
take time to get a franchise that has been a one-hit wonder to a
consistently high level. &QL; 
 &UR; WILL PREVAIL IF: The defense matures quickly. There are lots of new
faces. &QL; 
 &UR; WILL PERISH IF: No one steps forward to claim the quarterback spot.
Former Cardinal Steve Beuerlein is challenged by former Northern
Arizona quarterback Jeff Lewis and veteran Steve Bono to run
Seifert's new offense. &QL; 
 &UR; CYBERSPACE HOME: www.cpanthers.com. &QL;
</P>
