<HEADLINE>
NFC CENTRAL CAPSULES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; 1. Minnesota Vikings &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; 1998 ISSUE: 15-1, first. &QL; 
 &UR; FEARLESS LEADER: Dennis Green (73-47). &QL; 
 &UR; HALL OF JUSTICE: Hubert H. Humphrey Metrodome (64,121). &QL; 
 &UR; THE NEW AVENGERS: Free agents QB Jeff George, LB Corey Miller;
rookie QB Daunte Culpepper. &QL; 
 &UR; STILL A GOOD  &UR; GUY: WR Randy Moss, RB Robert Smith, QB Randall
Cunningham, WR Cris Carter, DT John Randle, LB Dwayne Rudd. &QL; 
 &UR; GONE TO EVIL FORCES: QB Brad Johnson, NT Jerry Ball, DE Dimitrius
Underwood. &QL; 
 &UR; TEST OF WILL: Three late-season Monday night games in a six-week
span coupled with having to wait until late November for the open
week could take a toll. Otherwise, the highest-scoring team in the
history of the NFL is ready to take the next step to the Super
Bowl. &QL; 
 &UR; WILL PREVAIL IF: Aging QB Randall Cunningham stays at the same high
level that brought the team 15 wins. &QL; 
 &UR; WILL PERISH IF: The secondary is exposed as soft. &QL; 
 &UR; CYBERSPACE HOME: www.vikings.com. &QL; 
 &UR; 2. Green Bay Packers &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; 1998 ISSUE: 11-5, second. &QL; 
 &UR; FEARLESS LEADER: Ray Rhodes (30-36-1). &QL; 
 &UR; HALL OF JUSTICE: Lambeau Field (60,790. &QL; 
 &UR; THE NEW AVENGERS: Free agents G Raleigh McKenzie, WR-RET Desmond
Howard; rookies CB Antuan Edwards, CB Fred Vinson. &QL; 
 &UR; STILL A GOOD  &UR; GUY: QB Brett Favre, RB Dorsey Levens, WR Antonio
Freeman, DT Santana Dotson, DT Gilbert Brown, DE Vonnie Holliday, S
LeRoy Butler. &QL; 
 &UR; GONE TO EVIL FORCES: Coach Mike Holmgren, DE Reggie White, WR
Robert Brooks, G Adam Timmerman, P Sean Landeta. &QL; 
 &UR; TEST OF WILL: It's a new era. The Pack has been backsliding. A
question that needs to be answered: Can Ray Rhodes really coach or
was he just saddled with a bad organization in Philadelphia? He
inherits the league's seventh-toughest schedule to make his mark
with his new team. &QL; 
 &UR; WILL PREVAIL IF: Favre finds the old magic and new receivers. &QL; 
 &UR; WILL PERISH IF: Anyone messes with the defense, which was the
league's fourth-stoutest last season. &QL; 
 &UR; CYBERSPACE HOME: www.packers.com. &QL; 
 &UR; 3. Tampa Bay Buccaneers &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; 1998 ISSUE: 8-8, third. &QL; 
 &UR; FEARLESS LEADER: Tony Dungy (25-25). &QL; 
 &UR; HALL OF JUSTICE: Raymond James Stadium (65,000). &QL; 
 &UR; THE NEW AVENGERS: Rookies DT Anthony McFarland, QB Shaun King, K
Martin Gramatica. &QL; 
 &UR; STILL A GOOD  &UR; GUY: RB Warrick Dunn, QB Trent Dilfer, FB Mike
Alstott, DT Warren Sapp, LB Hardy Nickerson. &QL; 
 &UR; GONE TO EVIL FORCES: S Charles Mincy. &QL; 
 &UR; TEST OF WILL: If the Bucs thought they had a difficult schedule
last season, this year's is tied for second toughest, based on 1998
winning percentage of foes. Among them are Super Bowl competitors
Denver and Atlanta. &QL; 
 &UR; WILL PREVAIL IF: They can shake a bad year and show they're for
real. It's essentially the same cast of characters that two years
ago was the surprise team in the league. &QL; 
 &UR; WILL PERISH IF: They get behind early. Theirs is not a high-scoring
comeback offense. &QL; 
 &UR; CYBERSPACE HOME: www.buccaneers.com. &QL; 
 &UR; 4. Detroit Lions &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; 1998 ISSUE: 5-11. &QL; 
 &UR; FEARLESS LEADER: Bobby Ross (64-55). &QL; 
 &UR; HALL OF JUSTICE: Pontiac Silverdome (80,311). &QL; 
 &UR; THE NEW AVENGERS: Free agent QB Gus Frerotte; rookies LB Chris
Claiborne, OT Aaron Gibson. &QL; 
 &UR; STILL A GOOD  &UR; GUY: WR Johnnie Morton, WR Herman Moore, QB Charlie
Batch, DE Tracy Scroggins. &QL; 
 &UR; GONE TO EVIL FORCES: RB Barry Sanders, QB Scott Mitchell, LB Rob
Fredrickson. &QL; 
 &UR; TEST OF WILL: The Lions have to hope that Sanders is kidding or
that somebody who can carry the ball hops into their hands. The
degree of difficulty increases given one of the league's 10
toughest schedules coupled with the loss of Aaron Gibson for the
season because of a shoulder injury. Absent a running game or a
run-stopping defense, Batch will get a workout. &QL; 
 &UR; WILL PREVAIL IF: The defense becomes tougher against the run. &QL; 
 &UR; WILL PERISH IF: The players on a roster that is not devoid of
talent tire of coming close and losing, and then throw in the
towel. &QL; 
 &UR; CYBERSPACE HOME: www.detroitlions.com. &QL; 
 &UR; 5. Chicago Bears &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; 1998 ISSUE: 4-12, fifth. &QL; 
 &UR; FEARLESS LEADER: Dick Jauron (first season as NFL head coach). &QL; 
 &UR; HALL OF JUSTICE: Soldier Field (66,944). &QL; 
 &UR; THE NEW AVENGERS: Free agents OT Blake Brockermeyer, DE Clyde
Simmons, CB Chris Canty; and rookie QB Cade McNown, DL Russell
Davis. &QL; 
 &UR; STILL A GOOD  &UR; GUY: RB Curtis Enis, CB Walt Harris, DT Jim
Flanigan. &QL; 
 &UR; GONE TO EVIL FORCES: QB Steve Stenstrom, QB Erik Kramer. &QL; 
 &UR; TEST OF WILL: The coach is new, the cupboard is bare. The only
possible saving grace is that the schedule is weak. This shell of a
once dominant franchise is at least a year away from making a
comeback with young McNown. &QL; 
 &UR; WILL PREVAIL IF: It catches a foe on a week when it has a ton of
injuries. &QL; 
 &UR; WILL PERISH IF: The sun rises. There isn't much to be excited about
here. Yet. &QL; 
 &UR; CYBERSPACE HOME: www.chicagobears.com. &QL;
</P>
