<HEADLINE>
NFC EAST CAPSULES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; 1. Dallas Cowboys &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; 1998 ISSUE: 10-7, first. &QL; 
 &UR; FEARLESS LEADER: Chan Gailey (10-7). &QL; 
 &UR; HALL OF JUSTICE: Texas Stadium (65,812). &QL; 
 &UR; THE NEW AVENGERS: Free agents C Mark Stepnoski, WR Rocket Ismail,
LB Quentin Coryatt, DB Alonzo Spellman; rookie DE Ebenezer Ekuban. &QL; 
 &UR; STILL A GOOD  &UR; GUY: QB Troy Aikman, RB Emmitt Smith, RB Chris
Warren, OL Larry Allen, OL Flozell Adams, LB Dexter Coakley, CB
Deion Sanders. &QL; 
 &UR; GONE TO EVIL FORCES: WR Patrick Jeffers, G Nate Newton, LB Fred
Strickland. &QL; 
 &UR; TEST OF WILL: Nov. 8-Dec. 5 they're at Minnesota, home vs. Green
Bay, at the Cardinals, home vs. Miami, and at New England, a killer
late-season stretch against 1998 playoff teams. &QL; 
 &UR; WILL PREVAIL IF: Deion Sanders' toe ever heals and if the Cowboys
ever get the services of Leon Lett. With them, their defense can be
just as dangerous as their offense, which promises to be even more
wide open in the second season under Gailey. While they are
light-years removed from their Super Bowl era, the Cowboys still
have enough players who are among the best in the league at their
positions to be taken seriously, especially in a weak division. &QL; 
 &UR; WILL PERISH IF: The defense succumbs to injuries and off-field
problems. Losing Lett and Sanders could be fatal. &QL; 
 &UR; CYBERSPACE HOME: www.dallascowboys.com. &QL; 
 &UR; 2. Arizona Cardinals &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; 1998 ISSUE: 9-7, second. &QL; 
 &UR; FEARLESS LEADER: Vince Tobin (21-29). &QL; 
 &UR; HALL OF JUSTICE: Sun Devil Stadium (73,014). &QL; 
 &UR; THE NEW AVENGERS: Free agent LB Rob Fredrickson; rookies WR David
Boston, OT L.J. Shelton, LB Johnny Rutledge, FB Joel Makovicka. &QL; 
