<HEADLINE>
AFC WEST CAPSULES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; 1. Denver Broncos &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; 1998 ISSUE: 14-2, first. &QL; 
 &UR; FEARLESSS LEADER: Mike Shanahan (62-30). &QL; 
 &UR; HALL OF JUSTICE: Mile High Stadium (76,082). &QL; 
 &UR; THE NEW AVENGERS: The Broncos already were good before signing
free-agent CB Dale Carter, division-rival Kansas City's best
defensive back. &QL; 
 &UR; STILL A GOOD  &UR; GUY: Terrell Davis, the NFL's Most Valuable Player a
year ago, is the best RB in the league. &QL; 
 &UR; GONE TO EVIL FORCES: The Broncos let FS Steve Atwater go to the
enemy _ the AFC runner-up New York Jets. &QL; 
 &UR; TEST OF WILL: The Broncos better not get off to a slow start,
beginning with games against Miami, at Kansas City, at Tampa Bay
and the New York Jets &QL; 
 &UR; WILL PREVAIL IF: Brian Griese, John Elway's replacement at QB,
spends most Sunday afternoons handing off to Davis. &QL; 
 &UR; WILL PERISH IF: Griese, who has little experience, makes sophomore
mistakes. &QL; 
 &UR; CYBERSPACE HOME: www.denverbroncos.com. &QL; 
 &UR; 2. Oakland Raiders &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; 1998 ISSUE: 8-8, second. &QL; 
 &UR; FEARLESSS LEADER: Jon Gruden (8-8). &QL; 
 &UR; HALL OF JUSTICE: Networks Associate Coliseum (63,142). &QL; 
 &UR; THE NEW AVENGERS: Would someone explain why the Raiders decided
Chiefs backup Rich Gannon was good enough to be their starting QB? &QL; 
 &UR; STILL A GOOD  &UR; GUY: It would be nice if veteran WR Tim Brown could
end his career with a winner, but don't count on it. &QL; 
 &UR; GONE TO EVIL FORCES: The Raiders finally gave up on starting QB
Jeff George, who now is a backup in Minnesota. &QL; 
 &UR; TEST OF WILL: Owner Al Davis' conspiracy theory lives. The Raiders
play on the road at Green Bay, Minnesota and Seattle three of the
first four weeks. &QL; 
 &UR; WILL PREVAIL IF: Gannon and backup Wade Wilson could enter a time
tunnel and be back with the Minnesota Vikings in the late 1980s. &QL; 
 &UR; WILL PERISH IF: They don't get to the Super Bowl. This franchise
that calls itself the ``Team of the Decades'' has neither been to
the playoffs since 1993 nor had a winning record since '94. &QL; 
 &UR; CYBERSPACE HOME: www.raiders.com. &QL; 
 &UR; 3. Seattle Seahawks &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; 1998 ISSUE: 8-8, second. &QL; 
 &UR; FEARLESSS LEADER: Mike Holmgren (84-42). &QL; 
 &UR; HALL OF JUSTICE: Kingdome (66,400). &QL; 
 &UR; THE NEW AVENGERS: The Seahawks already had one of the best
defensive lines in the league before they added first-round pick
Lamar King. &QL; 
 &UR; STILL A GOOD  &UR; GUY: There isn't a better DT in the NFL than Cortez
Kennedy. &QL; 
 &UR; GONE TO EVIL FORCES: Mike Holmgren decided he wasn't going anywhere
with a 42-year-old QB, Warren Moon, who now plays for the Chiefs. &QL; 
 &UR; TEST OF WILL: The final five weeks of the schedule will determine
how the Seahawks do in their division. They play Oakland and Denver
on the road and San Diego and Kansas City at home before finishing
the season at the Jets. &QL; 
 &UR; WILL PREVAIL IF: Starting QB Jon Kitna is the real deal and can
master the West Coast offense. &QL; 
 &UR; WILL PERISH IF: They continue to have problems at WR. Joey Galloway
hadn't reported to camp as of late August and Mike Pritchard was
slowed because of injuries. &QL; 
 &UR; CYBERSPACE HOME: www.seahawks.com. &QL; 
 &UR; 4. Kansas City Chiefs &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; 1998 ISSUE: 7-9, fourth. &QL; 
 &UR; FEARLESSS LEADER: Gunther Cunningham (first year as NFL head
coach). &QL; 
 &UR; HALL OF JUSTICE: Arrowhead Stadium (79,451). &QL; 
 &UR; THE NEW AVENGERS: After losing Dale Carter to the Broncos, the
Chiefs hope that veteran CB Cris Dishman has something left. &QL; 
 &UR; STILL A GOOD  &UR; GUY: The Chiefs are always strong up the middle in
the offensive line. C Tim Grunhard and OGs Will Shields and Dave
Szott could play for anybody. &QL; 
 &UR; GONE TO EVIL FORCES: Carter will be sorely missed despite his past
off-field problems. &QL; 
 &UR; TEST OF WILL: The three-week stretch of games at Oakland (Nov. 28),
at Denver (Dec. 5) and Minnesota at home (Dec. 12) could decide the
Chiefs' playoff chances. &QL; 
 &UR; WILL PREVAIL IF: Gunther Cunningham instills some discipline into a
team which led the league in penalties last season. &QL; 
 &UR; WILL PERISH IF: The Chiefs lose their poise as they did against
Denver on national TV last year. QB Elvis Grbac needs to show he
can be a consistent starter in this league. &QL; 
 &UR; CYBERSPACE HOME: www.kcchiefs.com. &QL; 
 &UR; 5. San Diego Chargers &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; 1998 ISSUE: 5-11, last. &QL; 
 &UR; FEARLESSS LEADER: Mike Riley (first year as NFL head coach). &QL; 
 &UR; HALL OF JUSTICE: Qualcomm Stadium (71,000). &QL; 
 &UR; THE NEW AVENGERS: Retreads Jim Harbaugh and Erik Kramer replace
disappointing rookie Ryan Leaf at QB. &QL; 
 &UR; STILL A GOOD  &UR; GUY: No matter where the Chargers line Junior Seau up
at LB, he's almost impossible to block. &QL; 
 &UR; GONE TO EVIL FORCES: LB Kurt Gouveia was one of their few
free-agent defections. &QL; 
 &UR; TEST OF WILL: The opener is a breeze. The Chargers are off. The end
of the season is scary, road games at Seattle, Miami and Denver in
three of the final four weeks. &QL; 
 &UR; WILL PREVAIL IF: The offense is good enough to give league's best
defense a few plays off. &QL; 
 &UR; WILL PERISH IF: Harbaugh and Kramer go down and the Chargers have
to use Leaf, who doesn't ever want to play for the Chargers again.
Imagine how many hecklers would target him on the road. &QL; 
 &UR; CYBERSPACE HOME: www.chargers.com. &QL;
</P>
