<HEADER>
A1418 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-MUTINY     09-05 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-MUTINY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUTINY MAUL REVOLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The Revolution's playoff chances should be
fading along with their confidence. But even after a 5-1 loss to
the Tampa Bay Mutiny Saturday &UR;  &LR; night, the Revolution remain in
contention for an Eastern Conference playoff berth.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Revolution will have to rediscover their mental
edge and also rebuild their defense if they expect success against
Kansas City here Tuesday and at Miami Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   This latest loss, the Revolution's eighth home defeat, continued
their nearly pointless second half of the season. They had a
strong, aggressive start of the game but were far too vulnerable
defensively to contend with a Tampa Bay team that has rejuvenated
itself for a playoff run.
</P>
<P>
   This was the most lopsided Revolution home defeat since a 5-1
loss to Los Angeles Aug. 22, 1998, the day Walter Zenga agreed to
join them as coach. Zenga initially appeared to have reorganized
the Revolution and kept them in contention for much of this season.
But they have collapsed in the second half, failing to win in
regulation time since July 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have learned in my life to deal with the positive and the
negative,'' Zenga said. ``And the only positive thing now is that
we are still alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have had a lot of time to try to understand what happened
since we beat New York July 4. The players are the same and the
practices are the same. This is my first year coaching and I've
made some mistakes. It's my responsibility, my job, and I have to
try to keep the team positive for Tuesday's game.''
</P>
<P>
   Zenga had reorganized the New England defense and appeared to
have transformed the team's mentality during the first half of the
season. But the Revolution have broken down much as they have in
the last three seasons, enduring long losing streaks and seldom
appearing to have the resourcefulness to overcome their problems.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday &UR;  &LR; night, Tampa Bay began with a defensive mindset, using
Raul Diaz Arce and Manny Lagos as strikers. The Revolution went on
the offensive early, but the Mutiny retained its composure.
</P>
<P>
   Paulo Dos Santos, making his first start since May 15, energized
the Revolution midfield while marking Carlos Valderrama. In the
14th minute, Dos Santos made an interception and carried over the
center line before curling a cross that Joe-Max Moore volleyed
right at goalkeeper Scott Garlick.
</P>
<P>
   Seconds later, a long pass to Valderrama caused a defensive
mixup, and Lagos converted.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Revolution quickly tied the score. Joe-Max Moore
set up the goal by chipping a soft pass for Mario Gori to head
toward Giovanni Savarese, who headed in from 10 yards in the 17th
minute. It was Savarese's seventh goal of the season, his first
since July 4.
</P>
<P>
   But in the 21st minute Tampa Bay went ahead again, as Lagos
capitalized on a Gori mistake and went in alone on Zenga.
</P>
<P>
   That goal seemed to deflate the Revolution. Diaz Arce, who
scored 18 goals for the Revolution last season, had two near misses
in the 34th minute, then scored in the 38th, rolling in a pass from
Mauricio Ramos.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution regrouped at halftime, and in the first 10
seconds of the second half Ivan McKinley volleyed a long John
Harkes pass just wide of the far post after colliding with Dominic
Kinnear, who was injured and replaced by Steve Trittschuh.
</P>
<P>
   In the third minute, the Mutiny sealed the victory as Lagos
outpaced Mike Burns and Brian Dunseth and crossed to Valderrama,
who scored for a 4-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Zenga soon brought in several substitutes, including Jeff Causey
in goal.
</P>
<P>
   Lagos set up Ramos for Tampa Bay's final goal in the 74th
minute.
</P>
<P>
   Zenga was philosophical, saying, ``That was symptomatic of our
situation: We have a great ball and miss by inches on a shot that
would have made the score 3-2, and they score on their first action
of the half.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
