<HEADLINE>
AFC CENTRAL CAPSULES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; 1. Jacksonville Jaguars &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; 1998 ISSUE: 11-5, first. &QL; 
 &UR; FEARLESS LEADER: Tom Coughlin (38-32). &QL; 
 &UR; HALL OF JUSTICE: ALLTELL Stadium (73,000). &QL; 
 &UR; THE NEW AVENGERS: The Jaguars not only added S Carnell Lake, they
took him away from division-rival Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STILL A GOOD  &UR; GUY: Fred Taylor was the leading rookie rusher a
year ago and finished second to Denver's Terrell Davis with 4.6
yards per carry. &QL; 
 &UR; GONE TO EVIL FORCES: A year ago, the Jaguars couldn't stop the run
so they let DTs John Jurkovic (Browns) and Kelvin Pritchett (Lions)
go in free agency. &QL; 
 &UR; TEST OF WILL: December is a rugged month for the Jaguars, who play
host to Pittsburgh and Super Bowl champion Denver and then travel
to division rivals Cleveland and Tennessee. &QL; 
 &UR; WILL PREVAIL IF: Quarterback Mark Brunell can stay healthy. He
takes too many risks. &QL; 
 &UR; WILL PERISH IF: The defense doesn't grow. Each year, the Jaguars
have problems stopping anybody in big games. &QL; 
 &UR; CYBERSPACE HOME: www.jaguars.nfl.com. &QL; 
 &UR; 2. Pittsburgh Steelers &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; 1998 ISSUE: 7-9, third.  &QL; 
 &UR; FEARLESS LEADER: Bill Cowher (76-47). &QL; 
 &UR; HALL OF JUSTICE: Three Rivers Stadium (59,600). &QL; 
 &UR; THE NEW AVENGERS: Ray Sherman had such a first season as offensive
coordinator, the Steelers fired him. He has been replaced by former
Chargers Coach Kevin Gilbride. &QL; 
 &UR; STILL A GOOD  &UR; GUY: Inside linebacker Levon Kirkland is a freak, a
270-pounder who can run sideline to sideline. &QL; 
 &UR; GONE TO EVIL FORCES: It has become a yearly occurence for the
Steelers to lose starters in free agency. Departing this year are S
Carnell Lake to Jacksonville and WR Charles Johnson to
Philadelphia. &QL; 
 &UR; TEST OF WILL: Will six games against the lowly Bengals and Ravens
and expansion Browns leave the Steelers bored? &QL; 
 &UR; WILL PREVAIL IF: QB Kordell Stewart doesn't self-destruct again. It
will be up to Gilbride to help Stewart grow up.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WILL PERISH IF: Stewart and Cowher go jaw-to-jaw on the
sideline again this season. It was great entertainment but didn't
help the Steelers win. &QL; 
 &UR; CYBERSPACE HOME: www.pittsburghsteelers.com. &QL; 
 &UR; 3. Tennessee Titans &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; 1998 ISSUE: 8-8, second. &QL; 
 &UR; FEARLESS LEADER: Jeff Fisher (32-38). &QL; 
 &UR; HALL OF JUSTICE: Adelphia Coliseum (67,000). &QL; 
 &UR; THE NEW AVENGERS: There will be a whole new defensive line. Free
agents Jason Fisk (formerly of Vikings) and Mike Jones (formerly of
Rams) and first-round pick Jevon Kearse are expected to start.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STILL A GOOD  &UR; GUY: Eddie George is considered one of the best
backs in the league after three consecutive 1,000-yard seasons. &QL; 
 &UR; GONE TO EVIL FORCES: C Mark Stepnoski never felt comfortable in
Tennessee and has returned to Dallas. &QL; 
 &UR; TEST OF WILL: There will be big changes if the Titans don't make
the playoffs, which could be determined by the final three games _
Atlanta (Dec. 19), Jacksonville (Dec. 26) and at Pittsburgh (Jan.
2).  &QL; 
 &UR; WILL PREVAIL IF: QB Steve McNair finally lives up to his potential.
He made few mistakes last season but also not many big plays. He
completed only two passes of more than 40 yards and averaged only
6.56 yards per attempt. &QL; 
 &UR; WILL PERISH IF: The coaches don't take the shackles off McNair and
let him use his athletic ability. He has been hurt by a
conservative offensive philosophy. &QL; 
 &UR; CYBERSPACE HOME: www.titansonline.com. &QL; 
 &UR; 4. Baltimore Ravens &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; 1998 ISSUE: 6-10, fourth. &QL; 
 &UR; FEARLESS LEADER: Brian Billick (first year as NFL head coach). &QL; 
 &UR; HALL OF JUSTICE: PSI Net Stadium (69,354). &QL; 
 &UR; THE NEW AVENGERS: Billick might have rebuilt Randall Cunningham's
career a year ago, but he will be tested this time with this motley
crew of QBs _ Scott Mitchell, Tony Banks and Stoney Case. &QL; 
 &UR; STILL A GOOD  &UR; GUY: The Cardinals bypassed Jonathan Ogden in the
draft three years ago and he has become one of the best OTs in the
league. &QL; 
 &UR; GONE TO EVIL FORCES: How did the Ravens let free-agent offensive
linemen Willie Williams (Saints) and Orlando Brown (Browns) get
away? &QL; 
 &UR; TEST OF WILL: The Ravens were given one of those dreaded
back-to-back-to-back trips. Midway through November, they play at
Cleveland, Jacksonville and Cincinnati. &QL; 
 &UR; WILL PREVAIL IF: Billick truly is an offensive genius. He has
little talent at quarterback and running back.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WILL PERISH IF: Mitchell is the starting QB. He couldn't even
win in Detroit playing alongside RB Barry Sanders and WR Herman
Moore. &QL; 
 &UR; CYBERSPACE HOME: baltimoreravens.com. &QL; 
 &UR; 5. Cincinnati Bengals &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; 1998 ISSUE: 3-13, last. &QL; 
 &UR; FEARLESS LEADER: Bruce Coslet (43-63). &QL; 
 &UR; HALL OF JUSTICE: Cinergy Field (60,389). &QL; 
 &UR; THE NEW AVENGERS: Nobody wants to play in Cincinnati. All you need
to know is that former Pittsburgh Steelers NT Oliver Gibson was the
prize of their free-agent class. &QL; 
 &UR; STILL A GOOD  &UR; GUY: RB Corey Dillon has helped the Bengals make up
for the Ki-Jana Carter disaster. &QL; 
 &UR; GONE TO EVIL FORCES: CB Ashley Ambrose got tired of losing. So, why
then did he pick New Orleans? &QL; 
 &UR; TEST OF WILL: A brutal four-game stretch in October and November
likely will end the Bengals' chances of making the playoffs. They
play Pittsburgh (Oct. 17), at Indianapolis (Oct. 24), Jacksonville
(Oct. 31) and at Seattle (Nov. 7). &QL; 
 &UR; WILL PREVAIL IF: Rookie quarterback Akili Smith is the real deal.
But because of a training camp holdout, he isn't expected to start
until midseason. &QL; 
 &UR; WILL PERISH IF: The Bengals' 3-4 defense still can't stop the run.
They were last a year ago, allowing 163.3 yards per game. &QL; 
 &UR; CYBERSPACE HOME: www.nfl.com/bengals. &QL; 
 &UR; 6. Cleveland Browns &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; 1998 ISSUE: Didn't play. &QL; 
 &UR; FEARLESS LEADER: Chris Palmer (first year as NFL head coach). &QL; 
 &UR; HALL OF JUSTICE: Cleveland Browns Stadium (72,000). &QL; 
 &UR; THE NEW AVENGERS: Everybody. This is an expansion team. &QL; 
 &UR; STILL A GOOD  &UR; GUY: Former Cardinals LB Jamir Miller has been the
team's best player in camp. &QL; 
 &UR; GONE TO EVIL FORCES: The only reason the expansion Browns are in
existence is because owner Art Modell moved the old Browns to
Baltimore. &QL; 
 &UR; TEST OF WILL:The Browns likely will be favored in one game this
year _ the Jan. 2 open date. &QL; 
 &UR; WILL PREVAIL IF: They can find a running back to play behind their
experienced offensive line. &QL; 
 &UR; WILL PERISH IF: They have to pass or kick a field goal. So far, the
Browns have been unable to do either. &QL; 
 &UR; CYBERSPACE HOME: www.clevelandbrowns.com. &QL;
</P>
