<HEADLINE>
AFC EAST CAPSULES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; 1. New York Jets &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; 1998 ISSUE: 12-4, first. &QL; 
 &UR; FEARLESS LEADER: Bill Parcells (141-98-1). &QL; 
 &UR; HALL OF JUSTICE: Giants Stadium (78,739). &QL; 
 &UR; THE NEW AVENGERS: Parcells thinks former Broncos All-Pro S Steve
Atwater will be the glue to hold the secondary together. &QL; 
 &UR; STILL A GOOD GUY: WRs Keyshawn Johnson and Wayne Chrebet have
kissed and made up. They combined for 158 catches for more than
2,200 yards and 18 touchdowns. &QL; 
 &UR; GONE TO EVIL FORCES: Wasn't Kyle Brady the Jets' TE of the future? &QL; 
 &UR; TEST OF WILL: Games against Miami twice in three weeks in December
could determine the division crown. &QL; 
 &UR; WILL PREVAIL IF: The Jets' makeshift offensive line can give star
RB Curtis Martin some room to run.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WILL PERISH IF: QB Vinny Testaverde doesn't stay healthy.
Backup Rick Mirer couldn't handle Chicago. How is he going to deal
with New York? &QL; 
 &UR; CYBERSPACE HOME: www.newyorkjets.com. &QL; 
 &UR; 2. Miami Dolphins &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; 1998 ISSUE: 10-6, second. &QL; 
 &UR; FEARLESS LEADER: Jimmy Johnson (79-60). &QL; 
 &UR; HALL OF JUSTICE: Pro Player Stadium (75,192). &QL; 
 &UR; THE NEW AVENGERS: Jimmy Johnson figured if he drafted enough RBs,
he'd find at least one keeper. Rookies J.J. Johnson, a second-round
pick, or Cecil ``The Diesel'' Collins, a fifth-round pick, could
start. &QL; 
 &UR; STILL A GOOD GUY: It would be nice to see QB Dan Marino get back to
the Super Bowl. &QL; 
 &UR; GONE TO EVIL FORCES: Johnson rarely loses anybody he wants to keep.
WR Charles Jordan was the biggest loss, going to Seattle in free
agency. &QL; 
 &UR; TEST OF WILL: The Dolphins will find out how good they are quickly
when they open at Super Bowl champion Denver on ``Monday Night
Football''. &QL; 
 &UR; WILL PREVAIL IF: Half their team doesn't end up behind bars. &QL; 
 &UR; WILL PERISH IF: They don't get to the Super Bowl soon. Johnson
doesn't have a 10-year plan. &QL; 
 &UR; CYBERSPACE HOME: www.miamidolphins.com. &QL; 
 &UR; 3. Buffalo Bills &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; 1998 ISSUE: 10-6, second. &QL; 
 &UR; FEARLESS LEADER: Wade Phillips (27-27). &QL; 
 &UR; HALL OF JUSTICE: Ralph Wilson Stadium (75,300). &QL; 
 &UR; THE NEW AVENGERS: First-round pick Antoine Winfield could start at
CB. &QL; 
 &UR; STILL A GOOD GUY: DE Bruce Smith doesn't act or play like a
36-year-old. &QL; 
 &UR; GONE TO EVIL FORCES: Didn't lose anyone significant. &QL; 
 &UR; TEST OF WILL: Back-to-back road games in December at the Cardinals
and New England could make or break the Bills' season. &QL; 
 &UR; WILL PREVAIL IF: QB Doug Flutie can continue his magic of a year
ago. But how long do you keep $5 million-a-year QB Rob Johnson on
the bench? &QL; 
 &UR; WILL PERISH IF: Starting RB Antowain Smith doesn't get healthy. &QL; 
 &UR; CYBERSPACE HOME: www.buffalobills.com. &QL; 
 &UR; 4. New England Patriots &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; 1998 ISSUE: 9-7, fourth. &QL; 
 &UR; FEARLESS LEADER: Pete Carroll (20-15). &QL; 
 &UR; HALL OF JUSTICE: Foxboro Stadium (60,292). &QL; 
 &UR; THE NEW AVENGERS: A season-ending injury to veteran middle
linebacker Ted Johnson will force first-round pick Andy Katzenmoyer
to start. &QL; 
 &UR; STILL A GOOD GUY: The Patriots have made a lot of drafting
mistakes, but cornerback Ty Law isn't one of them. &QL; 
 &UR; GONE TO EVIL FORCES: Punter Tom Tupa is the latest to spurn the
Patriots to rejoin Bill Parcells' Jets. &QL; 
 &UR; TEST OF WILL: What a brutal early schedule. The Patriots open at
the Jets and play three playoff teams in three weeks in October _
Miami, Denver and at Arizona. &QL; 
 &UR; WILL PREVAIL IF: They can find a RB. Rookie Kevin Faulk is going to
have to produce. &QL; 
 &UR; WILL PERISH IF: The running game is so bad, QB Drew Bledsoe will
have to throw on almost every down. &QL; 
 &UR; CYBERSPACE HOME: www.patriots.com. &QL; 
 &UR; 5. Indianapolis Colts &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; 1998 ISSUE: 3-13, fifth. &QL; 
 &UR; FEARLESS LEADER: Jim Mora (96-99). &QL; 
 &UR; HALL OF JUSTICE: RCA Dome (56,637). &QL; 
 &UR; THE NEW AVENGERS: RB Edgerrin James has a chance to be the league's
Rookie of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STILL A GOOD GUY: TE Ken Dilger doesn't get much publicity but
is very steady. &QL; 
 &UR; GONE TO EVIL FORCES: RB Marshall Faulk was sent to St. Louis in a
controversial draft-day trade. &QL; 
 &UR; TEST OF WILL: A three-week stretch of home games against the Jets
and New England sandwiched around a trip to Miami will show if the
Colts can be taken seriously. &QL; 
 &UR; WILL PREVAIL IF: Second-year QB Peyton Manning has a sophomore
season anything close to his brilliant rookie year. &QL; 
 &UR; WILL PERISH IF: Free-agent acquisitions Chad Bratzke and Shawn King
aren't dominant players. The Colts couldn't stop anybody last
year. &QL; 
 &UR; CYBERSPACE HOME: www.colts.com. &QL;
</P>
