<HEADER>
A1422 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     09-05 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDERSTUDY STEALS OPENING SHOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ The quarterback stood at the top of the
staircase, waiting for his close-up. In his junior year, the
cameras finally rolled for him. He stepped into the bright lights,
blinked ... and was bowled over by the fabulous freshman waiting in
the wings.
</P>
<P>
   But enough about Jim Bonds having his star turn pre-empted by
Tommy Maddox in 1990. If UCLA's season opener against Boise State
was a preview of its Pacific-10 season, the final year of the
decade could end up following the same script as the first.
</P>
<P>
   The new Bonds? It might be Drew Bennett, a marvelous athlete
many believe is miscast as a quarterback. He made his starting
debut behind center Saturday evening at the Rose Bowl, but it's not
a stretch to imagine him lining up at receiver before his college
career is done, catching passes thrown by Cory Paus.
</P>
<P>
   As far as debuts go, Bennett's in the Bruins' 38-7 victory over
Boise State fell somewhere between this summer's ``The Sixth
Sense'' and ``Wild Wild West.''
</P>
<P>
   He fell off the proverbial horse early on. His first pass was
one only John Wooden could love, the redshirt junior bouncing the
football to Brad Melsby.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett's third throw was swatted at the line of scrimmage and
his fourth was intercepted.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't exactly how Bennett pictured himself coming out of the
gate after cooling his spurs behind Cade McNown for three years and
35 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have a very good first series,'' Bennett said. ``I
came off the field and I was kind of (ticked) off.''
</P>
<P>
   Bennett, splitting time with Paus, misfired on four of his five
passes in the opening half. His confidence at the intermission had
to have been a little black-and-blue but Bennett knew what he had
to do.
</P>
<P>
   He dusted himself off, climbed back in the saddle and threw a
rope to Randy Hakes in UCLA's second series of the third quarter
that Hakes high-tailed in for a 65-yard score.
</P>
<P>
   It was the fourth of six consecutive passes Bennett completed in
the quarter. ``I was a little upset with my first-half
performance,'' Bennett said. ``I was kind of embarrassed, actually.
I came out in the second half with the attitude that I'm going to
just put the ball in there where it goes. I wanted to prove that I
may start slow but I'll get the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   If Bennett was forcing his passes instead of letting his
mechanics flow, there was a reason. It's no trifling thing,
replacing a four-year starter and a first-round NFL pick. Bennett
could be forgiven his opening-night jitters.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Bennett's numbers _ 8 of 16 for 120 yards _ were
respectable if not redoubtable. It's a good thing he steadied his
nerves in the second half because the setting will be none too
serene come Saturday when the Bruins travel to Columbus to take on
Ohio State.
</P>
<P>
   The Buckeyes have a couple of bulls in linebacker Na'il Diggs
and Brent Johnson who'll look at Bennett's jersey and see red.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to change a thing,'' fourth-year head coach
Bob Toledo said of his quarterbacks. ``We'll start Drew and we'll
play Cory.''
</P>
<P>
   Never mind Carson Palmer across town. The best-kept secret in
the Pac-10 may have the initials CP, all right, as in Cory Paus.
</P>
<P>
   Paus connected on the first pass he tried, to tight end Bryan
Fletcher, and finished with 12 completions in 18 attempts for 128
yards.
</P>
<P>
   Midway through the second quarter Paus threw a 5-yard scoring
pass to tight end Gabe Crecion to become the first Bruin
quarterback in 11 years to throw a touchdown in his first game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know what it was going to feel like,'' Paus said. ``I
was just winging it. I'm sure it'll be a lot different next week.''
</P>
<P>
   As long as he brings to the task the same presence and pinpoint
passing, Paus should be fine. He has a more charismatic personality
than the quieter Bennett and on this night he definitely was seeing
dead people. They were called defensive backs. With that kind of
clairvoyance, Paus makes it easy for Bruins fans everywhere to
divine the future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
