<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990905.0063 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-05 01:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1427 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKL-LIBERTY-COMETS-HN     09-05 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-LIBERTY-COMETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By W.H. STICKNEY JR.  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Fifty-two feet and one tick of the scoreboard clock separated the
Comets from their third WNBA championship Saturday afternoon at
Compaq Center.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fifty-two feet Teresa Weatherspoon covered with one long and
improbable shot that caromed off the backboard and into the basket
after time expired to give the Liberty an improbable 68-67 victory
that crushed the hearts of the Comets.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most disappointing loss I've had in all the years
I've been coaching,'' Comets coach Van Chancellor said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt good when it left my hands,'' said Weatherspoon, who
was 3-of-5 from the field. ``I was just praying it would go in to
get us to Game 3.''
</P>
<P>
   There will be a rubber game at 2:30 p.m. today at Compaq Center
to decide who walks away with the 1999 WNBA title.
</P>
<P>
   But what transpires might be anticlimactic to one of the most
dramatic moments in all of professional sports.
</P>
<P>
   Until Saturday, the Comets never had lost a playoff game at
Compaq Center (6-0). They had a WNBA-record 14-game home winning
streak that included two playoff victories over the Los Angeles
Sparks in the Western Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   Weatherspoon destroyed the perfect game, no-hitter and shutout
with one Hail Mary toss that spoiled the three-peat celebration for
the sellout crowd of 16,285.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather put it on my shoulders (to win a last-second game)
than to leave it to another of our players,'' Weatherspoon said.
</P>
<P>
   The Comets led 62-58 when Janeth Arcain, off an assist from
Cynthia Cooper, converted a reverse layup with 2:41 left.
</P>
<P>
   The lead alternated over the next 2:38 before a turnaround shot
by Tina Thompson with 2.4 seconds left gave the Comets a 67-65 lead
and appeared to put them in the driver's seat.
</P>
<P>
   But Kym Hampton, who plans to retire at the end of the season,
tossed the inbounds pass to Weatherspoon, who dribbled up near
midcourt and launched the shot that killed the Comets' party.
</P>
<P>
   It's a shot, Weatherspoon said, several Liberty players try each
day at the end of practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of us just flip it up and see what we can do,''
Weatherspoon said. ``Each one of us gets only three shots. If you
don't make it in three, you're out of there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Comets looked like they were on the way to victory in the
first half after taking a 37-23 lead.
</P>
<P>
   They had been excellent from the free-throw line (16-for-21,
including 13 straight), good on offense after a slow start and
tenacious enough on defense for the champagne to be iced in
anticipation of a three-peat.
</P>
<P>
   New York missed 13 of its first 14 shots and 21 of 30 through
the first 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Crystal Robinson (21 points) couldn't find the basket, and until
midway of the opening period, the Liberty had scored only two
points.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were on two for a long, long time and couldn't get anything
going,'' said coach Richie Adubato.
</P>
<P>
   But there was a dramatic reversal of form once play resumed in
the second half. The Comets' intensity was replaced by a cavalier
attitude toward playing offense and defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't come out like a championship team in the second
half,'' Cooper said. ``We didn't come out like we were ready to win
a championship. We came out like we were going to cruise through
the second half and New York had other plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a veteran team; they got aggressive on defense; they
got the job done on the offensive end; they knocked down some
3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that was all she wrote.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson got out of her first-half shooting slump by scoring 11
points during a 14-2 New York run that cut the lead to 39-37.
</P>
<P>
   The Comets, meanwhile, were in full retreat in the face of a
half-court trap and rapidly switching defense employed by the
Liberty.
</P>
<P>
   The Comets didn't score a field goal in the first 8:19 of the
second half.
</P>
<P>
   Arcain got that first basket for a tie at 42. She was fouled on
the play by Weatherspoon and completed the three-point play to give
the lead to the Comets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just hard to get the momentum back once you've lost it,''
said Cooper, who was 1-for-10 from the floor and finished with 12
points.
</P>
<P>
   What the Comets lost, the Liberty found, perhaps because of the
halftime speech of Adubato.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, I told them that right near the end of the first half I
thought we were playing better basketball,'' said the former coach
of the Dallas Mavericks and Orlando Magic. ``I said we couldn't
play any worse than we did in the first 10 minutes, and if we
executed our offense and went to simplify our offense we'd be
better off.''
</P>
<P>
   A little bit of luck didn't hurt. Consider this:
</P>
<P>
   With 28.4 seconds left, Thompson missed one of two free throws
and the Comets led 65-63. Robinson tied it at 65 on a bucket with
16.3 seconds left. Thompson's shot with 2.4 seconds left put the
Comets back on top, and the Liberty was out of timeouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good thing we didn't have a timeout,'' Adubato said,
``or I would have called it and set up a play that wouldn't have
worked. We have a play designed for any time there's under three
seconds left, when we throw the ball the length of the court.''
</P>
<P>
   The Liberty didn't need that play. It had Weatherspoon.
</P>
<P>
   And she delivered a little redemption for Adubato.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've lost games like that, and I've been coaching a long
time,'' he said. ``This is the first game I've ever won on a lucky
shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it was due me after all these years.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-99 0158EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990905.0064 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-05 02:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1428 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKL-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     09-05 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DALE ROBERTSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
HOW do you count it? You can't. No way. She didn't call glass.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I didn't call anything,'' Teresa Weatherspoon said. ``I just
let it go. When it left my hand, I knew it was good.''
</P>
<P>
   Honestly, those of us courtside right behind her did, too. You
could see it all the way, flying straight and true, then smacking
off the middle of the backboard square like a smart bomb and
swishing through the net, a latter-day 52-foot shot heard 'round
the world.
</P>
<P>
   Move over, Bobby Thomson, and, yes, start spreading the news.
New York ain't leavin' today. The WNBA's third season isn't over,
and the Comets aren't yet 3-for-3 champions, a little bit of
prematurely spewed confetti notwithstanding.
</P>
<P>
   Oops.
</P>
<P>
   But you can hardly blame the poor people charged with pulling
those switches. With 2.4 seconds left Saturday, Tina Thompson had
kissed a nifty turnaround jumper off the glass from just to the
right of the paint _ a pretty cool shot in its own right, by the
way, under the tense circumstances _ to give the Comets an
apparently signed, sealed, delivered 67-65 victory for their
much-coveted three-peat.
</P>
<P>
   Even with 0.0 seconds left, it was still the Comets' game
because Weatherspoon's running, tryin'-one Hail Mary from beyond
midcourt was airborne and the sellout Compaq Center crowd was
starting to whoop its collective fool head off. The WNBA's
championship trophy was being carried to the court as the ball
slapped the glass and careened in.
</P>
<P>
   Weatherspoon dropped to her knees and fell backward. Within
seconds, her Liberty teammates were all over her, creating a giant
pile of happiness.
</P>
<P>
   The Comets? They didn't know what to do. Neither did the fans.
Other than the sound of jaws dropping and the muffled shrieks
coming from the Liberty's human anthill, the building was quiet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe she made that shot,'' the Comets' Cynthia
Cooper said afterward. ``I can't believe she made that shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Seconds earlier she had encountered Weatherspoon in the
interview area, and, after giving her longtime rival a bearhug,
Coop shrieked, ``I can't believe you made that shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Coop was laughing, though, and why not? Honestly, how do you cry
over such a crazy thing, after everything she has had to cry about
these last few weeks? Sudden death might be a tough prospect, but
it's not like real life and death.
</P>
<P>
   Probably never has the outcome of any game of such import, of
such magnitude, been so suddenly and outrageously and miraculously
reversed. One second the Comets are again on top of the world; the
next second they are wiping the blood from their noses and trying
to clear their heads.
</P>
<P>
   It might well have been the most important bucket in the history
of women's basketball in the United States, but that will be of
little consolation to coach Van Chancellor and his stunned charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely the most heartbreaking defeat I've ever been
associated with,'' Chancellor said.
</P>
<P>
   So Game 3 is today. Everybody returns with backs to the wall,
save for the Peacock network. Lots of curious folks, most of them
in the monster New York market, will hear about the ending of Game
2 and turn on their TVs. A seminal moment for women's hoops in
America? It could be.
</P>
<P>
   Great for the sport, bad for the Comets. But Cooper, the Comet
most desperate to win No. 3 for No. 10 _ the late Kim Perrot, her
best friend _ found a way to be philosophical in defeat. She didn't
blame Weatherspoon's silver spoon of a trey. She blamed herself and
her teammates for lacking the intensity to finish what they
started.
</P>
<P>
   After 10 minutes, the Comets led 17-2. Hence, Coop was of the
opinion it probably shouldn't have come down to any 52-foot banker
at the buzzer.
</P>
<P>
   She's right, you know.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a terribly played game,'' Cooper said, winning points
for brutal honesty. ``Especially in the second half. And especially
for the Houston Comets. If we're going to win a third championship,
we've got to play better.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news is that we get a second chance to play better.''
</P>
<P>
   Coop realizes her role in same. Liberty coach Richie Adubato had
a suffocating defensive plan for the WNBA's most prolific scorer,
and his players worked it to perfection. Her every step dogged by a
rotating core of Libertarians, Coop made just one basket and
managed but 10 shots, although she did go to the free-throw line
often enough to sink 10 of 12.
</P>
<P>
   If Coop doesn't fly the coop today and find some daylight, the
Comets are in trouble. No, they aren't. This is still their series
to lose.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to get Cynthia more looks, and better looks, at the
basket,'' Chancellor said.
</P>
<P>
   As he spoke, he looked as though he had been run over by a
truck.
</P>
<P>
   An impossibly hard season just got harder. But maybe this was
Kim's fault. Ever the hoops junkie, perhaps she wanted to see
another game. And, these days, she has connections.
</P>
<P>
   We hope.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
