<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MADDON RE-DECORATES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ One change in the Anaheim Angels' clubhouse
that was immediately noticeable Saturday morning was the absence of
the two 60-inch television screens that sat in the middle of the
clubhouse and faced opposite directions.
</P>
<P>
   Interim manager Joe Maddon said the removal of the TVs wasn't a
punishment for the players.
</P>
<P>
   ``We discussed it and determined (removing the televisions) adds
an airy attitude to the clubhouse,'' Maddon said. ``It was
cluttered before.''
</P>
<P>
   Prior to Saturday's game, instead of watching other baseball
games or football games on TV, they talked to each other and
listened to music.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consulted with several interior designers,'' Maddon joked.
``And they determined the TVs weren't suitable.''
</P>
<P>
   A visit: Maddon and the other Angels coaches were paid a visit
by former manager Terry Collins Saturday after the game. Collins
did not go into the clubhouse, instead going into equipment manager
Ken Higdon's office to chat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesterday when I came down (to the clubhouse) I tried to talk
to him but I couldn't do it,'' Maddon said before his visit with
Collins. ``I tend to get really emotional. I gave him a hug and
said I'd like to talk to you in about two days when I could talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to totally verbalize how much I appreciate what he did
for me. I know he knows that, but I want him to hear it come from
my mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   No big changes: Maddon doesn't plan any drastic changes in the
final month of the season, other than what he does himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the biggest differences is what I do,'' he said.
``Nobody here knows how to run the computer.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not that the other Angels coaches are computer illiterate,
it's that Maddon is a computer whiz and has all his programs --
consisting of stats and trends on opposing players -- set up in a
way that is familiar to him.
</P>
<P>
   Maddon regularly prints out the day's lineup sheet on his
computer, but Saturday's was hand-written because Maddon was too
busy to get on the computer.
</P>
<P>
   This is Maddon's third tour of duty as the Angels' interim
manager. He was 8-14 in 1996 after taking over for Marcel
Lachemann, who resigned. Last season, he was 6-2 when Collins was
suspended for eight games after the club's fight in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not easy, especially under these circumstances,'' Maddon
said. ``The routine itself is not difficult because I've done it
before, it's not like I don't know what to do. But the
circumstances surrounding the situation make it difficult to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Transaction: The Angels purchased the contract of pitcher Brian
Cooper from Triple-A Edmonton. Cooper, a 1992 graduate of Glendora
High School, was 2-1 with a 3.77 ERA in five starts for Edmonton
this year. Before that, he was 10-5 with a 3.30 ERA in 22 starts
for double-A Erie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm relieved and excited,'' said Cooper, who is expected to
start Tuesday's game against the White Sox at Edison Field. ``I had
been getting calls from friends and family who were reading in the
papers that they were planning on calling me up. It's a big
relief.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper said he didn't expect to reach the big leagues this
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``From what I heard I was going to stay at double-A the whole
year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Also: Shortstop Gary DiSarcina did not play Saturday because he
was stiff and sore after sliding awkwardly into third base with a
triple Friday night. ... Mad-don said the Angels will bring in
coaching help sometime next week. It isn't related to the departure
of Collins, Maddon said. Teams usually bring in coaches from the
minor league system after the minor league season is complete. ...
Lost in all the news Friday was the presentation of the Rawlings
Gold Glove award to center fielder Jim Edmonds for the 1998 season.
It was Edmonds' second Gold Glove. ... The Angels and Yankees play
the third game of their four-game series today at 5:05. Chuck
Finley (8-11, 4.74 ERA) will start for Anaheim against New York's
Ed Yarnall (0-0,0.00).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
