<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-05 02:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1434 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-UCLA-REWRITE-LADN     09-05 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-REWRITE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAUS LIFTS UCLA TO VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(OPTIONAL: Adds quotes, details) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ From the FBI investigation to the disabled
parking scandal and his son-in-law's successful battle with a brain
tumor, it was a grueling offseason for Bruins coach Bob Toledo. He
was as exhausted when training camp began as he usually is in
November.
</P>
<P>
   But Toledo couldn't have scripted a better start to his fourth
regular season _ with or without 12 suspended players and injured
receiver Danny Farmer.
</P>
<P>
   In UCLA's 38-7 victory over Boise State on Saturday night before
46,752 at the Rose Bowl, the kicking game held, the defense was
superb and the quarterback quagmire lurched toward a resolution as
second-stringer Cory Paus outplayed starter Drew Bennett.
</P>
<P>
   A redshirt freshman from New Lenox, Ill., Paus completed 7 of 9
passes for 78 yards and directed two touchdown drives in the
decisive first half. The second touchdown _ a 5-yard pass to
tight-end Gabe Crecion _ gave the Bruins a 24-0 advantage five
minutes before halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Accurate and savvy, Paus completed 12 of 18 passes for 128 yards
in a performance reminiscent of Cade McNown's uncanny play as a
true freshman in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know what it was going to feel like,'' Paus said. ``I
was just winging it. I'm sure it'll be a lot different next week.''
</P>
<P>
   Bennett recovered from a 2-of-9 start _ ``I was kind of
embarrassed,'' _ and looked sharp in the second half. Afterward,
Toledo said Bennett will start Saturday at Ohio State, with Paus
playing early and often.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not changing a thing,'' Toledo said. ``We'll do exactly
like we did this week.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA's defense, maligned last season, was organized and
effective in its first game under new defensive coordinator Bob
Field. Despite missing five suspended starters, the Bruins held
Boise State scoreless for 57 minutes, until a coverage breakdown
foiled their first shutout in three years.
</P>
<P>
   And how's this for role reversal? While the offense struggled in
the first half, the defense broke the game open with interceptions
on consecutive plays in the second quarter. First, safety Julius
Williams scored on a 53-yard-interception return, then safety Joey
Strycula plucked a screen pass to set up the Paus-to-Crecion
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   In attitude and execution, it was a starkly different defense
than last year's version.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to prove a point,'' Williams said. ``We had to show the
defense isn't like last year. We had things to prove. We're not
soft. We don't surf. We made some mistakes last year, but this is a
new year.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Toledo bemoaned the sloppiness (eight combined
turnovers) and UCLA's sporadic running game (3.7-yards per carry),
the victory nevertheless negated the two-game disabled
parking-suspensions. The No.17 Bruins can do no worse than split
their first two games, the same fate most expected with a full
roster.
</P>
<P>
   What happens next week _ whether they execute in Ohio Stadium
like they executed against a Big West team _ remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll know a lot more Saturday,'' Field said.
</P>
<P>
   About the defense and about the quarterbacks. True to Toledo's
pregame strategy, Bennett played three series, then Paus entered
with 5:18 left in the first quarter. He completed his first pass, a
screen to tight-end Bryan Fletcher, then hit Brad Melsby for a
first down near midfield. The drive sputtered, but UCLA's defense
quickly forced a punt and Paus returned to lead the first touchdown
drive of the season.
</P>
<P>
   It began with a screen to tailback DeShaun Foster, who scooted
for 23 yards to Boise State's 45. Six plays later, facing
third-and-12, Paus lofted a delicate pass to Fletcher, who made a
fabulous diving catch at the Broncos' 4. Foster plowed over
linebacker Bryan Johnson for a 10-0 lead with 11 minutes left in
the half.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins' defense took command on the following series. On
third-and-6, Boise State quarterback Bart Hendricks passed to
tight-end Dave Stachelski, who was battling Williams for position
near midfield. Before the ball arrived, Stachelski stumbled, giving
Williams an uncontested interception.
</P>
<P>
   A converted cornerback playing his first game at safety,
Williams looked like a tailback as he raced 53 yards down the right
sideline for a touchdown that gave the Bruins a 17-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were jockeying for position, he slipped, and I stepped in
front,'' Williams said. ``I saw some space to the right and took
off. I didn't know I was going to the house (end zone).''
</P>
<P>
   Boise State's next play _ i.e., Hendricks' next mistake _ broke
the game open. With defensive end Kenyon Coleman charging hard,
Hendricks panicked and threw a screen pass to Strycula, giving the
Bruins possession at Boise State's 32.
</P>
<P>
   After three tough runs by Jermaine Lewis, Paus rolled right and
connected with Crecion for a touchdown and a 24-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the third quarter, Bennett tossed his first career
touchdown, a 65-yard pass to tight-end Randy Hakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not happy with my performance, but I think I did fine for
the first time,'' said Bennett, who completed 8 of 16 passes for
120 yards. ``I was a little upset at my first-half performance. I
was tentative.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
