<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLANOTES-REWRITE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIGHT ENDS LEND A HAND TO YOUNG QUARTERBACKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(OPTIONAL: Adds quotes, details) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ UCLA's receivers are among the best in the
nation, and its tailback tandem of DeShaun Foster and Jermaine
Lewis is the focus of every opposing defense. But Saturday night,
the Bruins unleashed their talented tight ends on unsuspecting
Boise State.
</P>
<P>
   The result was five catches for 105 yards and two touchdowns _
and some very relieved rookie quarterbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't something that was in the game plan, it just worked
out that way,'' said sophomore tight end Bryan Fletcher, whose
diving catch set up UCLA's first touchdown in a 38-7 victory.
``Cory (Paus) and Drew (Bennett) were a little nervous, and the
tight ends are one of the safest throws on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   If Fletcher's catch established the tight ends' presence, then
Randy Hakes and Gabe Crecion substantiated it. Hakes, who had one
reception last year, caught a 65-yard touchdown pass from Bennett,
and Crecion, who sat out last season, caught a 5-yard touchdown
pass from Paus that gave the Bruins a 24-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Helping hands: With 12 suspended players, the Bruins were
counting on a slew of inexperienced players to contribute, and they
did not disappoint.
</P>
<P>
   _Sophomore safety Julius Williams, a converted cornerback,
returned an interception 53 yards for the game-breaking touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   _Senior safety Joey Strycula, whose primary duty until this
season was holding on place-kicks, intercepted a pass that set up
the Bruins' final touchdown of the first half.
</P>
<P>
   _Freshman cornerback Joe Hunter, who redshirted last season,
prevented a Boise State touchdown by intercepting a pass at the 6.
</P>
<P>
   _Receiver-turned-cornerback Paul Nelson, a freshman, recovered a
fumbled punt early in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Touching tribute: Before the game, UCLA honored former Boise
State player and Covina resident Paul Reyna, who died last month
from injuries suffered during practice. Reyna's parents, Carolyn
Gusman and Art Reyna, were honorary captains for Boise State.
</P>
<P>
   Injury report: Defensive end Travor Turner's sprained right knee
was UCLA's most serious injury of the night. He'll be evaluated
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   No show: Because of technical difficulties, the postgame
fireworks show was rescheduled for the Sept. 18 game against Fresno
State. Anyone holding a single-game ticket for Boise State can
redeem it for a general admission ticket on Sept. 18.
</P>
<P>
   And finally: Saturday's game at Ohio State starts at 5 p.m.
</P>
</TEXT>
