<P>
   PALESTINIAN-PRISONERS_RAMALLAH, West Bank _ Portrait of a
Palestinian family that may soon be touched by the the accord
between the Palestinians and Israelis. The sons of Palestinian
mother Raba Abu Radaha Sunday might soon be released from their
Israeli prison as a result of the new pact. One son, Amir, was
convicted of murdering a Palestinian for helping Israeli s. The
other, Sahdi, hit a Jewish woman settler in the head with a bar. To
their family, they are prisoners of a war that is now ending.
(Kaplow, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-PACTQ&AMP;A_JERUSALEM _ A Q&AMP;A on the Sharm El-Sheikh
agreement the Israeli Cabinet approved Sunday. The pact restarts
the Wye River Memorandum peace process. (Kaplow, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   AIRPARTICLES _ Scientists from around the world are wrapping up
a month-long study in Atlanta to determine the best ways of
measuring and anaylzing ultrafine particles that pollute the air in
large urban areas, and which may be killing thousands of Americans
per year. The $1.4 million study is a prelude to other intensive
studies that will be kicked off around the nation to determine the
best ways of reducing levels of pollution known as particulate
matter. Researchers say exceedingly tiny particles of dust, soot,
sulfates, metals and other pollutants spewed out by car exhausts,
smokestacks and construction and farming may be even more dangerous
than ozone. Some studies say that particulate matter may be
responsible for up to 950 deaths per year in metro Atlanta alone.
(Seabrook, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) 25.
</P>
