<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-DAGESTAN (Moscow) _ A powerful bomb demolished an
apartment building full of Russian officers and their families in
Dagestan late Saturday night, as Islamic militants mounted a
ferocious assault in the Russian republic. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-CARBOMBS (Jerusalem) _ Two apparent car bombs explode in
separate Israeli cities, in each case killing the bombers, shortly
after the Israelis and Palestinians sign a new peace accord. By
Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   TIMOR-VIOLENCE (Dili, Indonesia) _ As the outside world looked
on in horror and the Indonesian government continued its promises
and evasions, armed thugs systematically take over the territory of
East Timor, terrorizing residents and trapping U.N. workers in
their compound. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-ELECTIONS (Berlin) _ German Chancellor Gerhard
Schroeder's Social Democrats appear to suffer setbacks in two state
elections, as an anti-foreigner far-right party makes a strong
showing. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-SCANDAL (Moscow) _ On a reported kickback scandal that
may, or may not, touch the Kremlin. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIER-ARRESTED (Frankfurt, Germany) _ More on the arrest of
Martin R. Frankel, a fugitive Connecticut money manager suspected
of defrauding insurance companies of millions of dollars. By Edmund
L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-PEACE (Belfast, Northern Ireland) _ Saying that failure
would be ``unforgivable,'' former U.S. Sen. George Mitchell begins
a rescue effort Monday to halt the disintegration of the Northern
Ireland peace agreement. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-PAYRAISE (Beijing) _ The government announces sweeping
increases in salaries, pensions and welfare payments for 84 million
people, describing the move as a birthday gift as the country
prepares to celebrate the 50th anniversary of the founding of the
People's Republic. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   PERU-ORPHANS (Vicus, Peru) _ An estimated 50,000 orphans were
created in the fighting that raged in Peru between 1987 and 1993,
and psychologists speak of a coming harvest of resentment, drug
abuse and alcoholism from children who have been traumatized by the
fighting. By Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   EDUC-STANDARDS _ In a big change, states across the nation are
enforcing uniform school standards, giving successful teachers
bonuses and generally raising the level of student performance. By
Tamar Lewin.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-CUBANS (Miami) _ Two years after the death of the undisputed
leader of Cuban Americans in Miami, no single leader has emerged.
No one has Jorge Mas Canosa's charisma, influence and ties to
Washington. Besides, the Cuban American population, dominant in
South Florida, no longer speaks with one voice, nor is it
controlled by any single viewpoint. By Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   MRSCLINTON-CLEMENCY-FLAP (New York) _ Local fallout from First
Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton's statements that her husband should
retract his clemency offer to 16 imprisoned members of a Puerto
Rican separatist group because they have failed to renounce future
acts of violence. By Jonathan P. Hicks.
</P>
<P>
   NY-CARDINAL-REACT (New York) _ At Catholic churches across the
city Sunday, the list of the sick to be prayed for included a
well-known name: Cardinal John O'Connor, who, it was disclosed
Saturday, underwent surgery for a brain tumor last week. By Amy
Waldman.
</P>
<P>
   UNIONS-CLERGY (Chicago) _ In Protestant and Roman Catholic
churches on the Sunday before Labor Day, evidence of increasing
ties between the unions and the clergy. By Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   VET-CLUBS-DECLINE (Berwyn, Ill.) _ Veterans clubs are dying as
the number of World War II veterans, who sustained clubs like the
American Legion, diminishes rapidly. We go to the clubs, or what's
left of them, and talk to the aging veterans in places like Berwyn,
a working class town near Chicago. By Dirk Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   BOCCI-GEEK-CHIC (Los Gatos, Calif.) _ The latest craze among the
tekkies in Silicon Valley is bocci, the Old World game associated
with old Italian men. But having conquered the world, the nerds and
geeks have little else to do but try something old. By Evelyn
Nieves.
</P>
<P>
   HOMELESS-KIDNEY-DONOR (Alexandria, Va.) _ An unemployed woman
who donated a kidney to a little boy she helped care for has been
staying in a homeless shelter since being evicted from a public
housing project where she had been living in violation of the
rules. By Irvin Molotsky.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (Moving in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   STATES-RIGHTS (Washington) _ Hoping to tilt the balance of power
away from the federal government and the courts, a broad bipartisan
coalition of lawmakers is moving legislation that would make it
harder for Congress and the regulatory agencies to adopt laws and
rules that pre-empt state and local laws. The legislation is
opposed by a rare coalition that includes the Chamber of Commerce
and other big business groups, as well as a number of big labor,
environmental and consumer organizations. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   CISNEROS-TRIAL (Washington) _ Henry Cisneros, a former Clinton
cabinet officer, is to go on trial Tuesday in federal court here in
what is almost certain to be the last major trial to be brought
under the two decade-long grand experiment of the independent
counsel law. By Neil A. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   HERMAN-PROFILE (Washington) _ A profile of Labor Secretary
Alexis Herman, one of few remaining survivors of every blessed day
of the Clinton administration. By John M. Broder. (With a photo.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;  (Moving in ``k'' news file.)
