<HEADER>
A1529 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-LABORDAY-FILMS-1000&AMP;A     09-05 1115
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABORDAY-FILMS-1000&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN THE DREAM FACTORY TAKES A HOLIDAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By RICK LYMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ The summer movie season typically ends with
something approaching a sigh, a little breather between the
summertime crowd pleasers and the somewhat more adult-oriented
autumn fare.
</P>
<P>
   And this one, which started with the ear-shattering cymbal clash
of ``Star Wars: Episode 1 _ The Phantom Menace'' and has produced
an unprecedented number of $100-million-plus box-office hits, ended
with just two relatively small-scale releases to attract audiences
over the three-day weekend.
</P>
<P>
   What does Hollywood have against Labor Day?
</P>
<P>
   For virtually every other important holiday weekend _ even
relative newcomers like Presidents' Day _ Hollywood cranks up the
hype machine, and the studios jostle for space and attention. But
Labor Day is the orphan of American holidays, the ugly cousin that
no one wants to play with.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few years Miramax Films has been one of the few
production companies regularly to release films nationally over the
Labor Day weekend, including ``Outside Providence'' this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our films don't have ambitions to be $100 million movies,''
said Mark Gill, president of Miramax's Los Angeles division. ``We
do nicely if they make $20 million to $30 million. But if you're at
a studio, your costs are so much higher. If you're a studio, you're
trying to make $60 million to $100 million, and it's a lot harder
to do that with an opening in early September.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Dergarabedian, chairman of Exhibitor Relations, a Los
Angeles-based company that monitors movie releases and box-office
trends, said, ``Very rarely do the studios bring out the big-event
pictures'' for Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   The thinking goes like this: A holiday weekend is a good time to
open big films because people are off work and out of school and
more likely to have pleasure on their minds. The best holiday
weekends (Memorial Day, Independence Day, Christmas) come at the
beginning of extended vacation periods, when a movie can not only
get a good opening blast but a solid bounce into the subsequent
weekends that will decide whether it transmutes into a blockbuster.
</P>
<P>
   But Labor Day comes at an end, not a beginning. Vacations are
drawing to a close, eyes are turning back to school books, noses to
grindstones. And even if a movie does manage a box-office burst on
the holiday weekend, it has little to look forward to in the first
weekend or two of September when there is historically a
significant drop-off in movie attendance.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, many of the parents use the Labor Day weekend as the last
chance to do shopping, the last chance to get away to the cottage
before the summer is over,'' said Chuck Viane, head of distribution
for Walt Disney Co.
</P>
<P>
   Often the drop-off in the number of releases over Labor Day is
particularly striking because it comes after a few solid weeks
jammed with new movies. This year, it was especially marked.
</P>
<P>
   Six films opened on Aug. 27 in wide release around the country:
Albert Brooks and Sharon Stone in ``The Muse,'' Antonio Banderas in
``The 13th Warrior,'' Johnny Depp and Charlize Theron in ``The
Astronaut's Wife,'' Omar Epps in ``In Too Deep,'' Brendan Fraser in
``Dudley Do-Right'' and Jon Voight in ``A Dog of Flanders.''
</P>
<P>
   But only two _ ``The Chill Factor,'' an action-adventure about
frozen toxins starring Cuba Gooding Jr., and ``Outside
Providence,'' a smaller-scale coming-of-age film about a
working-class Rhode Island boy who is thrust into a fancy prep
school _ were offered for the longer and potentially more lucrative
Labor Day weekend. As is customary with holiday releases, both
opened on Wednesday, in advance of the holiday, to give them a
five-day box-office sprint.
</P>
<P>
   ``A producer, by launching a movie the last weekend in August,
has a feeling that if it gets strong word of mouth, he can use that
the second weekend to hold up the size of his gross, perhaps
getting stories about how strong his hold is,'' said Viane. A film
that opens on Labor Day weekend, on the other hand, has only the
second weekend in September to look forward to, a weekend that is
traditionally among the slowest on the box-office calendar. ``Labor
Day can potentially be a nice launch pad, but then the second week
is low-grossing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, if a movie opens well in the last weekend of
August, and the people who see it like it and tell their friends,
the movie can then approach the Labor Day weekend with expectations
of selling almost as many tickets, or perhaps even more, than it
did in its opening weekend. Since films in Hollywood are viewed as
strong, and therefore kept in theaters longer and written about
more frequently, when the amount of money that they earn in
successive weekends goes down only slightly _ or, very rarely, goes
up _ an otherwise modest film might generate some attention and the
illusion of box-office strength by using Labor Day as its second
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't seem to be happening this summer. The unexpected
and overpowering success of the Bruce Willis psychological thriller
``The Sixth Sense'' has steamrollered over most of the August
releases, holding onto first place at the box office throughout the
month and probably into Labor Day, a paradoxical turn of events for
producers who schemed to move their films later in the summer to
get away from the ``Stars Wars'' and ``Austin Powers'' juggernauts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Labor Day is typically not the biggest holiday weekend of the
summer for moviegoing,'' Dergarabedian said. ``But with `Sixth
Sense' out there doing so well, I think we're going to see another
big weekend this Labor Day. It could even be a record Labor Day
weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason that Labor Days have traditionally performed
so poorly at the box office is that studios and producers have
shunned them, perhaps creating a self-fulfilling prophesy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are Labor Days slow because the big pictures aren't released
then or because the audience wouldn't be there for them?''
Dergarabedian said. ``I think it's a little of both.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Viane acknowledged that like most Hollywood truisms, an
exception can be found for the Labor Day jinx as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, historically the week after Labor Day is one of the
slowest of the year,'' he said. But he pointed back to 1992, when a
caper-thriller with Robert Redford and Sidney Poitier called
``Sneakers'' was released in early September.
</P>
<P>
   ``It did a ton of business,'' Viane said. ``It's really
indicative of the movie. If you've got the right movie, you can
open it anytime.''
</P>
</TEXT>
