<HEADER>
A1544 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-LEAH- &LR;      09-05 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH- </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; HOW TO LOOK THE VERY BEST YOU CAN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   At a premiere party thrown by the Humane Society in New York for
the forthcoming movie ``All the Little Animals,''  &UR; Monique Van &LR; 
 &UR; Vooren &LR; , 66, told Personals' spy &UR; Baird Jones &LR;  that 12 years ago, a
fall from a pony detached both her retinas.
</P>
<P>
   Subsequently, she had seven operations to restore her sight. ``I
became very depressed, and I think as an odd defensive
compensation, I started to completely envision myself as if I were
in my mid-20s. I blocked out all my memories of getting wrinkles
and sagging. In my own mind, out of this denial, I became again the
pretty young thing being pursued everywhere by Rudolf Nureyev. When
I went out, I kept feeling surprised that no one had complimented
me on my beauty. ... Then my doctor was able to use a new
technology, and in one single operation my eyesight was completely
restored.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they took the bandages off, I couldn't believe how old I
suddenly looked. It was `The Picture of Dorian Gray' in reverse.
I'd even managed to convince myself that I had no gray hair. My
self-image was so absurdly out of step with my years that frankly,
I think I was delusional.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Vooren, whose description of this event wasn't shared
without a purpose, also used the opportunity to say she was using
the experience she gained in a Learning Annex course she's teaching
in New York on ``How to Look Half Your Age.''
</P>
<P>
   P.S. And  &UR; Linda Evans &LR; , fitness mogul, is appearing on
infomercials for the $199.95 Rejuvenique Ultimate Facial Toning
System, which delivers ``electrical impulses to your facial
muscles,'' says People magazine. ``In my profession,'' says Evans,
looking young ``is the key to survival.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HAPPY LABOR DAY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The staff at the progressive magazine Mother Jones has organized
a bowling team called the Bowlsheviks, a name credited to bowling
widow  &UR; Carmel Vermeltfoort &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   The team's uniform shirts will read: ``Mother Jones: Leading
strikes since 1873.''
</P>
<P>
   P.S. The first 75 mothers who send proof that they gave birth on
Labor Day to Fruit of the Loom (at 132 W. 21st St., 10th floor, New
York, NY 10011) will receive free underwear for 21 years.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - With a referendum on the issue scheduled for November,  &UR; Jane &LR; 
 &UR; Leudecke &LR; , who lives in Sydney and is sister of the  &UR; Duchess of &LR; 
 &UR; York &LR; , says she's in favor of Australia dumping any allegiance to
 &UR; Queen Elizabeth &LR;  and becoming a republic. ``It is time for
Australia to move on,'' she said in comments quoted by the Times of
London.
</P>
<P>
   - Special events: In a new event at the Grand National Rodeo
Horse and Stock Show _ which opens October 29 in San Francisco _
senior citizens walk the jump course designed for horses. And
 &UR; Mary Ann Spencer &LR;  and  &UR; Charlie Lott &LR;  were married in mid-August at
the Santos-Robinson Mortuary in San Leandro, after which the
mortuary's  &UR; Robert Rein &LR;  told the San Leandro Times that he was
happy to have an event where the people ``are standing up.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Elton John &LR;  and  &UR; Tina Turner &LR;  had a spat during an appearance
together in New York this summer _ John stalked off the stage
midperformance _ but they will play together on December 30 in Las
Vegas. MSNBC says they're rumored to be getting $5 million each,
which is enough to make anyone kiss and make up.
</P>
<P>
   - ``Sopranos'' star  &UR; Lorraine Bracco &LR;  filed for bankruptcy on
June 9, but the New York Post says she ordered a $250 bottle of
wine in the Hamptons the other night.
</P>
<P>
   - Reading that Thomasville is selling a new line of  &UR; Ernest &LR; 
 &UR; Hemingway &LR;  furniture, intended to be ``romantic'' and
``adventurous,''  &UR; Robert Sexton &LR;  says he'd prefer if the tables and
chairs ``not be drunk and suicidal.''
</P>
