<SLUG> BC-LEAH- </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; HOW TO LOOK THE VERY BEST YOU CAN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   At a premiere party thrown by the Humane Society in New York for
the forthcoming movie ``All the Little Animals,''  &UR; Monique Van &LR; 
 &UR; Vooren &LR; , 66, told Personals' spy &UR; Baird Jones &LR;  that 12 years ago, a
fall from a pony detached both her retinas.
</P>
<P>
   Subsequently, she had seven operations to restore her sight. ``I
became very depressed, and I think as an odd defensive
compensation, I started to completely envision myself as if I were
in my mid-20s. I blocked out all my memories of getting wrinkles
and sagging. In my own mind, out of this denial, I became again the
pretty young thing being pursued everywhere by Rudolf Nureyev. When
I went out, I kept feeling surprised that no one had complimented
me on my beauty. ... Then my doctor was able to use a new
technology, and in one single operation my eyesight was completely
restored.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they took the bandages off, I couldn't believe how old I
suddenly looked. It was `The Picture of Dorian Gray' in reverse.
I'd even managed to convince myself that I had no gray hair. My
self-image was so absurdly out of step with my years that frankly,
I think I was delusional.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Vooren, whose description of this event wasn't shared
without a purpose, also used the opportunity to say she was using
the experience she gained in a Learning Annex course she's teaching
in New York on ``How to Look Half Your Age.''
</P>
<P>
   P.S. And  &UR; Linda Evans &LR; , fitness mogul, is appearing on
infomercials for the $199.95 Rejuvenique Ultimate Facial Toning
System, which delivers ``electrical impulses to your facial
muscles,'' says People magazine. ``In my profession,'' says Evans,
looking young ``is the key to survival.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HAPPY LABOR DAY &LR;
</P>
