<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUSTOM-PUBLISH-MEDIA-ART-1050(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING HAY WITH `CUSTOM' MAGAZINES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stacks of glossy publications compete for attention
in the pane-glass vitrines of Universal News, a sprawling magazine
emporium in Soho favored by the downtown intelligentsia. Wired and
Vogue sit side by side in the front windows, sharing space with a
new title: Sony Style, a quarterly that sells for $5.95 in the
United States and $8.95 in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Sony Style? It is just one of a growing number of ``custom
published'' magazines. While advertisers like Philip Morris,
Mercedes-Benz and Starbucks used to push magazines to mention their
products in the editorial pages, they have now adopted a more
sophisticated approach, creating magazines in which they control
the mix of feature articles and product placement.
</P>
<P>
   Flip through the pages of Sony Style and the editorial feeling
is that of a technology lover's version of People magazine. There
is a loving profile of the actress Jennifer Lopez, an interview
with an up-and-coming Danish filmmaker, a page about the designer
Diane von Furstenberg and her newest fashion accessory _a vest
designed to hold Sony electronic equipment. And what woman can go
without a vest with a special pocket for her Memory Stick?
</P>
<P>
   A few pages further into the magazine, there is an article about
a Sony computer called the Vaio, which begins: ``Sony designers
express a product's power and potential through its form and
detailing. Each product looks and feels unique, yet all share a
family resemblance that says `Sony' wherever they go.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, saying Sony _ make that trumpeting Sony _ is what the
magazine is all about. Call it custom publishing, relationship
marketing or naked self-promotion, it all boils down to the same
principle: A publisher like Time Warner's Time Inc. produces a
magazine for a customer like Sony or Starbucks to use in its
marketing program.
</P>
<P>
   Custom-published magazines are either sold on newsstands, given
out as freebies at stores or sent to a list of customers. The
magazine publisher is almost without exception guaranteed a profit,
because to the corporate sponsor, the magazine is a marketing tool
intended for one purpose alone _ to reach the consumer _ and losses
are counted as marketing expenses. In the words of one custom
publisher, ``the companies marketing the products lose money and
the magazine publishers make money.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why we like it,'' the publishing executive said.
</P>
<P>
   And it has grown into big business for publishers. Custom
publications generate $650 million in revenue for the magazine
industry, according to a survey to be released this month by the
Magazine Publishers of America. David Wilkofsky, chairman of
Wilkofsky Gruen Associates, the consulting firm that conducted the
survey, said the business had grown exponentially in the last five
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a relatively new industry that's arrived on the radar
screen in the last five years,'' Wilkofsky said, adding that the
economics of custom publishing are a welcome balm to magazine
publishers. ``When someone as big as Time Inc. goes into the
business, it's another stream of revenue to add to the dozens of
streams of revenue that company already has. The issue is not `does
this make money?' The issue is how major a profit center custom
publishing is going to be.''
</P>
<P>
   And every major publisher is doing it, with varying degrees of
editorial glasnost. For example, Hachette Filipacchi Magazines,
part of Lagardere Group and the publishers of George and Elle,
produces Momentum, which is underwritten by Mercedes-Benz, owned by
DaimlerChrysler AG. ``As the miles flew by,'' reads one travel
article in the current issue, ``I felt myself slipping into the
first phase of our hedonists' holiday. Mercedes offers three
special seat options on the S500, and our car has them all!''
</P>
<P>
   But Hachette also publishes Unlimited, a seeming men's outdoor
adventure magazine _ complete with articles about sports gear,
surfing and mountain climbing _ that is paid for by Philip Morris
Cos. and distributed to 2 million consumers on the Philip Morris
database. The only clue that Unlimited is produced by the cigarette
maker is two tiny lines of type on the magazine's masthead that
identify it as a Philip Morris publication.
</P>
<P>
   Time Inc.'s custom publishing division produces Sony Style and
Joe, a joint venture with Starbucks, a lavishly produced
quasi-literary magazine that is sold for $2.95. A Time executive
said Joe will actually lose money for the company this year. And
its coffee connection is not readily visible, because there are, in
fact, no articles about coffee. Instead, the second issue featured
articles by James Salter (on flying), Frederick and Steven
Barthelme (on gambling) and Dusko Doder (on Yugoslavia).
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Time has been in the custom publishing business for the last
four years, and the company policy is ``to keep a very low
profile,'' said Tim Hildebrand, president of Time Inc. Custom
Publishing. The division publishes magazines for about 18 clients,
Hildebrand said, but he declined to name them. ``There is no upside
to telling my competition what we're doing, and how we are doing
it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Time produces other custom publications for Ford Motor Co.'s
Jaguar division and Dayton Hudson Corp.'s Target chain of discount
stores, as well as one called S that is distributed in 200 shopping
malls owned by Simon Debartolo Group Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Meredith Corp. publishes dozens of custom titles, from Mature
Outlook (with Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co.) and You &AMP; Your Dog (with Iams
Co.) to Bond, a publication of the Lutheran Brotherhood distributed
to 3 million households. Christopher Little, the president of the
Meredith Publishing Group, said all the magazines are profitable.
``The advertiser or marketing company has a very clear idea of who
they are trying to reach and what sort of message they want to
deliver and they are not thinking in terms of a true consumer
magazine that they would charge people for,'' Little said. ``They
are trying to get their message to a targeted audience, and that's
the value.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As for Sony Style, Howard Stringer, president of Sony Corp. of
America, said he expected his new quarterly to sell as well as any
consumer magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sony is not just about hardware anymore,'' Stringer said.
``It's about life and culture. What better way to let consumers
know that than through a magazine?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
