<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-05 16:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1555 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-GROSSMAGS-MEDIA-NYT &LR;      09-05 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROSSMAGS-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON BRITISH NEWSSTANDS, BABES AND BEER ARE IN DECLINE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Too much sex may be a bad thing. At least that is what
British publishers of the so-called laddie magazine market seem to
be confronting as recent circulation figures for magazines like FHM
and Loaded, the originators of the men-behaving-badly genre,
dropped almost across the board.
</P>
<P>
   Whether this presages things to come on the western side of the
Atlantic remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   The circulation falloff in Britain is occurring while the
appetite for men's lifestyle magazines in the United States still
seems far from sated. In fact, in New York, Conde Nast recently
acknowledged the sector's potential by recruiting Mark Golin from
the American version of the British laddie book Maxim to inject
some extra sex and bathroom humor into Details, its American men's
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to emulate the success of Dennis Publishing, which
produces Maxim in both Britain and the United States, other
publishers are eyeing the American possibilities for their
testosterone-driven journals. Among them is EMAP Petersen Inc., a
unit of Britain's EMAP PLC, which is preparing for the American
debut of FHM (formerly called For Him), Britain's largest laddie
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Yet whatever the staying power of this British invasion in the
United States, here in the laddie book's native land, after almost
five years of double-digit circulation growth, demand seems to be
flagging. Circulation figures reported by the Audit Bureau of
Circulations in Britain for FHM declined 9.6 percent from June 1998
to June 1999, a sharp turnaround from growth of 53.6 percent in the
prior 12 months. The most recent circulation figure reported was
701,089.
</P>
<P>
   Loaded magazine, published by IPC Magazines Ltd., was down even
more, dropping 15.8 percent, to 384,351, compared with a rise of 20
percent in the previous year. And Maxim, despite its burgeoning
circulation in the United States, grew here by only 3.1 percent _
to 310,096 _ from June to June, compared with 63 percent growth in
circulation in the prior year.
</P>
<P>
   Arena and Face, two of the oldest of the group, fell by 26.2
percent and 28 percent, respectively, to 46,777 and 57,703.
</P>
<P>
   All this has left editors and publishers on both sides of the
pond asking: Is the boom over? Is it possible that sex no longer
sells?
</P>
<P>
   ``A little bit of sex and hedonistic bad behavior goes a long
way, but after a while that's all it was,'' said Mike Soutar, whom
Dennis Publishing recently hired away from EMAP's FHM to become
editor of the American edition of Maxim. Soutar said he was working
to keep Maxim from lapsing into laddie-book formula. But he would
provide no specific examples, saying simply that the British
circulation decline was ``a timely reminder that we have to keep
evolving.''
</P>
<P>
   In essence, the laddie formula involves a couple of photo
spreads of women, often in lingerie, interviews with and
photographs of scantily clad models and actresses, some barroom
jokes and a twist of how-to-get-the-girl advice for good measure.
</P>
<P>
   In the last several months, British magazine publishers have
rushed a bevy of imitators to market, hoping to cash in on the
sector's phenomenal growth. EMAP introduced a spinoff of its
successful FHM, called FHM Collections. Cabal Communications Ltd.
joined the fray with a magazine called Front, which is risque
enough that some retailers display it on the top shelf with the
likes of Playboy and Penthouse. And IPC introduced Later, a spinoff
of Loaded aimed at older readers.
</P>
<P>
   Some editors worry that the market is now too crowded and that
some of the newcomers are dragging standards down by focusing so
narrowly on sex. Moreover, men's lifestyle magazines now sell more
than 2 million copies a month in Britain, reaching close to 60
percent of their target market of 18- to 34-year-old men.
</P>
<P>
   ``The marketplace is saturated,'' Soutar said. ``It's a
relatively small country. Once your core gets bored, it's like a
souffle _ the whole thing collapses.''
</P>
<P>
   But Philip Thomas, managing director of FHM in Britain, is not
ready to declare the feast at an end. Despite their circulation
drops, all of the magazines have said that ad pages are actually
up. ``The men's lifestyle market is still immature,'' Thomas said.
``There are still only seven men's magazines in the U.K., compared
with 17 women's magazines.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas contends that the market is actually not in a decline
because several of the new titles are not yet included in the
industry's audited figures, and he said that the July issue of FHM
sold a million copies _ a figure the June-to-June circulation
report does not reflect.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market is just settling down for the time being,'' Thomas
said. He noted that even in a weak month, FHM still reaches more
than 700,000 readers, a number he said was ``way beyond our
imaginations'' when the magazine was reintroduced in its current
form in 1994 after it was acquired by EMAP.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pundits say the bubble has burst, but it has no relation
to anything,'' he insisted. ``It's all hot air.''
</P>
<P>
   But it seems that readers and even some former editors are
starting to think that the laddie book's heyday may be over. The
market ``is starting to show signs of fatigue, especially if, like
me, you are old enough to remember a time when magazines like Arena
were something to genuinely look forward to,'' Barbara Ellen, a
former staff member for Loaded, wrote in an article in The
Observer, a weekly newspaper here. ``After a while, digging for
gold beneath the pile of filth, innuendo, and glamour model bikini
bottoms gets so exhausting.''
</P>
<P>
   As for any implications the circulation drop in Britain may have
for the U.S. market, editors and publishers say it would take much
longer for an American downturn _ if only because the market is so
much larger that it will take longer to become saturated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if the men's magazines in the U.S. can ever have
the same scale of success that was had in the U.K.,'' Soutar said.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, as he settles in at Maxim in New York, he says he
will welcome the stateside arrival of his old employer, FHM.
``Competition always helps the sector,'' he said. ``We need it or
we'll become fat and lazy and complacent.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's something no laddie wants to be.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
