<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, Sept. 6, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(js) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Finally, after an entire week of tropical storm warnings and
hurricane watches, the North Carolina Coast will be dry and
tranquil Monday, though low clouds may persist along the Outer
Banks. A tropical depression, the remnants of Dennis, will move
north along the western slopes of the Appalachians from near
Charleston, W.Va., early Monday to Bradford, Pa., Monday night.
This will cause the steadiest rain to fall into the upper Ohio
River Basin. Up to four inches may accumulate in northern West
Virginia and western Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   An air flow from the southeast at the surface to 30,000 feet
will draw moist, tropical air from the western Atlantic into the
Middle Atlantic and New England states. Showers and scattered
thunderstorms will drench some sections with more than an inch of
rain and miss others as they move toward the northwest. Maine
should be quite warm with increasing clouds.
</P>
<P>
   High pressure over the Middle West will promote very warm but
dry conditions from the Upper Plains to the Gulf states. The
merging of a weak tropical wave from the western Gulf of Mexico
with a jet stream disturbance in the Red River Valley will bring
numerous thunderstorms to eastern Texas, Oklahoma and sections of
Louisiana and Arkansas. Sea breezes will cause a few storms near
the eastern Gulf Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Cooler air will surge into the Northwest behind a front in the
northern Rockies. Offshore winds will keep Oregon and the northern
California coast on the sunny side. Fog will be stubborn to leave
coastal valleys of southern California. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: Tropical Environs
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of last week, there was serious discussion that
Dennis had lost its tropical characteristics as record cool air was
swept into its circulation even as it stalled off the coast. But
when Dennis finally made landfall, there was little question that
it had stayed a tropical storm. Indeed, readings in Kentucky, west
of the storm, and in Vermont, well to the north, reached the lower
90s. Burlington rose to 93 degrees, just shy of its all-time
September record. Certainly, Dennis had brought part of the tropics
to those on the periphery of its circulation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-99 1656EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990905.0085 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-05 17:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1559 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-E-COMMERCE-REVIEWS-NY     09-05 1150
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-E-COMMERCE-REVIEWS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLINE RETAILERS DISCOVER THAT CUSTOMER REVIEWS CAN BUILD LOYALTY 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By BOB TEDESCHI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   E-commerce companies fill their sites with reviews of products
they sell, generally taken from marketers or magazines, but they
know that consumers frequently give much more credence to the
opinions of ``real people'' _ friends or peers who buy similar
products.
</P>
<P>
   The problem for Internet retailers is how to harness the
opinions of those real people without letting the negative comments
chase prospective buyers away. The solution, some e-commerce
companies are finding, is to allow customers to have their say, and
hope that it ultimately builds sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a role for this kind of voice on the Net,'' said
Barry Parr, an analyst with the International Data Corp., a
research firm. ``You need to wear your filters when you read them,
but you can glean some really useful information.''
</P>
<P>
   The trend of posting customer reviews started, predictably
enough, at Amazon.com, which launched its reader reviews when it
started its online bookstore in July 1995. In addition to including
excerpts from published reviews, the site allowed readers to rate
books based on a five-star scale, and to post comments of their
own. At the time, such reviews were a novelty because online stores
generally relied on authoritative third parties, like professional
book reviewers, to help readers decide what to buy.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we introduced it, people asked, `If your goal is to sell
products, how can you allow it?''' said Paul Capelli, an Amazon
spokesman. ``But it's been a very effective tool to get attention
and move product.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, he said, a recent novel, ``Lip Service'' by M.J.
Rose, failed to attract a publisher, but Ms. Rose published the
book on her own and offered it for sale on Amazon. It was reviewed
so favorably by Amazon users that it entered the site's Top 100
list. The author was then signed by Pocket Books, and when the book
was re-released, it was among Amazon's top five best sellers during
a recent week. ``The customer reviews were driving her sales,''
Capelli said.
</P>
<P>
   The book's success is no longer limited to Amazon; it is now
moving well on Barnesandnoble.com, where it ranks in the current
top 100 sellers.
</P>
<P>
   Following Amazon's lead, other online retailers have instituted
programs that allow buyers to rate products. For sellers of
computers and other high-priced goods, posting customer reviews is
an even greater departure from the traditional retail norm,
analysts and executives said, because there are many established
sources for advice on buying these products. Indeed, an entire
publishing industry has been built on giving computer buyers
authoritative advice.
</P>
<P>
   NECX Direct, an Internet computer and electronics retailer that
began posting customer reviews of products two years ago, says such
reviews augment buying guides from publishers. ``This is a very
potent motivator for helping people decide what to buy,'' said
Keith Halloran, the company's director of marketing. ``In the end,
sales are made by the testimony of real users, not rebate offers or
what PC Magazine says.''
</P>
<P>
   Halloran said the site could afford to risk turning customers
away from certain products because, like many other Internet
retailers, NECX does not carry its own inventory. Rather, when a
customer places an order, NECX has the product delivered directly
from a distributor. So even if the customer is turned away from one
product, he said, the company offers enough products in each
category to make sales likely.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the customers say, `It's a bad product; you shouldn't buy
it,' we don't lose because we don't hold anything in stock,'' he
said. ``So we print everything _ the good, the bad and the ugly.''
</P>
<P>
   Provided it's not too ugly. Halloran said NECX edited customer
reviews for profanity ``or transparent efforts to discredit
manufacturers,'' and also watched for obvious boosterism from
manufacturers. ``I'm sure that happens,'' he said, ``but most
reputable manufacturers refrain from it.''
</P>
<P>
   Parr, of the International Data Corp., said that even if such
reviews failed to help sales, they could still serve an important
purpose: increasing the reviewer's loyalty to the site. ``People
who are big contributors to reviews tend to have a sense of
ownership,'' he said. ``It gives them a sense of status in a place
that really matters to them, and it's pretty hard to place a price
tag on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Notably, the trend toward using customer reviews is also being
embraced by publishers who have built their businesses on offering
objective, often lab-tested, reviews. For instance, Consumer
Reports, which is published by Consumers Union, recently announced
that it would publish reviews of e-commerce Web sites from
Bizrate.com, a company that aggregates customer feedback. In
addition, Cnet, an Internet company that publishes reviews of
computer products, recently began posting readers' comments about
products, as well.
</P>
<P>
   Alice Hill, editorial director for Cnet, said that decision was
not easy. ``It took some letting go of that attitude that you're
the editor, saying, `This is all you need to know,''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hill said the service, which allows readers to submit a
``thumbs up'' or ``thumbs down'' review alongside their comments,
has even helped the site's professional reviewers, who test
products in a laboratory environment. For instance, she said, Cnet
editors recently confirmed a flaw in a digital camera's lens cover
after a flurry of customers pointed out the problem. ``So this
gives us a volume approach as well as a lab approach,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the number of sites that offer customer reviews is
growing, analysts said one important online category _
manufacturers who sell directly to consumers _ would not follow the
trend anytime soon. ``Companies are so protective of their brands
and image, it would be hard to imagine any of them taking that kind
of risk,'' Parr said, referring to companies like Nike and Compaq
Computer.
</P>
<P>
   Among manufacturers that sell directly to consumers, Dell
Computer comes the closest to offering customer reviews. In the
Talk Forum section of its Web site, Dell allows readers to post
questions or speak their minds about products they have bought.
Manish Mehta, senior manager for online support, said the company
edited only offensive, profane remarks. ``The fact that you can
absolutely slam Dell frees up people to be open,'' Mehta said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the company would be reluctant to post reviews in areas
of the site where buyers are poised to purchase, like the Dell
Shop. ``Conversion is so critical in e-commerce,'' he said. ``When
you finally get customers to select a product, to introduce
something that might cause them to abandon a purchase would not be
a good thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
