<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK CITYSCAPES; STUDENT ARTISTS; CONSUMMATE CONCERTOS; BRITISH
SCULPTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash., Britain)  (js) 
 By KATHRYN SHATTUCK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ New York. It's a state of mind or a matter of
perspective, depending on how you look at it. The undecided can
journey to the New-York Historical Society to check out how four
generations of native sons saw things. ``Putting It on Paper,''
through Jan. 2, features a sampling of the more than 5,000 rarities
housed by one of the nation's pre-eminent collections. Many, like
William Rickarby Miller's watercolor of New York Harbor as seen
from a farm-riddled Jersey City, depict a metropolis in the throes
of change. Others simply pay tribute to New Yorkers' favorite
heroes, like Charles Balthazar Julien Fevret de Saint-Memin's
portrait of a foppish Capt. Meriwether Lewis. Information: (212)
873-3400.
</P>
<P>
   APT PUPILS
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They have heralded the budding talent of no less than
Andy Warhol, Robert Redford, Truman Capote, Sylvia Plath and
Richard Avedon. Only time will tell what young genius might be
lurking among the winners of the 1999 Scholastic Art and Writing
Awards. Viewers can decide for themselves when 75 of the top works
are displayed from Tuesday through Friday at Artists Space, 38
Greene St., in SoHo. Sponsored by The Scholastic magazine, the
awards were founded in 1923 to encourage early achievement in the
creative arts and foster its development. This year's competition
invested in the futures of 1,100 students, who cashed in on
$170,000 in scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   CONCERTO TIME
</P>
<P>
   They're not for the fainthearted or the technically feeble. So
to do justice to ``the consummate concertos,'' the National
Symphony Orchestra has called on the consummate pros. Under Leonard
Slatkin, the orchestra will present all of Beethoven's concertos in
its annual festival devoted to the composer's oeuvre. There will be
four concerts, on Thursday, Saturday and Sept. 17 and 18, at the
Kennedy Center Concert Hall in Washington. Among those on hand to
tackle the powerhouse program: the violinist Hilary Hahn, the
Kalichstein-Laredo-Robinson Trio and the pianists Andre Watts,
Garrick Ohlsson, and Jonathan Biss. Information: (202) 467-4600.
</P>
<P>
   CHANGE OF PLACE
</P>
<P>
   Canary Wharf, the real-estate behemoth that transformed London's
East End in the early 1990s, is on a mission to polish its image.
Starting Monday, 80 works by major British sculptors will grace its
vast public spaces. ``The Shape of the Century'' traces the art
form in the last 100 years and juxtaposes it with the country's
social evolution. But that's not all. The works were originally
exhibited in the reverent spaces of Salisbury Cathedral. Installed
in this modern environment through Oct. 24, they will assume
``entirely different resonances,'' says the show's curator, and
become a sounding board for future Wharf art commissions.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
