<HEADER>
A1576 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-TELLING-TALES-NYT &LR;      09-05 1277
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-TELLING-TALES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVISIONS COLUMN: TELEVISION AS STORYTELLER, SHAPING HISTORY INTO
LEGEND 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By MARGO JEFFERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Watching ``Strange Justice,'' the terrific Showtime film based
on the bizarre encounters among Anita Hill, Clarence Thomas and the
Senate Judiciary Committee that resulted in the confirmation of
Thomas' Supreme Court nomination, makes one think that television
may still be the single strangest piece of technology in our daily
lives.
</P>
<P>
   Televisions have memories as formidable as any computer's.
Editing makes them more selective and, in that way, less
democratic. But a single television show can retrieve layers of
visual, historical and emotional information.
</P>
<P>
   ``Strange Justice,'' which will be rebroadcast throughout
September, instantly brings back the the experience of watching the
real hearings. And it summons up other hearings too, from the
recent Clinton-Lewinsky-Starr doings to the Watergate investigation
of a quarter-century ago. Add the televising of court trials, from
the high and mighty O.J. Simpson's to the militantly humdrum
defendants who crowd into Judge Judy's courtroom, and you have a
medium that belongs as much to oral history as to written and
visual traditions.
</P>
<P>
   Millions of people sit in front of their television sets all the
time, watching the same mesmerizing events. Then these events get
reshaped, not only through editing but also through storytelling,
just as ancient chronicles of war and conquest once did. And thus
they become part legend and part history as they are passed down.
</P>
<P>
   Part of what keeps old tales alive is all the different
versions. How do heroes and villains change as time passes and
beliefs shift? How are events interpreted as new facts and
once-submerged feelings show themselves? One hundred years from
now, when viewers compare the televised Thomas-Hill hearings to
``Strange Justice,'' will they view the first as we view texts like
Holinshed's Chronicles and treat the second as we treat the plays
that Renaissance writers made from them?
</P>
<P>
   The script for ``Strange Justice'' is based on the impressively
reported and documented book of the same title by Jane Mayer and
Jill Abramson, as well as on the hearing transcripts. The top-notch
actors add their own inflections. Which lets us compare the Anita
Hill and the Clarence Thomas we see here to the ones we saw in the
Senate eight years ago as if they were on a split screen.
</P>
<P>
   Regina Taylor does look, sound and carry herself very much as
Anita Hill did, but she reveals what Ms. Hill could not permit
herself to: the assault on what she most prized in herself,
rectitude and the ability to make decisions that were both
practical and ethical. Delroy Lindo is a less exact physical match
for Thomas, but he gets exactly what the hearings allowed us to
see, then subtly heightens it: a man taut with self-restraint who
denies all details and seizes on pieties with increasing bitterness
and rage.
</P>
<P>
   And here's one of the scariest things about all those
behind-the-scenes politicos led by Mandy Patinkin as Kenneth
Duberstein, the lobbyist who was Thomas' most jaunty, Machiavellian
handler. We knew little or nothing about these men when they were
part of a story that was being written as history, not rewritten as
entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   But television isn't just a repository for history, memory and
myth making. It's a repository for genres and styles, too, that
have run their course elsewhere but still meet a real need in us.
Physical comedy faltered when vaudeville floundered and silent
movies died, but it was revived in television variety shows and by
comics like Lucille Ball, Sid Caesar and Imogene Coca and Carol
Burnett.
</P>
<P>
   ``Strange Justice'' turns melodrama ultramodern. The dialogue is
naturalistic (daytime soaps are more rhetorically high-pitched) but
preserves the required moral clashes: good versus evil, cynicism
versus innocence, lies versus truth, the sacred versus the
blasphemous. (``You're God's warrior,'' Thomas' wife tells him,
meaning that he must defend his reputation. You don't mess around
with prime time, Duberstein tells him with a brisk obscenity,
meaning exactly the same thing).
</P>
<P>
   The language of melodrama shortcuts ambiguity and irony. In the
old days it risked the banality of exaggeration. Today it risks the
banality of banality. But it works here because the plot is racked
with ironies and ambiguities alongside moral absolutes, both as we
see them and as the participants see them.
</P>
<P>
   The director of ``Strange Justice,'' Ernest Dickerson, uses a
wonderfully flamboyant but condensed style. The camera supplies all
of melodrama's trusty, thrilling stage effects. Those freezes at
moments of decision or revelation are like the tableaux of
19th-century plays. (My favorite stage direction, a French one,
calls for a tableau of ``general stupefaction.'') A white light
floods the screen during the testimony of Ms. Hill and Thomas, when
we are supposedly made privy to their private thoughts and emotions
(denied us in the actual hearings).
</P>
<P>
   And when the television lights recreated by Dickerson's lighting
first shine on Thomas they strike his glasses and give back only
glare. This works because after so much subterfuge and so many
conflicting tales, we at last have the illusion that all is being
revealed.
</P>
<P>
   No old form looking for a new home is interesting unless it
redesigns itself. Television has plenty of tired melodrama; the
major networks specialize in it. ``Strange Justice'' is fresh and
powerful because it uses television to intensify but also to
abstract the melodrama. The camera pulls back again and again
during the hearings, and periodically the actors are spliced into
film clips of the real events (Lindo next to President George Bush
the day he nominated Thomas). All to remind us that we are watching
a film of a film of something that really happened, and that all
three experiences have an equal claim on us.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing could be further from ``Strange Justice'' than ``The
Sopranos,'' that sensational HBO series about the professional and
domestic travails of a New Jersey Mafia family. But with its own
inimitable mix of tones (grisly, rueful, desperate, savvy) and
forms (crime thriller, domestic drama, absurdist comedy), it also
uses resources only television provides.
</P>
<P>
   We've had brilliant movies about Mafia life. What we haven't had
is a serial _ not a soap opera rushing headlong toward a dramatic
apotheosis each week _ but a serial attuned as much to the ordinary
as to the extreme. How can the extreme flourish in any kind of
family without careful maintenance of the ordinary?
</P>
<P>
   For all its inventiveness ``The Sopranos'' has the look and feel
of a beautifully crafted documentary. The camera lets itself be
drawn to minor characters, peering into people's homes, recording
their private little rituals, making its way back to the center
where momentum is gathering. The director's ego is cunningly
disguised in this way.
</P>
<P>
   We are seeing how a particular world operates when murder,
shakedowns and the FBI have to share space with all the things we
know from our own lives and the lives of countless other television
families: Do you fight with your teen-age daughter or shut your
mouth? How do you keep your employees in line? How do you tell your
psychiatrist you hate your mother and she hates you, too?
</P>
<P>
   And on top of everything else they have a name like ``The
Sopranos.'' We all know that nothing is too low for television at
its worst. It turns out that under the right circumstances, more
can be done than most of us thought possible.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
