<HEADER>
A1583 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT &LR;      09-05 0648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Big Advertisers Turning to Their Own Magazines
</P>
<P>
   While advertisers like Sony, Philip Morris, Mercedes-Benz and
Starbucks used to press magazines to mention their products in the
editorial pages, they have now adopted a more sophisticated
approach, creating magazines in which they control the mix of
feature articles and product placement.
</P>
<P>
   Custom-published magazines are either sold on newsstands, given
out free at stores or sent to a list of customers. The magazine
publisher is almost always guaranteed a profit because, to the
corporate sponsor, the magazine is a marketing tool intended for
one purpose alone _ to reach the consumer _ and losses are counted
as marketing expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Moving From News to Baseball
</P>
<P>
   Michael Gartner, a longtime newspaper editor and a former head
of NBC News, is selling The Tribune _ the 10,000-circulation
newspaper in Ames, Iowa, that he has edited for six years and owned
for 13 _ to become part-owner of the Iowa Cubs, the AAA
minor-league franchise of the Chicago Cubs. Gartner said the death
of a partner, David Belin, and the tax consequences for Belin's
family ``made it clear we were going to have to sell.''
</P>
<P>
   Greece to Apply for Euro in March
</P>
<P>
   Greece will apply to join Europe's single currency in mid-March
next year, probably only days before a parliamentary vote for the
nation's presidency that could topple the ruling Pasok party
government, Prime Minister Costas Simitis said.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Bank Considers Alliances
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Bank, the world's largest bank, is talking to rivals
including Dresdner Bank about linking up in businesses like retail
banking, the company's chief executive said. By combining,
commercial banks would be able to extend their networks and cut
costs.
</P>
<P>
   Review Sought for Retail Merger
</P>
<P>
   Finance Minister Dominique Strauss-Kahn of France said he would
ask the nation's Competition Council to examine a planned merger
between Carrefour and Promodes. He said he was concerned that the
resulting company would have too much control over supermarket
sales in some cities.
</P>
<P>
   Paper Turns Tables on Amazon.com
</P>
<P>
   When Amazon.com came under fire recently for publishing lists of
books and CDs popular with employees at major corporations, a
writer for Seattle Weekly, an alternative newspaper, decided to
find out which pages on the paper's Web site were most popular with
people who work at Amazon. The results showed that Amazon employees
were frequent visitors to the newspaper's online help-wanted
section and that they tended to use the site most in the early
afternoon, checking out restaurant reviews and horoscopes.
</P>
<P>
   Letting Customers Do the Selling
</P>
<P>
   Electronic commerce companies fill their sites with reviews of
products they sell, reviews that are generally taken from marketers
or magazines. But they know that consumers often give more credence
to the opinions of friends or peers who buy similar products. The
problem is how to harness the opinions of those real people without
letting the negative comments chase prospective buyers away. The
solution, some e-commerce companies are finding, is to allow
customers to have their say and hope that it ultimately builds
sales.
</P>
<P>
   Venture Salvages Classic Books
</P>
<P>
   The New York Review of Books has vowed to reach a wider audience
than the usual intellectuals with its new book-publishing venture,
which salvages out-of-print classics. So far, 12 titles have been
published in sleek paperback editions, including vanished titles by
Anton Chekhov and Henry James.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Markets Closed Monday
</P>
<P>
   U.S. financial markets and banks are closed Monday in observance
of Labor Day. Most financial markets in other countries are open.
</P>
</TEXT>
