<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-05 17:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1587 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-HERMAN-PROFILE-ART-65     09-05 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERMAN-PROFILE-ART-655&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAITH AND SOUTHERN HERITAGE SUSTAIN LABOR SECRETARY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ala.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Serving in Washington in the 1990s has sorely taxed
the faith of Alexis Herman, the labor secretary and one of the few
remaining survivors of every blessed day of the Clinton
administration.
</P>
<P>
   She has endured a nasty confirmation battle, the embarrassment
of President Clinton's dalliance with an intern, and a
little-noticed but ongoing investigation by an independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican Congress has nickel-and-dimed her agency's
requests for increases in spending for job-training programs and
other labor initiatives. And she is tempted at times to despair of
politics in an age of cynicism and the poisoning of public
discourse.
</P>
<P>
   Yet her faith abides, rooted in the teachings of her father, a
courageous early advocate of black voting rights in her native
Alabama who once was dragged from his car and beaten by a gang of
Ku Klux Klansmen as his 5-year-old daughter looked on.
</P>
<P>
   Herman said she still remembers the heft of the pearl-handled
pistol her father handed her before the attack with instructions to
use it if any of the Klansmen threatened her.
</P>
<P>
   But Herman, in a conversation over a pre-Labor Day lunch late
last week, did not want to dwell on that day 47 years ago. It was
part of the upbringing that launched her lifelong devotion to
Democratic politics and minority rights and that landed her in the
24-by-36-foot corner office at the Labor Department with a
commanding view of the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Her devotion has been shaken in recent years, but never to the
point of apostasy. ``It does cause me to go back and remember the
early days and the path I took to get here,'' she said over a plate
of cold sliced turkey and lifeless green beans in the private study
off her huge ceremonial office. ``I try not to be distracted by the
cynicism and the negative climate in politics today.''
</P>
<P>
   An observant Catholic since childhood, Herman begins every meal
with grace (``Bless us, O Lord, for all of our gifts and for these
we are about to receive'') and fluently recites her favorite
biblical passage, from the Book of Proverbs (``Lean not unto thine
own understanding but in all ways acknowledge Him and He shall
direct thy paths'').
</P>
<P>
   Prominently displayed on a side table is a picture of the labor
secretary with her pastoral and political shepherds, Pope John Paul
II and Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Steeped in Southern gentility _ she takes four bites to finish a
single cherry _ she is enduringly gracious and reluctant to talk
about her personal life. She has never been married, except to her
work, and finds relaxation in hiking, biking and reading. She
entertains her friends and her large extended family with
``old-style Southern cuisine,'' including about a half-dozen
versions of her signature dish, red beans and rice.
</P>
<P>
   Herman is at once earnest and glib (one friend once called her
``the queen of schmooze''). But she did not want to talk about the
inquiry by an independent counsel ordered in May 1998 by Attorney
General Janet Reno to try to resolve accusations of
influence-peddling and conflict of interest against her.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators are looking into her role in a series of White
House fund-raising coffees in 1995 and 1996, as well as her private
business dealings in the 1980s when she was a consultant on
affirmative action and minority business contracts.
</P>
<P>
   She would discuss the investigation only off the record, and
only then to express bewilderment at the charges and to profess
ignorance on the progress of the inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Her attorney, Neil Eggleston, would say only, ``It's not taking
up too much of my time, and almost none of the secretary's.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Herman nor Eggleston would estimate how much the
investigation has cost her in legal fees, but the final bill will
almost certainly be in six figures.
</P>
<P>
   Calls to the office of the independent counsel, Ralph Lancaster
Jr., a semiretired lawyer from Maine, went unreturned.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Herman has spent virtually her entire working life engaged in
the struggles of working women and minorities. Her first job after
graduating from Xavier University of Louisiana in New Orleans was
with Catholic Charities in Pascagoula, Miss., lobbying the local
shipyard to give apprenticeships to unskilled black workers.
</P>
<P>
   She lent her good dresses to black women applying for office
jobs in the 1970s. She served as director of the Labor Department's
women's bureau in the Carter administration. And she worked on the
presidential campaigns of Jesse Jackson before joining the
Democratic Party in 1989 as deputy director under Ron Brown.
</P>
<P>
   She was involved in the presidential transition in 1992 and
worked in the White House as director of the office of public
liaison through Clinton's first term. She was nominated for the
Labor post in January 1997 and confirmed four months later after a
bitter struggle with Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The position of labor secretary _ she is the first black woman
to hold the job _ has given her an enviable platform to address
issues that have animated her all her life: the rights of workers
in the United States and abroad, the difficulty of balancing work
and family, job programs for disadvantaged youth, the transition to
an information economy.
</P>
<P>
   She listed as her priorities for her remaining months in office
an expansion of the administration's welfare-to-work programs,
additional help for unskilled workers and passage of the
president's health-care bill of rights.
</P>
<P>
   On l'affaire Lewinsky, Herman toed the company line: She was
``disappointed'' in the president's behavior but never doubted his
ability to lead the nation or the sincerity of his contrition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president made a mistake and he told us he made a
mistake,'' Herman said, the smooth smile never fading from her
perfect-oval face. ``I was raised in a faith and a tradition of a
forgiving gospel.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
