<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Monday, Sept. 6, Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
Weekend Editor is Tim Hilchey; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
hilchey(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   TIMOR-VIOLENCE (Dili, Indonesia) _ As the outside world looked
on in horror and the Indonesian government continued its promises
and evasions, armed thugs systematically take over the territory of
East Timor, terrorizing residents and trapping U.N. workers in
their compound. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-DAGESTAN (Moscow) _ A powerful bomb demolished an
apartment building full of Russian officers and their families in
Dagestan late Saturday night, as Islamic militants mounted a
ferocious assault in the Russian republic. By Celestine Bohlen.
(With a map.)
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-CARBOMBS (Jerusalem) _ Two apparent car bombs explode in
separate Israeli cities, in each case killing the bombers, shortly
after the Israelis and Palestinians sign a new peace accord. By
Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL-GENERAL &LR;  (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   EDUC-STANDARDS _ In a big change, states across the nation are
enforcing uniform school standards, giving successful teachers
bonuses and generally raising the level of student performance. By
Tamar Lewin.
</P>
<P>
   MRSCLINTON-CLEMENCY-FLAP (New York) _ With sentiments ranging
from exasperation to bewilderment, several New York Hispanic
political leaders offered sharp criticism Sunday of Hillary Rodham
Clinton's call on her husband to withdraw his offer of commuting
the prison sentences of members of a Puerto Rican terrorist
organization. By Jonathan P. Hicks.
</P>
<P>
   VET-CLUBS-DECLINE (Berwyn, Ill.) _ Veterans clubs are dying as
the number of World War II veterans, who sustained clubs like the
American Legion, diminishes rapidly. We go to the clubs, or what's
left of them, and talk to the aging veterans in places like Berwyn,
a working class town near Chicago. By Dirk Johnson. (With a photo.)
</P>
<P>
   NY-ANCIENT-SKULL (New York) _ An intriguing fossil skull,
presumably from a Homo erectus and possibly a revealing piece of
evidence for understanding human evolution, has been found not on a
parched hill in Africa or along a river in Java, but at a cozy
little shop on the Upper West Side of Manhattan. By John Noble
Wilford. (With a photo.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS &LR;  (Will move in ``s'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BBO-GAY-EXPLAYER _ All-America Billy Bean burst into his 20s
consumed by two struggles: to play center field in the major
leagues and to deny his homosexuality. Eventually he would have to
choose between his personal and professional lives. ``For nine
years,'' Bean said recently, ``I felt as though I had one foot in
the major leagues and one on a banana peel.'' The combination of
those two struggles offers a rare look into the fiercely
competitive and hyper-masculinized arena of major-team sports. By
Robert Lipsyte. (With photos.)
</P>
</TEXT>
