<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-05 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1595 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-AGUILERA-POPSTAR-ART-     09-05 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AGUILERA-POPSTAR-ART-860(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SINGER SEEKS TO PROVE SHE'S NOT A ONE-HIT WONDER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By LUISITA LOPEZ TORREGROSA    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two stories above Broadway, in the MTV studio that
looks out on Times Square, the cameras are rolling, flitting across
an audience of girls in braces and ponytails, tank tops and shorts,
and panning on the scene below, on the mass of people who have been
gathering on the street for hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty seconds ... 10 seconds ... two seconds .... And here
she is! Christina Aguilera!'' Applause, big applause, and from the
street giddy screams rise from the throng of fans herded with their
homemade posters and banners behind police barricades.
</P>
<P>
   Whirling and waving in front of the window looking out on the
crowd, Christina Aguilera, in low-hip leather pants, 3-inch-heel
boots and bare midriff, leaps, her slight frame twisting, her arms
raised, ready to take flight. For a second or two, she looks all of
13.
</P>
<P>
   But she is 18, and for five weeks has had the No. 1 pop single
in the nation, ``Genie in a Bottle.'' Her first album, named after
herself, is now making its debut, not with a single-day splash but
with a weeks-long schedule of signings, television appearances and
interviews in New York and Los Angeles, all intended to make her
not just this summer's pop sensation but a major star.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives me a feeling that's different from any other feeling
in the world,'' she said of her fans' clamoring. ``When I see all
these people screaming and chanting and holding those signs that
they made just for me, my eyes light up, and my whole body just
lifts, and I just feel in another state. I feel like I'm floating
on air. It's the most incredible feeling, and I've always wanted
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Just two months ago Ms. Aguilera was an obscurity, one of the
lesser-known singers in a new crop of teen-age performers. She had
cut her teeth on the Disney Channel's ``Mickey Mouse Club,'' along
with Britney Spears and members of 'N Sync, and she had drawn some
attention with her rendition of ``Reflection'' on the ``Mulan''
soundtrack. But she had released no songs or videos and had made no
major national television appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Then, on June 22, her single came out, and she seemed to spring
out of nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   It was not so simple, of course. Since teen-age artists are
often one-hit wonders, RCA Records, which gave her a seven-album
contract in June 1998, worked especially hard to create a
packaging, producing and promotion campaign for her.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has an incredible voice and presence,'' Bob Jamieson, the
president of RCA Records, said in an interview. ``You know
immediately that she's a star. She has that X factor.'' But that
was not enough. ``We worked on her clothes, her makeup, her hair.
The main thing, we helped her find the material.''
</P>
<P>
   Top pop songwriters were signed up, and an album was put
together mostly for the teen-age market but skewed smartly with
bluesy cuts toward an older audience also. ``I think we've done
Christina fairly uniquely in that we knew that she would appeal to
teens, but we also knew that she was much more than just a teen
artist,'' said Nick Cucci, RCA's marketing vice president.
</P>
<P>
   The Christina team at RCA wishfully likens her to Mariah Carey
or Whitney Houston or Celine Dion. Ron Fair, her record producer at
RCA, calls her, in the hyperinflation of the business, ``our
Streisand.'' And MTV has booked Ms. Aguilera on several
high-profile shows like ``Total Request Live,'' where she appeared
on Aug. 23.
</P>
<P>
   Still, critics reviewing her album have run from hot to
lukewarm. In Time magazine, David Thigpen called her ``one of the
most strikingly gifted singers'' since Mariah Carey. In The New
York Times, Ann Powers said, ``This album hints at a real singer's
emergence.'' But Rolling Stone gave it only two and a half stars
out of five and scoffed at the choice of songs on the album as
``the empress' old clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   After spending four hours in and out of the wardrobe and makeup
rooms and taping segments for MTV, Ms. Aguilera led her entourage _
manager, publicist and bodyguards _ out of the building, her red
cell phone planted on her ear. A black limousine waited to take her
around the block to the RCA offices. She is, her handlers believe,
too precious a commodity to simply cross the street.
</P>
<P>
   Ten minutes later she was ready for a photo shoot in the RCA
conference room, 35 floors above Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   In carefully honed sentences that seemed rehearsed, she said:
``Actually being 18 does put even more pressure on you if you want
to be taken seriously as an artist, because you have to be on top
of what you want to say, how you want to say it, what you want your
points to be and how to get them across. You have to be way sharper
than anybody else because people expect you to be this bubble-gum
airhead, like a dipsy young girl who doesn't know what she's
talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   She continued, ``I plan to take this to its absolute fullest,
venturing off into all sorts of different areas of this business,
all aspects of creativity,'' like movies, television, Broadway,
record-producing. ``I look up to people like Madonna, who has been
able to just completely reinvent herself over and over and over
again.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A life of limousines and people catering to every whim can be
intoxicating at any age, but this singer shows little of the
flighty teen-ager, except for nervous giggles that come when she
lapses into what can seem like studied seriousness, the
Mousketeer-trained smile deserting her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a very spiritual person, and I have a very strong belief
in God and he's completely led me to this point,'' she said.
``There were days years ago when I wanted this more than anything
in this entire world, and I would pray so hard. It was a complete
need I had to do this.''
</P>
<P>
   She added, ``I tend to be a control freak, and I have to be a
perfectionist. I think that's what drives me, because it gives me
control over a situation. I hate feeling vulnerable to this day.''
</P>
<P>
   The blue eyes looked away. She went on: ``A lot of people don't
get to see my personal side, because right now my whole persona is
that of a pop star, and since I am 18 years old, I think that if I
became this serious, appeared to be this deep thinker all the time,
people would almost be scared. They want to see the very bubbly,
perky, outgoing personality.''
</P>
<P>
   But she is ``fearless,'' she said. ``I'm more afraid of the
little things than of the bigger things,'' like ``wanting to
conquer something, to make an impact on the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Aguilera was born in New York, the daughter of an Army
sergeant. She spent her early years in Texas, New Jersey and Japan.
Her parents separated when she was 7, and she and her mother,
Shelly, moved in with her grandmother in a suburb of Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   At age 9 she made her national television debut on ``Star
Search,'' a talent competition that she lost. She auditioned for
``The Mickey Mouse Club,'' was signed when she was 12 and traveled
to Orlando, Fla., to tape the show in the summer. She was
successful but became an outcast at school, the object of snubs and
ridicule, so she left after the eighth grade, her mother and an
occasional math tutor taking over.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, in one of those scenes from a teen-age movie, she
went back to her high school for its prom, saying she wanted ``to
do a normal thing for once,'' just another pop star at the school
dance. But there was no applause, only cold glares.
</P>
<P>
   These days she has no real home. She rents an apartment in New
York and, with bookings through the end of the year, can hardly
think of settling down. She sees little of her mother, with whom
she says she is close, and has lost track of her father, Fausto.
</P>
<P>
   But she wants to go to Ecuador, her father's homeland, and she
plans, besides writing songs for her next album and going to the
Far East and Latin America on tour, to release one record in
Spanish. ``I want to be part of that,'' she said, ``and let people
know I'm part of that, that I have Latin roots as well.''
</P>
<P>
   She also wants to use her popularity, if it lasts, to take up
the cause of battered children and women. ``That's what I meant
when I said I wanted to make an impact on the world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
