<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-05 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1597 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-PALESTINIAN-PRISONERS     09-05 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PALESTINIAN-PRISONERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PALESTINIAN PRISONERS AWAIT FREEDOM WHILE ISRAELIS ARE DIVIDED
OVER THEIR RELEASE
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service(at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   RAMALLAH, West Bank The dream of a Palestinian mother, Raba Abu
Radaha, may be a nightmare for many Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   One of her sons was convicted of killing a Palestinian who
collaborated with Israel. The other hit a Jewish woman settler in
the head with a bar. Today they sit in an Israeli jail.
</P>
<P>
   But under the new agreement signed over the weekend, the pair
may be able to come home.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Israelis want to make peace, they can only make it with
families and people themselves, not with governments,'' said the
mens' brother Samiya Hassan Abu Radaha. ``To do that, you must
release the prisoners.''
</P>
<P>
   A committee of Palestinians and Israelis was gathering names
Sunday night to decide who will be among the 350 prisoners released
under this weekend's revision of the Wye River Memorandum. It was
one of the last items worked out in the weekend's negotiations and
the most emotional issue for Israelis and Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, only prisoners arrested for crimes before
the 1993 beginning of the Oslo peace process would be released. The
Oslo process is aimed at ending hostilities by giving autonomy to
the Palestinians in land Israel captured in 1967. According to
reports, approximately half of the 2,000 palestinians held for
anti-Israeli crimes would be eligible.
</P>
<P>
   But even among the pre-Oslo group, not all will go free. Israeli
officials say they will not release any prisoners who killed
Israelis. They also balk at releasing anyone who belongs to groups
still opposed to peace. Thus, fundamentalists of Hamas or Islamic
Jihad would not be eligible.
</P>
<P>
   But the sons of Raba Abu Radaha do not fall into any of thes
categories. They were activists in Yasser Arafat's Fateh movement
and were both arrested in the early 1990s, before Oslo.
</P>
<P>
   When she visited them in jail Sunday, she said they were ``happy
and optimistic'' this weekend's peace agreement between
Palestinians and Israeli leaders would allow them to go home.
</P>
<P>
   For Palestinians, there is near unanimity that all the political
prisoners should be released.
</P>
<P>
   But, Israelis know the prisoners as terrorists and their
opinions are divided.
</P>
<P>
   Dov Kalmonovitz said he disagrees with the release of prisoners
who only wounded their Israeli targets. A 44-year-old Israeli
accountant, he was burned over 75 percent of his body when a
Palestinian set his moving car ablaze with a Molotov cocktail in
1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``The person who threw the Molotov cocktail wanted to kill me.
Just because I survived and am still standing does not mean he
should be released,'' Kalmonovitz said. ``The people who did these
terrible things must stay in jail.''
</P>
<P>
   His attacker was never caught, but he has campaigned against the
release of Palestinian prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   Chava Stern, 70, takes a different view. Her 64-year-old
husband, Menachem Stern, was a prominent professor at Hebrew
University when he was stabbed to death in 1989 by three men.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot stand in the way of peace. Menachem will not return
and we cannot change that, but we have to go forward,'' Chava Stern
said. ``We have to do everything we can to make sure that more
families will not join the cycle of sorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   (Optional trim)
</P>
<P>
   In Palestinian communities, almost every family has a relative
who is or was in Israeli jails. It's considered an honor in the old
struggle against an Israeli occupation to which they lost land,
homes and their political rights. Most prisoners' families receive
small subsidies from the PLO.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to her two sons now in jail, another son, Hani,
spent four years in prison for throwing rocks and Molotov cocktails
at Israeli troops. He was released in an earlier Oslo-related
amnesty in 1994. He is now in the Palestinian National Authority
security forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a situation of struggle,'' said Amin Abu Radaha, 27.
``A fight for freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
