<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-05 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1598 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-WACO-0906-COX     09-05 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WACO-0906-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dems, GOP spar over Waco
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As partisanship escalated Sunday over belated
revelations about the 1993 tragedy in Waco, Republican lawmakers
demanded a congressional investigation and the ouster of Attorney
General Janet Reno while Democrats blamed the FBI and said Congress
should hold off on hearings.
</P>
<P>
   Reno, who denied for the past six years that the government used
incendiary tear gas grenades in their assault on the Branch
Davidian compound, announced last month that she was mistaken.
Claiming that she only learned recently that the devices had been
used, Reno has called for an outside investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Phil Gramm of Texas was among the Republicans calling for
Reno to resign.
</P>
<P>
   ``You reach a point where not knowing is not an excuse,'' said
Gramm on ``This Week'' on ABC-TV. ``When you have a high position
of public trust, I think part of your job is knowing and when you
don't know you're not doing your job.''
</P>
<P>
   Chairman Dan Burton, R-Ind., said his House Government Reform
Committee will look into all aspects of the April 19, 1993, FBI
assault that ended with the deaths of Branch Davidian leader David
Koresh and 75 of his followers, including 21 children. Burton said
he is disturbed by new reports that Army Special Operations forces
were at Waco throughout the 51-day siege.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think all of this needs to be investigated,'' said Burton on
``Face the Nation'' on CBS-TV. ``We thought we had all the answers
six years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal agents ``were in my opinion incompetent in doing the
investigation or there was a cover-up, one or the other,'' said
Burton. ``But (Reno) should be held responsible, because she was
the attorney general and it was on her watch.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Democrats defended Reno and blamed FBI Director Louis
Freeh because his agency conducted the Waco operation and
subsequent investigation into the incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an incident here in which Janet Reno is now being
blamed for what the FBI didn't do,'' said Rep. John Conyers, D-Mi.,
on NBC's ``Meet the Press.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as blaming (Reno) for the investigation, we should
remember that she used primarily the FBI to do the investigation,''
said Sen. Pat Leahy, D-Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   In their appearances on Sunday TV talk shows, Democratic
congressmen appeared to be following the White House line. On
Saturday, President Clinton pointedly supported Reno but not Freeh
in answering questions from reporters.
</P>
<P>
   On Freeh, he said he said there wasn't ``any purpose to assign
blame until the investigation is concluded.''
</P>
<P>
   However, on CNN's ``Late Edition,'' Sen. Orrin Hatch, a
Republican presidential hopeful, said he would fire Reno while
calling Freeh the ``single best'' FBI director he has seen during
his years in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Although Congress is returning from its summer recess this week,
Democrats said this is not the time for committee hearings on Waco.
Wait until an independent investigator is appointed and has
completed the outside probe, they urged.
</P>
<P>
   ``My worry is that congressional investigations will bring up a
lot of heat and not very much light. Each party will play its
preordained role, there will be lots of fighting, and the
conspiracy theorists will be given even more feelings against the
facts,'' said Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., a member of the
Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans -- who control both the House and Senate --
predicted there would be hearings.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't have the country misled for six years by the Justice
Department and the FBI and not have Congress do something about
it,'' said Gramm.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a number of questions that have to be answered as to
the role of the Delta Force, as to the use of the incendiary
devices, and at what level up the chain the approval was given,''
said Rep. Asa Hutchinson, R-Ark. ``And so Janet Reno accepted
responsibility, and we have to ask what does that mean.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bob Barr, R-Ga., also said there is much for Congress to do
on the Waco investigation. Appearing on CNN's ``Late Edition, Barr
also suggested Atlanta attorney Griffin Bell as a competent and
credible outside investigator. Bell served as attorney general in
the Carter administration.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
