<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-05 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1601 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-GERMANY-ELECTIONS-ART     09-05 1096
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-ELECTIONS-ART-530&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO GERMAN STATES HAND SCHROEDER A SETBACK 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ Voters in two German states handed a sharp rebuff to
Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder on Sunday, ousting his long-dominant
Social Democratic Party in the western Saarland and ushering a
far-right party into the state Parliament for the first time in
Brandenburg.
</P>
<P>
   The results amounted to a humiliating setback for the
chancellor, who has been unable to exploit the wave of enthusiasm
that brought him to office a year ago. He has seen his support
dwindle steadily as unemployment in Europe's largest economy has
remained high, with disgruntlement widespread.
</P>
<P>
   In a televised statement, Schroeder said that he was
``disappointed and sad'' about the results, but that they would in
no way affect ``my readiness to fight on.''
</P>
<P>
   In Saarland, where the Social Democrats have been in power for
15 years, projections by leading television networks showed the
Christian Democrats edging out Schroeder's party by 45.3 percent to
44.3 percent _ a remarkable result in what amounts to a heartland
of German labor.
</P>
<P>
   Voters in Brandenburg, a former East German state surrounding
Berlin, turned away from the Social Democrats in droves, bringing
the party's share of the vote down to about 39.5 percent from 54.1
percent in 1994. The Social Democrats will now be obliged to form a
coalition government in the state.
</P>
<P>
   One of the main beneficiaries of the disillusionment with
Schroeder was the far-right Deutsche Volksunion, which spent
heavily in recent weeks to ram home a xenophobic message that
unemployment of about 20 percent in Brandenburg was attributable to
the presence of foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   The Volksunion took about 5.3 percent of the vote, projections
showed, just over the 5 percent needed in Germany to qualify for
parliamentary representation. The result clearly reflected anger
among youths in the eastern states who have been unable to find
jobs and have chosen to vent their frustration through skinhead
violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an outstanding achievement and I am highly
satisfied,'' said Gerhard Frey, the wealthy Bavarian publisher who
is the Volksunion's main backer. After its success last year in
another eastern state, Saxony Anhalt, where the party took 13
percent of the vote, the result Sunday suggested that the east
remains fertile ground for neo-Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's outcome indicated that the coming months will not be
easy for Schroeder. After a long spell of policy zigzags, he has
been trying to project a more decisive air, particularly over
economic policy.
</P>
<P>
   In effect, he now seems ready to gamble that unpopular measures
_ including freezing pensions in real terms and huge budget cuts _
will over the medium term help revitalize a state-heavy economy and
so create the jobs that Schroeder promised to deliver when he came
to power under the banner of the ``New Middle.''
</P>
<P>
   The gamble is a considerable one and, with three more state
elections approaching in the coming weeks, the chancellor's
authority may be further undermined. But for now, his own party and
his coalition partners, the Greens, are trying to present a united
face despite evident tensions.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The results Sunday will erode Schroeder's support in the upper
house of Parliament where the Social Democrats had a clear majority
until a defeat in the state of Hesse in February. The 69-seat upper
house consists of delegations from the 16 state governments, with
Saarland holding three seats and Brandenburg four.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder will be obliged, more than ever, to compromise with
the Christian Democrats on major legislation because the upper
house can amend or reject bills from the lower house.
</P>
<P>
   Pending legislation includes the budget offered by Hans Eichel,
the finance minister, which amounts to the cornerstone of
Schroeder's domestic policy. It proposes a $16-billion cut in
federal spending next year _ a step the government regards as
essential to bring down spiraling federal debt and eventually open
the way for tax cuts seen as vital to spurring the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Eichel's draft budget has not proved popular, especially his
proposal to end the longstanding German practice that pensions rise
at the same rate as wages. The pension proposal provided a great
deal of ammunition for the Christian Democrats in this campaign.
</P>
<P>
   It has also divided the Social Democrats. Reinhard Klimmt, the
party's candidate in Saarland, has in recent weeks been a sharp
critic of what he has portrayed as Schroeder's rightward turn away
from the party roots in organized labor.
</P>
<P>
   The message went down well with labor unions in Saarland. But
high unemployment and anger over the departure from government and
party leadership earlier this year of Finance Minister Oskar
Lafontaine, the former Social Democratic Saarland state premier,
evidently undermined the Klimmt campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Klimmt will now hand the state premiership, which he inherited
from Lafontaine, to Peter Mueller, a young Christian Democrat who
appealed to voters with a vision of a new Saarland economy based in
the service, software and telecommunications industries of the
future. Mueller has said the heavily subsidized regional coal
industry will have to close.
</P>
<P>
   The defeat of Klimmt, after the departure from politics of
Lafontaine, leaves the left wing of the Social Democrats without
any obvious representative. This may help Schroeder as he tries to
push through his program, but may also cause anger and frustration
among Germany's powerful unions.
</P>
<P>
   In Brandenburg, the Christian Democrats and the Party of
Democratic Socialism _ the former East German Communist Party _
each benefited from the collapse of the Social Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The Christian Democrats took about 26 percent of the vote,
projections showed, compared with 18.7 percent in 1994, and the
Party of Democratic Socialism took about 25 percent, 7 percent more
than five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   It was not immediately clear which party Manfred Stolpe, the
Social Democratic state premier, would invite to form a coalition.
But it is already clear that the eastern states, a bulwark of
Schroeder's electoral victory a year ago, have quickly shifted
their allegiance and still amount to turbulent, unpredictable
political turf a decade after the fall of the Berlin Wall.
</P>
</TEXT>
