<HEADER>
A1604 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-CARBOMBS-ART-4     09-05 1182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-CARBOMBS-ART-475&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAR BOMBS BRING TERROR TO RENEWED PEACE EFFORT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Less than 24 hours after a new Israeli-Palestinian
agreement was signed, two cars packed with explosives blew up
almost simultaneously in two northern Israeli cities Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   In Tiberias and Haifa, the cars' occupants, presumed to be
failed car bombers, were killed and several passersby were injured,
one seriously.
</P>
<P>
   The explosions offered a jolting reminder of the terrorist
threats that had hovered over recent negotiations. And they forced
a very quick test of what the newly restored Israeli-Palestinian
relationship could weather, since terrorism has interrupted the
peace process many times before.
</P>
<P>
   Early Sunday night, Ehud Barak, the prime minister of Israel,
issued a terse statement saying that Israel would not tolerate
``violence or terrorism against innocent civilians.'' But he did
not make any indication that he would halt the peace process he had
just revived.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the attempted attacks did not even derail his evening
plans. The prime minister spent most of the night locked in heated
debate over his budget cuts with the Israeli Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   The two cars, both Fiat Unos, detonated almost simultaneously,
just after 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   In the city of Tiberias on the Sea of Galilee, debris from the
blast injured several passers-by, one woman seriously. The two
presumed bombers went up in flames in a car left badly mangled.
</P>
<P>
   In the Mediterranean port town of Haifa, the police labeled the
explosion a work accident, indicating that the man who was killed
was presumed to have been rigging his car bomb. The blast took
place in a nearly deserted parking lot in a mixed, Israeli and
Arab, commercial area. Surrounding cars, which were empty, burst
into flames, and the lot lay strewn with the Fiat driver's body
parts Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   The car bombers were presumed to be acting in coordination.
Israeli police said the explosions bore the hallmarks of Islamic
militant terror attacks.
</P>
<P>
   No group immediately took responsibility for the bombings. The
police were also allegedly investigating a possible coordination
between Israeli Arabs and Palestinian terrorist groups, television
reports said.
</P>
<P>
   The explosions came minutes after the Israeli Cabinet
overwhelmingly approved Barak's new deal with the Palestinians. The
deal, signed early Sunday morning in Egypt, modifies a previous
agreement, creating a timeline for Israeli withdrawals from the
West Bank and for the release of Palestinian prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the timing, I think this clarifies that there is a
war going on between the peace process and terror,'' said Yaron
Ezrhahi, a leading political scientist. ``The paradox is that when
there is no terror, it is usually the victory of terror over the
peace process. Now, they are fighting the peace process because
they know it promises to kill terror once and for all.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As the General Security Services investigated the two scenes,
the Israeli police set up road blocks at the entrances to every
city in the north.
</P>
<P>
   Five hours before the attempted attacks, Jibril Rajoub, a senior
Palestinian security official, had told Israel Radio that
Palestinian security had evidence that both Hamas and Islamic
Jihad, two fundamentalist groups, were planning terror incidents to
disrupt the peace effort.
</P>
<P>
   Rajoub said his officers had arrested 50 Hamas members in the
last few weeks in an effort to foil their plans to commit terrorist
acts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though we don't know the full story, I would like to
express here the Palestinian Authority's firm policy of zero
tolerance for terror,'' Saeb Erekat, a senior Palestinian
negotiator, told CNN Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   The explosions Sunday followed a string of seemingly incompetent
terrorist attempts last fall. At the time, security experts
questioned whether the incompetence was a sign that terrorist
groups had been disabled by Palestinian-Israel security cooperation
and by a series of assassinations of key operatives.
</P>
<P>
   But, as was pointed out then, even a bumbling car bomber can
wreak havoc.
</P>
<P>
   Both Israeli and Palestinian negotiators condemned the attacks
and their implications for the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Erekat said that he had hoped ``the enemies of peace'' would not
resume their terrorism. ``I hope that nothing will stop the peace
process,'' he said. ``If this proves to be a terror attack, we
totally condemn it. It's time for reconciliation.''
</P>
<P>
   But his counterpart, Gilad Sher, the senior Israeli negotiator,
said that continued terrorism could indeed derail the joint effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``No peace process will prevail over the personal security of
the people of Israel,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The attempted attacks provided ammunition for critics of Barak's
peace efforts, who had failed to capture much public attention
during the day.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night, they called on him either to suspend the new
agreement or to put the Palestinians on alert that another attempt
or attack would freeze the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an appropriate moment for Barak to stop unless the
Palestinians fight terror,'' said Limor Livnat, a Likud Party
member of parliament.
</P>
<P>
   ``Otherwise I think the public will not let him return to those
days of blood-soaked streets.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Likud members blamed the Palestinian security forces for
making half-hearted efforts to clamp down the Islamic opposition
parties. But Ephraim Sneeh, Israel's deputy defense minister,
defended the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no evidence the Palestinian Authority has reduced its
battle against terror in the last few days,'' Sneeh said. ``On the
contrary, we have opposite indications.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot dance to the tune of Hamas and Islamic Jihad,'' he
continued. ``They want to the peace process to stop. We want it to
continue.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the attacks were aborted, life in Israel did not stop in
its tracks Sunday. After Israeli television halted its regular
programming to make the initial reports, they returned to coverage
of an Israel-Cyprus soccer match. (Israel lost).
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the Israeli Cabinet, after taking a break to
investigate the situation, plunged back into tense budget
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Returning Sunday morning from the midnight signing ceremony in
Egypt, Barak faced mounds of fetid garbage in the streets of
Jerusalem, evidence of a nationwide municipal workers' strike.
</P>
<P>
   Then he plunged into meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Barak enjoyed the overwhelming support of his Cabinet for his
peace initiative earlier Sunday; only Natan Sharansky, the Russian
immigrant leader, and Yitzhak Levy, the National Religious Party
leader, voted against it.
</P>
<P>
   But he faced open rebellion over his planned budget cuts, with
opposition from at least 11 populist-minded ministers, including
several of his key allies in the peace effort.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-99 1824EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990905.0108 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-05 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1605 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-DAGESTAN-ART-4     09-05 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-DAGESTAN-ART-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOMB IN DAGESTAN KILLS AT LEAST 30 PEOPLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ In a painful setback for the Russian military, Islamic
militants mounted a ferocious assault in Dagestan, and a powerful
bomb demolished an apartment building housing Russian officers and
their families in that Russian republic.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials, who had all but declared victory against the
rebels nearly two weeks ago, said at least 30 people had been
killed and about 110 wounded in the blast, which occurred late
Saturday night when a car bomb exploded in Buinaksk, Dagestan's
second-largest city.
</P>
<P>
   Russian television showed the ruins of the five-story apartment
complex: a heap of collapsed walls, twisted metal and debris beside
a 10-foot-deep bomb crater.
</P>
<P>
   The bombing coincided with a separate rebel offensive in western
Dagestan, as the militants _ estimated to number several hundred to
more than a thousand _ streamed across the border from Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   The renewed fighting was an unwelcome political test for
Vladimir Putin, the former intelligence official who was elevated
to the post of prime minister last month by President Boris Yeltsin
and touted as a presidential successor.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing in an interview on the ORT Russian television network,
Putin sought to assure a jittery public, still haunted by Russia's
humiliating defeat in Chechnya, that the Russian army's campaign
against the militants would prevail.
</P>
<P>
   ``The operation in the Caucasus is going according to plan, not
slowly and not too fast,'' Putin said in the interview, which was
taped Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But his calm demeanor contrasted with the frantic efforts in
Dagestan to repulse the rebels. Russian air force SS-25s and
Russian artillery pounded rebel positions Sunday as the local
authorities in Dagestan, stung by the surge in the fighting,
announced a mobilization of all able-bodied men.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the most dramatic clashes, a column of Russian forces
sought to break the rebel attack on a garrison of 50 policemen that
had found itself outnumbered and surrounded by the militants in the
village of Novolakskoye in western Dagestan. Russian news reports
said the garrison had been involved in a vicious fire fight for
more than seven hours and was running out of ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's troubles in Dagestan began last month when several
thousand Islamic rebels crossed into the Botlikh region of the
Russian republic from Chechnya, vowing to evict Russians from the
northern Caucasus and create an Islamic state.
</P>
<P>
   They were led by Shamil Basayev, a Chechen commander, and
Khattab, a Jordanian-born Chechen. The assault, however, was not
supported by the Chechen government of President Aslan Maskhadov,
which has been unable to exert its will over rival warlords.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The rebel incursion sparked Russian fears of a brutal
Chechnya-style conflict. Certainly the rebels have some advantages.
They know the terrain and operate with relative impunity from bases
across the Chechen border.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian military has bombed bases in Chechnya, but has been
reluctant to invade the disputed province, fearing that that would
draw more Chechens into the fighting and involve the Russian
military in a quagmire.
</P>
<P>
   But the Russians have some factors in their favor, too. Much of
the Dagestani population is against the rebels. The Russians also
have enormous firepower, including bombers, helicopters and
artillery, which have been used extensively in an effort to hold
down Russian losses.
</P>
<P>
   After the initial two weeks of heavy fighting near the border,
the Russian military appeared to have chased many of the Islamic
fighters back to Chechnya. The Russian forces declared victory,
though the military warned that the militants might still engage in
hit-and-run tactics.
</P>
<P>
   But what happened this weekend was clearly much more than the
Russians had expected. On Sunday night the war was being carried
out on several fronts.
</P>
<P>
   First, there was the bombing of the apartment complex at
Buinaksk, where the Russian military's 156th brigade is stationed.
</P>
<P>
   Situated southwest of the Dagestani capital of Makhachkaka,
Buinaksk is near two villages _ Karamakhi and Chabanmakhi _ that
have been the scene of clashes between Russian troops and Islamic
militants and their supporters among the Wahhabi sect. The sect has
enforced Islamic law and until recently has enjoyed relative
autonomy in Dagestan.
</P>
<P>
   The car bomb in Buinaksk went off at 9:45 p.m. Saturday, as
soldiers, their families and ordinary civilians were watching a
soccer match on television between France and Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
   Women and children were reported to be among the dead and
wounded, and on Sunday rescue crews dug through the rubble
searching for survivors. Other explosives were reportedly found and
defused near another apartment complex occupied by Russian troops
and a military hospital.
</P>
<P>
   A second rebel attack took place in the Novolakskoye region in
western Dagestan as the militants attacked from Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   One goal of the rebels, Russian officials said, was to secure
this region of Dagestan and declare an Islamic republic, which
would be centered in the nearby town of Khasavyurt.
</P>
<P>
   Vladimir Smirnov, a senior Russian intelligence official in
Dagestan, said the separate attacks were part of a carefully
coordinated plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are links in the same chain,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-99 1825EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
