<SLUG> BC-FOOD-OWEN-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COOL CHICKEN SALAD CAN BE HORNET FREE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN OWEN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Never mind what you read in the travel brochures _ you don't
even have to leave the state of Washington to experience the best
saltwater cruise value in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Starting in Anacortes, the ship winds its way through the
picturesque San Juan Islands and terminates in Friday Harbor, an
almost too-cute community spilling from the forested hills down to
the shore.
</P>
<P>
   Total price is $5.30, or $2.70 for seniors or juniors. That
includes port taxes, gratuities, and excursions to the sun deck,
the drinking fountain or the rest rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, that is the walk-on fare for the state ferry ride. But
you don't bring your Subaru onto the Sun Princess, do you?
</P>
<P>
   Once in Friday Harbor you can rent a bike or a scooter, take a
shuttle bus across the island or tour the community's art
galleries, shops and numerous cafes.
</P>
<P>
   My wife and I recently spent 30 minutes trying to decide which
tree-shaded outdoor table we would select at lunchtime. When we
informed the hostess of our choice she shook her head and
suggested: ``I think you'd rather eat indoors.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bees!''
</P>
<P>
   Yup, there are thorns in the Garden of Eden. Flying thorns. A
tourist wandering down the street with an ice cream cone quickly
becomes the object of dive-bomber assaults. If the tourist begins
to slap at the buzzing intruders, everybody within a 30-yard radius
considers a swan dive into the harbor.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, they're not bees. They are hornets, or yellow jackets.
And they perform a lot of helpful services to the flora of San Juan
Island, since they reduce the population of aphids, caterpillars
and other insect pests.
</P>
<P>
   Guess it takes a pest to recognize another one.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the yellow jackets have spoiled more than one recent
barbecue and picnic, on and off San Juan Island. Even so, they are
more to be pitied than censured.
</P>
<P>
   Do you know why the yellow jackets wait until August or
September before deciding to hand-wrestle your maiden aunt for a
chicken wing at your annual family hoorah?
</P>
<P>
   Just like your maiden aunt, they're hungry. They are also
motivated by a hidden urge to fill the skies with more yellow
jackets. The hornets lack an enzyme needed to digest the food they
gather. So they deliver the food to larvae, who do have the needed
enzyme. When the kids have eaten, the adult hornets get the
leftovers, which have now been provided by the larvae with the
needed enzyme.
</P>
<P>
   However, by August or September the larvae have hatched, or
whatever, the enzymes are gone and the adult hornets are on their
own and literally starving. That's why they develop waspish
dispositions. And that's why you'd better eat indoors at Friday
Harbor, where the food is just as good ... and bug-free.
</P>
<P>
   You might find salads as good as these.
</P>
<P>
   San Juan Salad
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds cooked chicken or turkey meat
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces water chestnuts, sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 pound seedless green grapes
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup chopped celery
</P>
<P>
   One-third cup toasted almonds
</P>
<P>
   1 and one-half cups mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon curry powder
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   Crisp lettuce leaves
</P>
<P>
   Cut the poultry into bite-size pieces and plunk into a large
bowl with the water chestnuts, grapes, celery and almonds. Chill in
refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   When ready to eat, mix the mayonnaise with the curry, soy and
lemon juice. Mix with the chicken.
</P>
<P>
   Put a lettuce leaf on each plate and top with portions of the
salad. This should serve six to eight.
</P>
<P>
   American Camp Salad
</P>
<P>
   One-half pound small penne pasta
</P>
<P>
   3 red peppers, seeded and cubed
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch broccoli
</P>
<P>
   12 black olives, halved
</P>
<P>
   2 7-ounce cans solid white tuna
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons drained capers
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dry oregano leaves, crumbled
</P>
<P>
   Three-quarters teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 small clove garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter teaspoon black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Peel broccoli stems and cut diagonally { inch thick. Divide
florets into 1-inch pieces. Steam the broccoli until crisp but
tender and cool under running water. (If you can't abide hornets or
broccoli, substitute an equal amount of Chinese pea pods.)
</P>
<P>
   Cook the pasta according to package instructions or until it is
tender to the bite. Drain and dump into a tub of cold water.
</P>
<P>
   In a jar combine the olive oil, vinegar, capers, oregano, salt,
garlic and pepper. Shake to combine.
</P>
<P>
   Use paper towels to pat dry the pasta and broccoli. Lay out in a
bowl with the red pepper hunks and olives. Toss with some dressing.
Add the tuna. Add more dressing if needed and toss again, lightly.
</P>
<P>
   Chill until ready to serve and this should suffice as main dish
for four, with French or garlic bread.
</P>
<P>
   For dessert, you can have an ice cream bar on the ferry boat
ride home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
