<SLUG> BC-EXP-ISRAEL-CARBOMBS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO CAR BOMBS EXPLODE HOURS AFTER ISRAELI-PALESTINIAN DEAL SIGNED 
</HEADLINE>
 (nk) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Less than 24 hours after a new Israeli-Palestinian
agreement was signed, two cars packed with explosives blew up
almost simultaneously in two northern Israeli cities Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   In Tiberias and Haifa, the cars' occupants, presumed to be the
unsuccessful bombers, were killed and several passers-by were
injured, one seriously.
</P>
<P>
   The explosions were a jolting reminder of the terrorist threats
that had hovered over recent negotiations. And they forced a quick
test of what the newly restored Israeli-Palestinian relationship
could weather, since terrorism has interrupted the peace process
many times before.
</P>
<P>
   Early Sunday night, Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak issued a
terse statement saying that Israel would not tolerate ``violence or
terrorism against innocent civilians.'' But he did not make any
indication that he would halt the process he had just revived.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the attempted attacks did not even derail his evening
plans. The prime minister spent most of the night locked in heated
debate over his budget cuts with the Israeli Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli police said the explosions bore the hallmarks of Islamic
militant terror attacks. No group immediately took responsibility
for the bombings. The police were also investigating possible
coordination between Israeli Arabs and Palestinian terrorist
groups, television reports said.
</P>
<P>
   The explosions occurred minutes after the Israeli Cabinet
overwhelmingly approved Barak's new deal with the Palestinians. The
deal, signed early Sunday morning in Egypt, modifies a previous
agreement, creating a timeline for Israeli withdrawals from the
West Bank and for the release of Palestinian prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   The attempted attacks provided ammunition for critics of Barak's
peace efforts, who called on him either to suspend the new
agreement or to put the Palestinians on alert that another attempt
or attack would freeze the deal.
</P>
<P>
   But Ephraim Sneeh, Israel's deputy defense minister, defended
the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no evidence the Palestinian Authority has reduced its
battle against terror in the last few days,'' Sneeh said. ``On the
contrary, we have opposite indications.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot dance to the tune of Hamas and Islamic Jihad,'' he
continued. ``They want to the peace process to stop. We want it to
continue.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
