<HEADER>
A1617 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-PACTQ&AMP;A06-COX     09-05 0645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-PACTQ&AMP;A06-COX-1SLEDE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    BC-COX-MIDEAST -PACTQ&AMP;A-1STLEDE
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Eds: adds line to fourth question.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    NEW WYE DEAL DIFFERS IN SPIRIT, SIMILAR IN DETAIL
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service(at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM The Israeli Cabinet Sunday gave its approval to the
Sharm El-Sheikh agreement signed with the Palestinians hours
earlier on restarting the Wye River Memorandum peace process. The
process will start within days.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why was this agreement signed now?
</P>
<P>
   A: The peace process had been stalled since January, meaning the
Israelis had stopped turning over land to the Palestinians in the
so-called ``land-for-peace'' arrangement outlined in the Oslo
accords of 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The new Israeli Prime Minister, Ehud Barak, had promised to
restart the process when he was elected in May, but he wanted to
renegotiate the terms.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How does the peace process work?
</P>
<P>
   A: In the 1967 war, Israel captured the Arab areas of the Gaza
Strip and the West Bank. It occupied them until Oslo, despite the
often violent protests of the 2.5 million Palestinians there. The
Oslo process requires Israel to give back some of the land and the
Palestinians to drop their opposition to the existence of a Jewish
state.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the process come the tough ``permanent status''
issues. They determine whether Israel will share Jerusalem with the
Palestinians, allow Palestinian refugees back to their land or let
the Palestinians establish an independent state.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why do they keep signing agreements if they signed the Oslo
pact in 1993?
</P>
<P>
   A: Including the original Oslo accords, seven agreements have
been signed and more are expected.
</P>
<P>
   Oslo was just an outline, not a detailed plan. It was always
expected that more agreements would be needed.
</P>
<P>
   Secondly, the process has broken down frequently. Its original
signatory, Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin, was assassinated in 1995.
In 1996, Israelis elected Benjamin Netanyahu, who had opposed Oslo,
pact. Despite signing two agreement he effectively shut the process
down by January, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How is Sunday's agreement different from the Wye agreement
just signed in October?
</P>
<P>
   A: They are very similar. But, the Wye accord was not carried
out. The new agreement includes specific dates for when Israel is
supposed to fulfill its commitments.
</P>
<P>
   In the deal, Israel has to let the Palestinians begin
construction of a port in Gaza and create a route through Israel
for Palestinians to travel between Palestinian territories items
promised in Wye but not delivered.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has to give back the same amount of land as in the Wye
agreement another 11 percent of the West Bank but gets a longer
time to do so.
</P>
<P>
   The new agreement also sets a Sept. 2000 deadline for settling
all disputes between the Israelis and Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So, what did Barak get out of the deal?
</P>
<P>
   A: He got to renegotiate a deal his country had already signed
and ended up with almost everything he wanted. He got to stretch
out the land transfers until Jan. 20. By that time, at Barak's
insistence, the two sides will be forming the outline for the
``permanent status'' issues.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has been concerned that Israel should not be giving away
land until it knows roughly how the final issues will be resolved.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why are most Palestinians so skeptical of the process?
</P>
<P>
   A: Many items now being discussed were supposed to be resolved
long ago. Israel holds the land and the power to shut the process
down when it wants. Just as Palestinians did not want to
renegotiate Wye but did in the face of ultimatums from Barak, they
fear he can give them just take-it-or-leave offers on all the
remaining issues.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-09-05-99 1811EDT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
