<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BC-KAN-BUDGET-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Monday,
Sept. 6, 1999. If you have any questions, please call Miranda
Kennedy or Patricia Hardin on the Star's News Desk at (816)
234-4720.
</P>
<P>
   HEASTER-COLUMN (Undated) _ Economics column by JERRY HEASTER.
Story will move in the ``f'' category.
</P>
<P>
   LABOR-TIGHT (KANSAS CITY, Mo.) _ Many workers in the Kansas City
area this Labor Day are enjoying life in a tight labor market.
Mobility has never been better for job hoppers and many are being
showered with high salaries and bonuses. By RANDOLPH HEASTER. Story
will move in the ``a'' and ``f'' categories.
</P>
<P>
   LABOR-WORKER (KANSAS CITY, Mo.) _ (Sidebar to LABOR-TIGHT) The
economy is chugging along at unprecedented levels. Productivity is
up, unemployment is down, and real wages have finally begun to
rise. These seem to be the best of times for workers. But are all
workers doing better as a result of the economy's staggering
growth? By RANDOLPH HEASTER. Story will move in the ``a'' and ``f''
categories.
</P>
<P>
   TIFFANY-ROY (KANSAS CITY, Mo.) _ Tiffany was born with her
umbilical cord wrapped around her neck. The cord starved her brain
of oxygen, with devastating results. She had cerebral palsy. She
couldn't see. She couldn't hear. Doctors predicted the baby girl
would live only a few months. She was headed to a group home
because her mentally disabled mother couldn't take care of her.
That fate didn't sound fair to Roy Hutchison, a paramedic who heard
talk of Tiffany at the hospital. ``You lock up prisoners _ you
don't lock up children,'' Hutchison thought. Within days Hutchison,
his wife and son gave the baby a home. That was the fall of 1984.
Hutchison has gotten divorced since then. He's lost his son in a
car crash. But he's held on tight to Tiffany, who will soon turn
15. By KIM KOZLOWSKI and DONALD BRADLEY. Story will move in the
``a'' category.
</P>
<P>
   CONVICT-FATE (KANSAS CITY, Mo.) _ The investigation into
Claire-Marie Monti's death would develop into one of the most
complex and hard-fought murder cases in recent Johnson County,
Kan., history _ a literal life-and-death struggle for the fate of a
smooth-talking ex-convict with a violent temper named Carl Dean
Rails. By TONY RIZZO. Story will move in the ``a'' category.
</P>
</TEXT>
