<DOCNO> NYT19990905.0122 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-05 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1629 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-LABOR-TIGHT-KAN &LR;      09-05 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABOR-TIGHT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS LABOR DAY, MOST WORKERS ARE BASKING IN TIGHT MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDOLPH HEASTER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Employees at American Century Cos. can
receive as much as $10,000 in bonus money for a successful referral
in certain high-tech positions.
</P>
<P>
   Workers in information technology at the Kansas City mutual fund
company also can earn an extra year's salary over a four-year
period for meeting performance standards.
</P>
<P>
   Many workers in the Kansas City area this Labor Day are enjoying
life in a tight labor market. Mobility has never been better for
job hoppers, and many are being showered with high salaries and
bonuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bonuses aren't just for football players anymore,'' said Don
Feltham, a principal with Burgess and Associates, a Lenexa, Kan.,
human resources consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of where you work, most likely your company is
hiring. Although wages have not skyrocketed for everyone in the
trenches, employers have had to come up with creative ways to
retain employees and lure new workers. In some cases, companies
have bent or broken laws to bolster their work force, government
officials say.
</P>
<P>
   The area unemployment rate hit a record low for the month of
July, and demand for labor is pervasive here and in many parts of
the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that a lot of employers are looking at
what they can do to deal with a tight labor market,'' Feltham said.
``Even if you're only seeing base wages and salaries increase 3 or
4 percent annually, a lot of these employers are having to come up
with variable pay or incentive packages that create additional
income for their employees.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, Gear for Sports, a Lenexa sports apparel
manufacturer, changed its bonus program in 1996. Hourly employees _
including office, production and customer service workers _ can
receive bonus payments up to six times a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, it seems to be working,'' said Jim Keaton, Gear's
vice president of human resources.
</P>
<P>
   People who work in information technology are highly sought in
many industries, particularly with so many resources being poured
into fixing potential year 2000 problems.
</P>
<P>
   American Century's retention program started in January 1998,
and the first bonus payment was made last summer, said spokeswoman
Julie Bartels Smith. So far, the program has reduced the turnover
rate of information technology employees from 16 percent to 5
percent, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Financial incentives aren't the only way businesses are trying
to keep their employees.
</P>
<P>
   Surveys at Station Casino Kansas City revealed that its 2,400
full- and part-time employees wanted a child-care facility. The
casino opened one in May.
</P>
<P>
   ``The No. 1 perk or benefit going back two years was child
care,'' said John Finamore, the casino's president and general
manager. ``The child-care facility was not so much to attract new
team members but to help existing team members.''
</P>
<P>
   Finamore said 305 children from the 225 employee families were
registered at the facility.
</P>
<P>
   Finamore sees the facility, which operates 24 hours a day, as an
advantage for the company in the gambling and services industries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we're also starting to see it's helping as a recruitment
tool,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As a company gets bigger, camaraderie among employees can lessen
because of the lack of contact among some workers. Barkley
Evergreen &AMP; Partners has taken an unusual approach to combat that
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this summer, workers at the Kansas City advertising
agency were treated to what's called a ``kidnap,'' in which
virtually all employees were hustled onto a bus and taken to an
undisclosed location.
</P>
<P>
   They were treated to an afternoon at the Incred-A-Bowl in
Overland Park, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody had a ball,'' said Kay Moore, the agency's vice
president of human resources.
</P>
<P>
   Moore said the firm began the practice last year. It also serves
as a way to bring together employees who don't run into one another
in the course of a workday.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we grow, the biggest complaint we get is people don't get
to know each other,'' said Moore, whose firm now employs about 185
people.
</P>
<P>
   There's also a dark side to the worker shortage.
</P>
<P>
   Some immigrants are being paid substandard wages, labor
officials said. Earlier this year, for example, an area nursing
home company agreed to pay a fine to federal regulators after being
accused of hiring Filipino women as nurses' aides and paying them
less than half the wages they were promised.
</P>
<P>
   Some businesses also have run into difficulties when hiring
children. In some cases, the problems involve the number of hours
worked, as well as children working beyond a certain time. Another
problem involves adults hiring youths to illegally peddle wares
door to door by using deceptive sales practices.
</P>
<P>
   Colleen Baker, director of the Missouri Division of Labor
Standards, said between 3 million and 4 million children 16 and
younger were working in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tight labor market definitely has led to more kids
working,'' she said. ``There's been more abuse of wage-and-hour
laws, and there's more potential for abuse in the youth-peddling
area.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker said her division was investigating youth-peddling
activities that could be illegal in the Kansas City area.
</P>
<P>
   The Division of Labor Standards has issued guidelines for youths
who want to participate in legitimate door-to-door sales, as well
as questions for residents to ask children who are selling in their
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Those seeking more information or who want to identify an
illegal youth-peddling operation can call the Division of Labor
Standards at (800) 475-2130.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-99 1910EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990905.0123 </DOCNO>
