<HEADLINE>
NOT ALL AMERICANS ARE CASHING IN ON BOOMING ECONOMY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDOLPH HEASTER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The economy is chugging along at
unprecedented levels. Productivity is up, unemployment is down, and
real wages have finally begun to rise.
</P>
<P>
   These seem like the best of times for workers. But are all
workers doing better as a result of the economy's staggering
growth?
</P>
<P>
   Of course, job opportunities abound and some people are striking
pay dirt. But it's clear the earnings gains of recent years also
depend on your line of work and the financial condition of your
company.
</P>
<P>
   Employees in the mutual fund industry, for example, most likely
are doing better than most right now. On the other hand, employees
at financially weak Trans World Airlines Inc. received their first
substantial raise last month since the mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite our nation's booming economy and overall prosperity,
over 4 million Americans work full time but remain poor,'' the
Machinists union, which represents TWA workers, said in its Labor
Day message. ``Just having a job doesn't guarantee a worker a piece
of the American Dream.''
</P>
<P>
   And many who are employed are working longer hours to keep up or
get ahead, said Judy Ancel, director of the Institute for Labor
Studies, a program of Longview Community College in Lee's Summit,
Mo., and the University of Missouri-Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an excessive use of overtime by employers,'' Ancel
said.
</P>
<P>
   But working longer hours doesn't necessarily mean those workers
are getting wealthy, according to a study released today by the
Economic Policy Institute, a pro-labor organization.
</P>
<P>
   The study found that despite a 12 percent growth in productivity
from 1989 to 1998, wages for all middle-income men were 1.8 percent
lower over the same period when adjusted for inflation. Pay for all
middle-income women was 3.4 percent higher than the 1989 level.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
