<HEADLINE>
ANTI-FEDERALISM MEASURES HAVE BIPARTISAN SUPPORT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio, Conn., Tenn., Ind., Utah)  (js) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hoping to shift political power back to the states,
a broad bipartisan coalition in the Senate and House of
Representatives is preparing legislation that would make it harder
for Congress and the executive branch to adopt laws and rules that
pre-empt the states on a wide range of issues, from drugs and the
environment to health and worker safety.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation would provide local authorities with broad new
power to go to court to challenge federal laws and regulations that
fail to explicitly mention what state statutes and regulations are
pre-empted. Lawmakers say the House and Senate measures follow the
overall political philosophy embodied in three opinions handed down
by the Supreme Court in June, on the last day of its term. The
decisions imposed sharp new curbs on the ability of Congress to
make federal law binding on the states.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, the measure is called the Federalism
Accountability Act. Sponsored by Sen. Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., and
supported by Democrats including Carl Levin of Ohio and Joseph I.
Lieberman of Connecticut (both former local officials), it sailed
through the Governmental Affairs Committee last month, 12-to-2,
with little public notice. In the House, a similar bill, the
Federalism Act, is sponsored by Rep. David M. McIntosh, a
Republican who last week began his campaign to become the next
governor of Indiana. The measure recently passed a House
subcommittee and is expected to be considered by the House
Committee on Governmental Reform and Oversight later this month.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation has been written at the urging of seven
organizations representing state and local lawmakers, including the
National Governors' Association, the National Conference of State
Legislatures and the National League of Cities.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the groups have maintained that Washington officials,
supported by the courts, have ignored the impact of federal
decisions on the authority of the states. Even when Congress and
the agencies have not explicitly overridden the states, judges have
found many instances in recent years of ``implied pre-emption''
when, as the Supreme Court has said, ``state law stands as an
obstacle to the accomplishment and execution of the full purposes
and objectives of Congress.'' Among other things, the legislation
would largely abolish the legal doctrine of implied pre-emption.
</P>
<P>
   ``For 20 years or so we saw Congress employing the unfunded
mandate to deal with the states, compelling us to do things without
providing adequate funding,'' said Gov. Michael O. Leavitt of Utah,
the chairman of the National Governors' Association. ``The new tool
of Congress is pre-emption, which prohibits states from doing
things. The problem is that states and local authorities are often
left unable to protect citizens because the national government,
which moves into these wide areas, doesn't have the tools to
enforce its actions.''
</P>
<P>
   But the proposed legislation has prompted opposition from an
unusual coalition of big business, environmental, labor and
consumer advocacy groups.
</P>
<P>
   The Chamber of Commerce has waged a major campaign to kill or
substantially weaken the measures. Although officials at the
chamber reported late last week that they were close to negotiating
important changes in the House legislation, Thomas J. Donohue,
president of the chamber, has been deeply critical of both the
House and Senate measures. He has said they would result in the
elimination of a national standard for many issues that affect
commerce and lead to a balkanization of rules on everything from
auto standards to worker safety, making it far more expensive to do
business.
</P>
<P>
   Other groups opposing the measures say they fear that any
weakening of the ability of the federal government to impose
uniform national standards could lead to a substantial weakening of
environmental and consumer protections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under the framework of attempting to provide flexibility for
state and local governments, this legislation undermines public
health, safety and environmental protections by requiring
burdensome analytical requirements, imposing unrealistic and unfair
requirements to favor states and local governments and creating a
mountain of litigation that would delay or stop federal government
activities,'' said Gary D. Bass, executive director of OMB Watch, a
nonpartisan regulatory watchdog organization.
</P>
<P>
   Bass, who is leading a coalition of 300 environmental, labor,
consumer and other groups against the legislation, said it would
enable a mayor in any town in the nation to use the courts to delay
or block any regulation that failed to fully assess the federalism
consequences of the regulation.
</P>
<P>
   But Thompson, chairman of the Senate Governmental Affairs
Committee, said that critics were wildly distorting the
consequences of the legislation, which he said was not much more
than ``truth in government and truth in legislating.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The two most fundamental questions in government are, number
one, what should the government be doing and, number two, at what
level should it be doing it,'' he said. ``This fits with my
longstanding concern I have had that every time there is a news
story, we run to the floor and we want to federalize something.
This legislation says that we will not be willy-nilly pre-empting
state and local governments without explicitly saying that is what
we intend to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to slow down the legislation's momentum, President
Clinton last month issued an executive order on federalism that
falls far short of the bills, particularly since it does not give
local officials any new authority to go to court to challenge
regulations. Rather, the order requires all agencies to appoint a
federalism assessment officer to review the consequences of major
regulations and to consult with state and local officials.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials have been more critical of the House bill,
which gives judges less flexibility in striking down federal
legislation and regulations and are closer to reaching an accord in
which they said they would be able to support the Senate measure.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In letters sent to Congress in recent weeks, officials from a
number of executive agencies, including the Treasury, the
Department of Education, the Environmental Protection Agency and
the Department of Health and Human Services, complained that the
legislation could have sweepingly devastating effects on the
ability of the federal government to do business.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Shalala, the secretary of health and human Services, wrote
that the proposed legislation in the House would ``hamper the
effectiveness of important health and social service programs for
which we are responsible.'' She said such actions as the Food and
Drug Administration's 1982 requirement of tamper-resistant
packaging following the cyanide-poisonings of Tylenol products, and
the 1998 regulation requiring warning labels on apple juices
following a pathogen scare ``would have been impossible had the FDA
been required to consult with officials of every potentially
affected state and local government before issuing these rules.''
</P>
<P>
   And last month Linda Robertson, an assistant treasury secretary,
wrote to Congress that the proposed legislation would preclude the
Internal Revenue Service from making wage adjustments for tax
withholding rates on employee wages because states and local
governments would be affected as employers subject to withholding
rates.
</P>
<P>
   But local officials have said that decisions made by Washington
have led to many unintended and harsh consequences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Legislation tends to be so voluminous that congressional
delegations don't always understand the full impact of what they
are doing until long after the fact,'' said Mayor Alex Fekete of
Pembroke Pines, Fla., a Democrat. ``No assessment is every really
done on the cost to municipalities.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
