<HEADLINE>
ANALYSTS EXPECT PRODUCER PRICE INDEX TO RISE A MODERATE 0.3
PERCENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the expert consensus is valid, the latest report on inflation
is likely to be greeted as good news on Wall Street. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The most anticipated economic report of this holiday-abbreviated
week will be Friday's release of the {Producer Price Index} numbers
for August, which are expected to show wholesale inflation is tame.
The weekly survey of leading economists by Thomson Global Markets
shows most expecting a rise of 0.3 percent. Though that would be an
increase from July's 0.2 percent gain, it still would be viewed by
economists as benign. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, a reading in the forecast neighborhood would be seen
by investors as a sign that should help convince Federal Reserve
policy-makers that interest rates need not be raised further to
keep inflation at bay. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The core rate, which excludes the volatile food and energy
components of the index, is expected to be up 0.1 percent after
remaining unchanged in July. &QL; 
Today &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although summer's end is still officially a couple of weeks
away, the traditional windup to the summer season comes today with
observance of the {Labor Day holiday.} As a result, most markets,
financial institutions, and business and government offices will be
closed. &QL; 
Wednesday &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A substantial surge in {consumer installment credit outstanding}
is expected to be reported for July. The consensus call from expert
observers expects an expansion of more than $6 billion, which would
more than double June's rise. An increase of this magnitude would
be seen as good news because it would reflect the sort of continued
consumer confidence the economy depends on for growth. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   - The rate of accumulation of {wholesale inventories} is
expected to have continued at its recent moderate pace during July.
Most analysts are forecasting an expansion of 0.3 percent, which
would match June's gain. This trend is good news because it means
there's no danger of an inventory overhang developing. Excessive
inventories cause manufacturers to cut back on production, and thus
often result in worker layoffs. &QL; 
Thursday &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The latest figures on {export and import prices} are scheduled
for release, which probably will provide an early indication of
what the next monthly trade deficit will be. If the forecasts are
near target, they portend continued large trade deficits.
Economists at Merrill Lynch predict that import prices rose 0.6
percent in August, after a 0.9 percent jump in July, while export
prices remained flat after dipping 0.2 percent the previous month. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
