<HEADER>
A1646 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s BC-BBO-GAY-EXPLAYER-ART-     09-05 1270
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-GAY-EXPLAYER-ART-3TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
346-9867.)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Fla., Mich., Ill.)  
 EX-BIG LEAGUE BALLPLAYER KEPT HIS HOMOSEXUALITY A SECRET  (ART ADV:
Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can
make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)(mk) 
 By ROBERT LIPSYTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   All-America Billy Bean burst into his 20s consumed by two
driving dreams: to play center field in the major leagues and to
deny his homosexuality. Eventually he would have to choose between
his personal and professional lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``For nine years,'' Bean said recently, ``I felt as though I had
one foot in the major leagues and one on a banana peel.''
</P>
<P>
   Bean's story of isolation and subterfuge may be familiar to
millions of gay men and lesbians, and his passion to play big
league ball, which he did for parts of six seasons with the Detroit
Tigers, Los Angeles Dodgers and San Diego Padres, is shared by
thousands of high school and college baseball stars. But the
combination of those two struggles offers a rare window into the
fiercely competitive and hyper-masculinized arena of major team
sports.
</P>
<P>
   Because he did not want to ``embarrass what I hold sacred _ my
family and baseball,'' it took the unexpected deaths, over an
eight-year period, of his father, his first partner and a college
teammate for him to address his sexuality, leave the game and
accelerate the process of coming out. He is the first major league
baseball player to so publicly discuss his homosexuality and the
first athlete in a major American team sport to do so since the
football player Dave Kopay, who came out in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Burke, the former Los Angeles Dodgers outfielder,
acknowledged his homosexuality in 1994, the year before he died of
AIDS. In recent years, a number of celebrated athletes in
individual sports, including Billie Jean King, Martina Navratilova
and Greg Louganis, have come out. But the homophobic environment of
most male team sports, particularly professional football and
baseball, have deterred many gay athletes from pursuing their
talents, and driven those who persisted deep into the closet.
</P>
<P>
   Kopay, a running back who was out to some members of his team,
the Washington Redskins, was protected from at least one gay basher
by a powerful locker-room leader who would allow no bullying of any
player so long as he was producing for the team. Kopay came out
publicly after his nine-year career was over and went on to success
as a businessman. Burke, who played for the Dodgers and the Oakland
A's, was dogged by rumors of his homosexuality, which drove him out
of the game after four years and into a spiral of drugs and
depression.
</P>
<P>
   At least one well-known sports counselor, Dr. Bruce Ogilivie,
has advised major league athletes to stay closeted during their
playing careers. Although one former manager of Bean's thinks that
his sunny personality would have protected him on the club, a
former teammate thinks the reaction would have been ``brutal.''
Bean believes he would have been ostracized if he came out while
playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never dated another major leaguer and I have no idea whether
or not there are other gay ballplayers,'' Bean said. ``One would
think so, but if they were as deeply closeted as I was, who would
know?
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to Hooters, laughed at the jokes, lied about dates
because I loved baseball. I still do. I'd go back in a minute. I
only wish I hadn't felt so alone, that I could have told someone,
and that I hadn't always felt God was going to strike me dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Bean, 35, is now a restaurant owner in the trendy South Beach
section of Miami Beach. While he lives openly with his business
partner and confides in his family, he had withdrawn until recently
from his college and professional baseball friends. He did not want
to continue lying to them about his life or to risk their
rejection. Then in late June, Tim Layana, a former Cincinnati Reds
pitcher and Bean's college teammate at Loyola Marymount, was killed
in a car accident. No one from their circle of old buddies had
Bean's telephone number.
</P>
<P>
   ``I missed the funeral of my college roommate, one of my best
friends,'' Bean said. ``Tim would have understood if I had told
him. I began to think, I'm not living some horrible existence, I'm
proud of my life. Where do I finally draw the line and just say,
`Accept me or don't'?''
</P>
<P>
   Intense, upbeat, quick to laugh, Bean was sitting in the living
room of the elegantly furnished, art-filled terra-cotta palazzo on
Biscayne Bay that he shares with Efrain Veiga and their three dogs,
a Jack Russell terrier, a whippet and a weimaraner. Their second
restaurant, Mayya, is scheduled to open early next month. Unusual
in the home of a former athlete, there is little memorabilia
besides the jerseys of his three major league teams _ the Tigers,
the Dodgers and the Padres. In a painting commissioned by Veiga
that hangs over the mantel in the dining room, two baseball-card
Billy Beans are swinging from the heels, but a strand of barbed
wire beneath home plate signifies that they are not truly free.
</P>
<P>
   Bean cannot remember when he has felt as free as he says he is
beginning to feel now. High school quarterback, point guard and
valedictorian, college baseball all-American, handsome, thoughtful
and a celebrated ``babe magnet,'' Billy Bean was the golden child
of a tough cop's blended family. Yet he was nagged by the feeling
that something was missing, that there was an emotional hole at the
center of his life. His mother would later describe it as ``a
sadness in him I couldn't reach.'' Bean long suspected that he was
homosexual despite being heterosexually active since high school.
He was married for three years. He had his first homosexual
experience at 28.
</P>
<P>
   By that time, the pattern of his baseball career was set. In
nine years of bouncing among major, minor, winter and Japanese
league rosters, Bean logged less than four years of major league
pension time. Six-feet tall and 200 pounds, Bean was not considered
fast enough to be an everyday center fielder. Left-handed, he was a
sound defensive player in the outfield and at first base but he did
not have enough power to start i at those positions. His career big
league batting average was .226 in 272 games. He hit only five home
runs. He rarely played three major league games in a row.
</P>
<P>
   He describes himself as one of those ``scrappy scrubs who will
do anything to stick in the show'' _ running extra wind sprints,
cheerleading from the bench, even giving teammates free clubhouse
haircuts ('60s-style astronaut cuts called ``Beanies'') to boost
camaraderie and morale.
</P>
<P>
   His debut, however, on April 24, 1987, in Detroit, was a Hall of
Fame day. Bean relishes replaying the game from a video in his
head. Not quite 23, he had been rushed up from Toledo so abruptly
he did not have time to take batting practice before leading off
for the Tigers against the Kansas City Royals. He lashed his second
big league pitch against the right-field fence for a double. He hit
line-drive singles his next two at-bats and basked in a standing
ovation before his fourth appearance. He struck out looking at
pitches he says were balls. (His opinion of umpires, as bullies to
end-of-the-bench players and toadies to stars, is standard.) On his
fifth and last at-bat, he hit another double and ended his first
big league day with two runs batted in, three runs scored and an
.800 batting average. He lowered it to .667 the next day, getting
two hits off the great Bret Sabrehagen in four appearances.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
