<P>
   BEACON (Undated) _ The Coast Guard and the state of Washington
are spending hundreds of thousands of dollars a year chasing down
false emergency beacons from planes. The reason: Every plane must
carry an emergency-broadcast beacon, but planes built before the
mid-1990s carry beacons which broadcast at 125.25 mhz, the same
frequency as a garage-door opener, or a miskeyed plane mike.
Mandated by law to investigate each beacon alert, the Coasties and
the state aeronautics board are getting frustrated.
</P>
<P>
   By Judd Slivka. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BOY'S DEATH (OLYMPIA) _ Laura Mjelde had a history of drug use
and a file filled with complaints of child neglect and abuse,
nearly all determined to be unsubstantiated. For months a
Washington state social worker had tried to get her into drug
testing and treatment, but she always found excuses to avoid them.
By last September, the frustrated social worker became so concerned
about Mjelde's two children that he told his supervisor he was
prepared to take the case to court _ the first step in taking the
children from the mother. But Child Protective Services officials
decided they didn't have enough evidence for court intervention.
Less than a month later, Mjelde's 14-month-old son, Christopher
Hutton, drowned in a bathtub while under the care of Mjelde's
boyfriend. Stanley D. Red. Mjelde, Red, and Red's sister, Cynthia,
then cremated the baby, drinking brandy while the tiny body burned
in an aluminum trash can.
</P>
<P>
   By Robert Gavin. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
