<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-05 19:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1648 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s BC-BBO-GAY-EXPLAYER-ART-     09-05 1239
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-GAY-EXPLAYER-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: four appearances. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like most major leaguers, he had been a star since boyhood. He
was born in Santa Ana, in California's conservative Orange County,
to 18-year-old Linda Robertson. Her high school classmate, Bill
Bean, married her after she became pregnant, but left when Billy
was about six months old; his Mormon family disapproved of the
union.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was always little Billy Bean, small but bighearted, a gamer,
play hurt, stick it out,'' he said. ``My mom worked two jobs and I
started a new elementary school every year. Because it was mostly
the two of us, I always felt grown-up, responsible. I was precise
and methodical like her. And very emotional. I wanted to please
people, make them proud of me. When she married for the third time,
I was 9 and gave her away in a tux.''
</P>
<P>
   That marriage, to Ed Kovac, a police officer, has lasted more
than 25 years. Billy became the oldest of six and the most
accomplished in school and in sports. He was quickly a star of the
Northeast Santa Ana Little League. Nevertheless, his stepfather
made Billy do chores with everyone else and shoot free throws with
him to see who washed the dishes.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids have to learn responsibility, dedication, concentration,
and it should be fun,'' said Kovac, a former Marine who retired as
a homicide investigator. ``Billy was always responsible and a
leader. He did his chores and practiced those free throws. It
wasn't long before I was doing the dishes.'' At 13, Billy won the
state free-throw shooting championship and a family trip to San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Billy led Santa Ana High School to a state baseball championship
and won a full athletic scholarship to Loyola Marymount, a Jesuit
college in Los Angeles. The Yankees drafted him in his junior year
and offered a $55,000 bonus, which was raised after Bean did well
in a summer league. But Kovac reminded Billy that he had promised
his college coach, Dave Snow, that he would return.
</P>
<P>
   ``A handshake is binding in our house,'' Kovac said. ``And
that's Billy. Always been a credit to the family, the game, and
it's not for me to say, of course, but probably to the gay
community as well.''
</P>
<P>
   In his senior year, Bean, Layana and Jim Bruske, an outfielder
who later pitched for the Yankees, led Loyola Marymount into the
early rounds of the College World Series. Bean signed for $12,500
as Detroit's third draft pick, in the fourth round. He did well
enough that summer in the minors, and during spring training in
1987, for Detroit manager Sparky Anderson to bring him up to the
big club in April for his auspicious debut. Bean started his first
10 games for the Tigers and was hitting .268 in July when he was
sent back down for further seasoning at bat. By then, the Tigers
had played in Anaheim, and Bean's old Little League canceled its
games and showed up in a block waving signs that read Beantown.
</P>
<P>
   Dark fears surfaced, too. Bean remembers standing at the batting
cage with tough veterans like Kirk Gibson, Alan Trammell, Lou
Whitaker and Darrell Evans, wondering, ``Is Little Billy Bean
strong and tough enough to compete with these real men? Male
enough?'' He knew that Anderson liked him, Bean said, but felt that
if the manager knew the truth he would slam the door.
</P>
<P>
   Snow, who is now the coach at Long Beach State, says he never
thought Bean was gay, but does remember Anderson telling him at the
time that ``this guy is not overly gifted but he is ready to come
in and play the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Snow agreed with that assessment: ``Billy maximized his
potential. If you broke down his game, every tool was average at
best, not much speed, size or power, but he was just so good
all-around. He could play the game.''
</P>
<P>
   That winter, playing in Venezuela at the Tigers' strong
recommendation, he was runner-up to Cecil Fielder for the batting
title. In the exotic locale, he said, he felt disturbing sexual
stirrings that he sublimated with longer and harder workouts. By
this time, he was dating ``the beautiful wild bird'' he had first
spotted at Loyola as she whizzed past on a skateboard. Three
hundred guests came to their wedding at the campus chapel.
</P>
<P>
   His baseball life yo-yoed on. He was called back up to the
Tigers in August 1988, after leading his minor league club in
hitting, but he never played enough to develop a batting rhythm. He
got to the plate 11 times in 10 games and hit .182. In nine games
for the Tigers the following year, he was hitless. He was sent down
to the minors, then traded to the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   The Dodger experience overwhelmed him. With most of his friends
and family in southern California, he was barraged with requests
for tickets, inside baseball gossip, a few minutes of his time. His
parents remember him trying to please everyone. He was thrilled
when the Dodger broadcaster Vin Scully acknowledged his existence
by dubbing him ``Guillermo Frijoles'' on air, then crushed by the
avalanche of phone messages he felt he had to answer.
</P>
<P>
   OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   The chilly Dodger culture was particularly tough on a backup
player with a secret fear. Manager Tommy Lasorda was not the warm
father figure of his publicity. Bean was told that young players
had to knock on the manager's door, and then only when it was open.
Bean regarded the nameplates over each locker as symbolic _ they
were erasable chalkboards. He batted .197 in 51 games, and the
Dodgers sent him back down.
</P>
<P>
   When Bean's biological father died of a heart attack in 1991, at
44, Bean says he felt a sense of mortality that motivated him to
deal with his sexual feelings. Within a year, he had left his wife
and had his first homosexual experience. He says he still regrets
not having told her the truth at the time, although she has since
learned it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something was just drawing me to that other side,'' he said.
``I've had good sex with women and good relationships, but
something was missing, even with my wife. I wasn't fulfilled, I had
a fear of not being understood, not being totally accepted. I was
looking for a soul mate, someone I could let my guard down with. I
only found that with men.''
</P>
<P>
   After a year playing for the Kintetsu Buffaloes in Osaka, Japan,
in 1992, his baseball life came alive again in 1993, on a San Diego
team that was selling off its stars and giving subs a chance.
``Until I got to the Padres, I always felt as though I was renting
the uniform,'' he said. ``Then suddenly I felt I had a place. I
lockered next to Tony Gwynn. One of my biggest thrills was hitting
a home run in the game in which he got his 2,000th hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great, I'd get to the yard early, sit in my locker
feeling the adrenaline kick in, and then walk out into that
beautiful setting, feeling this is the day I'll get some knocks,
maybe hit a bomb. There was a great manager there, Jim Riggleman,
who gave me a lot of encouragement.''
</P>
<P>
   Riggleman, now the manager of the Chicago Cubs, remembers Bean
fondly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Class act, everybody loved Billy on the club,'' Riggleman
said. ``It surprised me that he's gay, but it doesn't diminish my
feelings. He was one of the most pleasurable guys to manage. He was
such a good guy that I think it would have been all right on the
club. The news crews, that might have made it tough.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-99 1924EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990905.0133 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-05 19:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1649 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s BC-BBO-GAY-EXPLAYER-ART-     09-05 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-GAY-EXPLAYER-ART-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: it tough.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bean's best year was 1993. He appeared in 88 games, batted .260,
tied the Padres record of five pinch-hits in a row and broke up a
no-hitter with two outs in the ninth. And he got to shake hands
with his boyhood hero, Steve Garvey, now a teammate, and tell him
he had been too shy to introduce himself when both were Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   But there were also midnight walks on road trips to get away
from his tomcatting teammates, to work off the stress of being a
spy in his own life. There were anonymous sexual encounters after
which Bean, who was raised Roman Catholic, would come back hoping
God would forgive him. There was a great deal of guilt and
self-hate, he said, until he began living with Sam, an Iranian he
met at a health club. But he kept the relationship a secret, even
refusing to let his brothers stay at his Del Mar house. Sam hid in
the car when teammates dropped by.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, even though he batted only .215 in 84 games, he felt he
was contributing to the team before the season was cut short by a
players strike. Then, for the second time, sudden death became a
catalyst. On April 23, 1995, Bean returned from an exhibition night
game to find Sam feverish and semiconscious. He died of cardiac
arrest in the emergency room the next morning, eight years to the
day after Bean's major league debut.
</P>
<P>
   Bean remembers calling his mother, crying, ``Not fair, not
fair,'' and her urging him to take a shower and go to the ballpark.
She had no idea that Sam was more than just a pal. He felt
confused. How could he explain to the club he needed a day off to
grieve? Riggleman was no longer the manager. Bean got a hit that
day. After the game, he was called in for an announcement he knew
too well: He was being sent back down to Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I swore to myself I would never again let baseball take
precedence over my life,'' Bean said. ``If I ever fell in love
again, that relationship would come ahead of my career.''
</P>
<P>
   Later that season, in Florida to play the Marlins, he met Veiga,
owner of the popular restaurant Yuca in Miami Beach. In town again
four months later, he called Veiga. An urbane, 47-year-old
Cuban-born graduate of Georgetown University who had never seen a
major league game, Veiga told him: ``There is only one flight, life
is one way. Lighten up. Be yourself.'' At Thanksgiving, Bean went
home and told his mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``While he was trying to get the words out, I said it: `You're
gay,''' Mrs. Kovac said. ``We left the house and drank coffee in
the car and we both cried. I wondered what it would mean to him.''
</P>
<P>
   With dread, Bean went back inside to wake up his stepfather, the
tough old homicide cop. Kovac opened his eyes, listened, nodded,
hugged and kissed his son and said, ``OK, now it's official. Can I
go back to sleep?''
</P>
<P>
   Kovac says he had suspected for a long time, and had no problem.
One of his longtime law enforcement partners had been gay.
</P>
<P>
   Bean did not return to baseball in 1996. He assumes he would
have been assigned to a minor league team. He knew he could no
longer live so furtively. To come out while still playing, he
thought, would mean lurid headlines and talk shows, and then
baseball would find a way ``to kick me out.'' He moved to Miami
Beach and worked in radio and television as his relationship with
Veiga became professional as well as personal. Precise and
methodical, a leader, he began taking over more and more
operational duties at Yuca as he learned the business. He was sent
to intern at Charlie Trotter's restaurant in Chicago. Yuca was sold
and he became a partner in the new restaurant, Mayya.
</P>
<P>
   It was the third sudden death, Layana's on June 26, that pushed
Bean out to a more public platform. In late July, Bean allowed a
persistent writer for The Miami Herald, Lydia Martin, who is gay,
to profile him in her Sunday column and quote him on his major
league experiences.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   He called his old college teammate, Jim Bruske.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of suspected,'' said Bruske, home in Phoenix recovering
from elbow surgery. ``I wouldn't say anything till he did, no one
knew for sure, but he kept shying away from us. I'd come to Miami
to play the Marlins and he always had some reason we couldn't get
together and he'd be short and change the subject when it got
personal. That wasn't like him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was right to keep it a secret. The guys would have been
brutal. Billy could have been a great player, but he tried too hard
to make everyone happy, he wanted everyone to like him and he put
too much pressure on himself. I'm glad it's out. I told him it
would have no impact on our friendship.''
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   But Bean's mother is fearful. ``I feel he's happy now, he's
resolved it,'' she said. ``Maybe I'm being too protective, but I
wonder if he can be hurt. And I know he'd like to be in baseball,
and we would like him to be, too. Billy in baseball always gave the
family such joy.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Emboldened by the generally positive, though muted, response to
the article in The Herald, Bean agreed to extend the platform. He
seems both elated and anxious. He likes to think there is a young
gay athlete who will feel less alone. He is afraid it will damage
his chance to someday be a baseball executive, perhaps a general
manager. (Bean is sometimes confused with the general manager of
the Oakland A's, Billy Beane, especially since their playing
careers coincided. Beane is two years older.)
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, Bean wishes he could have brought himself to tell
his family sooner so he would have had their support earlier. He
wishes that his partner, Veiga, could have seen him play. He enjoys
talking baseball and has kept himself in shape, working out,
playing tennis and basketball. Some corner of his mind seems to be
expecting an emergency call for a backup outfielder.
</P>
<P>
   One of his greatest pleasures is running his daily six miles in
the midday heat of Miami Beach while listening to baseball on a
headset. As he sweats, he imagines he is in the game. The fantasy
includes a dialogue more permanent than any erasable chalkboard
identity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who is Billy Bean?''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the guy on second base. He just hit a double.''
</P>
</TEXT>
