<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-05 19:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1658 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-TIMOR-VIOLENCE-900(2T     09-05 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMOR-VIOLENCE-900(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIOLENCE ERUPTS IN EAST TIMOR AND MANY ARE KILLED 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By SETH MYDANS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ As the outside world looked on in horror
and the Indonesian government promised East Timor protection but
evaded fulfilling those pledges, armed thugs systematically took
over the island territory on Sunday, killing and terrorizing
residents and trapping U.N. workers in their compound.
</P>
<P>
   Late Sunday night, there were many reports of large numbers of
killings, with an overall death toll reaching perhaps into the
hundreds. In New York the U.N. Security Council held an emergency
evening session to discuss the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   In Dili, the territory's capital, armed men were said to have
fired into crowds of refugees at the port and at a school beside
the U.N. compound and to have set fire to a building adjacent to
the headquarters of the Roman Catholic Diocese, where refugees had
taken shelter. The gunmen were reported to be massacring residents
in the pro-independence neighborhood of Becora.
</P>
<P>
   There were reports of killings and terror in other towns,
including an unconfirmed report that 100 people had been killed in
the town of Same and 20 in the town of Atsabe.
</P>
<P>
   The reports could not be confirmed, because foreigners have been
evacuated from most rural areas and roads are blocked by militia
gangs. But Ana Gomes, Portugal's envoy to Jakarta, told a
Portuguese radio station that ``over 100 dead would be a
conservative estimate.''
</P>
<P>
   Several top Indonesian officials, including the armed forces
chief and the foreign minister, flew to Dili for a brief visit and
promised to restore order. But they did not venture beyond the tiny
airport as the irregular militias _ created and armed by the
military _ fired their weapons and burned houses in the streets
beyond.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. officials estimated that in Dili some 25,000 people had
taken shelter where they could, and witnesses reported thousands
huddled in police headquarters, the U.N. compound and the few other
sanctuaries available. Terrified parents tried to pass their
children over coils of razor wire outside the besieged U.N.
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Security worsened, rather than improved, after the visit of the
Indonesian dignitaries, said Prime Minister Antonio Guterres of
Portugal. His country abandoned East Timor as a colony in 1975,
opening the way for Indonesia to invade and declare the island
territory its 27th province.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is time for Indonesia itself and the international
community to understand that Indonesia is no longer able to keep
law and order,'' Guterres told Reuters.
</P>
<P>
   In a referendum last Monday, 78.5 percent of the East Timorese
who voted favored breaking free as a separate nation. But that
vote, administered by the United Nations, does not take effect
until it is ratified by the Indonesian Parliament later this year,
leaving the territory of 800,000 people in a dangerous limbo after
decades of virtual civil war between pro-independence forces and
the Indonesian military.
</P>
<P>
   The mayhem this weekend spurred increasing calls for the United
Nations or individual countries _ like nearby Australia, which has
volunteered its armed forces _ to send in peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   But Foreign Minister Ali Alatas asserted Indonesia's
responsibility for East Timor and said no foreign forces would be
allowed into the territory. Other officials insisted that they
would maintain order on their own.
</P>
<P>
   The armed forces chief, Gen. Wiranto, said, ``I call on those
people causing the deteriorating situation to stop their actions.''
But as of Sunday evening, residents reached by telephone said the
shooting and burning continued.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia's apparent yearlong policy of issuing statements but
taking little action to curb militia violence drew expressions of
exasperation from abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very concerned about the continuing violence,'' President
Clinton said, ``and the people who lost the election should
recognize that they lost it fair and square and should now find a
way to go forward peacefully. The Indonesians should do all they
can to keep the peace and prevent the bloodshed. They have the
capacity, I think, that would enable them to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gomes, the Portuguese diplomat, placed the responsibility
for the violence directly on the Indonesian military.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an uncontrolled chaos,'' she said. ``It is a
provoked, planned and orchestrated chaos by military forces. They
want to scare the international community _ the observers and the
journalists _ to get them out and massacre the East Timorese.''
</P>
<P>
   Residents said Sunday evening that part of the Mahkota Hotel,
where most journalists stayed until they were evacuated Sunday, had
been burned. They said the territory's main human rights
organization, Yayasan Hak, had been attacked with stones and
gunfire.
</P>
<P>
   Given the serious damage that is being done to Indonesia's
international standing, with the eyes of the United Nations and the
foreign press focused on East Timor, a number of Indonesian and
foreign analysts said they found the government's motives difficult
to understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine anything more damning to the image of
Indonesia than this sort of thing,'' said James Fox, director of
Pacific and Asian studies at the Australian National University,
who was in East Timor for the vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wouldn't take much to provide law and order,'' he said.
``There is obviously an unwillingness to do it. Either they don't
realize the cost that this will entail or they have decided they'll
pay that cost.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Indonesian military has a long and intense attachment to
East Timor, where thousands of its men have died and others have
made their careers. The military recruited and armed the militia
groups early this year after President B.J. Habibie suddenly
announced that he would let East Timor go free if it voted down his
offer of more autonomy within Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   With some members of the military viewing the possibility of
independence as a defeat, their aim in creating the militias
appeared to be to influence or derail the vote through a campaign
of intimidation and terror.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts also say that the military, which traditionally
has helped keep together the diverse 13,000 islands that make up
Indonesia, fears that if East Timor gains independence, other parts
of the nation will seek to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   In the two days since the result of the vote was announced early
Saturday, the militias have run wild. ``To what end?'' Fox said.
``This is so counterproductive and self-defeating. It has to be
stubbornness and upset.''
</P>
<P>
   The chaos drove some 5,000 East Timorese to flee Sunday aboard
inter-island ferries, according to reports from Dili, although
militia thugs reportedly prevented some people from departing.
</P>
<P>
   Another 2,000 people took shelter at the compound of the
territory's Roman Catholic prelate, Bishop Carlos Belo, who in 1996
shared the Nobel Peace Prize with the pro-independence activist
Jose Ramos Horta.
</P>
<P>
   The police said as many as 15,000 people were crowded into the
grounds of the main police headquarters. More than 1,000 broke
their way into the U.N. compound, where most of the remaining U.N.
workers and a handful of journalists also took shelter.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds more journalists, aid workers and U.N. officials who
had completed their electoral work fled Sunday aboard chartered
aircraft. As their planes took off, they could see flames and smoke
rising from fires burning within and around the outskirts of the
tiny seaside capital.
</P>
<P>
   But David Wimhurst, the chief spokesman for the United Nations
in East Timor, said no U.N. staff were leaving before their time
was up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We plan to stay put,'' he said by telephone from within the
besieged compound. ``All this violence is clearly an attempt to
intimidate us out of here, and we have resisted this
intimidation.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``The United Nations is obviously doing everything it
can to put pressure on the Indonesian government to maintain law
and order, but it is increasingly apparent that these appeals are
falling on deaf ears.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those calling for quick intervention by the United Nations
was Ramos Horta.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are facing an imminent, extraordinary humanitarian
catastrophe right under the eyes of the Security Council, and they
are not acting promptly to stop the killings,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Whole villages have fled for safety into the barren hills, and
Ramos Horta said that in the coming days ``thousands will be
starving and dying.''
</P>
<P>
   Belo echoed his call for help. ``This is the time that we badly
need some peacekeeping troops in this region to protect ordinary
people who have no weapons, such as children, women and the
elderly,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Australian officials said they had prepared an intervention
force, but Prime Minister John Howard said Sunday, ``You can't go
into the territory of another country without that country's
approval, and East Timor remains a part of Indonesia until a formal
act of separation takes place.''
</P>
</TEXT>
