<HEADLINE>
FOUR-MONTH MANHUNT ENDS IN QUIET ARREST OF U.S. MONEY MANAGER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn.)  (js) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ Although he was the target of a four-month
trans-Atlantic manhunt, Martin Frankel lived for eight weeks at one
of the finest hotels in the German city of Hamburg before he was
arrested on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Frankel, 44, a secretive Connecticut money manager whom U.S.
authorities suspect of embezzling more than $200 million from
insurance companies, played a cat-and-mouse game with the FBI that
took him through Italy and maybe other countries before it ended in
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Hamburg police officials, who arrested Frankel after getting a
request from the FBI, said the fugitive millionaire checked into
the luxurious 53-room Prem Hotel about eight weeks ago. His
unusually long stay in Room 5 on the third floor apparently excited
little curiosity among hotel employees, who were reluctant to
discuss it on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   A senior FBI official in Washington said Sunday that tips from
friends and disgruntled former associates who had been in contact
with Frankel, along with a winding trail of bank account and credit
card charges, had led federal authorities to the fugitive
financier.
</P>
<P>
   An FBI agent from the agency's legal attache office in Berlin
and the German police staked out the Hotel Prem beginning on
Thursday after learning of Frankel's whereabouts, said Thomas
Pickard, assistant director of the FBI Criminal Investigative
Division.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were getting more and more into Germany in the last couple
of weeks and intensified our search when we got a couple of tips
that matched with information from tracking the movement of his
funds and his credit cards,'' Pickard said.
</P>
<P>
   He said authorities seized a substantial sum of cash, diamonds
and potentially significant financial records and two or more
laptop computers. The records and computers are likely to yield
important clues to unraveling what is left of Frankel's fallen
financial empire, Pickard said.
</P>
<P>
   At the time Frankel was arrested, he was sharing his double room
at the waterfront hotel with Cynthia Allison, 35, one of his many
female associates. She was living under the name Susan Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   Hans-Juergen Petersen, a spokesman for the Hamburg police, said
Ms. Allison had been detained for questioning but was later
released.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Justice Department has begun preparing papers to have
Frankel extradited from Germany to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Hamburg police are holding Frankel in the Holstenglacis jail, a
detention center filled mainly with suspected drug dealers and
users. He was expected to be brought before a judge for arraignment
on Monday, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Petersen said Frankel seemed ``clearly surprised'' when police
officers entered his room at the Prem, an elegant old hotel
overlooking the Alster lake in one of Hamburg's best neighborhoods.
He said Frankel had put up no resistance and showed no signs of
weariness from his four months as a fugitive.
</P>
<P>
   His arrest on Saturday night was pedestrian compared to the
surreal drama of Frankel's abrupt disappearance and subsequent
reports of his lifestyle _ which included his repeated use of false
names, his ever-present coterie of attractive young women and his
penchant for traveling first-class even when he was on the run.
</P>
<P>
   Local and federal German police arrived at the Prem hotel
shortly after 9 p.m. on Saturday and entered his room with a
passkey. Frankel reportedly admitted his identity immediately and
gave himself up.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Agents matched an earlier set of Frankel's fingerprints with a
set taken from him shortly after his arrest to confirm his
identity.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials cautioned that the extradition might take several
months, though German officials said it could proceed much more
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   German officials said Sunday that a key issue was whether
Frankel needed to be investigated for any crimes here. At the
moment, he is not a target of any allegations in Germany, although
there may be questions about his use of false names. Officials
declined to say which alias he used at the Hamburg hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Frankel probably had no trouble travelling between Italy and
Germany. He was carrying at least two passports and both countries
are part of a group within the European Union that allows people to
travel between member countries without showing their passports.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, insurance regulators have accused Frankel
of embezzling at least $218 million from insurance companies that
had invested money with the brokerage firm, Liberty National
Securities, which he ran from his mansion.
</P>
<P>
   The total amount of missing money could be much higher. A
lawsuit filed by some of the insurance companies puts the loss at
$915 million. Also missing is as much as $1.98 billion from the St.
Francis of Assisi Foundation, a charitable foundation that law
enforcement officials say Frankel established in the British Virgin
Islands last August.
</P>
<P>
   Frankel disappeared in May, shortly before his mansion caught
fire. Responding to a fire alarm at the mansion, fire fighters
found a file cabinet in flames and piles of documents stuffed into
the fireplace.
</P>
<P>
   Police issued a warrant for Frankel's arrest and came close to
catching up with him in July in Rome, where he had been staying in
some of the city's best hotels. But he fled before the FBI obtained
an arrest warrant from Italian authorities.
</P>
</TEXT>
