<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-05 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1674 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-WORKER-WEIGHT-ART-2TA     09-05 1108
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKER-WEIGHT-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMPLOYERS SEE COST SAVINGS IN TRIMMER EMPLOYEE WAISTLINES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By MILT FREUDENHEIM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With health costs spiraling again, employers are taking a closer
look at their workers' waistlines, tackling a complicated and
sensitive issue that affects not just medical costs but morale and
productivity.
</P>
<P>
   While companies typically tread softly to avoid giving offense
or violating discrimination laws, many are trying harder to promote
exercise and nutrition regimens to reduce the health risks of being
overweight.
</P>
<P>
   With the population getting older and more sedentary by the day,
excess weight is a growing national issue for everyone from
children to the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   Companies have tackled this issue before, but their efforts have
taken on a new urgency as revamped statistics have shown a sharp
rise in both the number of overweight Americans and the enormous
costs associated with excess weight. While few employers have come
up with new tactics to attack the problem, more of them are joining
the crusade.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1970s, 46 percent of adults were overweight,
according to new guidelines introduced last year, but by 1991, that
had soared to 54 percent _ 97 million people, by the latest
estimate. Adults classified as being acutely overweight, or obese,
went from 15 percent to 23 percent in the same period. ``It is
clearly an epidemic,'' said Nancy Chockley, president of the
National Institute for Health Care Management Foundation, a
research and lobbying group financed by health plans and government
grants.
</P>
<P>
   And business is paying a good part of the bill, with much of the
rest adding to taxpayers' costs for Medicare and Medicaid. Obesity
cost the nation $99.2 billion in 1995, about half for medical care
and $39 billion in productivity losses, according to an estimate
last year by Anne Wolf of the University of Virginia and Graham
Colditz of the Harvard School of Public Health. That statistic
combines the costs of doctor visits, lost productivity, absenteeism
and hospital stays. It does not include $33 billion in annual
spending for weight-loss products and services.
</P>
<P>
   ``The increase in loss of productivity was phenomenal,'' Ms.
Wolf said. ``People were sicker, missing more days of work. It
looks like people who are overweight became more obese, and those
who were obese became more so.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Foster, clinical director of the weight and eating
disorders program at the University of Pennsylvania, adds that
obesity is also often associated with morale problems and
depression.
</P>
<P>
   According to David Thompson of Policy Analysis Inc., a
consulting firm in Brookline, Mass., the direct cost to employer
health plans was $12.7 billion in 1994, which he said was the first
year such costs were tallied.
</P>
<P>
   But companies are not taking it sitting down. Last year, 93
percent of employers had programs that fostered employee health, up
from 76 percent in 1992, according to Hewitt Associates, a benefits
consulting firm outside Chicago. Such ``wellness'' programs
typically offer help in stopping smoking, managing stress, prenatal
care and nutrition and fitness. Programs are also offered by some
insurers, like Highmark Blue Cross and Blue Shield, which runs 17
wellness centers in western Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   The programs vary widely. Many big companies have on-site
fitness centers with aerobic exercise classes, machines and
coaches. Some employers have indoor or outdoor running tracks,
while others subsidize memberships in health clubs. Companies often
display nutrition information in their lunchrooms and subsidize
nutrition classes with lectures and menus and recipes to take home.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, at least, the programs are paying off. Xerox said
that savings in medical costs were five times the cost of its
health promotion programs. Progressive, a Cleveland auto insurer,
said that having fitness centers helped it attract desirable
employees in a tight labor market.
</P>
<P>
   A variety of studies underscore the problem. One involving
17,118 members of Kaiser Permanente, the health maintenance
organization, reported that annual costs of hospital care,
laboratory tests, radiology and drugs were 25 percent higher among
obese members.
</P>
<P>
   And Shell Oil, reviewing its own costs for nine years, found
that as obese women grew older, their sick leaves increased at
twice the rate of those who were not obese.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live in a toxic environment with regard to obesity,'' said
Dr. F. Xavier Pi-Sunyer, director of obesity research at St.
Luke's-Roosevelt Hospital Center in New York. ``Food is very
palatable, very cheap, very easy to get. Labor-saving devices are
everywhere. Everybody is working at desks, expending a lot less
energy and eating a lot more.''
</P>
<P>
   Recent studies have attached dollar price tags to employee
weight problems. University of Michigan researchers reported last
year that health care costs for obese male employees of a Chicago
bank averaged $4,047, spread over three years, or $718 higher than
for all men. Costs for obese women were $10,926, or $4,182 higher
than the average for women employees.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Wayne Burton, corporate medical director of Bank One Corp.
and the chief author of the Michigan obesity survey, said that
especially for women, weight seemed to be associated with heart,
lung, joint and digestive diseases as well as mental health
problems and some types of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Following up on the survey, he said, the bank is expanding its
network of fitness centers from four to six. At one center in
Chicago, Carla Crnkovic, 43, a computer programmer and exercise
enthusiast, has attended a lunch-hour nutrition program since early
1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost 110 pounds, my blood pressure came down to normal and
my cholesterol level dropped 40 points,'' she said. ``It's
wonderful. My tennis game is much improved.'' Her current weight,
175 pounds, is considered appropriate for her 6-foot height, but
she recently added a bank-sponsored walking program to her routine.
</P>
<P>
   Company programs get more attention, not surprisingly, when top
executives are sympathetic. Michael Critelli, chairman of Pitney
Bowes, the office-machine company based in Stamford, Conn., noticed
last year that a fat-laden bacon, egg and cheese croissant was
cheaper than a serving of fruit in the company cafeteria. The
prices were soon readjusted to push fruit.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   With similar attention to detail, Pitney Bowes encourages
employees to leave their cars in the most remote spot in the
company lot and walk in.
</P>
<P>
   Retired employees were recently invited to use a company fitness
center in Stamford. David Hom, executive director of corporate
benefits at Pitney Bowes, said it planned to extend fitness and
nutrition counseling to retirees around the country.
</P>
<P>
   In another case of heightened corporate attention, the drug
maker SmithKline Beecham recently hired an outside firm, Health
Decisions Inc., based in Golden, Colo., to create a national
wellness program for 1,600 SmithKline employees who reported weight
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Without waiting for the new program, Regina McCairns, 47, a
SmithKline quality control investigator in Upper Providence, Pa.,
gave up her lunch hour to lift weights and use a treadmill in the
company gym. ``I keep my clothes for the fitness center in my file
drawer,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McCairns would not give her weight but said she had taken
off 38 pounds. Once a week, she consults with a personal trainer at
the fitness center and checks on her diet with an outside doctor.
</P>
<P>
   At least on paper, the extent of the problem became much clearer
last year when a federal panel of scientists, after studying
illnesses like diabetes and heart disease, lowered the threshold
defining overweight to a height-to-weight relationship, or body
mass index, of 25 or higher. For a woman of average height, 5 foot
5, that works out to 150 pounds; or the average man, 5-foot-10,
it's 174 pounds. Obesity starts at a body mass index of 30.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Although some scientists say obesity is a chronic illness, not
all overweight people are destined to become sick. Pi-Sunyer, who
headed the federal study, estimates that 10 percent to 20 percent
of overweight people are not disease prone.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. William Dietz, director of the nutrition and physical
activity division at the federal Centers for Disease Control in
Atlanta, said, ``People who are overfat and have a negative family
history for all the obesity-associated'' diseases ``will live to
over 85 and not have any'' of these diseases. He added, ``We don't
know a lot about those people.''
</P>
<P>
   Most employers have shied away from rewarding weight loss or
trying to force workers to slim down. For one thing, ``researchers
don't understand obesity all that well, and we don't have a
permanent cure for it,'' said Carol Johnson, a sociologist who is
president of Largely Positive, an advocacy group that she said
``promotes self-esteem and health among larger people.''
</P>
<P>
   Dee Edington, director of the University of Michigan health
management research center, said being overweight in itself was not
dangerous. But obesity combined with other risk factors like
smoking and lack of exercise _ ``that is dangerous,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although some employer health plans will pay for diet drugs when
a doctor declares them a medical necessity, Morgan Downey,
executive director of the American Obesity Association, said that
for the most part, the drugs were poorly covered.
</P>
<P>
   His organization, which is financed by drug makers and Weight
Watchers International, has petitioned the IRS to allow a tax
deduction for obesity treatment under employer-sponsored medical
savings accounts. The IRS recently announced a limited tax break
for smoking cessation programs.
</P>
<P>
   But Lynn McAfee, director of medical advocacy for the Council on
Size and Weight Discrimination, an advocacy group, questions the
long-range effectiveness of weight-loss drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are looking at 5 to 10 percent weight losses,'' she said.
``Whether they can be maintained is an open question.'' She also
questioned whether a relatively small weight loss would make a
difference in diseases like diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   What is not disputed is the importance of exercise and nutrition
in heading off many major diseases, whether or not a person is
overweight.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you get a person exercising more and improving their diet,
their health problems may clear up, even if they don't lose
weight,'' said Glenn Gaesser, a professor of exercise physiology at
the University of Virginia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
