</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-ARIZONA06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves throw one away in 9th
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A few minutes after recording the day's 27th and
presumably final out, the Atlanta Braves lost a game Sunday. If
Atlanta and Arizona are to meet again next month, the Diamondbacks
administered a departing karate chop to remember them by.
</P>
<P>
   After coming back from a three-run deficit against Randy
Johnson, a one-run Atlanta lead was washed out on three unearned
runs in the ninth after John Rocker had fanned pinch hitter Kelly
Stinnett to apparently end the game. In a mind-numbing sequence,
rookie Randall Simon failed to cover first base on a dropped third
strike, catcher Eddie Perez threw over Simon's head, and Tony
Womack and Luis Gonzalez drove in three runs with singles to end
the game a second time, 7-5 Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves were not pleased.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suddenly it's over and we lose,'' said starter Tom Glavine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my worst game ever,'' said Perez.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we played an unbelievable ballgame and then took
something for... granted and got ... beat,'' said manager Bobby
Cox. ``It amounts to that.''
</P>
<P>
   So, the Braves' NL East lead dropped to 2 1/2 games after a Mets
win, despite their comeback against Johnson. Down 4-1 after five
innings, the Braves scored twice in the sixth, including Chipper
Jones' second solo home run of the game, and Gerald Williams'
two-run, two-out double in the seventh gave Atlanta a 5-4 edge.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker had all but pocketed his 32nd save with two outs and none
on in the ninth, when Perez bobbled the third strike to Stinnett.
He lunged and missed a tag, and when he looked to first base, Simon
wasn't covering.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he struck him out, I kind of turned around, thinking that
we won the game right there,'' said Simon. ``I didn't see the ball
when Eddie threw it at first.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going over to second base to start giving guys
high-fives,'' right fielder Brian Jordan said, ``and the next thing
I know, I'm chasing the ball down the line.''
</P>
<P>
   No one in the clubhouse had ever seen anything like it, hardly
in the crucible of September.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hope,'' said Glavine, ``you don't make the same mistake
again.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
