<SLUG> BC-FBN-VIKINGS06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Defeat drives Vikings
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is with great sadness that I walk out to my car this morning
to scrape the Vikings sticker off my bumper. When that is
accomplished, I will go inside to turn on my computer, go to the
favorite files and delete all of my Vikings links. I have been a
Vikings fan for as long as there have been Vikings, through grade
school, high school, college and all of my adult life. I have stuck
by them while living in three other states, through four Super Bowl
losses and all of the ``rebuilding'' years. But a time has to come
when a player, a team or a fan says enough is enough. ... It hurts
to lose, but the pain would be a lot less if, in my heart, I did
not have the suspicion the Lombardi trophy never will wear purple.
</P>
<P>
   _ Letter from Minnesota Vikings fan Vince Reed, of Murphysboro,
Ill., published in the St. Paul Pioneer Press on Jan. 24, a week
after Minnesota's 30-27 overtime loss to Atlanta in the NFC
Championship.
</P>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ As Minnesota kicker Gary Anderson lined up for a
38-yard field goal with 2:07 left in regulation in January's NFC
Championship game, hats proclaiming the Vikings ``NFC Champions''
were being passed out in owner Red McCombs' private suite. Outside
the Metrodome, local newspapers were hawking commemorative Super
Bowl sections, with one headline blaring, ``On To Miami.''
</P>
<P>
   Holding a 27-20 lead over the underdog Atlanta Falcons,
Anderson's field goal would have given the Vikings an
insurmountable lead. Surely, Anderson wouldn't miss. Not after he
became the first perfect kicker in NFL regular-season history,
making all 94 of his attempts _ 35 field goals and 59 extra points.
Surely, this game was in the bag. Minnesota was going to Miami and
back to the Super Bowl, where it hadn't been since losing for an
NFL-record fourth time in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson missed.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's offense took over and scored a game-tying touchdown
with only 49 seconds remaining, sending the game into overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``What made it hurt so badly was that I, along with my entire
family and I think the Vikings fans and players, just knew that we
had the game won,'' McCombs said. ``It was a great lesson.''
</P>
<P>
   Evidently, a short-lived one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that we had the game won, even in overtime,''
McCombs said. ``I turned to my family and said, 'Don't worry. We
won the coin toss and we'll score on the first possession.'''
</P>
<P>
   But Atlanta's defense shut down Minnesota's high-octane offense,
which set an NFL record with 556 points last season, and the
Vikings didn't score on their two possessions in overtime. With
8:28 left, the Falcons took over at their own 9-yard line and drove
to the Vikings' 29, where kicker Morten Andersen nailed a 38-yard
field goal with 3:08 remaining for a shocking 30-27 upset.
</P>
<P>
   There was no joy in Slushville. The Mighty Norsemen struck out.
</P>
<P>
   When the teams meet again Sunday in the Georgia Dome in the 1999
opener, Minnesota hopes to take the first step in erasing the
memories of that fateful afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a huge, huge loss,'' McCombs said. ``I've got three
young grandchildren and I realized, just as that game ended, that
we never had explained losing to them. They really didn't
understand losing. It was a difficult situation. I turned to my
wife and said, 'You've got to explain to these grandkids that we
lost and we're not going to Miami. It's over.'''
</P>
<P>
   Three days later, McCombs gathered his family at home. They had
dinner _ and wept.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a big crying session,'' he said. ``We'd all made plans
to go to Miami, but everybody just decided that they weren't going.
I really couldn't handle football at the time. It was a very, very
unusual situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Minnesotans are used to losing. And they've learned it's a lot
like lutefish _ hard to swallow. The Vikings lost the first of four
Super Bowls under coach Bud Grant in 1970, just two years after
Hubert Humprey lost the presidential election to Richard Nixon.
Seven years after Minnesota was pounded by Oakland in their last
Super Bowl appearance, native son Walter ``Fritz'' Mondale lost to
Ronald Regan in the 1984 election.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps none of those defeats stung as much as Minnesota's
loss to Atlanta. The Vikings were supposed to win and few believed
they wouldn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't close the gate or do it like we should have last
year,'' offensive lineman Randall McDaniel said. ``We should have
closed the gate and we didn't. To get that close and not make it,
after doing everything we did last year, it makes you want to get
back.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd be lying if we said we didn't think about it,'' running
back Robert Smith said, ``but (this week) is just another game.
It's our first game and that's most important.''
</P>
<P>
   Those memories undoubtedly will be motivation this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so obvious, it's not even talked about,'' McCombs said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
