<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-THRASHERS06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fraser says Buchberger already 'perfect example'
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ A franchise turned the key Sunday, and it seemed
Kelly Buchberger was there to make sure the engine turned over. He
was the first one on the ice for the first practice in the first
training camp. He was first in line for drills in the morning,
first to be singled out later by the coach for compliments.
</P>
<P>
   ``You like to see guys who jump out to get in front of the
line,'' Thrashers coach Curt Fraser said Sunday, when the team
began on-ice workouts. ``He's the perfect example we want here for
the players.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider them nice set-up comments, assuming the 32-year-old is
named team captain soon. Buchberger says that's not on his mind.
His actions were not an orchestrated effort to gain the attention
of others and assume control of this fledgling hockey team. His
actions merely were borne out of habits he formed as a youth, a
work ethic instilled in him by his parents and a near-tragedy that
gave him an appreciation for life out of a hospital bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was 7, I was burned in a fire and I had to battle to
overcome that,'' said Buchberger, who was acquired from Edmonton in
the expansion draft. ``I couldn't play hockey that year. It was an
uphill battle. I knew it would take me giving 100 percent to
succeed every night.''
</P>
<P>
   The fire, Buchberger said, was his fault. ``I was young and
foolish, playing with gas.'' He doesn't give specifics, saying,
``It's a long story and I'd rather not talk about it.''
</P>
<P>
   But the burns on his left leg were so bad that he had to spend
two-and-a-half months in the hospital. Before every practice, he
must wrap his left leg in gauze for extra protection. Otherwise,
sweat and material rubbing against the scar tissue can cause layers
of skin to peel off.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the difficulties he's had in life, he's had to overcome a
lot just to play,'' said teammate Ray Ferraro. ``It's made him more
resilient than most of us have had to be. He'll get hurt but he'll
come back and play the same way he did before. That's the key.
After being burned, it's not that big a deal to break a bone.''
</P>
<P>
   Which, he has done: a broken ankle; a dislocated shoulder; other
shoulder and knee ailments; a fractured forearm last year that
limited him to 52 games and, he admits, affected his play when he
returned late in the year.
</P>
<P>
   In 13 seasons with the Oilers, Buchberger was known more for his
leadership and physical play than his scoring, although he did have
a 20-goal season in 1991-92. He was popular with teammates and
fans, making it a difficult situation when general manager Glen
Sather left him unprotected in the expansion draft.
</P>
<P>
   Buchberger admits it was ``difficult'' to learn Sather had put
him out there, but stopped short of saying he was bitter. ``I'm
excited about being here now,'' he said. ``I want to be part of
building a winning team, hopefully early.''
</P>
<P>
   The Thrashers made a commitment to the right winger, giving him
a three-year, $2.85-million contract.
</P>
<P>
   Buchberger was born in Langenburg, Saskatchewan, the son of a
potash miner and a mother who's a cook at the only restaurant in
town. His brother runs oil rigs in Dubai. One sister is a pro
volleyball player, the other a police officer. ``Everybody works
hard,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, he recalled the first day of his first training camp
with Edmonton in 1985, when he took a run at veteran Lee Fogolin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't realize who it was,'' Buchberger said, still
embarrassed. ``All of a sudden, I feel this stick go across my
legs. He was saying, `You hit me one more time, you're going
down.'''
</P>
<P>
   Buchberger said he was just as nervous Sunday as he was 14 years
ago. ``You can't get comfortable,'' he said. ``If you're in a
comfort zone, you won't be as hungry.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
