<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-05 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1687 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-LIBYA-GADHAFI-ART-2TA     09-05 1295
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIBYA-GADHAFI-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIBYA'S LEADER MAKES A BID FOR RESPECTABILITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By DOUGLAS JEHL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRIPOLI, Libya _ Moammar Gadhafi's Libya turned 30 last week,
and a spree of congratulations here has been intensified by a
conviction, at least in some quarters, that the leader may finally
have outgrown his bad-boy past.
</P>
<P>
   From all across Africa, where Gadhafi's regime once meddled so
famously, other heads of state are on their way to Tripoli for an
extraordinary meeting of the Organization of African Unity that is
to begin Monday, timed in his honor to coincide with the
anniversary celebrations.
</P>
<P>
   Among those who have already paid tribute was King Abdullah of
Jordan, whose father, King Hussein, could never abide the Libyan
leader. King Abdullah's visit last Wednesday came on the
anniversary of the date that King Idris I of Libya was toppled _
Sept. 1, 1969 _ in a coup led by a 27-year-old Gadhafi, who
replaced him as Libya's leader.
</P>
<P>
   The annual ceremonies to commemorate that revolution have always
been triumphal, with the capital covered in the trademark Libyan
green, on pennants and posters and innumerable tiny lights. But
even compared with a year ago, the backdrop this time is not at all
usual.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to a deal struck in July, Libya enjoys full diplomatic
relations with Britain _ a country that suffered from Libyan
terrorism _ for the first time in 15 years. Thanks to another deal
struck in April, it has been freed from the bind of U.N. sanctions
that, among other things, had since 1992 rendered its
``international airport'' international only in name.
</P>
<P>
   And the fresh flow of potential investors now arriving on direct
flights from European capitals is seen by the hopeful here and
outside Libya as a tangible symbol that an end to Libya's isolation
is at hand.
</P>
<P>
   Gadhafi is best known in the West as a serial troublemaker, with
the defiance and unreality of a perpetual youth. But lately he has
tried to project a fresh look, with acts and comments that some
believe reflect additional maturity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy has grown up,'' said a Tripoli-based Arab diplomat.
``He tried everything when he was young, but he's 57 now, and he's
made up his mind. In the next millennium, he wants to present a new
Libya.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, for example, Gadhafi told African journalists that
he in fact shared an aspiration, voiced by President Olusegun
Obasanjo of Nigeria, who said that people were eager to see
something new from the Libyan leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world knows Moammar Gadhafi as the leader of the world
revolution, which is contributing to the liberation of peoples,''
the Libyan leader said that Obasanjo had told him. ``And now that
the liberation stage has ended, the world wants to know Moammar
Gadhafi as the leader of peace and development in Africa and other
countries.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact, I hope that Moammar Gadhafi meets this description,''
the Libyan leader added.
</P>
<P>
   Gadhafi remains eccentric; at most international gatherings, he
usually stays apart, in a tent. But many African leaders _ like
President Robert Mugabe of Zimbabwe and President Idriss Deby of
Chad, who were helped greatly by Gadhafi in their own revolutionary
days _ now seem to see him as a force for stability.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Gadhafi is hardly a picture of youth. He hobbles on
an aluminum cane that he acquired last summer after he broke a
thigh under circumstances that have not been fully explained. His
skin looks puffy and wrinkled. Still, most observers say his firm
grip on power remains undiminished.
</P>
<P>
   And, with his flowing dark hair and striking features, he
retains his rugged glamour. For public appearances last week, his
outfits included a double-breasted white blazer, traditional Arab
robes, and a dashing white linen suit that he wore for a speech to
foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even as he tries to promote a new image, he sometimes
reverts to old patterns. In front of the gathering of investors, he
accused the United States of promoting ``a satanic policy'' by
using economic sanctions for political purposes. He then went on to
claim that the International Monetary Fund was ``controlled by the
Zionists,'' and complained that if Libya wanted to obtain a World
Bank loan, it would be necessary to ``go first to Tel Aviv.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite such lapses, most foreign observers here say they are
nevertheless convinced that Gadhafi is fully committed to better
behavior. And while it is not easy to gauge public opinion, the
changes of the last few months have clearly made many Libyans more
hopeful.
</P>
<P>
   For many, the most important change, which came with the
suspension of U.N. sanctions, is the fact that Libyans can once
again travel abroad without enduring an arduous journey by car or
ship. And, as they recognize, foreigners have begun to visit Libya
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing is that it will allow tourists and businessmen
to come, and that means more jobs,'' said Latif Abdelsaid, a
24-year-old computer technician who works in a government ministry.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Gadhafi's long record of political and economic
mismanagement means that many skeptics remain. In Libya, which is
Africa's richest country on a per capita basis, many people remain
poor, and some grumble over what they say has been Gadhafi's
longstanding disinclination to pay attention to problems at home.
The boldest among them say they are waiting now to see results.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now the excuse for the bad economic situation is over,'' said
a 40-year-old accountant who would give only his first name,
Abdelsalem. ``We can't blame the sanctions anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Among foreign countries, the main skeptic, of course, is still
the United States, and its grounds are Libya's long record of
support for terrorism, particularly as practiced by radical
Palestinian groups. Together with Britain, the United States
supported the plan to suspend U.N. sanctions against Libya after a
deal was struck to try the suspects in the 1988 bombing of a Pan Am
airliner over Lockerbie, Scotland, that killed 270 people.
</P>
<P>
   But now the Clinton administration stands as the main obstacle
to a Security Council decision to lift those sanctions altogether.
Beyond that, the administration has left in place tough unilateral
sanctions against Libya, some of which date back to 1978.
</P>
<P>
   These include a comprehensive trade embargo imposed in April
1986, at a time when U.S. outrage over Libya's sponsorship of
terrorism led to bombing raids which hit Gadhafi's house, among
other targets, and were said by Libyans to have killed one of his
daughters.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has said those sanctions will not be lifted
until Libya can demonstrate that it has renounced terror ``in word
and deed.'' For now, Libya still appears on the State Department's
list of international sponsors of terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   European countries, struck by the new softening in Libya's old
intransigence, have proved far more willing than the United States
to give Gadhafi the benefit of the doubt.
</P>
<P>
   A general consensus among observers here holds that after seven
years of U.N. sanctions, Gadhafi decided that defiance was no
longer sustainable. Not only did the sanctions cut off air links to
Libya but they also banned the import of aircraft parts, weapons,
and equipment needed for oil production.
</P>
<P>
   Although Libya has succeeded in maintaining oil production at
undiminished levels, the cost to the Libyan economy has been
estimated at $24 billion, and the incalculable cost to popular
morale may have been greater.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``I think probably Gadhafi himself recognizes that he might have
made some mistakes,'' said a Western ambassador here. ``But the
past is the past, and now they want to move quickly into a
different future.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Lockerbie case, the Libyan leader agreed to surrender the
two suspects only after the United States and Britain first bent to
his demand that the trial of the two men, said by Western officials
to be Libyan intelligence officers, take place in a third country.
</P>
<P>
   The trial is now expected to begin next year in the Netherlands,
and Gadhafi's government is obligated under the Security Council
resolution that suspended the sanctions to cooperate with
prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   In two other notorious cases, Gadhafi has quietly moved closer
to accepting some responsibility. In one, involving the 1989
bombing of a French UTA airliner over Africa, the Libyan government
in July transferred $31 million to France to compensate relatives
of 170 people killed in the attack. But Gadhafi specified in a
recent interview that the move should not be construed as an
admission of guilt.
</P>
<P>
   It came after Libya cooperated in a French investigation that
led to the conviction of six Libyans for their role in the attack,
including Abduallah Senoussi, Gadhafi's brother-in-law and top
security aide.
</P>
<P>
   Libya always refused to surrender the defendants to the French
court, so the trial was held in their absence. All of the men were
sentenced to life in prison, but French officials have little
expectation that any will spend even a day behind bars. Even so,
President Jacques Chirac of France proclaimed at a conference of
French diplomats last month that France and Libya had turned past
``a dark page.''
</P>
<P>
   In the second case, Libya has now explicitly accepted
responsibility for the 1984 killing of a British policewoman,
Yvonne Fletcher, by shots fired from the Libyan Embassy in London's
St. James Square. That step, also taken in July, was the one that
prompted Britain to restore diplomatic relations with Libya, which
had been severed since the incident.
</P>
<P>
   Now, for first time in 15 years, there is officially a British
Embassy in Tripoli, although the old quarters have not yet been
restored, and diplomats are working from lower-profile quarters
established previously on the grounds of the Italian Embassy.
</P>
<P>
   One effect of all these moves, taken together, is that rarely a
week goes by in which Gadhafi is not visited by a foreign head of
state trying to make up for lost time after the long ban on
international air flights. Another can be measured in the crush of
foreign delegations that have descended on Tripoli. Some 30 have
visited from Italy alone; others have come from Saudi Arabia, South
Africa, the United Arab Emirates and countless private firms.
</P>
<P>
   Still, few here expect any investment boom soon. Gadhafi's
government has issued scores of new contracts, but it has not
signed any of them yet; it is not known for swift decision-making.
Investors remain wary too, particularly of the fact that the U.N.
sanctions could technically be renewed at any time.
</P>
<P>
   Libya has held talks with British Aerospace on a multibillion
dollar deal to acquire new aircraft for its debilitated commercial
fleet and rebuild the country's crumbling airports. But some
observers say that Libya would prefer to persuade the United States
to join in the new embrace.
</P>
<P>
   In the minds of some Libyans, it would also mark a true end to
the bad old days. ``Things have been going downward for a long
time,'' said a storekeeper who would give his name only as
Mohammed. ``The politics are too complicated for me to understand,
but things were better when the Americans were around.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
