<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RADIOCITY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
500 WORKERS LABOR AT RENOVATING RADIO CITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By JULIE V. IOVINE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Shiny flecks of silvery foil drifted down from the
third mezzanine at Radio City Music Hall, the 67-year-old icon of
Art Deco glamour. They floated past two 30-foot tubular glass
chandeliers, gold mirrors, Pompeian-red velvet-covered walls and
marble wainscoting to settle in small mounds on the bare concrete
floor of the Grand Foyer.
</P>
<P>
   From his ladder, Ed Kaplan, his eyebrows and mutton-chop
sideburns crusted with sparkling bits, pulled another roll of
gossamer-thin foil from his pocket, tore off a piece and pressed it
into the ceiling with a squeegee. ``I'm looking forward to bringing
my grandchildren here,'' said Kaplan, 28, a gilder. ``And I'm going
to show them the parts I did.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan is one of 29 artisans who have spent the last eight weeks
hand-rubbing aluminum leaf into a vast expanse of ceilings,
balconies and walls. The surfaces will soon be shellacked to a
golden sheen _ one of the richest details in an ambitious
restoration which has kept the hall closed since February and sent
costs spiraling from an early estimate of $25 million to $70
million. And there seem to be acres more to go.
</P>
<P>
   Only one month before the scheduled reopening of Radio City
Music Hall on Oct. 4, more than 500 workers _ masons, electricians,
plumbers, plasterers, steamfitters, metalworkers, carpet installers
and more _ are bent to the task of both preserving and modernizing
this architectural treasure for the HDTV generation. Much still
needs to be done.
</P>
<P>
   Last Thursday, the 112-foot-wide shimmery gold silk curtain,
newly woven in Queens, was hoisted on 13 motorized cables up to the
famous sunrise rings of the proscenium arch. ``There's no place on
earth like this,'' said Dave Checketts, president of Madison Square
Garden, which manages Radio City Music Hall for Cablevision
Systems, as he watched two tons of silk cloth swaying. ``Our goal
is to give it back to New York just as it was,'' he added, ``with
all the problems solved.''
</P>
<P>
   He stood amid hundreds of boxes containing the new plush
salmon-pink seats, which are still unpacked. Carpets are yet to be
laid in the 450,000-square-foot space, light sconces and doorknobs
must be installed, the famed Donald Deskey furniture is out being
reupholstered and new red, blue and gold neon has yet to be added
to the marquees.
</P>
<P>
   When visitors enter the refurbished Radio City Music Hall, they
should expect to be awed or shocked by the brightness of colors,
the complexity of rug and wall patterns and the vast reflective
ceilings, now that the tarnishing effects of smoke and time have
been swept away.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a very closely watched renovation,'' said Laurie
Beckelman, vice president of the World Monuments Fund. ``After all,
we have no other space comparable to it at this scale but for Grand
Central. And we're going to be living with what's done now for a
long, long time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to destroy it to rebuild it,'' said Hugh Hardy of Hardy
Holzman Pfeiffer Associates, the architect in charge of the
project, as he picked his way around python-thick coils of cables
spitting from gaping holes in the walls. Every stick of furniture,
wall fabric, lighting fixture and rug was cleaned, reupholstered or
entirely remade. Most significantly, the infrastructure was
completely overhauled. ``It was grotesque,'' Hardy said.
</P>
<P>
   The electrical wiring had fused with the insulation, the
acoustics were miserable and the light dimmers still relied on
old-fashioned vacuum tubes. The stage where Sinatra once sang was
notorious for microphone feedback.
</P>
<P>
   It has taken $30 million and 175 electricians just to rewire the
building and to add high-definition television and 32 new camera
positions for live-wire feeds. Starting after the first of the
year, expect to see frequent events and concerts broadcast ``live
from Radio City.''
</P>
<P>
   Tickets for the premier-event ``Grand Reopening'' will be sold
starting Sept. 12. No one is saying yet who will be on the program
_ count on the 36 Rockettes kicking in two new dance numbers _ but
Dan Schoenberg, the director of publicity at Radio City
Entertainment, said management was talking to 10 to 12 ``A-list
celebrities.'' He tossed out the names Rosie O'Donnell, the
Eurythmics, Liza Minnelli and the kiddie-pop group 98 Degrees _
perhaps not everyone's idea of megawattage entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever they choose will enjoy new lighting that is three times
brighter than it used to be. The renovation now under way, the
music hall's third, is the most ambitious by far since Radio City
opened in 1932 as a vaudeville and movie theater _ an antidote to
the Depression.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
