<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOCCE-GEEK-CHIC-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TECHIES OF SILICON VALLEY FIND A NEW WAY TO UNWIND: BOCCE
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By EVELYN NIEVES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS GATOS, Calif. _ It was a work day, but not the usual kind
spent hunched in cubicles, 12 hours at a time, cooking up the next
big thing to change the world and send the stock soaring.
</P>
<P>
   This was a workday play day, or, in Silicon Valley terms,
off-site team-building time, and the 100 engineers from 3Com
Corp.'s Palm Computing division looked ready for it. They stepped
lightly off chartered buses from their corporate campus, 10 miles
away in Santa Clara, squinting into the sun. Most wore navy blue
company polo shirts, like summer campers on a field trip.
</P>
<P>
   Their hosts here at Campo di Bocce _ eight bocce courts, four
indoors and four outdoors, located at a former lumberyard _ were
well prepared. They had already set out tubs of soda and bottled
water, nestled in ice. The pomodoro and penne bolognese were ready
for the buffet table. And for the group's first lesson, Joe
Morelli, Campo di Bocce's general manager, knew just what to say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bocce,'' Morelli said, scanning the group, ``is a sport you
don't have to be an athlete to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that explains it. Or maybe not. Whatever the reason,
bocce, a 7,000-year-old cousin of lawn bowling best known as the
sport of old men from the old country (if that country happens to
be Italy), is becoming one of the hottest ways to team-build in the
team-charged atmosphere that rules Silicon Valley. This day, bocce
was team-building for 3Com. The next, Hewlett-Packard. The next,
Sun Microsystems. The next, Apple.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've been booked with tech companies almost every day
this summer,'' said Tom Albanese, a local cement contractor who
opened the courts two years ago. Campo di Bocce was a labor of
love, a homage to his ancestral home, Campo Basso, Italy, which
happens to be a mecca for the sport. ``I knew we'd get groups,''
Albanese said. ``I didn't know it would take off like this.''
</P>
<P>
   The things that charmed Albanese about bocce are the same things
that seem to charm computer geeks: it's easy to learn and both
competitive and social. Bocce is played with two teams of up to
four players each. A small ball (the pallino) is rolled down a 12-
by 90-foot (or sometimes 12- by 60-foot) court of packed dirt
topped by oyster shells (or gravel). Then each team takes turns
rolling its colored resin (or wooden) balls toward the small ball.
The team with the most balls closest to the small ball wins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw whole families, three generations, playing in Italy,''
Albanese said. ``It was a beautiful thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The 3Com crowd didn't take long to settle into the game. After
15 minutes, people were hooting and hollering, as if someone had
slam-dunked a basketball. And even when it was time to eat, two
teams opted to finish their games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is so great,'' said Sheryl McGrath, a Palm
Computing secretary who had set up the event. Last year, she said,
the group had spent a day at an indoor ``beach'' _ a warehouse set
up to feel like a beach, complete with beach sports _ and people
wanted another outing.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were asking, `Are we going to do something fun
again?''' Ms. McGrath said, ``and I had read about other companies
coming as a team-building activity.''
</P>
<P>
   As a social event, the day looked like an unqualified success.
Players who might have felt self-conscious about others watching
them as they tossed or slammed their balls into the netherworld,
instead of rolling them deftly down the court, had nothing to fret
about.
</P>
<P>
   Bocce is not the most scintillating game to watch, at least as
beginners play it. In fact, it's a lot like watching a clock. Those
not playing spent their time standing around the cool, cavernous
building or sitting outside at the patio tables, merrily chatting
away, oblivious of their clumsier comrades.
</P>
<P>
   Morelli spent his time gently handing out pointers. ``It's a lot
like putting,'' he would say, when someone tried pitching a ball
like Pedro Martinez. Or: ``Think of it as miniature golf. You have
to work in small strokes.''
</P>
<P>
   A few in the group had lost a little interest. Sasha Golovin, a
software engineer, was more absorbed with Palm Computing's newest
hand-held computer, the Palm VII.
</P>
<P>
   Golovin smirked a bit as someone who had obviously just scored
shouted a ``Yes!'' loud enough to echo across the floor. Bocce was
perfectly nice, he said, as he demonstrated how to get on the
Internet wirelessly with the Palm VII, ``but I think I prefer a
more physical sport.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
