<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-QUARTERBACKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME COACHES CAN'T DECIDE ON A STARTING QB _ YET 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Michigan coach Lloyd Carr sounds as if he is singing the chorus
of a country song when he warbles that he is a one-quarterback guy.
Penn State's Joe Paterno gives the refrain a doo-wop flavor with
his Brooklyn accent. Nebraska's Frank Solich hums the harmony with
Midwest roots rock.
</P>
<P>
   But each has begun this college football season with a cheatin'
heart and a pair of passers they so far are reluctant to choose
between.
</P>
<P>
   Against Notre Dame on Saturday, Tom Brady led Michigan to two
first-quarter field goals, sat out the second quarter as backup
Drew Henson led another 3-point drive, then rallied the Wolverines
for 17 points and a 26-22 victory as the sole quarterback in the
second half.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Carr said, the Wolverines, ranked seventh going into the
game by the Associated Press poll of writers and broadcasters, will
continue some type of rotation for at least their next two games,
against Rice and Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to change what we're doing,'' he said. ``I've
always said I was a one-quarterback guy, but sometimes it's time to
change.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, the 72-year-old Paterno is willing to throttle the
instincts that have won him 309 games, two national championships
and four undefeated but uncrowned teams.
</P>
<P>
   Before his 50th season at Penn State (and 34th as head coach),
before he unleashed an offense that has put up 111 points in two
games, Paterno acknowledged that he had a quandary in deciding
between Kevin Thompson, the senior captain, and the junior Rashard
Casey, a scrambler. But Paterno gave little indication how he would
solve it.
</P>
<P>
   ``These things aren't logical and as precise as some of you
folks might think,'' said Paterno, who has never played two
quarterbacks for a full season. ``A lot of this is by the seat of
the pants.''
</P>
<P>
   He was not any more definitive after Thompson and Casey rotated
series in the No. 2 Nittany Lions' 70-24 thrashing of Akron on
Saturday. Thompson started and was 5 of 8 passing for 188 yards and
two touchdowns; Casey finished 2 of 2 for 29 yards and a touchdown
and ran for another score.
</P>
<P>
   How long will they share time?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' Paterno said. ``They were both pretty good
today. I'm not trying to create any problems for myself by trying
to establish one guy as quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   Solich was grateful he had two good quarterbacks when his
fifth-ranked Cornhuskers struggled to a 7-0 halftime lead against
Iowa. Bobby Newcombe had three first-half turnovers before
rebounding with a passing touchdown and two running scores in the
second half. He finished 7 of 10 for 128 yards and an interception.
</P>
<P>
   While Newcombe struggled early, his backup, Eric Crouch, ran for
Nebraska's first score, added two running touchdowns in the fourth
quarter and clicked off 92 yards on the ground and 68 in the air.
The result: Nebraska 42, Iowa 7.
</P>
<P>
   There are other tandems, too, early this season. Arizona is one
of the few teams committed to rotating quarterbacks _ Keith Smith
and Ortege Jenkins _ as it did last year. Ohio State coach John
Cooper said both of his young quarterbacks, Austin Moherman and
Steve Bellisari, would see time, as they did in the 23-12 loss on
Aug. 29 against Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is startling to see so many top teams wrestling with
the most important position on the field, especially following a
season in which Tim Couch, Akili Smith, Donovan McNabb, Daunte
Culpepper and Cade McNown were selected in the first round of the
National Football League draft.
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of excellent quarterbacks leading teams _ the
best is perhaps Tennessee's Tee Martin, who threw for two
touchdowns and 159 yards to lead the defending national champion
Volunteers to a 42-17 victory over Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   There are also Heisman Trophy hopefuls Chris Redman and Drew
Brees. Louisville's Redman passed for 324 yards and five touchdowns
to beat Kentucky, 56-28, and Purdue's Brees was 26 of 43 for 273
yards and four touchdowns in a 47-13 victory over Central Florida.
</P>
<P>
   More often than not in a quarterback rotation, there is a
perception that the coach does not believe either candidate can
play _ or at least that neither can be entrusted alone to drive a
team to a national championship. In the case of Michigan, Penn
State and Nebraska, each coach insists, however, that the summer
quarterback competition was too close to call.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel it was fair to start one and not play the other
at all,'' Carr said. ``They competed well and hard against each
other.'' Against Notre Dame, ``I think they were both extremely
effective.''
</P>
<P>
   But Carr might have indicated which way he was leaning when he
stuck with Brady in the second half against Notre Dame. Brady, a
senior, finished 17 for 24 for 197 yards; Henson, a sophomore, was
3 of 8 for 40 yards in his second-quarter appearance. Tight games
tend to make coaches abandon enlightenment for comfort.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, once Michigan, Penn State and Nebraska play their
toughest opponents, watch Carr, Paterno and Solich change their
tunes. It's a good bet there will be only one voice in the huddle.
And from the sideline, the coaches will revert to their favorite
song: ``Stand by Your Man.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-99 2032EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990905.0154 </DOCNO>
