<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-05 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1693 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-TIFFANY-ROY-KAN &LR;      09-05 1593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIFFANY-ROY-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADOPTIVE FATHER'S LOVE SUPPORTS A 15-YEAR FIGHT FOR LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIM KOZLOWSKI and DONALD BRADLEY  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Tiffany was born with her umbilical cord
wrapped around her neck. The cord starved her brain of oxygen, with
devastating results.
</P>
<P>
   She had cerebral palsy. She couldn't see. She couldn't hear.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors predicted the baby girl would live only a few months.
She was headed to a group home because her mentally disabled mother
couldn't take care of her.
</P>
<P>
   That fate didn't sound fair to Roy Hutchison, a paramedic who
heard talk of Tiffany at the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``You lock up prisoners _ you don't lock up children,'' he
thought.
</P>
<P>
   Within days Hutchison and his wife and son gave the baby a home.
</P>
<P>
   That was the fall of 1984. Hutchison has gotten divorced since
then. He's lost his son in a car crash.
</P>
<P>
   But he's held on tight to Tiffany. The two live in a ranch home
in Oak Grove, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   Tiffany, who will turn 15 next week, has the mind of an infant.
She can't walk or talk.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison, 51, is a 6-foot-2-inch Harley biker with a ponytail
and 10 tattoos.
</P>
<P>
   And though Tiffany can't see, she knows his touch. She often
cries when others try to help her, but she calms quickly when she
feels his gentle strokes on her arm or cheek.
</P>
<P>
   Tiffany's blindness doesn't stop her dad from wrapping her new
clothes in colorful gift paper.
</P>
<P>
   He gave her a home. She taught him about life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here I was _ a big, tough Harley rider, ridden thousands of
miles and taken bugs in the face at 65 miles per hour. Then calling
in sick because my foot hurt after a three-day ride,'' Hutchison
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I know the pain she lives every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every morning when I leave for work, I give her a kiss and
tell her to have a good day. And each day, I know I may never see
her again. She's taught me how precious life is and how important
love is.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors marveled over the years as Tiffany survived her original
medical problems plus heart disease, a curved spine and severe
respiratory problems. She requires round-the-clock care.
</P>
<P>
   ``I promised her as long as she fights, I'll fight for her,''
Hutchison said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And when her little body gets tired of fighting, I'll
understand.''
</P>
<P>
   He believes that time is near.
</P>
<P>
   Near the end of 1983, Tiffany's mother, 18, conceived a child.
</P>
<P>
   But she never knew she was pregnant. Her mind functioned at the
level of a 6-year-old's, and her pregnancy didn't show. On Sept.
16, 1984, Tiffany's mother was taken to Truman Medical Center with
pains thought to be appendicitis.
</P>
<P>
   She gave birth to a baby girl while she sat in the bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   One minute passed. No oxygen for the newborn. Another minute.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, after four minutes, doctors unwrapped the umbilical
cord that had snaked around Tiffany's neck. They performed CPR.
</P>
<P>
   But the brain damage was done.
</P>
<P>
   Tiffany's mother didn't understand what had happened. To her,
the baby was like a doll she could play with when she wanted.
</P>
<P>
   This was the story that state social workers told Hutchison when
he first learned about Tiffany at Truman Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison had just taken a patient there. His wife also happened
to be at Truman, doing some work for the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   After talking it over with their son, they decided to become the
girl's foster parents, for however long she lived.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison remembers the first time he saw her.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was in a little basket. I thought she was beautiful,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   As Tiffany clung to life that winter, the bond between her and
the Hutchisons grew.
</P>
<P>
   They adopted her in 1986, just after her second birthday.
</P>
<P>
   But the couple's marriage began to unravel. They divorced and
agreed to joint custody, with Tiffany living with Hutchison's
ex-wife. She corroborated his account but did not wish her comments
to be included in this story.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, Hutchison's ex-wife wanted to put Tiffany in a home for
children with special needs.
</P>
<P>
   But just as when she was born, Roy Hutchison wouldn't stand for
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``People raise children,'' Hutchison said. ``You don't put them
in homes.''
</P>
<P>
   They battled in court, and Hutchison prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   He brought Tiffany home to live with him and his son, Chad.
</P>
<P>
   Six years ago, Hutchison was asleep on the living room couch
when someone knocked on the door. He thought Chad, then 18, had
forgotten his keys.
</P>
<P>
   But a sheriff's deputy and a minister stood at the door.
</P>
<P>
   Chad had been killed in a car wreck.
</P>
<P>
   He soon made a promise to Tiffany.
</P>
<P>
   ``When my son died, that was a car accident, and he couldn't
call and say, `I'm in a car accident, can you be here?' ''
Hutchison said. ``I told Tiffany I would always be there for her.''
</P>
<P>
   Except for work, he seldom leaves her side. One of Tiffany's
lungs has failed, and doctors have told him that her heart is
working too hard.
</P>
<P>
   And the smiles that come when he strokes her arm are rarer now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her little heart will probably just quit some night,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   He hopes, though, that she survives until his Oct. 10 wedding,
at which he's expecting more than 1,000 biker friends who know him
as ``Hutch.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I want her to die with a mother,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Every morning, Hutchison dresses Tiffany, changes her diaper,
combs her long brown hair and brushes her teeth.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, she will start back to school at the Blue Springs
(Mo.) Special Services Center, a public school for severely
disabled students.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison works eight hours a day installing lights and fans for
The Fixture Gallery, a home fixture business in Blue Springs.
</P>
<P>
   A pager will alert him if Tiffany develops breathing problems,
seizures or coughing fits. Sometimes he leaves work early to meet
her at Children's Mercy Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   He realizes he doesn't match up to some people's perception of a
biker.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't smoke or drink. His choice of music is not
Steppenwolf, but George Jones. He dresses up like Santa Claus and
visits children with special needs.
</P>
<P>
   And he would take Tiffany along when he went on dates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted them to know right up front that we're a package
deal,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And he finds plenty of time for his motorcycle. He and Tiffany
are regulars at meetings of Harley owners.
</P>
<P>
   When Tiffany underwent surgery recently, Hutchison said, more
than 250 of the group's members donated blood.
</P>
<P>
   But she's never ridden on a bike.
</P>
<P>
   Mary McKee, an assistant area director of the Missouri Division
of Family Services, commended Hutchison for what she called an
extraordinary dedication to a special child.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know of a father who has a child born naturally that
would do the things he's done for her,'' McKee said.
</P>
<P>
   Tiffany's worsening condition has tempered the joy of planning a
wedding for Hutchison and his fiancee, Eilene Brown. The two were
introduced by her sister, who worked next door to the place that
cared for Tiffany outside school hours.
</P>
<P>
   Brown knows Hutchison feels his daughter's pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tiffany has outlived all expectations because of his love,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison has been asked why he does it. What keeps him going
after years of doctor visits, seizures, hospital stays and
sleepless nights when he feared she would die?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a hardship,'' Hutchison said. ``It's love. Tiffany
doesn't wake up in the morning and say she loves her dad. But when
I pick her up and carry her to the truck, it's like she hugs me.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like she says, `Thanks, Dad.' ''
</P>
<P>
   It was 5 p.m. on a typical day during the school year that ended
last spring. Hutchison had just arrived at Caudell Specialized Care
in Independence, Mo., where Tiffany had spent time after school.
</P>
<P>
   A boy in a wheelchair stopped him to say hello.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, how are you doing today?'' Hutchison said, reaching down
to touch the boy's arm.
</P>
<P>
   Then he walked over to Tiffany, who was lying on a recliner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tiffany,'' Hutchison said, bending to hold her hands. ``How
was your day today?''
</P>
<P>
   She turned her head and lifted her upper body toward him.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Hutchison carried Tiffany into their little house on a
cul-de-sac. He placed her on the living room couch and they began
their night together.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a sweat shirt and Joe Boxer pants, Tiffany sat with her
arms bent at the elbow and her fists clutched to her chest. A
pillow propped her head, which her spinal curvature has cocked to
the right.
</P>
<P>
   Her hazel eyes appeared to be gazing at a corner of the ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison tended to chores. The home was filled with portraits
of him, Tiffany, his son and his motorcycle.
</P>
<P>
   Around 7 p.m., Hutchison carried Tiffany to bed. He adjusted the
pillow under her head and propped another underneath her knees.
</P>
<P>
   He stroked her cheek.
</P>
<P>
   Because Tiffany can't chew food, her father inserted a feeding
tube into her stomach.
</P>
<P>
   Tiffany broke into a smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're in a good mood tonight,'' Hutchison said, as he grabbed
Tiffany's hand. ``Do you want to play?''
</P>
<P>
   Tiffany grinned, but soon began to cry. Hutchison cradled her
head in his hands, adjusted her pillow, massaged her legs.
</P>
<P>
   When Tiffany continued to fidget, he fetched a handheld massager
to use on her neck.
</P>
<P>
   Tiffany calmed. He waited a few minutes, then pulled a blanket
over her.
</P>
<P>
   ``How about if I let you rest for a while and then I'll come
back in and check on you?'' Hutchison said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Holler if you need anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Hutch, the tough, old biker, is never far away from his little
girl.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
