<SLUG> BC-AZR-BUDGET-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Monday, Sept. 6. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
AFRICA (undated) _ From the primitive wilds of Africa, via
satellite phone and laptop, an Arizona State University professor
hopes to inspire the world's children to learn, to think, to dream.
Dennis Wilson will use the Internet to bring students along on his
``African Edventure'' _ with videos of scuba diving in Lake Malawi,
hiking the 19,340 foot summit of Kilimanjaro and bungee jumping 709
feet from a bridge. By PATRICIA BIGGS. Story will move in the ``A''
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
PRESBOOK (undated) _ On Tuesday, Arizona Sen. John McCain will make
some New York book-tour appearances that strongly resemble campaign
opportunities to boost him in the race for the GOP presidential
nomination. It's not an uncommon event. But to some observers, it
also raises questions about whether the mix of book publicizing and
political preening has gone too far, whether publishers are
improperly, even illegally, helping underwrite campaigns. McCain is
not the only candidate who has piggybacked a book on his campaign.
The Federal Election Commission advises campaigns that if
publishers pay for a book tour closely tied to a campaign, it could
could be considered a corporate contribution to the campaign.
Corporate contributions to presidential campaigns are illegal. By
KRIS MAYES. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW&AMP;NOTABLE (undated) Anne Stephenson's capsule reviews of new
books. By ANNE STEPHENSON. Story will move int the ``E'' category. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
