<SLUG> BC-RAC-DIANA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERITAGE OF GOLD PROVES HER CUP FUTURE IS ON THE GRASS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ She is a 4-year-old filly named
Heritage of Gold, and she has been knocking on the door of
Breeders' Cup opportunity all year. Sunday, the door opened.
</P>
<P>
   One month after her five-race winning streak was broken by last
year's 3-year-old champion filly, Banshee Breeze, Heritage of Gold
resumed her run of success Sunday when she won the $300,000 Diana
Handicap at Saratoga by one length over Irish filly Khumba Mela.
And if the Diana was a prelude to the Breeders' Cup race for
fillies and mares on the turf, which will be run for the first time
in November, then Heritage of Gold positioned herself for a shot at
even greater success.
</P>
<P>
   She not only won a scramble down the homestretch but also outran
Mossflower, the speed demon who is making a comeback from a year's
absence forced by arthritic ankles and who finished third. And for
a real coup, Heritage of Gold buried Soaring Softly, who came into
the race with a winning streak of five but left it as the beaten
favorite in fifth place.
</P>
<P>
   But the most significant thing for Heritage of Gold may be her
versatility. She has won five races on grass, five on dirt. And her
jockey, Shane Sellers, saw a strategic edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``On dirt, she may be just a notch below Banshee Breeze,'' he
said. ``But on grass, she's a different mare. And on grass, you
don't run into the likes of Banshee Breeze.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Amoss, who took over Heritage of Gold's training from Steve
Asmussen this summer, agreed that he had one goal in mind for her.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to make sure she's healthy tomorrow,'' he said,
``and then sit down and map out a plan that leads to the Breeders'
Cup.'' He hopes to have the plan by midweek.
</P>
<P>
   Amoss made no bones about avoiding Banshee Breeze and Beautiful
Pleasure, who outran Heritage of Gold in the Go For Wand Stakes one
month ago. ``I didn't want to face the two fillies we ran against
last time,'' he said. ``I learned a lot from her last race. We
decided in the paddock that we were just going to let her be
comfortable wherever she might be.''
</P>
<P>
   Heritage of Gold ran the 1 1/8 miles in a speedy 1:45 4/5, only
two-fifths of a second off the track record, in defeating Khumba
Mela, who saved second place by a head over Mossflower. The winner
paid $13.80 for a $2 bet to win and earned $180,000.
</P>
<P>
   Mossflower, who stalked the fast early pace before closing with
a burst, drew praise from her trainer, Rich Schosberg. Since
starting her comeback two months ago, she has run second, fourth
and third. ``She never gave up, and it was a superb effort,''
Schosberg said. ``She really came on again in the last few yards.''
</P>
<P>
   Schosberg said he would run Mossflower in the $500,000 Flower
Bowl at Belmont Park on Oct. 2. And Christophe Clement, who trains
Khumba Mela, said that ``she ran a great race to be second,'' but
that he was not sure where he would place her for an encore.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
