u a BC-HOMELESS-KIDNEY-DONOR     09-05 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMELESS-KIDNEY-DONOR-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOMELESS KIDNEY DONOR TO GET AN APARTMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By IRVIN MOLOTSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ An unemployed woman who donated a kidney to a young
boy but was left homeless when she was evicted from a public
housing project in Alexandria, Va., has been offered her own place
to live.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, Marian Neal, has been staying in a homeless shelter
since she was kicked out of the housing project, where she had been
staying in a friend's apartment. Managers of the project said Ms.
Neal's presence violated the friend's lease, and a complaint had
been filed.
</P>
<P>
   But on Friday, after Ms. Neal's ordeal had been widely
publicized in the Washington media for weeks, Andrew Cuomo, the
secretary of housing and urban development, said his department
would lease Ms. Neal a recently renovated one-bedroom town house in
Washington. The rent will be based on her income, which Ms. Neal
said made the town house affordable.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was a heroine who should be treated decently,'' Cuomo told
The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   William Dearman, executive director of the Alexandria
Redevelopment and Housing Authority, which runs the housing project
on the edge of Alexandria's Old Town neighborhood, said he had been
unfairly cast as the heavy because he had evicted Ms. Neal. But he
defended his actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a great thing that she did,'' Dearman said,
``donating a kidney to this kid. But, you know, we have rules in
this world.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Neal said she had no hard feelings for whoever turned her
in.
</P>
<P>
   ``We pray for them,'' she said. ``We feel no anger.''
</P>
<P>
   People who have met Ms. Neal say they come away impressed by her
spirituality and her stoicism, beneath which lies a sharp sense of
public relations. That has helped her collect donations, but she is
still living in Carpenter's Shelter, a place for the homeless in
Alexandria, a Washington suburb.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marian has done most of her own publicity on this,'' said
Frances Becker, executive director of Carpenter's Shelter.
</P>
<P>
   There have been news features on three of Washington's four
major television stations. When a Washington radio station, WRQX,
told of the eviction of a woman who had donated a kidney, listeners
called in pledges of $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Ms. Neal sat in the living room of her friend's
apartment and talked about her decision to donate her kidney last
year to Terrance Varner, now 8, who lives in the Old Town
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   She said she began helping Terrance's grandmother take care of
him last year by taking the youngster, who suffered from renal
failure, to dialysis treatments three times a week. Terrance was on
a long waiting list for a new kidney.
</P>
<P>
   When Ms. Neal learned that none of Terrance's family members
were suitable kidney donors, she offered one of hers. Even though
they were not related, she was found to be a close match. The
transplant was a success and Terrance is doing well, Ms. Neal said.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Spieldenner, a spokesman for the United Network for Organ
Sharing in Richmond, Va., said that of the 4,038 kidneys donated by
living donors last year, just 163, or 4 percent, were from people
unrelated to the recipients by either blood or marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Neal, 40, is from Philadelphia, where she worked in
hospitals as a housekeeper and then sorted packages for Federal
Express. She said she had to stop working in 1994 because of a
degenerative back disease that has forced her to use a cane to get
around.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why she was not receiving Social Security disability
payments, Ms. Neal said she was appealing a decision in which her
application for benefits had been rejected.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all right,'' she said when asked if she harbored any ill
feelings toward the person who had made that decision. ``Everything
that happens in life, it's all for the good of the Lord.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision meant that she was forced to live on the $210 a
month that she received from the city welfare agency in Alexandria
and $120 a month in food stamps, which led her to move into the
tiny but well-kept apartment of Patrice Hall, whom she describes as
``my sister in Christ.''
</P>
<P>
   This summer, Ms. Neal and Ms. Hall provided Bible study,
tutoring and arts and crafts for the children in the housing
project, Ms. Neal said.
</P>
<P>
   Dearman of the housing authority said he had offered to allow
Ms. Hall to sign a new lease with Ms. Neal as the official
co-tenant, but she had declined. As a result, Ms. Neal had to go to
the bottom of a list of applicants for public housing in the city
and turn to the homeless shelter.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are 60 people on the waiting list ahead of her,''
Dearman said. ``Some of them are homeless. Would it be right to put
her ahead because she is a kidney donor? Sometimes there are hard
decisions that have to be made.''
</P>
</TEXT>
