<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA DEFENSE GOES BACK TO BASICS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ UCLA's defense is like commodity prices: Past
performance does not guarantee future results, so step carefully.
Translated, the Bruins' dominating performance against Boise State
means nothing Saturday at Ohio State.
</P>
<P>
   The Buckeyes have two superb tailbacks (Michael Wiley and
Jonathan Wells), they have a massive offensive line and, perhaps
most telling, they have video of the UCLA-Miami and UCLA-Wisconsin
games. After watching the Badgers and Hurricanes gain 1,186 yards
on UCLA, the Buckeyes probably expect to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   If they do, it'll have everything to do with talent and
experience and little to do with strategy and execution. That's the
difference between UCLA '98 and UCLA '99. Last year, the Bruins
didn't have a clue; this year, they have a plan, and they are
organized.
</P>
<P>
   The transformation began when embattled defensive coordinator
Nick Aliotti bolted for Oregon and assistant Bob Field became the
new defensive boss. (Actually, he's the new-old defensive boss,
having served 14 years as defensive coordinator under Terry
Donahue.)
</P>
<P>
   Aliotti treated the Bruins like the NFL veterans he coached in
St. Louis from 1995-97, installing numerous defenses at an
incomprehensible rate. Dazed and confused, the Bruins mulled every
assignment and lost critical reaction time. The results were
wide-open receivers (Stanford, Oregon State) and gaping holes for
runners to exploit (Miami, Wisconsin).
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Bruins devoted so much time to learning the
defenses they had nothing left over for fundamentals like shedding
blocks and tackling. Of course they couldn't tackle in games. They
didn't tackle in practice.
</P>
<P>
   Field and head coach Bob Toledo made sure not to repeat
Aliotti's mistake. They treated spring practice like elementary
math _ making sure the Bruins could multiply by 2 before moving to
3. Field spent the entire first week implementing his base defense,
deployed when an offense uses the standard two running backs, one
tight end and two receivers.
</P>
<P>
   That's more complicated than it seems. Each time a receiver goes
in motion, for instance, the defense must respond by changing its
assignments. Add formations that feature three receivers, four
receivers, one running back or two tight ends, and suddenly the
defense is responsible for dozens of assignments each week. Field
had 50 defenses prepared for Saturday's game alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We built a good foundation that first week of spring practice,
then began to add the pieces,'' Field said. ``You have to start
with the elementary approach, but eventually you have to move on to
junior high, high school and college.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought the most important thing was adding pieces at the
right time. We didn't want to overload the guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Field implemented 70 percent of the defensive playbook in spring
practice, which carved training camp time for fundamentals. The
linemen practiced pass-rush techniques and shedding blocks. The
defensive backs practiced footwork and locating the ball. And
always, Field made sure each player knew where he was supposed to
be every play. He also honed the substitution pattern so the Bruins
wouldn't repeat their 1998 mistake of having 10 men on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our whole approach with the players has been to make them
confident about the basics, like recognizing formations, so they
can just react and play,'' Field said. ``If you have to think,
you're paralyzed out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Note: UCLA's second-quarter interceptions by Julius Williams and
Joey Strycula occurred on consecutive series, not consecutive plays
as was reported in some of Sunday's editions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-99 2047EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
