<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC'S FOX KEEPS BUSY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONOLULU _ USC's most versatile player against Hawaii had to be
senior John Fox.
</P>
<P>
   In the 62-7 rout of Hawaii before 50,000 at Aloha Stadium, Fox
played special teams, participated as a reserve at middle
linebacker and took the final snaps at quarterback for the Trojans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was awesome,'' said USC quarterback Carson Palmer. ``That's
just the type of guy he is. I think that's what is special about
this team. We have a senior class full of guys willing to do
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox started nine games at quarterback for the Trojans in 1997,
before trying tight end and then linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   Kicking for joy: For the first time in several years, it appears
USC may have a reliable kicking game. Sophomore David Newbury
kicked a 48-yard field goal in the first quarter and a 34-yarder in
the second.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Assistant coach) Shawn Slocum asked me and I really hesitated
on the first one,'' USC coach Paul Hackett said. ``But Newbury
responded beautifully. The kicker was a big question that got
answered.''
</P>
<P>
   Newbury won the placekicking job over David Bell on Wednesday,
although Bell continues to handle kickoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Strong sinks: About the only player not leaving Hawaii in good
spirits was sophomore tailback Frank Strong, who fumbled twice in
six carries.
</P>
<P>
   That gives Strong five fumbles in only 43 career carries,
something that drew the ire of Hackett.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot fumble the football,'' Hackett said. ``You cannot
play at USC if you don't hang onto the football.''
</P>
<P>
   Arbet hurt: Freshman walk-on Kevin Arbet was set to make a
heralded debut by starting as the nickel back, but early in the
game, Arbet suffered a sprained ankle and did not return.
</P>
<P>
   Fullback Chad Pierson also suffered an ankle injury and was
forced to leave the game.
</P>
<P>
   Freshmen play: USC used seven true freshmen in the game: wide
receivers Marcell Allmond, Kareem Kelly and Steve Stevenson,
defensive tackle Bernard Riley, linebacker Troy Polamalu, defensive
end Omar Nazel and Arbet.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic woes: Even with a police escort, USC arrived at Aloha
Stadium about 25 minutes late, because game traffic clogged the
surface streets around the stadium. The announced crowd of 50,000
was Hawaii's first sellout since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   By the numbers: USC's margin of victory was the largest in a
season opener since a 76-0 win over UCLA in 1929.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Trojans' biggest win since 1994, when they defeated
Cal 61-0 and most points scored since USC had 66 against Utah State
in 1989.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-99 2048EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
