<SLUG> BC-CISNEROS-TRIAL-675&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER HOUSING SECRETARY GOES ON TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Calif.)  (lb) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Henry Cisneros, a former Cabinet officer in the
Clinton administration, goes on trial in federal court here on
Tuesday in what is almost certain to be the last major trial of the
two-decades-long grand experiment of the independent-counsel law.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros, a former mayor of San Antonio who was once believed to
have a bright political future, faces 18 felony counts on charges
that he lied to federal investigators about the amount of money he
paid over the years to a former mistress in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The charges do not concern the existence of a mistress while he
was married; that is something he acknowledged publicly in San
Antonio years before he accepted the post as housing secretary. The
charges do not involve the payments he made, which he acknowledged
to investigators and to the Clinton administration. Neither is a
crime.
</P>
<P>
   The charges for which he could face up to 90 years in jail
involve his telling agents of the FBI that he had paid the woman,
Linda Jones, about $60,000 over the years, when the evidence is
strong that the actual figure was closer to $250,000, and that he
had asked two assistants to help him in the deception.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution case will feature tape recordings that Ms. Jones
made of their telephone conversations after Cisneros was offered a
job in President Clinton's Cabinet. The tapes, which deal
occasionally with the payments, mostly lay out a familiar tale of
former lovers awkwardly testing each other's loyalty. Cisneros
repeatedly expresses fear that Ms. Jones could betray and ruin him,
and she says she is worried that she will be cut off financially.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their pledges on the tapes to never do those things, in
the end that is exactly what they did.
</P>
<P>
   Jury selection is set to begin on Tuesday for a trial that
encapsulates for many the peculiar nature of the
independent-counsel law, born after Watergate and allowed to die
this summer by a Congress wearied by what the law had produced,
notably Kenneth Starr's investigation of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The enormous attention given to Starr's investigation probably
shielded the Cisneros investigation from scrutiny by the law's
critics.
</P>
<P>
   A wide range of commentators have noted that the law provided
for a single prosecutor to focus on one person with few practical
limits on expenditures. In such a situation, the critics have said,
there is an inherent and unhealthy incentive for the prosecutor to
spend a great amount of time and money to find something worth
prosecuting.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor in the Cisneros case, David Barrett, has spent an
estimated $10 million over four years.
</P>
<P>
   The law was also supposed to divorce politics from the
prosecution of officials high in the executive branch by
transferring decisions from the Justice Department to the
independent counsel. But few now argue that the law has
accomplished that goal, as each investigation has produced a major
political debate.
</P>
<P>
   In the Cisneros case, Barrett, because of his background, has
seemed to many a strange choice to investigate a Democratic housing
secretary.
</P>
<P>
   The 62-year-old Washington lawyer is a well-known Republican
fund-raiser who prospered greatly by lobbying the Department of
Housing and Urban Development when it was controlled by Republicans
before Cisneros' tenure.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett, who has never been accused of wrongdoing in his
dealings with the housing agency, was nonetheless mentioned
repeatedly in a 1990 report by a House subcommittee titled ``Abuse
and Mismanagement at HUD'' in which he was depicted as a lobbyist
who successfully used access to friends at the agency to win
grants.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1980 presidential campaign, Barrett headed the group
Lawyers for Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   At some point early in the Clinton administration, lawyers and
congressional aides said, Barrett asked a friend to have his name
forwarded to Judge David Sentelle, the chief judge of the panel
that appointed special prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett declined to comment on his role as a lobbyist or on how
he came to the attention of Sentelle.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   One notable feature of the Cisneros case is that prosecutors are
using as their main witness against him his former mistress, who
has been branded a liar by those same prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, once known as Linda Medlar, now goes by the name
Linda Jones and is serving a term of 42 months in federal prison on
a variety of charges related to the Cisneros case. She hopes, her
lawyers have said, to have her jail time reduced by cooperating
with prosecutors who are trying to convict Cisneros.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors demonstrated that Ms. Jones lied about the
audiotapes of her telephone conversations with Cisneros, a pillar
of the Cisneros prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Jones repeatedly told prosecutors the tapes were originals,
but they were in fact copies that had been altered in parts.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Stanley Sporkin, who will preside over the trial, which is
expected to last longer than a month, has ruled that most of the
audiotapes may be admitted as evidence, even though many have been
tampered with.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to discussions of their affair and his payments to
her on the tapes, Cisneros makes some embarrassing and critical
remarks about President-elect Clinton, at the same time that he was
offered the job in the Clinton Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   On the tapes, Cisneros is heard telling Ms. Jones that Clinton
is the kind of cheerful politician ``who can't seem to decide hard
things'' and is ``willing to do a deal with the business
interests.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the conversations about their relationship, she warns him
on one occasion: ``Honey, I'm as smart as they come. I know exactly
what would sink you.''
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros tells her on another occasion that if the payments come
up at his confirmation hearing he would ``tell them what we
agreed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And the only person in the world who can sink me at that point
_ and I mean serious, I'm talking contempt of Congress, jail _ is
you,'' he continued.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Ms. Jones sold about a third of the 40 hours of tapes
she made to a tabloid television program for $15,000. The program,
``Inside Edition,'' distributed transcripts after its broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   That broadcast led Attorney General Janet Reno to start a
preliminary inquiry into Cisneros' behavior.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to seek the inquiry that led to Barrett's
appointment might have foreshadowed some of the current tension
between Reno and Louis Freeh, the director of the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   Law-enforcement officials said at the time the tapes were
disclosed that Freeh had pressed vigorously for an
independent-counsel investigation of Cisneros. The officials said
that Freeh was indignant that Cisneros might have lied to FBI
agents who conducted interviews about payments to Jones and said it
would set a bad example to treat that lightly.
</P>
<P>
   Reno, the officials said, had expected that an independent
counsel would judge the matter too small for a full-scale
prosecution and that it would be over in a few months.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros, who resigned from the Cabinet in 1994, is now the
president of Univision, the Spanish-language television network
based in Los Angeles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
