<HEADLINE>
USC GETS THE RIGHT ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONOLULU _ The traffic tie-ups this weekend around the city were
enough to give USC coach Paul Hackett fits. USC was late to
practice Friday and the game on Saturday from the congestion.
</P>
<P>
   And the Hawaii fans could have been a little more generous.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tough crowd,'' Hackett said. ``The guy behind me
yelled, `You can't use these points for UCLA!'''
</P>
<P>
   But when those are the worst things you experience on the road,
it has to be considered a pretty good trip. And USC's 62-7 victory
over Hawaii was about as good as it could get for a season opener.
</P>
<P>
   There wasn't really a single moment that defined the game,
because the Trojans simply dominated the Rainbow Warriors, scoring
on their first six possessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said before that I think we'll be a better team than last
year,'' Hackett said. ``It's one thing to say it and one to do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans did it Saturday night, and for those who couldn't
stay up late in Los Angeles, there were plenty of highlights.
</P>
<P>
   _Quarterback Carson Palmer demonstrated that he has improved
significantly from last season, completing 14 of 16 passes for 167
yards and a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game was in slow motion for me compared to last year,''
Palmer said. ``This win gives us tons of confidence. It shows this
offense does work.''
</P>
<P>
   _Wide receiver was supposed to be a thin position, but it just
might be the Trojans' most exciting. R. Jay Soward had a fairly
quiet start, suffering a mild ankle sprain. But Windrell Hayes
caught seven passes and the freshmen met all expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Kareem Kelly had a wonderful debut, with 104 yards receiving,
and Hackett singled out Marcell Allmond for his catch-and-run after
having his helmet torn off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told people about our freshmen, but they didn't believe
me,'' Soward said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The young receiving staff stood up and made plays,'' Hackett
added.
</P>
<P>
   _The secondary passed its first test. Even with freshmen Darrell
Rideaux and Kevin Arbet hurt, this group held together. Kris
Richard, Eric Reese and a sore-ankled Tanqueray Clark all played a
part in shutting down Hawaii's passing game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The preseason doubters were there and I never paid attention
to them,'' said Richard, who had an interception and fumble
recovery. ``It's so satisfying. There never was a single doubt I
was prepared.''
</P>
<P>
   _Linebackers apparently still make big plays, even without Chris
Claiborne. JC transfer Markus Steele certainly made an impression.
He returned a fumble 46 yards for a touchdown and tipped the pass
that Richard intercepted.
</P>
<P>
   Steele still needs work stopping the run, but who wants to hear
complaints after a 55-point victory?
</P>
<P>
   ``We as a defense couldn't ask for anything more,'' strong
safety David Gibson said. ``A shutout pretty much says it all.''
</P>
<P>
   Remember, Hawaii's only points came when Mike Van Raaphorst's
pass was intercepted by Quincy LeJay, who returned it for a
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   So where does this leave the Trojans after one game?
</P>
<P>
   ``Are there still doubters out there?'' Soward said.
</P>
<P>
   He then proceeded to answer his own question.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are going to say, `Well, it's Hawaii... but for us to
get out and play like that against Hawaii, it was a big game.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Gibson, who was so excited during the game that he was
actually talking trash to Hawaii's receivers, settled down
afterward to put it into perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't say we're great because we beat Hawaii,'' Gibson
said. ``We've got to take it for what it's worth.''
</P>
<P>
   It means the Trojans are 1-0, which feels a lot better than 0-1.
The opponent might have lost its 19th straight game, but USC will
savor any victory, especially following the Sun Bowl disaster. The
Trojans were supposed to have won that game, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just one game, but it's an important game because it's on
the road,'' Hackett said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
