<SLUG> BC-SOC-FIRE-METROSTARS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURF IS ARTIFICIAL, METROSTARS' DESPAIR IS BONA FIDE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The MetroStars have been disintegrating
piece by piece over the past two months. After Sunday's 2-1 loss to
the Chicago Fire, their 12th consecutive defeat, and a knee injury
to their best player, Sasa Curcic, the MetroStars' playoff hopes
all but vanished.
</P>
<P>
   It was the 22nd loss in 27 games for the MetroStars, who played
in a persistent drizzle Sunday at Giants Stadium. Three days ago
the grass field was removed and the artificial turf field brought
back.
</P>
<P>
   MetroStars coach Bora Milutinovic didn't appear to be quite
surprised when it was suggested that his team had all the
ingredients to go without a victory for the rest of the season,
which has five games remaining. Milutinovic must have been thinking
of all the defensive mishaps that have been the primary reason for
the losing streak and his smile revealed more pain than joy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The season is not over,'' Milutinovic said, ``but our
situation is getting more difficult every day. We have to work hard
to resolve this problem. If you have confidence, everything is
easy, but I'm not sure we have confidence. We took the lead in four
of the last six games and we lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Captain Mark Semioli, who was primarily responsible for
Chicago's winning goal when he slipped in his attempt to clear the
ball at the top of his penalty area, looked dejected as he sat in
front of his locker in the dressing room after the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're at the point where we're a very dispirited team,''
Semioli said. ``We don't seem to find solutions to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Semioli could have added that the MetroStars seem more adept at
finding ways to lose. At least once in every game during the losing
streak someone on defense has made a mistake that has led to a
goal.
</P>
<P>
   Mohammad Khakpour, the Iranian international who is the team's
most consistent defender, is his own most severe critic. He rarely
points fingers at anyone, always blaming the team collectively for
any misfortune. ``We seem to make the same mistake, and we don't
learn,'' Khakpour said. ``When you lose, you have to learn from
mistakes and we don't. I'm as guilty as anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   The artificial turf was most likely the guilty party in the
injury to Curcic, who tore the meniscus in his right knee. There
was no one around him when he was injured, almost the same way that
Wayne Chrebet of the Jets broke his foot Friday night. An official
diagnosis of Curcic's injury will be made after further examination
in a day or two.
</P>
<P>
   When Eduardo Hurtado scored his first goal since May 29 to give
the MetroStars a 1-0 lead in the 60th minute, the pain the
MetroStars and most in the crowd of 8,905 felt for losing Curcic
disappeared. It was the only bright spot of the day for the
MetroStars, who have only one game left here, against San Jose on
Sept. 22.
</P>
<P>
   Dema Kovalenko tied it for the Fire in the 69th minute, 11
minutes after he had entered as a substitute. Lubos Kubik gave
Chicago (15-11), the defending Major League Soccer champion, the
victory in the 73rd minute, when Semioli's slip allowed Kubik to go
in alone on Tim Howard.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
