<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-HOFFARTH-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S NO POWDER-PUFF PLAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Memo to Los Angeles city council folk who continue
to insist they're still lookin' out for our best interests:
Continue your no-public-funding stance with the NFL. That Sept. 15
``drop dead'' deadline next week for a decision will be the perfect
day for us to tell them to drop... y' know... dead.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, we have another pro football proposition that we're
interested in.
</P>
<P>
   Next month, a guy in the Midwest will introduce the Women's
Professional Football League _ WPFL _ starting with two teams, the
Minnesota Vixens and the Lake Michigan Minx.
</P>
<P>
   It's only a $50,000 franchise fee and $15,000 in annual dues.
And if it flies after the first year, they want to expand to six
teams.
</P>
<P>
   Ladies and gentlemen, we present to you: The Los Angeles Lushes.
</P>
<P>
   Our guess is the fine citizens of L.A. will find a way to fund
it. With anonymous, unsolicited donations, of course.
</P>
<P>
   We'll keep you abreast....
</P>
<P>
   Peter King, that Sports Illustrated reporter who butts his way
on for airtime on CNN/SI, was talking about what a waste NFL
exhibition games are and used the example of the St. Louis Rams
losing quarterback Trent Green in a meaningless game against San
Diego two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their owner, Georgia Frontiere made $800k on that preseason
game,'' King pointed out. ``You think she'd give back that $800k to
have their quarterback of the future back?''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia? Nope. She'll just tell Dick Vermeil to try a little
cosmetic surgery on the depth chart....
</P>
<P>
   Before the new Cleveland Browns' opener Sunday, Drew Carey is
going to lead the new Dawg Pound in a version of the ``Cleveland
Rocks'' song and then do the team intros.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it's a game on ESPN. Yes, Carey's show is on ABC....
</P>
<P>
   Seventy-nine of the 114 Division I-A football schools play on
grass fields this year, up from 73 (of 112) last year. Colorado,
Oregon State, UNLV and Vanderbilt switched, and Houston doesn't
play in the Astrodome anymore....
</P>
<P>
   For the going rate of having a free-swinging .235-hitting backup
outfielder for one season, Rupert Murdoch gives $10 mil to help
build a Catholic church.
</P>
<P>
   And you wonder about the Dodgers' priorities....
</P>
<P>
   Richie Phillips has a job, and 22 guys whose best interests he's
supposed to have in mind don't. You make the call....
</P>
<P>
   Marion Jones can run, but she can't hide.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when track and field needs her leadership, she's
quietly quit to prepare for the 2000 Summer Games, which begin in
about 375 days.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Globe track and field writer Barbara Huebner analyzed the
dichotomy that Jones finds herself in. Despite the fact many see
her as ``the potential savior of track and field in the United
States,'' the buzz on the Internet is that she's setting herself up
for failure by proclaiming her intentions to win multiple gold
medals so forthrightly.
</P>
<P>
   Huebner quotes Craig Masback, the CEO of USA Track &AMP; Field:
``She has the opportunity to be the first woman on a global scale
to transcend sport. Pele did it. Muhammad Ali did it. Michael
Jordan did it. No woman has ever done it.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he also points out: ``Marion has no responsibility for
the sport. It's no individual's responsibility to save, rescue,
build, whatever other term you want to use....'' &QL; 
Tom Hoffarth can be reached at sptmediaaol.com or (818) 713-3661.
</P>
</TEXT>
