<SLUG> BC-GEN-YESTERDAY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN IN ROME, DO WHAT JOHNSON DID
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As the year 2000 approaches, here's a look at some
of the interesting anniversaries that will occur this week in Los
Angeles sports history (followed by the ranking of the event from
the book ``Unforgettable: The 100 Greatest Moments in Los Angeles
Sports History'' in parenthesis, where applicable):
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 6, 1960: Former UCLA star Rafer Johnson defeats his best
friend and former Bruins teammate C.K. Yang in the Olympic
decathlon during the Rome Games. Yang, of Taiwan, won seven of the
10 events, but Johnson racked up an Olympic-record 8,392 points to
win by 58 points. Johnson scored easy wins in the shot put, discus
and javelin to make up for the other non-first-place finishes. (41)
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 6, 1970: Before what's believed to be the largest crowd to
see a sporting event in Southern California _ 180,223 _ the
California 500 breaks in the new $25 million speedway 40 miles east
of downtown Los Angeles called the Ontario Motor Speedway. Jim
McElreath wins the race against the likes of Al Unser (who led for
166 laps), Mario Andretti, A.J. Foyt and Dan Gurney.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 6, 1996: The Dodgers' Hideo Nomo throws a 9-0 no-hitter
against the Colorado Rockies in Denver, walking four and striking
out eight _ and pitching from the stretch the entire game to keep
his balance on a rain-drenched night.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 7, 1970: At Del Mar, Bill Shoemaker passes Johnny Longden
on the all-time wins list for jockeys with No. 6,033.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 7, 1957: Los Angeles Angels slugger Steve Bilko pounds out
a team-record 56th home run during a 6-2 Pacific Coast League win
at L.A.'s Wrigley Field (to help pitcher Tom Lasorda pick up the
victory). It was Bilko's final home run for the team. (100)
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 9, 1965: Sandy Koufax throws a perfect game against the
Chicago Cubs, a record fourth no-hitter of his career. He strikes
out 14, including the last six. The Dodgers manage just one hit off
Cubs pitcher Bob Hendley, a bloop double by Lou Johnson in the
seventh inning that doesn't figure in the 1-0 final. (7)
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 10, 1973: In the largest boxing gate ever attained on the
West Coast ($475,640), Muhammad Ali knocks out Ken Norton at the
Forum.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 12, 1970: USC's 42-21 football win over Alabama in
Birmingham is highlighted by a 135-yard, two-TD performance by
fullback Sam Cunningham. The game is credited for helping with the
integration of African-American athletes into Southern football
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Birthdays: Wednesday: Former Kings great Rogie Vachon (54).
Thursday: Former Hart High, UCLA and Dodgers third baseman Todd
Zeile (34). Friday: Former USC pitcher Randy Johnson (36). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
