<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-ROSENTHAL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITAKER'S PICTURE DEVELOPING NICELY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Lance Whitaker's future as a heavyweight contender
seemed a bit clouded only six months ago.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-8, 250-pound Valley-area product was unbeaten when he
was outpointed by capable but limited Lou Savarese on March 6. It
certainly wasn't the step toward a title shot he and his handlers
had hoped for.
</P>
<P>
   However, it was anything but a disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Whitaker (19-1, with 16 knockouts) almost knocked out Savarese
at one point _ something top contender Michael Grant couldn't do _
before running out of gas and points. In the process, he went from
raw prospect to credible heavyweight.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 28, he took another major step, outpointing then
unbeaten and favored Monte Barrett on the undercard of the David
Reid-Keith Mullings card.
</P>
<P>
   OK, Barrett isn't exactly Grant. He (begin ital)is(end ital)
slick and tough, the kind of opponent who could give anyone
difficulty and one who will remain a good prospect. Without
question, it was a significant victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``This puts him right into the heavyweight picture _ with an
exclamation point,'' said Dan Goossen of America Presents,
Whitaker's promoter.
</P>
<P>
   Whitaker's handlers were pleased not only with the victory but
(begin ital)how(end ital) he pulled it off.
</P>
<P>
   Learning from the Savarese fight, he paced himself and was able
to go the distance easily. He fought well defensively _ ``Barrett
never put a mark on him,'' his trainer, Joe Goossen, said. And he
came on strong in the 12th and final round to solidify his victory,
the sign of an in-shape, gutsy fighter.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, Whitaker still is developing. He seems to have lapses
in concentration, he doesn't throw his right hand enough and,
having fought just 20 times, he generally lacks the savvy of an
experienced boxer.
</P>
<P>
   However, he might be the strongest heavyweight in the world. He
has the punching style and much of the power of George Foreman, and
the former San Fernando High basketball player has more athletic
ability than people realize.
</P>
<P>
   On top of that, he's beginning to believe anything is possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lance seriously boosted his confidence,'' Joe Goossen said.
``Going into the Savarese fight, I think Lance had a few questions
about his own abilities and answered them in that fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, especially after the Barrett fight, he knows he belongs
in the race for the heavyweight championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitaker, as taciturn as they come, downplayed the victory over
Barrett, saying ``It's OK, it's a victory.''
</P>
<P>
   That's another good sign. It means he's able to gauge his
progress realistically and understands there is a lot of work
ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was good because I went 12 rounds,'' he said. ``But I'm not
really happy about my performance. I know I could do a lot better.
It's a learning experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``... I'm not fighting at the level I should be. I'm going on
athletic ability, I'm punching with my arms instead of with my
whole body. I think it'll be pretty scary when I fight like I
should be fighting.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Goossen said he'd like Whitaker to fight on the undercard of
Mike Tyson-Orlin Norris on Oct. 23. Jorge Luis Gonzalez, another
hulking heavyweight, is a possible opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Whitaker would rather face a high-profile opponent ``who could
do something for my career.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the winner of the Grant-Andrew Golota fight scheduled for
Nov. 20, which Dan Goossen hopes to arrange?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, something like that sounds good. That would definitely
put me near the top.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Lennox Lewises and Evander Holyfields might be after
that....
</P>
<P>
   More Whitaker: Main Events, which promotes frightening
heavyweight David Tua, has proposed a Tua-Whitaker matchup.
</P>
<P>
   However, make no mistake: No right-thinking heavyweight with
aspirations of winning a world title would choose to go through the
immensely powerful Tua to get there.
</P>
<P>
   Tua might be the best out there....
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya-Trinidad: Oscar De La Hoya, who faces Felix Trinidad
in a welterweight title-unification bout Sept. 18 in Las Vegas, has
had his distractions. Between personal appearances and his business
interests, it's a wonder he's been able to focus on boxing.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, he admits, he hasn't been the hungry fighter he was
early in his career.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he said, the feeling is back.
</P>
<P>
   ``It depends on the fight,'' he said.``For instance, for this
fight, since it's such a big, major event, I'm hungry again. It's a
matter of being motivated.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you go through so much the way I have, activities outside
boxing, you seem not to worry as much as you used to about
training. I seem to worry more about the future, things other than
boxing.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I wanted this fight so bad: It's made me refocus.''
</P>
<P>
   The right stuff?: De La Hoya, a natural left-hander, admits he
contradicts himself when he makes references to strategy. He
doesn't want anyone to know what he's up to.
</P>
<P>
   However, it wasn't difficult to see through comments he made
recently when asked why he doesn't throw many right-handed punches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a one-handed fighter,'' he tried to say seriously. ``It's
been proven in the past. My right hand hasn't really served me well
in a fight. I don't even use it. I would use it maybe just to
measure a guy up.
</P>
<P>
   ``My left hand I guess is the key to victory in this fight. I'm
not thinking about my right hand. It's just there.''
</P>
<P>
   Think Trinidad will catch a few rights?
</P>
<P>
   If he loses: De La Hoya, like any fighter, doesn't like to
recognize the possibility of a loss against Trinidad.
</P>
<P>
   However, he doesn't believe it would hinder his popularity if it
happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it would affect me in any way whatsoever because
of the marketing we've done, the foundation I've built for
myself,'' he said. ``I don't see anybody or any one of my sponsors
not wanting to be with me anymore because I have one loss.''
</P>
<P>
   Predictions: Trinidad has predicted he will knock out De La
Hoya. How does De La Hoya see it?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be satisfied with any win,'' he said. ``Whatever it takes
to win, I'm going to do. If it has to go the distance, let it be.
</P>
<P>
   ``... I'd be (begin ital)more satisfied, of course, with a
knockout.''
</P>
<P>
   Rabbit punches: Unbeaten junior welterweight sensation Zab Judah
is expected to fight a 10-rounder on the the Tyson-Norris
undercard. His opponent is yet to be determined....
</P>
<P>
   Former light-heavyweight champion Eddie Mustafa Muhammad, 47,
told the Philadelphia Inquirer he will fight 49-year-old Larry
Holmes in November. Muhammad hasn't fought since 1990. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Staff Writer Michael Rosenthal's boxing column appears Mondays
in the Daily News. He can be reached at (818) 713-3606 or on the
Internet at boxwriteraol.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
