<SLUG> BC-BKN-HILL-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STERLING TIGHT WITH CLIPPERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Donald T. Sterling had subsidized the Donner Party, an
unexpected Stuckey's sighting would have been followed by orders to
keep walking.
</P>
<P>
   Is the Clippers' owner really that tight with his loot? Well,
when it comes to basketball budgeting, witnesses say the man could
make a dollar holler. His seeming belief that NBA scoreboards
record decimal points has made the smart people in his organization
look dumber than a bag of hammers.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Sterling's ownership trip will reach a fork in the
road to nowhere. But there (ital)will(end ital) be an arrow
indicating an upcoming ramp to salvation. Sterling will be asked to
take it and dig deep. He'll be encouraged to grant one employee a
contract extension worth $70.9 million over six years. That would
have bought enough pecan rolls to keep the Donners from exchanging
funny looks before they were rescued.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, the aforementioned Clipper employee is power forward
Maurice Taylor, the resident go-to guy whose new agent has
threatened to make Taylor a guy going to another team if Sterling
refuses to cough up the league maximum.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor's new agent, by the way, is the mighty David Falk. And
calling Falk's bluff seems to be as wise as playing chicken with a
Pinto in reverse gear. If Falk had negotiated the Louisiana
Purchase, Memphis and New Orleans would be located in the same
state. Siccing him on Sterling is about as sporting as bringing
along Godzilla to fight a parking ticket.
</P>
<P>
   But Falk has promised that Wednesday's meeting with Sterling
will include no negotiating. If Sterling, as expected, puts the
burden of proof on another season from Taylor (who's in the final
year of his initial three-year NBA deal) before making an offer,
Falk will request a trade.
</P>
<P>
   If Taylor isn't traded, he'll be the lame-duck ringleader of a
gifted frontcourt that includes center Michael Olowokandi and
rookie phenom-in-waiting Lamar Odom. When the season is over, Falk
will take Taylor and his potential into a market where teams - at
this moment - are clearing space in the dusty garages of their
salary cap calculators. Chicago and Orlando have prepared to have
spending money with Tim Duncan and Grant Hill in mind, but when
they strike out on those two, Taylor will be on deck.
</P>
<P>
   And the Clippers, with no sign-and-trade leverage, will have a
grief index that's off the charts.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, did we just unleash the ``P'' word? Yeah, we did. Here it is
again: potential.
</P>
<P>
   That's what Falk and Taylor are selling. As any fan who's
blinded by financial jealousy will tell you, the 16.8 points and
5.3 rebounds ``Mo'' provided last season are not worth 70.9 million
scoots. But his potential for 20-plus and 8 - year after year --
is. His status as a scoring threat who can maximize the collateral
talents of Odom and Olowokandi is.
</P>
<P>
   Potential is a requisite risk. This is basketball, not condo
sales. Without taking a risk that's mitigated by informed talent
evaluation, you'll never own a contending team. However, you will
save enough chump change to buy goodies and impress your celebrity
cronies in a luxury closet at the Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   But some of the credit for the Clippers' dilemma should be
handed to Taylor. He's the kid who reported to their last training
camp in a condition that promoted lingering injury and an energy
deficit when rebounds were required. Mo's sickly rebounding ratio
is one of the cagey Sterling's convenient reasons for being
reluctant to make him rich.
</P>
<P>
   So if Sterling decides the fork in his road has been stained by
pie, the Clippers' future could be doomed.
</P>
<P>
   Preparing for Bull run
</P>
<P>
   If you think all professional athletes are lucky, lackadaisical,
cash machines, you've never met former Long Beach State star James
Cotton.
</P>
<P>
   Cotton, who was acquired with Hersey Hawkins by the Chicago
Bulls in the deal that shipped Brent Barry to Seattle, has been
haunting the Veteran's Park SportsComplex gym in preparation for
his third NBA season.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I need,'' said Cotton, ``is a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   He may get one in Chicago, where hometown hero Hawkins figures
to start ahead of Cotton at shooting guard. But Hawkins' mileage
and Cotton's capacity for hard work could provide the opportunity
he didn't get in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the full-court morning runs, Cotton often leads
the Vet regulars in game-speed shooting drills.
</P>
<P>
   He also reports that younger brother Schea, the prize of
Alabama's stellar recruiting class, loves Tuscaloosa.
</P>
<P>
   Absolute Condition
</P>
<P>
   A. C. Green, the newest old Laker, has been working out at the
Vet and appears to be in splendid shape. Although his Dallas
numbers seem dangerously pedestrian, Green's knowledge of what
needs to be done - on and off the court -- should make him a key
acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   Another Laker grapevine item involves a proposed reunion between
Phil Jackson and Ron Harper. The drum-beating has gotten a bit
louder. Harp, you recall, did a swell job defending point guards
for Jackson in Chicago, but won't have Michael Jordan or Scottie
Pippen to provide defensive help in L.A.
</P>
<P>
   We're not sure where Jerry West, the Lakers' V.P. of hoop
maneuvers, weighs in on this, but a source close to Harper said the
ex-Clipper would love to return to L.A.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers still have both exceptions available, but are
expected to use the $2 million slot to woo someone who can start at
power forward.
</P>
<P>
   Add Clippers
</P>
<P>
   The search for someone to compete with Troy Hudson at point
guard continues. The Clippers took a big swing at acquiring the
rights to Steve Francis, Vancouver's broken-hearted draft pick, but
the Houston Rockets were able to muster what the Grizzlies
considered a better deal. ... The hunt for a backup center also
continues, although the Clips were impressed with last week's
audition by 7-foot Zan Tabak, a skilled Croatian who's done NBA
time in Houston and Toronto.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-99 2110EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
