<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-KEISSER-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAC-10 STUMBLES OUT OF GATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today's well-packaged edition of The Sporting Muse:
</P>
<P>
   The Pac-10's slip is showing.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, USC and UCLA won their openers Saturday by a combined score
of 100-14, and Arizona should feel no shame (OK, maybe a litle) in
stumbling in State College (Pa.), and the conference will never be
judged by the ability of Stanford and Washington State to win
games.
</P>
<P>
   But clearly, this isn't the same conference that whipped the Big
Ten champ in the Rose Bowl game 19 out of 23 times between 1970 and
1992 and annually shared the distinct of best conference with the
SEC.
</P>
<P>
   The Pac-10 appears to be feeling the negative effects of too
much parity and too many coaching changes.
</P>
<P>
   Five different teams have played in the Rose Bowl the last five
years (Arizona State, Oregon, UCLA, USC and Washington State), nine
of ten teams have bowled in the last three seasons, and seven
different teams have won a bowl game dating back to 1995.
</P>
<P>
   This is all good if you're judging a league by its depth. Back
in the good old days, before all this BCS (Bowl Championship
Series) nonsense and rush to have a faux national champ, the sense
of great competition week in, week out, was more than enough.
</P>
<P>
   But the emphasis now is on the 20 or so teams who start a season
with a kernal of belief that they're going to contend for a major
bowl and maybe a national title. And it is very hard to do that
when talent in the west has been more evenly dispersed, when every
school can tell recruits that the Rose Bowl, or at least a bowl
game, is withing reach.
</P>
<P>
   What's better, the Pac-10 sending six teams to bowl games in
1997, or the Atlantic Coast Conference getting reams of publicity
and residual respect with Florida State being a national title
conetnder every year?
</P>
<P>
   If the best Pac-10 teams had maintained their focus in the big
games, the conference might be enjoying the best of both college
football worlds, like the SEC, which seems to send seven teams to
bowls every year while also producing national champs (Tennessee,
Florida).
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Pac-10 teams are losing the big games. The Big Ten has
won six of the last seven Rose Bowl games. Last year, UCLA gagged
against Miami and Washington was embarrassed by a mediocre Nebraska
team. The last big non-conference win by a Pac-10 team was Arizona
State's upset of Nebraska in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't make one very confident of UCLA's visit to Columbus
next week. ...
</P>
<P>
   Seven of the ten Pac-10 head coaches have also been on the job
for four years or less, too. And among the coaches moving on in the
last have been Terry Donahue, the Pac-10's all-time leader in wins;
John Robinson and Bill Walsh, in their second tours at USC and
Stanford; and Steve Mariucci (Cal), Mike Riley (Oregon State), and
Rich Brooks (Oregon), who ran off to the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   This turnover has less to do with the quality of the men hired
as much as the turnover it causes on coaching staffs. It's
difficult to create continuity in the recruiting world when new
head coaches hire new staffs. ...
</P>
<P>
   It also doesn't help that Pac-10 athletic directors are now
following the time-honored tradition of whipped cream scheduling.
Arizona-Penn State and UCLA-Ohio State are exceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Every team except Washington has at least one gimmes this year.
They include Boise State (UCLA), Hawaii (USC), Idaho (Washington
State), Middle Tennessee (Arizona), Nevada (Oregon, Oregon State),
New Mexico State (Arizona State), Rutgers (Cal), San Jose State
(Stanford), UTEP (Arizona, Oregon), and SW Louisiana (Washington
State).
</P>
<P>
   Second tier opponents include TCU, Texas Tech, Division I-AA
power Georgia Southern, Fresno State and San Diego State. Three
schools (USC, Stanford and Arizona State) will play Notre Dame. ...
</P>
<P>
   I will hold off on assessing the ability of UCLA quarterback
Cory Paus and USC's offense in general until they play teams with
more filling than an oreo. As opponents, Boise State and Hawaii
defy accurate analysis.
</P>
<P>
   But it was encouraging to see a dozen different Bruins catch a
pass. I even saw a few Bruins on defense actually make a tackle.
USC quarterback Carson Palmer also had a horde of quick receivers,
too. ...
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to beat the rush, here's my early Heisman ballot:
1, Wide receiver Peter Warrick, Florida State. 2, Quarterback Joe
Hamilton, Georgia Tech. 3, Quarterback Drew Brees, Purdue.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Dayne is obviously missing. My problem with the Wisconsin
back is all of the residual attention he is getting because he
might break Ricky Williams' career rushing record. The Heisman
shouldn't be a life achievement award.
</P>
<P>
   Dayne's a great bull of a runner, but he's piled up a lot of his
career yards against non-conference and Big Ten cupcakes, and I've
seen him exit a lot of big games with injuries. ...
</P>
<P>
   Memo to Bob Toledo: Do not, under any circumstance, let DeShaun
Foster, Danny Farmer and Freddie Mitchell play a single down of
defense, as they did Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   I understand the Bruins are shorthanded on defense, and the
defense-offense bickering of last year might be overcome by this
all-for-one philosophy. But risking your top tailback and two best
receivers to the whims of tackling is just stupid. Especially this
week against Ohio State. If Foster gets hurts playing defense
against the Buckeyes, Toledo can skip the plane trip home. ...
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-99 2111EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990905.0174 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-05 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
