<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAUTHIER READIES THE DUCKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- Only the shadows really know Pierre Gauthier and
that's justfine with the Mighty Ducks president and general manager
as he prepares hishockey team for another season.
</P>
<P>
   The way Gauthier sees it, a GM has a job to do and nowhere in
thedescription does it state he should be the focus of attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``The players and coaches are the heroes,'' he said. ``The
players are theones people pay to come and see, not me. A general
manager shouldn't be upfront and center.''
</P>
<P>
   Gauthier certainly can never be accussed of being an attention
grabber. Hewas dubbed ``The Ghost'' in Ottawa, where where he
helped turn around aSenators team that had been the laughing stock
of the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was just always in the background,'' said Ottawa president
Roy Malkar.``But he's very observant.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing has changed in Anaheim. Gauthier happily remains in the
shadows, butthere's no doubt whose vision the Ducks represent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key issue with a GM is vision,'' said Tony Tavares, the
president ofDisney Sports Inc. who stepped aside as Ducks president
when he hiredGauthier on July 16, 1998. ``Pierre can develop a
vision, be honest about thetalent and he sticks with his plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many (GM's) don't have a vision, they live day-to-day,
hour-to-hourjust plugging holes.''
</P>
<P>
   Gauthier had more than his share of holes to fill. Anaheim was
coming off a33-46-5 season and had just fired coach Pierre Page
after not renewing RonWilson's contract the previous spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were in disarray,'' said Tavares, who says his relationship
can best bedescribed as ``when you trust somebody, you don't bother
second guessing.''
</P>
<P>
   Left alone to put the pieces back together, Gauthier took the
1998-99 Ducksand asssembled a team that he entrusted to coach new
Craig Hartsburg, who wasallowed to run it without interference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in delegating, really delegating,'' Gauthier said.
``(General)managers manage, coaches coach, players play, scouts run
the draft . . . Imight say `draft the best guy.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Gauthier feels he must keep his distance from the players,
especially abouttheir performance. Last year, he addressed the team
once -- during a slump,to let the players know that he was not
planning any big moves and that hebelieved in them.
</P>
<P>
   But he did so only after getting Hartsburg's permission and
jokes ``Iprobably won't talk again for five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coach is the boss of the team,'' he explained. ``I never
go over hishead.''
</P>
<P>
   Gauthier was an assistant GM with the Ducks under Jack Ferreira
beforetaking the Ottawa job in December of 1995, a move that
Tavares said leftDisney chairman ``heartbroken.''
</P>
<P>
   After turning the Senators into a playoff team, Gauthier left a
lot ofpeople in the Canadian capital heartbroken and upset -- to
say the least.Members of the Ottawa media all but called Gauthier a
liar, a con man andsaid his integrity was lacking when he quit, due
to personal reasons,returned to Southern California and shortly
thereafter was hired by Tavares.To make things even tougher he then
replaced his longtime friend andassociate Ferreira as the GM.
</P>
<P>
   Mlakar was critcized when he didn't ask for any compensation --
something hedid do when Gauthier's replacement, Rick Dudley, left
to go to Tampa Bay thissummer.
</P>
<P>
   But the former Kings executivesaid there was no reason to askfor
any, especially since he feltnothing underhanded was doneby the
Ducks or Gauthier.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Mlakar said when askedif he felt betrayed. ``There
isabsolutely no way Tony Ta-vares would ever do anythingbehind my
back.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of my best friends,my kids call him Uncle Tony.''
</P>
<P>
   Mlakar also said there is noreason for people to doubt
Gau-thier's integrity.
</P>
<P>
   ``He turned things around (inOttawa), but he knew long term(he
wanted to get away),'' saidMlakar. ``He had a vision onand off the
ice.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened is betweenPierre Gauthier and I, it's no-body
business. (But) I know Ican look in the mirror and seetwo things,
first, I'm bald, andsecond that Pierre Gauthier isstand-up guy and
class act.''
</P>
<P>
   High praise from a man whojokingly admits the two hadvery little
in common.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a relationship based onbusiness,'' Mlakar said. ``I'm
aDiet Coke fanatic, he doesn'tlike soda . . . He likes choco-late,
I don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Gauthier said he knew hewould ``take some hits'' afterbeing
hired by the Ducks andadmits, ``I probably set myselfup.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I shouldn't have said sostrongly I wouldn't come to
An-aheim,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But once he took over in Ana-heim it wasn't long before
Gau-thier began to put his stamp onthe team in his usual,
subtleways.
</P>
<P>
   He made no blockbuster tradesor acquistions. Instead, he
dealtinconsistent defenseman DavidKarpa and a draft pick to
Caro-lina for defenseman Kevin Hal-ler and Stu Grimson.
</P>
<P>
   The move worked on two lev-els. Haller's veteran leadershipwas
critical as the Ducks at-tempted to improve their de-fense. Tough
guy and fan favor-ite Grimson, along with JimMcKenzie, who Ferreira
ac-quired from Phoenix earlier inthe summer, provided somemuch
needed security for PaulKariya and Teemu Selanne.
</P>
<P>
   He then picked up free agentFredrik Olausson at a bargainprice
and the defensemanhelped transform the Anaheimpower play to the
best in theleague.
</P>
<P>
   The moves may not have satis-fied the media and fans at thetime,
but ignoring outside pres-sure is one of Gauthier's greatstrengths,
according to Tavares.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of pressure to an-alyze and second guess
execu-tives, but he is totally unaffect-ed by that,'' said Tavares.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, Gauthier quietlyand efficiently dealt with all
ofthe important contract negotia-tions, especially Paul Kariya's.He
also tried to shore up Ana-heim's most pressing need --skill on
defense -- by acquiringformer Duck Oleg Tverdovsky,drafting veteran
Swedish EliteLeague defenseman Niclas Hav-elid and getting former
first-round pick Vitaly Vishnevskysigned. He also traded for
for-ward Ted Donato.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it's Gauthier's abilityto tune out outside
influencesthat cause some to call him``reclusive, aloof,
detached,Pierre Grouchy.''
</P>
<P>
   They are labels that Mlakarthinks are totally unfair.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd like make you think hedidn't have a heart, but he hasa
huge heart,'' Mlakar said.``Just ask about his childrenand wife.''
</P>
<P>
   Tavares admits Gauthier, whomight not say a word to a per-son
the night after talking ex-citedly about a movie like``Shakespere
In Love,'' can bein his own world, especiallywhen things aren't
going well.But Tavares quickly adds itmostly ``comes from being
adeep thinker. He's really abright guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Gauthier, who realizedhe wasn't going to be an
NHLcaliber player at an early age,has a masters degree in
sportsadministration and was takingclasses toward his doctorate
upuntil the time he was namedhead scout of the Quebec Nor-diques in
1988. Gauthier stillenjoys the academic setting andcould see
himself teaching afterhis career as a GM comes to anend.
</P>
<P>
   But right now Gauthier's dutiespretty much consume him 365days a
year and don't leavehim much time for much else.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife always said scoutingwas the best because when youwere
home you were home,'' hesaid. ``Management is 365 daysa year, there
are no holidays.''
</P>
<P>
   INFO BOX
</P>
<P>
   AGE: 46
</P>
<P>
   BIRTHPLACE: Montreal
</P>
<P>
   FAMILY: Wife (Manon), daugh-ter (Catherine), son (Vincent).
</P>
<P>
   HOBBIES: Movies, jazz andblues music, running, swim-ming.
</P>
<P>
   NHL EXPERIENCE: Scout: Que-bec 1983-93; Assistant GM:Ducks
1993-95, GM: Ottawa:1995-1998; GM/President: Ducks1998-present.
</P>
