<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-05 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1723 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-CONVICT-FATE-2TAKES-K     09-05 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONVICT-FATE-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEATH PENALTY CASE WAS STRUGGLE FOR FATE OF A SMOOTH-TALKING
EX-CONVICT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY RIZZO  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Browning's police radio crackled with typical
emergency-worker jargon: ``A nonbreather with extended downtime.''
</P>
<P>
   In plain English, it meant someone probably was dead.
</P>
<P>
   It was midmorning on April 26, 1998, a Sunday. Browning, a field
sergeant and shift supervisor for the Lenexa Police Department in
Johnson County, Kan., was dispatched to the Howard Johnson Express.
</P>
<P>
   The paramedics who met him outside Room 207 said the woman
inside had been dead for some time. A hotel housecleaning crew had
found her in the tub.
</P>
<P>
   Browning walked into the bathroom. She was a slender white
woman, nude, lying on her back. Her long brown hair covered her
face.
</P>
<P>
   Bruises were plainly visible on her torso, legs and arms.
Browning put a finger on her thigh. It was cold to the touch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go down to the front desk and find out who the room is
registered to,'' he told another officer.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation into Claire-Marie Monti's death had just
begun.
</P>
<P>
   It would develop into one of the most complex and hard-fought
murder cases in recent Johnson County history _ a literal
life-and-death struggle for the fate of Carl Dean Rails, a
smooth-talking ex-convict with a violent temper.
</P>
<P>
   The case ended last month after 16 months of acrimonious court
hearings, mountains of legal paperwork and a last-minute blowup
that nearly derailed Rails' plea agreement.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 27, at the age of 36, Rails quietly accepted his fate
and was sentenced to spend the rest of his life in prison. His
guilty plea allowed him to avoid a possible death sentence.
</P>
<P>
   A second defendant, Rails' co-worker Rodney Wayne Henry, was
convicted in May of first-degree murder, rape and aggravated
sodomy. He must serve about 68 years in prison before he can even
think about parole.
</P>
<P>
   For District Attorney Paul Morrison, the decision to accept
Rails' plea agreement was one of the most difficult of his career.
Morrison has consistently lauded the death penalty as a powerful
tool to induce guilty pleas and life sentences.
</P>
<P>
   But, comparing it to the nation's nuclear deterrent, he said it
could only be effective if people know you are not afraid to use
it.
</P>
<P>
   The two previous cases in which Morrison had filed capital
murder charges also ended in guilty pleas and life sentences. But
Rails was different from either of those defendants, who had little
or no criminal history.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Dean Rails once shot a man in the face with a shotgun.
Later, when told that his victim had survived, Rails said he wished
he had gone back and finished the job.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, he was out of prison and working as a foreman for a
remodeling company. When a customer refused to pay, Rails and his
boss clogged the customer's plumbing with a hidden piece of chicken
wire.
</P>
<P>
   ``An old contractor's trick,'' Rails' boss testified.
</P>
<P>
   When a previous employer fired him, Rails broke into his
business and stole all his power tools.
</P>
<P>
   Monti was a smart, ambitious 32-year-old woman working for a
computer software company in suburban Philadelphia. She was in
Kansas City, Mo., to train employees of a business in Lenexa, a
Kansas City suburb.
</P>
<P>
   Their paths crossed on April 25, 1998, on a sidewalk in
Westport, a Kansas City entertainment district. Rails was with
Henry, his younger drinking buddy and co-worker.
</P>
<P>
   Monti was alone, a stranger in town, looking to pass a Saturday
night dancing and listening to music.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen hours after their chance meeting, Monti's battered body
was found in her hotel room.
</P>
<P>
   The killers were smart enough to wipe fingerprints off
everything in the room, soak Monti's body in hot water to degrade
DNA samples, and take towels and bedding from the room and burn
them in a trash bin.
</P>
<P>
   They were stupid enough to tell their boss what they had done.
</P>
<P>
   When detectives got Henry alone, he crumpled. With a video
camera running, he spun a tale of Monti's last terrifying moments
of life and her death at the hands, he said, of Carl Rails.
</P>
<P>
   It was a story of unprovoked brutality. Rails mercilessly beat
Monti as she begged for her life. He strangled her until his hands
got tired. And then he defiled her lifeless body with the leg of a
metal luggage rack.
</P>
<P>
   Henry said his role was minimal. Afraid to defy his
out-of-control friend, Henry said, he helped Rails restrain Monti
and then dispose of evidence because he was afraid of what might
happen to him.
</P>
<P>
   When detectives questioned Rails, he provided few details but
conceded that he had choked Monti.
</P>
<P>
   Morrison didn't believe much of Henry's version, but he believed
enough to make Rails the third person to face capital murder
charges in Johnson County since Kansas reinstated the death penalty
in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Henry was charged with first-degree murder.
</P>
<P>
   A Johnson County jury didn't believe much of Henry's story
either. On May 11, he was found guilty and subsequently sentenced
to life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   From a legal standpoint, it was a typical case. Defense attorney
Scott Gyllenborg filed motions to suppress evidence. Hearings were
conducted and the judge made his rulings.
</P>
<P>
   But Rails' case was quite different. It was a point his
attorneys were to make again and again: A death penalty case is a
legal animal unlike any other.
</P>
<P>
   Rails was represented by two lawyers from the Kansas Death
Penalty Defense Unit, Ben Wood and Jeff Moots.
</P>
<P>
   Wood made it clear early in the case that everything he did was
with an eye toward how it would be seen by an appeals court 10
years in the future if Rails were indeed convicted and sentenced to
die.
</P>
<P>
   No issue, no matter how minor, would be handled informally.
Everything would be in writing and on the record.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to strap my client to a gurney and pump poison into
his veins,'' he said on several occasions as he paced and pointed
at a seated Rails.
</P>
<P>
   If there was a legal issue that could be conceived, he and Moots
conceived it. If the credibility of a witness could be cracked,
they would dig deep into his past to do it.
</P>
<P>
   They came at the case from every angle:
</P>
<P>
   - They used an argument of ``reverse inference.'' If a
pathologist failed to save a crucial piece of Monti's body as
evidence that she had been sexually assaulted, then the judge
should find the exact opposite of what the doctor said the evidence
showed.
</P>
<P>
   - They invoked the words of Pope John Paul II and argued that
the death penalty violated the ``evolving standards of world
decency.''
</P>
<P>
   - They provided the results of a North Carolina study showing
that imprisoning someone for life is more cost-effective than
executing them.
</P>
<P>
   - And they obtained an order from the judge to keep the district
attorney from going closer than 10 feet to Rails during trial. They
accused Morrison of ``basic primate aggression'' during Henry's
trial when he tossed a box of facial tissue to Henry.
</P>
<P>
   All told, the defense filed more than 60 motions and promised to
file more than 100. A retired judge was brought in to handle some
of District Judge Peter Ruddick's caseload so he could devote time
to the Rails case.
</P>
<P>
   Hearings, occasionally punctuated with angry outbursts, were
held every few weeks. A tentative trial date was not scheduled
until next January.
</P>
<P>
   A particularly contentious hearing took place on Feb. 18.
</P>
<P>
   Rails wanted his pubic hair back.
</P>
<P>
   Wood argued that the state had no probable cause to collect hair
samples from Rails earlier in the case. He accused prosecutors of
going on a ``fishing expedition'' for evidence or simply harassing
Rails by ``ripping out his pubic hair.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that they had been unable to match Rails' samples with those
found on a towel in the hotel room, Wood said, the hair should be
given back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since a portion of our client's body was taken improperly, we
ask that it be returned to the defense,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Morrison countered that such evidence collection is standard
procedure in cases of possible sexual assault. Morrison noted that
a head hair found at the scene did match Rails' hair.
</P>
<P>
   Wood promised that would be the subject of a future motion.
</P>
<P>
   He conceded that Rails' presence in Monti's room was not in
dispute, ``according to most of the evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   He also took a shot at the science of hair analysis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to insult voodoo by comparing it to hair
analysis, but hair analysis is not valid science,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Things got testy when Wood addressed a defense motion seeking
information about the problems of a witness in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Responding, Morrison described the motion as character
assassination. When he referred to the defense team as ``that
crew,'' Moots exploded from his chair, yelling ``I am not a crew.''
He kept objecting loudly until Ruddick threatened to leave the
courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing lasted two hours.
</P>
<P>
   The Rails defense team tendered its first serious plea offer
shortly before Henry went to trial in May. But his offer to plead
guilty and serve a sentence of life with no chance of parole for 40
years was quickly rejected by Morrison.
</P>
<P>
   It was only after Henry was convicted and sentenced that Rails
made the offer that Morrison couldn't refuse.
</P>
<P>
   The district attorney later said that Rails ``went belly up.''
He agreed to plead guilty to all charges and not contest the
doubling of state guideline sentences.
</P>
<P>
   He traded the possibility of a few years on death row and a date
with the state executioner for the certainty of the rest of his
life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Morrison accepted the deal, with the support of Monti's family.
</P>
<P>
   But one last problem cropped up on Aug. 12 _ the day Rails was
supposed to enter his guilty plea. The defense wanted to do both
the plea and sentencing that day.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, plea and sentencing hearings are conducted
separately. Morrison said no to the defense proposal. Monti's
parents, who live in Pennsylvania, wanted to be present for the
sentencing.
</P>
<P>
   A meeting between the attorneys in the judge's chambers ended
abruptly when the door flew open and Ruddick told Wood to leave
until he could cool off.
</P>
<P>
   The judge recessed the case until later that afternoon. Morrison
left the defense with one option to mull over _ a plea that day, or
the deal was off the table.
</P>
<P>
   Two hours later Rails walked into the courtroom and quietly
entered his plea.
</P>
<P>
   ``We dug our heels in,'' Morrison said. ``We had given him his
break. That was letting him live. Every other detail was
non-negotiable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
