<HEADLINE>
NEWS EXECUTIVE LEAVING IT BEHIND FOR BASEBALL LIFE  
 UNEXPECTED SUCCESS FOR REPRINT SERIES  
 MAGAZINE LETS PHOTOGRAPHERS SHOOT BACK 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Bylines follow individual items.) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``It's fun to be a small-town editor, especially when you own
the newspaper,'' Michael Gartner observed last week. ``You can say
any damn thing you want. You see these young people come and you
see them every day and you try to inoculate them with your values
and you take great pride when they move up. Plus writing the
editorials _ it's more fun than one person should have.''
</P>
<P>
   So why is the 60-year-old Gartner, a longtime big-time newspaper
editor and a former head of NBC News, giving it all up? Why is he
selling The Tribune _ the 10,000-circulation newspaper in Ames,
Iowa, that he has edited for six years and owned for 13 _ and
becoming a full-time baseball executive?
</P>
<P>
   Well, when it comes to writing for newspapers, Gartner has done
all right. He won a Pulitzer Prize for his editorial writing in
1997. He was the page-one editor at The Wall Street Journal in the
early 1970s and later the editor of The Des Moines Register.
</P>
<P>
   But owning them, or trying to, has been problematic. When he
tried to buy The Des Moines Register while he was serving as its
president in 1985, he was outbid by Gannett Co. Now, he said, the
death of a partner, David Belin, and the tax consequences for
Belin's family ``made it clear we were going to have to sell.''
</P>
<P>
   So sometime this fall, Gartner will be leaving the profession he
has worked in since the 1950s, and going into a whole new line of
work as part-owner of the Iowa Cubs, the Triple-A minor-league
franchise of the Chicago Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   Gartner has been The Tribune's editor since he resigned as
president of NBC News in 1993, following the revelation that _
unbeknownst to him _ an explosion of a General Motors pickup truck
videotaped for use in a ``Dateline'' program had been staged.
</P>
<P>
   He returned to Ames, the college town 35 miles north of Des
Moines where he and The Tribune's publisher, Gary Gerlach, had
teamed with Belin in 1986 to buy the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   An article in the American Journalism Review describes his
posting of the text of the First Amendment and quotations of Thomas
Jefferson on the newsroom walls, and he went on to secure jobs for
alumni of the 20-person editorial staff on newspapers like The
Baltimore Sun, The St. Petersburg Times, USA Today and The New York
Times.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief interview, Gartner said he did not yet know how his
life was going to change once he was out of the business. ``I've
never run a baseball team,'' he said. ``I expect to have fun and
enjoy myself.'' He said he had played a little baseball long ago.
Then, with a trace of self-consciousness, he delivered a line he
has used before, a sound bite that he recognizes is virtually
irresistible to a journalist.
</P>
<P>
   ``My problem as a shortstop,'' he said, ``is the same problem as
I had as an editorial writer. I couldn't go to my right.''
</P>
<P>
   _ FELICITY BARRINGER
</P>
<P>
   An Unexpected Success for a Reprint Series
</P>
<P>
   The New York Review of Books has vowed to reach a wider audience
than the usual intellectuals with its new book-publishing venture,
which salvages out-of-print classics. So far, 12 titles have been
published in sleek paperback editions, including vanished titles by
Chekhov and Henry James.
</P>
<P>
   But so far the most popular rescue has been a lost stray from
the 1950s that is drawing reviews from the venerable literary
critics at Dog World and The Bark magazines.
</P>
<P>
   The book, J.R. Ackerley's ``My Dog Tulip,'' has merited a
chapter excerpt and a review from Dr. Dog in The Bark, a canine
quarterly based in Berkeley, Calif., that likes to consider itself
The New Yorker of dog magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Ackerley, the late literary editor for the BBC's weekly
magazine, The Listener, wrote a wry portrait of his 16 years with
Tulip, an occasionally willful but loyal German shepherd that he
rescued and indulged and worried over, seeing to her selection of
proper mates and delivery of eight pups.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were looking for books that had a certain reputation, but
we wanted books that weren't standard school curriculum books,
books that could surprise people and look at things in unusual
ways,'' said Edwin Frank, the editor of the series. But the
surprise was that ``My Dog Tulip'' was already something of a cult
favorite for people who were elated by its reappearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thrilled; I was so excited,'' said Claudia Kawczynska,
the editor and publisher of Bark, which is offering the excerpt in
its fall literary issue. ``There are a lot of books on dogs being
published on the canine theme, but this one is so special. It comes
from such a deep understanding of the animal.''
</P>
<P>
   In coming months, The New York York Review of Books is planning
to publish additional rescued titles. Naturally the list includes
J.R. Ackerley's ``We Think the World of You.'' Tulip has no place
in this novel, but there is a beautiful, neglected German shepherd
named Evie.
</P>
<P>
   _ DOREEN CARVAJAL
</P>
<P>
   Magazine Lets Photographers Shoot Back
</P>
<P>
   If you were a photographer, you might think it would be nice to
have Time, Rolling Stone and Vogue on your resume.
</P>
<P>
   But you might also find it makes your life miserable, according
to Photo District News magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Which magazines are naughty and which magazines are nice?''
asks the September cover story of PDN, as it is known. The monthly,
which caters to the New York photography market, asked 100
photographers who regularly work for consumer magazines which
titles were terrific to shoot for and which were, well, lousy.
</P>
<P>
   The magazines that got a vigorous thumbs-down included Vogue
(photographers cited a ``lack of creative freedom''), Rolling Stone
(``bad paper stock and insensitive art direction''), Time
(photographers ``can't stop gnashing their teeth about it''), New
York (``cheap'' and ``disrespectful'') and Business Week, which was
recently boycotted by freelance photographers until the magazine
raised its page rates.
</P>
<P>
   The list of winners included Bloomberg Personal Finance, Vanity
Fair, Fortune, Wired, Smithsonian and GQ.
</P>
<P>
   Holly Stuart Hughes, editor of PDN, said some results were
surprising. ``I was really surprised by Rolling Stone,'' she said.
``It has won a lot of awards for design and I was surprised that
photographers reacted to the poor reproduction and the busy feel of
the design.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hughes said she was not surprised, however, that Vogue was
on the list of losers for photographers, citing a general bias
against Conde Nast publications by photographers because of
continued troubled contract negotiations. ``But I was surprised
that the prestige of being in Vogue and the visibility of it did
not outweigh the creative restrictions they place on
photographers,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick O'Connell, a Vogue spokesman, said the magazine had no
comment. Rolling Stone, as of the issue dated Sept. 30, had
upgraded its paper stock.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan Schaps, director of special projects at New York, said
the survey was unfair because PDN did not reveal which
photographers were polled. ``I'm really surprised they would do a
blind taste test,'' he said. ``Who are the qualifying
photographers? It doesn't sound fair.''
</P>
<P>
   He admitted that New York's rate is not the highest in the
industry: ``I'll acknowledge that I wish our page rate were
escalating at a better rate. But no one is saying `I'm not working
for you, you're too cheap.' Not yet. We are trying to be responsive
to photographers. And we're certainly not disrespectful.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ALEX KUCZYNSKI
</P>
</TEXT>
