<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-05 21:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1740 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TEN-ROBERTS-COLUMN-NY     09-05 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-ROBERTS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: YEARS LATER, CAPRIATI STILL COMES UP SHORT
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Eight years ago, Monica Seles and Jennifer Capriati
shared a court at the National Tennis Center like giddy kids
sipping a soda from two straws. So adorable and wholesome, so
talented and hard hitting, the teen-agers turned their riveting
semifinal match at the U.S. Open into a classic.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, life would curdle for both players, innocence would
be crushed like an overhead. But in a full circle that has passed
through darkness and now light, they are back together again.
Seles, now 25, and Capriati, 23, will play each other at the Open
Monday for the first time since 1991. While it's tempting to turn
the court into a stage for symbiotic comeback and mutual closure,
the similarities linking the two should end with the year of their
disappearance.
</P>
<P>
   It was 1993. Seles vanished as a victim and became a survivor,
while Capriati self-destructed and now pretends to be the victim.
Seles gained introspection from seclusion, Capriati gained nothing
from her experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can we just stick to the now and stop asking about the past?''
Capriati said, growing more irritable with each question after
advancing to the round of 16 on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Moments earlier, she was bouncing happily around the court like
a kid sneaking a few leaps on the couch cushions. While Capriati
appears thrilled by a resurgence that has revealed her character as
a fighter, she turns listless when asked about anything deeper than
her ground strokes.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of embracing her role as a cautionary tale, she bristles
when she is held up as Exhibit 1 for the Capriati Rule, an
age-eligibility clause that prohibits 14-year-olds from playing
tour events and Grand Slam tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate being labeled like that,'' Capriati said in a recent
interview with CBS. ``I think my situation was very unique. If the
14-year-old can go and make the finals of the tournament then it's
like protecting them from what?''
</P>
<P>
   She has to ask? In 1990, Capriati turned pro two weeks shy of
her 14th birthday. By 1993, she was searching for crawl space away
from the hype. Once the bubble gum lost its flavor, and the stuffed
animals failed as good company, once popularity became a real drag
and her acne became a corporate concern, Capriati began relating to
the hopeless lyrics of bands like Nirvana.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the nose ring, the rag doll's slouch and makeup from
the Goth home kit. It was called grunge back then. This sullen look
of a rebel was a more comfortable fit than celebrity for Capriati
as she dropped the girlish giggle, picked up a joint and vanished
from the tour like a plume of smoke. By 1994, she was a case file
for the police.
</P>
<P>
   Although she has pointed at peer pressure and the news media,
Capriati has rarely acknowledged her own culpability. To see a real
victim of her time, she could look at Seles.
</P>
<P>
   It was 1993. Once Guenter Parche wielded his boning knife, and
Steffi Graf was able to reclaim the No. 1 ranking ahead of Seles,
once the psyche healed slower than the gash, and every adoring
stranger felt like a threat, Seles was left to endure the demons
when she retreated from public view.
</P>
<P>
   Soon came the nightmares, the initial thoughts of ``Why me?''
and eventually a sense of what was really important in life. This
reflection added substance to a personality that had been defined
by her hair color and volume of her grunts. By late 1995, Seles was
ready to step out as a more completed person.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, such growth has escaped Capriati. It's one thing to
be a teen-ager and not get it. It's another to be 23 and still
treat her mistakes as don't-go-there material. From her recent
responses, she neither feels compelled to tell her story as a means
of reaching teen-agers teetering on self-destruction nor to accept
her role in creating a rule that might save another young player
from the same kind of creepy spiral.
</P>
<P>
   Capriati could talk about what pressure can do to a 14-year-old
girl, about the strain placed on children by overbearing parents,
about the pratfalls involved in a life of too much too soon. When
asked to mull over the past, Capriati has the same refrain: ``No
regrets.''
</P>
<P>
   It's too bad. Regrets can be healthy and instructional to kids _
and their parents _ who are eager to plunge into the pros without
their swimmies. Like Monique Viele, for one.
</P>
<P>
   The news release passed around last week read like this:
``Donald Trump introduces tennis professional 14-year-old Monique
Viele. Trump will be on hand with his latest find, tennis sensation
Monique Viele. Trump will outline his strategy for Viele's
professional debut. The 14-year-old, who boasts a booming 115 mph
serve, will reveal why she chose T Management Group and why she is
turning pro at such a tender age.''
</P>
<P>
   Why? Is it for herself, her parents, or so Donald Trump can
build her into a commodity so big, she will obstruct views of the
river?
</P>
<P>
   Capriati could talk about slick packaging, about the dangers of
fame. For some reason, it doesn't occur to her. If she has grown at
all over the last eight years, if she has looked inside herself as
Seles has, if she has flipped over her mistakes and probed for
answers, how would anyone know it?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
