<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KARROS UNIMPRESSED WITH RECENT WINS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Winning 12 of 16 games is a nice way to head into the
final four weeks of the season, but Eric Karros cautions about
reading too much into the Dodgers' recent success.
</P>
<P>
   Karros, who Saturday reached 30 home runs for the fourth time in
his career, says the real gauge for the team will come in series
against New York and Houston, two of the NL's elite.
</P>
<P>
   ``You obviously want to win these games,'' Karros said, ``but
when you are playing great teams with a lot at stake, that's when
you know where you stand.''
</P>
<P>
   After completing a three-game sweep of the lowly Chicago Cubs on
Sunday, the Dodgers move on to Florida, where they open a
three-game series this afternoon against the Marlins. Chicago and
Florida are both in last place and a combined 51 games under .500.
</P>
<P>
   In the last 16 games, the Dodgers have played only one team over
.500, Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers also have six games remaining with rival San
Francisco, which had won eight straight before a loss Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But to Karros, the clearest test will come against the Astros
and Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Houston, which hosts the Dodgers for the final three games of
the regular season, is leading the NL Central.
</P>
<P>
   New York, which dropped three of four to the Dodgers last month,
is second in the East but leads Cincinnati for a wild-card berth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both teams have great pitching and great intensity,'' Karros
said. ``When you think about what the Dodgers should do for next
season, games with those teams might give you a better idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Quick hits: Although Gary Sheffield went 0 for 4, including a
strikeout and double-play grounder, nobody hit the ball harder.
Twice he lined sharply to Cubs third baseman Cole Liniak, who made
a spectacular diving stop in the eighth. Sheffield finished the
series 1 for 10. . . . Mark Grudzielanek, who was 5 for 8 with two
homers in the first two games, went 0 for 4 to snap an 11-game
hitting streak.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
