<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-05 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1743 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CANADA-CAJUNS-ART-NYT     09-05 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-CAJUNS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANADA'S OTHER FRENCH-SPEAKERS COPE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: France)   (EDS: `K' in spelling of Robert MONCKTON is correct)  
(ART ADV: A locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEMRAMCOOK, New Brunswick _ On a state visit to Montreal in
1967, Charles de Gaulle launched a famous war cry: ``Vive le Quebec
libre.'' After a huge pro-independence crowd exploded in delirium,
Ottawa encouraged the French president to pack his bags and return
to Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, Jacques Chirac made the first official visit
by a French president to Canada's other French-speakers, the nearly
290,000 Acadians of the Atlantic provinces. Speaking here, in ``the
cradle of Acadia,'' Chirac vowed in an emotional speech to renew
``the action of France by your sides.''
</P>
<P>
   A crowd of several thousand applauded enthusiastically, many
waving Acadian flags, a French tricolor with a gold star. Then they
settled down for a Labor Day weekend afternoon of foot-tapping
fiddle music, family picnics under maple trees and rounds of golf
on nearby links.
</P>
<P>
   The different reactions reflect different times, different
political personalities, but also different approaches to living in
Canada by the nation's two largest French-speaking societies.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Quebec, you have a French-speaking majority that was
economically oppressed by an English-speaking minority,'' said
Michel Venne, an editor of Le Devoir, a Quebec newspaper that
reflects the pro-independence sentiments of the province's
political leadership. Noting that French-speakers account for
one-third of New Brunswick, he said: ``Here, the French-speakers
have always been a minority. They have developed different survival
strategies _ tolerance, an ability to get along.''
</P>
<P>
   While Quebec's official language is French, New Brunswick is the
only officially bilingual province in Canada. A people with a flag,
an anthem and a holiday, Acadians lack a territory that easily
lends itself to nationhood. It is an archipelago of communities
sprinkled among four provinces: 240,000 people in New Brunswick,
the 35,000 in Nova Scotia, 5,500 on Prince Edward Island and 2,300
in Newfoundland.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend, in a deliberate effort to shift the
French-speaking world's spotlight away from Quebec, the Canadian
government made a showcase of New Brunswick, painting it as a
province where French-speakers do not dream of secession but live
happily inside the federation. Although Quebecers outnumber
Acadians by about 20 to 1, Canada chose Moncton, New Brunswick, to
host a conference of leaders from 49 foreign nations with
French-speaking populations.
</P>
<P>
   Historically lukewarm on the idea of independence for Quebec,
Acadians fear that secession by Quebec would leave the rest of
Canada's French-speakers as powerless minorities in an
overwhelmingly English Canada. With Quebec, French-speakers account
for about one quarter of Canada's 30 million people. Without
Quebec, they fall to 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   From Quebec, nationalists objected to holding a world
French-speaking summit in Moncton, noting that it was named for
Robert Monckton, a British army colonel who helped to orchestrate
the deportation of about two-thirds of the Acadian population from
Nova Scotia, starting in 1755. Acadians, while acutely aware of
that sad 18th-century history, preferred this weekend proudly to
focus attention on their modern day cultural and economic
renaissance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was only a few years ago that people named `Brun' were
changing their name to `Brown,' and that `LeBlancs' were becoming
`Whites,''' said Rene Legere, general secretary of the National
Society of Acadia, a group which represents French-speakers in the
four provinces.
</P>
<P>
   Several factors, he said, have diminished Acadians' inferiority
complex. In 1994, a gathering of the ``Acadian diaspora'' drew
225,000 people to New Brunswick _ from the Canadian maritime
provinces, from Louisiana and from Atlantic communities in France.
More recently, Acadian musical groups have won wide audiences in
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Le Point, a Parisian newsweekly, placed a photo of an
Acadian fiddler on its cover, with the caption: ``The Revenge of
the Acadians.'' This international endorsement of Acadian culture
is fueling local pride here. In the last decade, about a dozen
French-language community radio stations have started broadcasting,
drawing tens of thousands of Acadians away from English-language
radio.
</P>
<P>
   International attention and tourism also have given Acadians
greater confidence in speaking French, a language once mumbled
among members of Acadian farming and fishing families who visited
big cities like Moncton for shopping trips.
</P>
<P>
   With French tourism growing, a weekly airline flight started
service in June between Paris and Moncton, a city of 100,000. In
July, diplomats from the French consulate in Moncton announced the
opening of the city's first Alliance Francaise. Every year, about
200 Acadian high school students and about 200 French high school
students fly across the Atlantic to study in each other's schools,
according to Bernard Oswald, vice president of a union of French
friendship groups.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Acadians' growing self-confidence dates from the
founding in 1963 of the Universite de Moncton, now North America's
largest French-speaking university outside of Quebec. In 1969, New
Brunswick became officially bilingual.
</P>
<P>
   Three decades later, Acadians have made a strong push into
business and culture here. Roger Bilodeau, the province's under
secretary of justice, said, ``As the institutions have become
stronger, Francophone Acadians have taken their place in business,
industry and politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Here in Memramcook, one local boy, Romeo LeBlanc, grew up to
become the first Acadian appointed governor general, the queen's
representative in Canada. Addressing the French president in fluent
French, this representative of the British Crown said here,
``Against winds and tides, Acadia has remained resolutely, proudly
French.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-99 2148EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990905.0183 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-05 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1744 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKL-COMETS-LIBERTY-HN     09-05 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-COMETS-LIBERTY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By W.H. STICKNEY JR.  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
This one was for Kim.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Comets made it No. 3 for No. 10, defeating the New York
Liberty 59-47 at Compaq Center on Sunday to capture their third
straight WNBA championship.
</P>
<P>
   As league president Val Ackerman said amid a whirlwind of flying
red, white and blue confetti: ``This is a team that refuses to
lose.''
</P>
<P>
   No miracle 3-point shot at the buzzer would beat the Comets on
this afternoon. And no amount of defense in a game turned ugly
offensively would stay the Comets from their title quest in memory
of late point guard Kim Perrot.
</P>
<P>
   But just for good measure, three-time WNBA Coach of the Year Van
Chancellor took out a little insurance. After all, in Game 2 on
Saturday, New York's Teresa Weatherspoon had nailed a 52-foot shot
at the final buzzer to beat the Comets 58-57, even the
best-of-three Championship Series and necessitate Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``After yesterday, I tried to cover all my bases,'' Chancellor
said. ``No. 1, after I left shootaround (Sunday morning), I went to
church. I just wanted the Lord to know whose side I was on, just in
case he had any interest in the WNBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I got out my lucky coat, tie and pants that I wore in '97
(when the Comets beat the Liberty 65-51 to win the first WNBA
title). My clothier told me not to do that, but I stayed with the
luck.''
</P>
<P>
   But luck wasn't needed in front of the sellout crowd of 16,285
that included Perrot's mother, Connie, sister Lorretta and a number
of other family members.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Chancellor had Cynthia Cooper, who for the third
straight year was named Championship Series Most Valuable Player.
He had super sub Tammy Jackson, who takes to the playoffs like a
warrior to combat. And he had Sheryl Swoopes, who put high-scoring
New York 3-point ace Crystal Robinson in a vise.
</P>
<P>
   Tina Thompson was there, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's probably not respected enough around the WNBA,''
Chancellor said of Thompson, ``but all she does is guard the
toughest player each night and do a great job.''
</P>
<P>
   But most of all, Chancellor had Cooper, who shot a nightmarish
1-for-10 some 24 hours earlier but played like a true champion
Sunday. She also danced on the scorer's table as she held up
Perrot's No. 10 jersey for all in the crowd to see.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cooper did what we thought she'd do,'' said New York coach
Richie Adubato. ``She raised her level up and did what a superstar
does.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper scored a game-high 24 points, going 13-for-15 from the
free-throw line. She fought through double teams, stole the ball
and scored from long range and on the fast break, inspiring her
team in a game that was rarely inspiring to watch.
</P>
<P>
   The Comets shot 28.8 percent _ a record low for a Championship
Series game _ but held the Liberty to 30.9 percent shooting
(17-for-55) and outrebounded New York 36-28 while forcing 16
turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both teams played great defense,'' said Adubato. ``We stopped
their people; they stopped ours. The person that made the
difference was Cooper.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the Comets became only the fourth franchise in
major-league professional basketball history to win three titles in
a row. The George Mikan-led Minneapolis Lakers were the first. Then
came the Boston Celtics of Bill Russell and finally the Chicago
Bulls of Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   From the opening tip, Cooper made it clear the Comets are her
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right from the beginning,'' she said, ``I wanted to establish
that I was going to the basket today, that I was going to be a
force to reckon with, that it was going to be tough to stop me and
that if we were going to go down, we were going to go down
fighting.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all we've been through as a team and me individually,
this feels great to three-peat, to win a third championship after
so many sacrifices to get here.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper over the past year has endured more than her share of
tragedy and hardship. First, she lost her mother to breast cancer.
In December, one of the two houses Cooper owns in Sugar Land burned
to the ground, though her seven nieces and nephews escaped
unharmed. Then her car was totaled when she was hit from behind by
another driver.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was the declining health and eventual death of
Perrot after a valiant fight that took her to Mexico in search of
alternative cancer treatment that might prolong her life.
</P>
<P>
   On the day after Perrot made her final trip from Tijuana,
Mexico, back to Houston's M.D. Anderson Cancer Center, Cooper, who
looked as though she wouldn't be able to stand, let alone play a
40-minute game, came within two points of her WNBA-record 44 in
leading the Comets to a 71-53 victory over Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Perrot's death Aug. 19 resulted in an emotionally drained Cooper
missing the first game of her WNBA career. But she and the rest of
the Comets put on hold much of their grief as they embarked on a
mission that would not be complete without bringing home title No.
3 for No. 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been extremely tough to stay focused and to stay
motivated through Kim's sickness and my mom's illness and
throughout the different things that have happened,'' Cooper said.
``The basketball season has been extremely tough. We've been
inconsistent at times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really wanted to leave the problems on the outside and focus
on the task at hand on the court. I was able to do that for the
most part. I did slip a couple of games, but I just prayed every
day and had faith that God was going to bring me through.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's game was exactly the type ``Kim-Bim'' would have loved,
since it was dominated by defense, Perrot's specialty. The Comets
led 33-25 at halftime, and New York missed its first 10 shots of
the second half. Sue Wicks, with 11 points, was the only Liberty
player to finish in double figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``This championship was the hard one because of everything going
on,'' said the Comets' Janeth Arcain. ``It's been a very emotional
season, watching Kim fight her battle. We won this championship for
her, and we know she was watching us today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
