<SLUG> BC-GM-UAW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GM OFFERS LIFETIME EMPLOYMENT IN CONTRACT TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ROBYN MEREDITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ General Motors Corp. has offered the United Automobile
Workers union lifetime employment guarantees for many current
workers as it negotiates a new contract, a GM spokesman confirmed
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   GM, along with DaimlerChrysler AG and Ford Motor Co., faces the
expiration of its three-year contract with unionized workers on
Sept. 14. In the expiring contract, workers effectively have
lifetime employment because the terms bar automakers from allowing
employment to fall by more than 5 percent nationally or in any of a
dozen regions.
</P>
<P>
   The automakers have found this encumbering, particularly the
regional requirement. The automakers are also worried that renewing
the so-called 95 percent rule would force them to hire tens of
thousands of new workers as they enter a period when up to 6
percent of their work forces will be retiring each year. A huge
generation of autoworkers that was hired in the late 1960s and
early 1970s will become eligible for retirement after 30 years
</P>
<P>
   The lifetime employment offer would cover current GM workers
with more than 10 years of seniority. The proposal's contents were
first reported Sunday by Bloomberg News and were confirmed by Edd
Snyder, a GM spokesman. The UAW did not return phone calls seeking
comment.
</P>
<P>
   GM's proposal is aimed at addressing workers' job security fears
while allowing the company to reduce overall employment more
rapidly. As such, the proposal could drive a wedge between workers,
who want lifetime employment security, and union leaders, who
prefer to keep a large membership base, regardless of which workers
belong.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the three companies hopes to be singled out by the union
as the company with which it first reaches a new labor contract.
The union then forces the other two companies to accept similar
terms. That allows the company that goes first to craft terms most
favorable to itself and even to agree to provisions that are
difficult for its competitors. Auto executives and labor officials
expect a decision from the union early this week, perhaps on
Tuesday, on which company, or companies, will take the lead.
</P>
<P>
   The union held separate talks with DaimlerChrysler and GM
through Sunday afternoon, company spokesmen said. Talks with Ford
have broken off, suggesting that Ford will not be the lead company,
as it has been for the last two sets of labor negotiations. The
Canadian Automobile Workers union has said it hopes to negotiate
first with Ford.
</P>
<P>
   GM, with a large pool of workers eligible for retirement, also
offered to hire significant numbers of workers in the coming years
and to consider placing new products in unionized factories,
according to a contract proposal made on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal also would allow GM to continue to contract out
parts-making jobs and to use leaner production methods at
unprofitable small-car factories. The UAW would be invited
periodically to address GM's board. GM also proposed a $500
lump-sum payment plus a 2 percent wage increase for the first year
of the contract, a 3 percent wage increase in the second year and a
$1,500 payment in the third year, and offered to increase pension
payments for those retiring after 30 years by 7.6 percent, to
$2,470 a month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-99 2200EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990905.0187 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-05 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1751 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-LOSANGELES-CHESS-ART-     09-05 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOSANGELES-CHESS-ART-435&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STREET CHESS THRIVES IN LOS ANGELES CAFES AND PARKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ ``It's time for truth,'' exclaimed John Graham in
his best chessboard trash talk, dispatching one opponent and
preparing to play another on a recent fading summer night at Fifth
Street Dick's coffee shop. ``I understand! I understand!'' Graham
continued, keeping what he understood to himself. Then he
questioned the man across from him: ``Do you understand?''
</P>
<P>
   This is street chess in Los Angeles, a distant cousin of last
month's International Chess Federation championship in Las Vegas.
It is a game played late into the night, not at Caesar's Palace but
in parks and cafes, in doughnut shops and on the beach. The victor
wins bragging rights and the occasional side bet instead of a
$660,000 purse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Street chess is much different,'' said Richard Fulton, 54, who
opened Fifth Street Dick's near Fifth Street downtown about eight
years ago after a bout of alcoholism and homelessness. ``It's more
talkative.''
</P>
<P>
   In a city where many restaurants stop seating at 11 p.m. and the
bars close at 2 a.m., street chess is an exception to the minimal
late-night street life. The game is as much an obsession as it is
recreation, with players continually trying to best one another,
the clock and themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the games continue into the early morning, some until
dawn or later, and each spot has its own culture. At Plummer's Park
in West Hollywood, the lingua franca is Russian, because many of
the competitors are immigrants from the former Soviet Union; at
Tang's Donuts in the Silverlake section of East Hollywood, which is
said to be among the most competitive shops in town, precious
little is said at all.
</P>
<P>
   At Dick's, in the Crenshaw District of south Los Angeles, the
game is played at outdoor tables, on a boisterous wave of
camaraderie with a healthy dose of good-natured razzing thrown in
by players and observers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You ain't got a rat's chance in hell,'' said one man as he
hovered over the shoulder of another on Friday night. ``You're
finished. Let me take it. Get up.''
</P>
<P>
   Defeated, perhaps as much by the running commentary as by the
game, the man vacated his spot.
</P>
<P>
   Graham, 36, a construction worker who has been playing chess
since he was 8, is said to be the man to beat here, especially in
the fast, timed matches he calls ``blitz.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just the competition, I guess,'' Graham said when asked
why he plays. ``The creativity of it. I like to play blitz because
it's less stressful. You play a slow game, you go home at night and
you're playing the game in your head. With blitz, you can't even
remember your move right after you make it.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Dick's is popular as much for its atmosphere as for the games
themselves. On any given night, a chess player might hear a trumpet
playing softly at the next table, or hear the jazz bands or poetry
readers inside.
</P>
<P>
   The players roll out plastic chessboards on rickety tables put
out by the doughnut shop. Several men, and the group is almost
always male, watch and wait to get in on games, some of which are
slow, deliberate matches, while others are races against the clock.
Some players bet on their games. There is the occasional scrape of
metal upon the art-deco patterned sidewalk, as a defeated player
pushes his chair back and another player replaces him.
</P>
<P>
   The pattern continues until Dick's closes, sometimes as late as
4 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they take the tables in, they have to run guys off the
tables because they play to the very last minute,'' said Matt
Gibson, 49, an actor and announcer who has been going to Dick's for
about six years. ``Chess is an obsessive game. Chess players go to
bed at night seeing black and white squares floating in their
heads, games they might have blundered or bungled away. It has to
be played obsessively to even be played moderately well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-99 2203EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990905.0188 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-05 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1752 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-UNIONS-CLERGY-ART-940     09-05 1119
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNIONS-CLERGY-ART-940(2TAKES)(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLERGY AND UNIONS TEAMING UP AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ On a weekend when millions of Americans see Labor Day
as little more than an opportunity to shop or go to the beach, the
Rev. Judith Kelsey-Powell tried hard Sunday to reconnect her
congregation to Labor Day's roots.
</P>
<P>
   In a stately Methodist church on this city's South Side, Ms.
Kelsey-Powell told her congregation: ``Over and over again,
brothers and sisters, we are called to discern justice. That's what
Labor Day is about. It's not about unions getting their perks,
although that's part of it. It's about every worker getting what
they need to live with dignity. That is justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Immediately afterward, she called to the altar Oscar Varnadoe, a
barrel-chested member of a printers' union, and he seconded her
message, declaring that ``all of God's children doing God's work''
should fight for those ``who go to work day in and day out,''
earning little as they humbly toil.
</P>
<P>
   The service was part of a fast-growing nationwide effort in
which clergy members and union members teamed up over the weekend
at more than 600 religious services _ about twice last year's
number _ with the goal of educating congregations on labor matters
and lending the church's moral authority to labor's cause.
Religious leaders and union officials see the services, including
nearly 100 in Chicago, as the biggest step so far toward rebuilding
the mighty labor-clergy alliance that existed decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   As the labor movement struggles to regain its strength of
yesteryear, it has pushed to forge new bonds with religious
leaders, knowing that they could provide pivotal help to workers in
battles for better wages and benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Labor's effort has begun to pay off, not just with labor-related
sermons but with clergy members who have fasted to support
strikers, joined pro-union sit-ins and pressured corporate
executives to shun a no-holds-barred approach to fighting
unionization.
</P>
<P>
   This renewed cooperation has brought labor and clergy members
closer than at any time since the 1960s, when differences over the
war in Vietnam, union corruption and much of labor's indifference
to poor workers fractured what had been a close alliance in the
1930s.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``There has historically been this alliance, but then there came
a serious break,'' said Bishop Jesse DeWitt, a Methodist who is
president of the National Interfaith Committee for Worker Justice,
a group based in Chicago that promotes labor-religious cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a natural alliance,'' DeWitt said. ``The whole
Judeo-Christian teaching is about justice for workers, the right
for people to have decent wages, a decent place to live and decent
medical care.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s many liberal clergy members put their energies into
helping the civil rights movement instead of labor, but after
seeing disparities between the rich and poor widen in the 1980s and
1990s, they have re-dedicated themselves to helping low-wage
workers, although not necessarily unions. For example, dozens of
clergy members in DeWitt's group have begun a campaign to pressure
poultry companies to improve conditions for their workers,
unionized or not. His group, with 45 chapters across the nation,
has also coordinated hundreds of labor-related services over the
weekend in a program called ``Labor in the Pulpit.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the new cooperation, more labor-related courses
are being taught at seminaries. Such courses were common 60 years
ago when the nation had hundreds of worker priests, whose mission
was to help laborers. In addition, religious leaders and the
AFL-CIO are planning to set up a program in which dozens of
seminary students would spend their summers working with different
unions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both unions and religious groups are guided by core values,
values that reflect the dignity of work,'' said John J. Sweeney,
the president of the AFL-CIO. ``We both share basic beliefs in
justice and fairness for everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   The labor-related services, held at churches, synagogues and
mosques, have gathered cachet with unions leaders, clergy members
and some politicians. Sunday in Detroit, Vice President Al Gore
joined Sweeney at a Roman Catholic service and a Methodist prayer
breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   There were labor services in more than 50 cities, including
Atlanta, Cincinnati, Denver, Los Angeles, San Diego and Seattle. In
New York City, Brian McLaughlin, president of the city's central
labor council, spoke at the First Baptist Church of Crown Heights
and Congregation Emunath Israel, an orthodox synagogue in
Manhattan. And officials with the Roman Catholic Archdiocese in
Manhattan said on Friday that a labor service was planned for next
Sunday at St. Patrick's Cathedral.
</P>
<P>
   Some business critics deride this labor-religion partnership,
asserting that unions are manipulating a naive clergy into joining
their selfish battles and that clergy members should not take sides
in complex labor battles in which there is no clear right or wrong.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney, who says he is a deeply religious Roman Catholic, has
steadfastly wooed the clergy since he became president of the
AFL-CIO four years ago. Aware that many clergy members had soured
on labor because they saw unions as an arrogant elite of high-paid
auto workers and construction workers, Sweeney has focused on poor,
marginal employees like farm workers, janitors and hotel maids.
These are the workers that the clergy says most need the church's
help.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Kelsey-Powell, said, ``I just have a strong feeling
about helping marginalized people wherever they are. But you can't
equate unions with the
</P>
<P>
   As at many other religious services Sunday, her Morgan Park
United Methodist Church was full of talk about Jesus, the
carpenter. Her co-pastor and husband, Keith Powell, recited a
litany, developed at the United Methodist Church's headquarters in
Washington, D.C., asking God to remember ``children whose childhood
has been cut short because they are forced to work,'' workers
``displaced by technical change or global pressure'' and those
``who have been discriminated against as a result of their union
activity.''
</P>
<P>
   After each group was cited, the congregation recited, ``Jesus,
worker and carpenter of Nazareth, hear our prayer.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The National Interfaith Committee on Worker Justice began
organizing Labor Day services four years ago, starting with just a
handful. This year, the Council of Bishops of the United Methodist
Church mailed a sample Labor Day message and litany to 5,000
pastors, and 18,600 Catholic churches received a mailing from
Sweeney and Cardinal John O'Connor, called ``Putting Labor into
Labor Day Services.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday night at Temple Judea Mizpah in Skokie, Ill., Robert
Drizin, a Cook County pubic defender who is a member of the
American Federation of State, County and Municipal Employees, gave
a talk examining the ties between Judaism and labor. He said that
Moses had led the first recorded labor protest when he shepherded
the Jews out of Egypt to escape slavery under the Pharaoh.
</P>
<P>
   Drizin urged the congregation not to forget how unions had
helped improve conditions when their ancestors worked in garment
shops or other factories.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a very good chance our parents and grandparents were
hard laborers, working six days a week, 15-hour days,'' he said.
``The Jews of those generations played a very important role in
making life better for us. All these benefits we enjoy, you forget
where they come from.''
</P>
<P>
   Two Spanish services at St. Pius Roman Catholic Church on the
South Side were crowded Sunday, and at both the congregations
listened intently to Veronica Meneses, action coordinator for the
National Farm Worker Ministry, a clergy group dedicated to helping
migrant laborers.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Meneses sought to rally the congregants, almost all of them
from Central America, to labor's cause, reminding them that papal
encyclicals and bishop's pastoral letters have praised the role
unions play in defending workers' interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``And they did this with reason,'' Ms. Meneses said, ``because
unions have achieved a lot _ the eight-hour day, the minimum wage,
job security and Social Security.''
</P>
<P>
   The priest at St. Pius, the Rev. Charles W. Dahm, said he was
more than glad to invite a labor-oriented speaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message of Jesus was working for the poor and the
oppressed and defending their rights,'' he said. ``I should think
that the church has a great responsibility aligning itself with the
workers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
