<SLUG> BC-REAL-LIFE-COMEDY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METROPOLITAN DIARY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ENID NEMY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A weekly column featuring readers' reports on life in the Big
Apple.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   My friend Marjorie Schoneboom and I visit Atlantic City, N.J.,
several times a year, staying overnight at a casino hotel. We allot
a certain amount of money for each trip and always resolve that
when it's used up, we'll resist the impulse to withdraw more from
the ATM (strategically placed near the slot machines). We promise
each other we'll simply retire to our room and read. This is a
promise we often break.
</P>
<P>
   On our last trip, Marjorie went through her stake very early in
the evening. Reluctant to stop playing after only an hour in the
casino, she started walking toward the nearest bank machine. I
followed and watched as she stood in front of it a moment debating
with herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Didn't you bring a book?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, I brought a book,'' she sighed. ``I always bring a
book. But somehow the only thing I've ever been able to read in
Atlantic City is `Do you wish to proceed in English or Spanish?'''
</P>
<P>
   _ ELLEN CONFORD
</P>
<P>
   Sue Shire's 3-year-old granddaughter, Danielle Slap, was looking
out the window into the back yard when she spotted a group of four
deer of varying sizes. ``Look,'' she said. ``There is a family:
There's a daddy, mommy, baby and the baby sitter.''
</P>
<P>
   William N. Farlie Jr., was racing north on Fifth Avenue, about
to cross 52nd Street despite the traffic signal blinking ``DON'T
WALK.'' As he started out, he heard what he described as a
distinctly New York voice explaining to a cluster of tourists:
``That's what it's like in New York. But you either do it really
well or you get killed.''
</P>
<P>
   Naomi Starobin's 10-year-old son, Max, found a big thermometer
and decided to experiment. He filled one mug with very cold water
and another with very hot water and called his mother over to see
the red line zoom up when he switched the thermometer from the cold
water to hot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you know what's happening?'' Mrs. Starobin asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' he said. ``The saturn is going up inside.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You mean the mercury,'' she corrected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' he replied. ``I knew it was one of those car names.''
</P>
<P>
   COMMUTER'S REVERIE
</P>
<P>
   Don't think of sitting next to me
</P>
<P>
   With your uncovered cup of hot coffee or tea
</P>
<P>
   If it's a cell phone you plan to use
</P>
<P>
   Another seat why don't you choose
</P>
<P>
   If it's smoke that you smell of or heavy perfume you wear
</P>
<P>
   Move somewhere else, please don't come near.
</P>
<P>
   By opening your newspaper into my face
</P>
<P>
   You are violating my personal space
</P>
<P>
   Other things that I find to be rude
</P>
<P>
   Are when you snore or chew loudly on food
</P>
<P>
   ``Train time is your own time'' is what they say
</P>
<P>
   But only if commuters make it that way.
</P>
<P>
   _ BETSY R. WEISS
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   Before I came to New York in 1974, via Portugal and Paris, I had
already traveled in a number of underground transportation systems
_ Paris, London, Madrid and Lisbon. I assumed that in a city like
New York, propelled by big financial resources and modern
technology, the transportation system had attained a high level of
efficiency, comfort and security.
</P>
<P>
   I imagined the New York subway as equipped with fast escalators
descending into vast clean marble chambers. I visualized
sophisticated electronic devices that would quickly tell passengers
where they were and the fastest way to get to their destination. I
expected to ride in sleek and silent subway cars of aerodynamic
design, fresh during hot summer days, warm in winter.
</P>
<P>
   The first time I descended into the subway my impression was
that I had somehow entered an underground construction site. Then I
heard a freaky noise coming from the tunnel as a train rolled in at
high speed, and I thought the price of a token should include ear
protectors.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, I've taken this noisy aggressive subway almost every
day. I believe it is one of the city's main attractions, reflecting
its fantastic urban anatomy. Now I say: New York subway, I don't
care about your unattractive underground structures, your rats,
your noise and your delays. For it was down there, in a cramped
clanging subway car that in 1980 I met her, Frances, the woman I
love and with whom, for almost 20 years, I have shared the joys and
pains of life.
</P>
<P>
   _ PEPE DINIZ
</P>
<P>
   A young couple were arguing just as Jon A. Overold was passing
the corner of Broadway and 40th Street. He heard only the following
intriguing sentences before the light changed and he crossed the
street. ``What do you mean it's not your problem?'' the young woman
exclaimed indignantly. ``I am your problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   A friend and I were at the movies, watching ``The Iron Giant''
and sitting among adults, children and adults with children. One
inattentive child, about 4 years old, resorted to playing an
electronic video game that frequently beeped.
</P>
<P>
   A man within earshot implored the child's father to intercede
and stop the noise. The father retorted that it was a children's
movie and his son had a right to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should teach your son how to behave in public,'' the
fuming adult countered. The father counterattacked, saying: ``It's
a kid's movie. I'll punch you in the face, and if you don't shut
up, the police will be called.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally a cost-conscious filmgoer burst out with what was the
common denominator to everyone. He called out loudly: ``$9.50!
$9.50!'' A reminder of the price of the film refocused attention to
the screen. The child's mother put a stop to the electronic play.
Silence was restored.
</P>
<P>
   _ SUSAN L. ROSENBERG
</P>
<P>
   Stanley Besen was standing near his parked car on Fifth Avenue
in the upper 90s, waiting for his wife, Eleanor. A taxi pulled up,
the driver got out and helped an elderly man with a cane out of the
cab. The man then took out his wallet, slowly counted out the fare
and handed it over.
</P>
<P>
   The driver, who had been standing by patiently, counted it and
to the amazement of Besen, took out a $10 bill and returned it to
the passenger. ``I'm sure you didn't mean to give me this as a
tip,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
