u s BC-BBN-METS-ROCKIES-NYT &LR;      09-05 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-ROCKIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FAMILIAR CHANT GREETS GRAND SLAM BY NEW MET
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At first the chants came weakly, perhaps even
insincerely. ``Darryl, Darryl,'' a modest number of fans shouted
Sunday as the Mets' Darryl Hamilton squared himself in the batter's
box against Darryl Kile, his former Colorado Rockies teammate.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, be it Queens or the Bronx, such cheers are usually
reserved for Darryl Strawberry, and Hamilton, a Met for barely a
month, knew it.
</P>
<P>
   But with one surprisingly mighty swing, Hamilton made the chant
his, at least for a day. Parking Kile's 86 mph fastball into the
Mets' bullpen behind the right-field fence, Hamilton recorded the
third grand slam of his career to catapult the Mets to a 6-2
victory and put an exclamation point on what has been a terrific
beginning with his new club.
</P>
<P>
   As Hamilton, who has batted .387 since being acquired from the
Rockies on July 31, rounded the bases, pumping his fist, the once
mild chant turned into a roar delivered by 49,117 fans at Shea
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that came from my man who wore 18 here,'' Hamilton
said, referring to the chant and to Strawberry. ``I recall it very
well. I'm a big fan of his. The fans here have been great to me.
It's been unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton's blast, just his eighth home run this season,
highlighted an outstanding day for the Mets. Masato Yoshii turned
in another fine pitching performance, and animated reliever John
Franco returned to action.
</P>
<P>
   Also, with Arizona beating Atlanta, 7-5, the Mets gained a full
game on the Braves in the National League East and now stand 2 1/2
games behind them. Cincinnati, which defeated Philadelphia, remains
four games behind the Mets in the NL wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   Yoshii, who less than a month ago was pitching from the bullpen,
continued a compelling bid for a spot in the postseason rotation.
Mixing his fastball and forkball in masterly fashion, he kept the
Rockies' batters guessing all afternoon, allowing two runs on six
hits and two walks while striking out nine. Yoshii improved to 3-1
with a 1.57 earned run average in five starts since regaining his
starter's role on Aug. 13 after replacing an injured Rick Reed in
the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Yoshii's personal- and team-best scoring streak of 161/3
scoreless innings was broken in the sixth inning when he
surrendered a two-run homer to Vinny Castilla. But by then, the
Mets had already taken a 6-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike was calling a great game, mixing up fastballs and
forkballs really well,'' Yoshii, referring to catcher Mike Piazza,
said through his interpreter, Kota Ishijima. ``Whenever they were
waiting for fastballs, he was calling for the forkball, and vice
versa. The pitch to Castilla that he hit out was a forkball and he
was waiting for it. That was a mistake, but everything else was
good stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Though clearly delighted with Yoshii's resurgence, Mets manager
Bobby Valentine remained noncommittal about the postseason. ``It's
a long ways away,'' Valentine said. ``But we need him now, and he
has risen to the occasion.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine called for Franco in the eighth inning, and the antsy
left-hander sprinted toward the mound while waving his glove in the
wind. It was Franco's first appearance for the Mets since being
placed on the disabled list with a sprained finger on July 3, and
the fans _ who have not always been kind to him _ cheered madly.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously on an adrenaline rush, Franco got Dante Bichette and
Todd Helton to ground out before walking Castilla and surrendering
a double down the left-field line to Edgardo Clemente. First
baseman John Olerud saved the inning by making a beautiful grab of
a line shot by Henry Blanco.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really nervous,'' Franco said. ``This is the first time
in a long time that I can really smile and say I contributed to the
team.''
</P>
<P>
   While Kile's 8-13 record and 6.33 ERA are not very impressive,
defeating him was huge for the Mets. Kile had been something of an
ace against the Mets, going 9-2 with a 3.21 ERA against them in his
career. He had not lost at Shea Stadium since 1992, defeating the
Mets in their home park four straight times.
</P>
<P>
   A bit wild, Kile showed signs of breaking in the fourth when he
walked two batters, but he escaped unscathed. He was not as
fortunate in the fifth. After striking out Yoshii, he was touched
for a single by Rickey Henderson and then loaded the bases by
walking Edgardo Alfonzo and Olerud. Piazza and Ventura followed
with run-scoring singles before Hamilton brought everyone home.
</P>
<P>
   When the Rockies arrived in New York before the series began
late last week, some of them were angry because Hamilton had said
his former team was unsound fundamentally. So he made it a point to
visit the visitors' clubhouse and assure the Rockies that he had
included himself in the comments.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton, whose last grand slam was on Aug. 11, 1995, while
playing with Milwaukee, also added that his uncharacteristic fist
pump while rounding the bases was not meant to taunt his former
teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't see a grand slam too often, so I'm not trying to
show up anybody or make anybody feel bad,'' he said. ``We were
getting some runs and, hey, it's a grand slam. I can count on one
hand the number of times I've done it. It doesn't happen very
often.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither do chants of ``Darryl'' for someone other than
Strawberry. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
