<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-05 22:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1770 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-TIMOR-STRIFE-BOS &LR;      09-05 1290
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMOR-STRIFE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN OF TERROR RAGES IN E. TIMOR  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ Overwhelmingly defeated at the polls by a people
desperate to cast off a quarter-century of harsh rule, vengeful
pro-Indonesian gunmen unleashed a terror campaign in East Timor on
Sunday, besieging a UN compound and a Catholic bishop's home,
reportedly slaughtering 100 people in a church and threatening to
massacre the pro-independence leadership, witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of people tried to flee the violence, and
Australia announced it would attempt an airlift Monday of
nonessential UN personnel and Australians.
</P>
<P>
   The descent into bloodshed, arson, and looting began hours after
the UN announced a landslide victory for independence in last
week's referendum on the territory's future.
</P>
<P>
   Terrified witnesses interviewed by telephone from East Timor's
capital, Dili, said Indonesian police and soldiers stood by or
joined in the violence.
</P>
<P>
   Gunmen laid siege to the offices of a human rights group, the
Australian Embassy, former US President Jimmy Carter's election
observers group, a hotel for foreigners, and refugee centers,
witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
   Other gunmen fired on at least 1,000 refugees camped out beside
UN headquarters, sending them scurrying over the razor wire into
the compound.
</P>
<P>
   A Western military officer in Dili said plainclothes Indonesian
soldiers were among those rampaging through the capital Sunday. The
officer said he spotted Indonesian military weapons, and recognized
members of the elite Kopassus commando branch.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Indonesian military is making an example of East Timor to
all other provinces who want freedom,'' said a member of the
National Council of Timor Resistance, speaking by telephone.
``They're saying, `We'll give you independence _ we'll kill the lot
of you!' ''
</P>
<P>
   It was impossible to verify reports of massacres early Monday,
but National Council officials said 100 people were slain in a
church in the town of Same, south of Dili, and another 24 were
killed in Atsabe, to the southwest. The woman who performed a song
advertising the UN-sponsored ballot also was hunted down and
killed, National Council officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 79 percent of East Timor's 450,000 voters voted for
freedom from Indonesia, which has ruled the territory on the
eastern end of the vast Indonesian archipelago since invading it in
1975. An estimated 200,000 East Timorese _ a quarter of the
population _ have died of civil war, famine, and disease.
</P>
<P>
   Despite an offer of independence by Indonesian President B.J.
Habibie if East Timorese spurned continued union with Jakarta, many
Indonesians fear that if East Timor goes free, other restive
provinces _ such as resource-rich Aceh and Irian Jaya _ also might
demand independence.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses in Dili said armed men were going door to door
searching for independence supporters, and had torched the Dili
office of the Nobel Peace laureate Bishop Carlos Ximenes Belo,
possibly killing people inside. The bishop's residence, where a few
thousand people were sheltering, was surrounded by men with heavy
weapons, cannon, and mortars, people inside said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like'' Indonesian military commander ``General
Wiranto has lost control. He told Bishop Belo that he gave the
order to stop'' the siege, ``but it hasn't stopped,'' said a member
of the CNRT, National Council of Timor Resistance.
</P>
<P>
   Across town at the UN compound in Dili, where more than 1,000 UN
staff and civilian refugees were holed up in darkness, UN political
officer Geoffrey Robinson said late Sunday night that pro-Jakarta
militiamen surrounded his compound and had been firing weapons
almost nonstop for the last 10 hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're virtual hostages here,'' Robinson said, as gunfire rang
out in the background. ``The militias _ with official acquiesence
or approval _ are willing to target the UN . . . as well as
international observers.''
</P>
<P>
   Two observers from the Carter Center were attacked by militias
Sunday as they tried to evacuate local employees on a ferry. When
they turned to nearby military officers for help, they were laughed
at. When they turned to police, the officers drove away, the Carter
Center observers reported.
</P>
<P>
   A UN convoy evacuating its workers from the western town of
Liquica on Saturday was fired upon first by militiamen, and then by
Indonesian police and soldiers, Robinson said. An American UN
officer was hit in the attack, and the UN helicopter that evacuated
him later was fired on as well. Militias also fired at UN vehicles
trying to get food and supplies in Dili Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Indonesian police have failed utterly to fulfill their
obligations'' to keep the peace, as stipulated in a May 5 agreement
signed at the UN, Robinson said angrily. ``Now it's time for
governments like the United States to act very, very swiftly to
insist on alternative security arrangements.''
</P>
<P>
   But in an apparent about-face from statements a few days ago,
General Wiranto reportedly rejected calls for an international
peacekeeping force Sunday, telling reporters that East Timor was
still part of Indonesia until the national assembly ratifies last
week's vote in November.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson said some 1,000 people, including local and
international UN staff who had been evacuated from numerous rural
offices, were sleeping on cardboard boxes in the Dili compound.
About 60 UN workers, plus most journalists and international
observers _ several of whom were attacked in plain view and without
intervention by police _ have been evacuated already from East
Timor.
</P>
<P>
   At least four local UN workers have been slain and others are
missing since Monday's vote, but Robinson said the UN will not pull
out. ``We're certainly not going to let a bunch of street thugs
chase us out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Resistance leader Jose Ramos Horta, who shared the Nobel Prize
with Bishop Belo, said it is not ``street thugs'' who are
orchestrating the terror, but rather the military.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not anarchy _ this is one-way violence, state-directed
violence against innocent women and children, against the church,
against the UN,'' Ramos Horta asserted in a telephone interview
from New York.
</P>
<P>
   Ramos Horta said that in a July meeting, General Wiranto told
him, jailed resistance leader Xanana Gusmao, and others that he
could disarm the militias ``in two days _ I just need to order the
commanders in the field.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's getting ignored by Kopassus,'' the special forces
command that is led by rival generals, Ramos Horta said.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses reported scores of killings in the outskirts of Dili
and in strongholds of pro-Indonesia forces in the south and west.
``There is every indication that a massacre is taking place, staged
by military forces,'' Ana Gomes, Lisbon's diplomatic envoy to
Jakarta, told Portugal's TSF radio. ``Over 100 dead would be a
conservative estimate.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked how quickly international peacekeepers would have to come
in to restore order, a National Council of Timor Resistance member
said resignedly, ``They're not going to make it in time. It's too
late for peacekeeping. It's over.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson said food and water shortages could spark a
humanitarian crisis. The neighboring province of West Timor was
bracing for 100,000 refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Also Sunday, a commander of East Timor's pro-independence
guerrillas said his fighters would take up arms again unless the
violence stops.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not accept further humiliation from the Indonesians,''
Taur Matan Ruak, commander of the Falintil guerrillas, told
Portuguese Radio Renascenca. ``We will use whatever is at hand _
machetes, stones, arms.''
</P>
</TEXT>
