<P>
   &UR; PROTEIN _  &LR; DNA research has spawned a new effort to unravel the
secrets of proteins. As the genome map nears completion, other
researchers are studying the essential building blocks produced by
DNA: the roughly 100,000 proteins that make up every muscle, nerve
and fiber in our bodies. Protein mappers have dubbed their study
``proteomics.'' Proteomics has same goal as genomics: to identify
the causes and possible cures for disease, and speed up the process
of developing new drugs. It might be years before this effort leads
to new drugs, but leading scientists think this new field with the
funny name could be the next big thing in biotechnology. By TOM
ABATE
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TEENCASH _  &LR; Seeing a huge potential market, three Bay Area
companies have introduced ``electronic wallets'' targeted at teens.
Parents open accounts for their teens with these companies, using a
credit card to establish a spending limit. Then, teens go to the
companies' Web sites, where they can buy merchandise until their
accounts run dry. Parents can review account activity to see what
their kids have bought and can restrict the hours when purchases
can be made. By STEVE GINSBERG
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KIDS _  &LR; A survey by software company Websense found there's a
huge gap between what parents think their children are viewing
online and what they actually are seeing. By DAVID LAZARUS
</P>
