<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-05 22:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1777 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-FINANCIER-ARREST-BOS &LR;      09-05 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCIER-ARREST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINANCIER WANTED IN FRAUD CASE IS CAUGHT IN GERMANY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN BARRY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Connecticut financier Martin Frankel's four-month run through
Europe ahead of the FBI ended Saturday, when German authorities
arrested him at a deluxe lakefront hotel in Hamburg. Frankel went
peacefully, saying, ``You got me,'' authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   The arrest essentially ends the career of a man whom associates
have depicted as simultaneously predatory and hapless _ who pulled
off what could turn out to be the biggest insurance heist in
history, authorities say, but whose flight was repeatedly stalled
because he had trouble making up his mind.
</P>
<P>
   Extradition proceedings will begin this week against Frankel on
federal charges of money laundering and wire fraud. The process
could go on for months, said Lisa Bull, an FBI spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Frankel was accompanied by a woman, identified by the FBI in
Connecticut as Cynthia Allison, 35. Allison was using the alias
Susan Kelly, the FBI said. She was detained for questioning but
later released.
</P>
<P>
   Frankel has been missing since May 5, when police responded to a
report of fire at his abandoned Greenwich mansion and found a file
cabinet and fireplaces full of burning documents. Insurance
regulators say Frankel's unlicensed brokerage siphoned at least
$215 million from a dozen small insurance companies, although a
lawsuit filed by several of these companies put the figure much
higher, at $915 million, according to the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Clues suggested that Frankel had fled the country in a state of
great anxiety. Among the papers police reported seizing in the
mansion were personalized astrological charts drawn to answer the
questions ``Will I go to prison?'', ``Will Tom turn me in?'',
``Should I wire money back from overseas?'', and ``Will I be
safe?'' A to-do list, authorities said, included the item ``Launder
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Later reports had him hiding out in Italy, living off a cache of
diamonds in the company of two women picked from a number of female
assistants.
</P>
<P>
   A New Haven lawyer, Hugh Keefe, who agreed to represent Frankel
in a phone conversation after Frankel left Greenwich, said he is
following his client's case ``100 percent'' through press accounts.
He said that he had not been officially informed of his client's
arrest, and that had no idea what Frankel's state of mind was.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I knew, I wouldn't tell you. But it's easy for me, because
I don't know,'' Keefe said. ``I've never met Marty Frankel.''
</P>
<P>
   Keefe said Frankel was arraigned Sunday on charges of possessing
a fake British passport.
</P>
<P>
   The native of Toledo, Ohio, will return to the United States as
an object of fascination to people who have followed reports on his
case, and who have heard about his multiple aliases and grandiose
misrepresentations. At his parents' home in Toledo, a woman
answering the telephone said the family would not comment on his
arrest out of concern for their ``safety and privacy.''
</P>
<P>
   But to those who say they were ripped off by Frankel, the arrest
is good news. Ted Bitter, a tool and die maker from Millbrook,
Ohio, said he knew Frankel could not have kept running forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was inevitable, because Marty Frankel is physically
and mentally weak. He just doesn't have the intestinal fortitude to
see something like this through,'' said Bitter, who won damages
from Frankel in 1991 after bringing a suit against him for a loss
of $64,000 he said he incurred when Frankel was his broker.
</P>
<P>
   Bitter said he had been dazzled initially by Frankel's knowledge
of the market, and later came to believe that he was too panicky
and indecisive to use that knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   George Dale, insurance commissioner for the state of
Mississippi, said Frankel's capture does not mean a lot unless the
state can recoup the $187 million Frankel allegedly took from three
Mississippi insurance companies. After Frankel's scam collapsed,
the insurance companies went into receivership, requiring the state
to pay out insurance claims to policyholders.
</P>
<P>
   Dale said the loss would be spread out among taxpayers. But
Frankel deserves to be punished, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's a kook, but I think he's a genius,'' Dale said.
``Frankly, knowing what we know about his lifestyle, I really
thought he would have committed suicide before they were able to
catch him.''
</P>
<P>
   Other observers regretted the end of the chase. It's not
uncommon for the flight of a high-profile fugitive to become a
matter of public fascination, such as Robert Vesco, the 1970s
wheeler-dealer who eluded federal authorities for more than two
decades before being arrested in Cuba in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sort of like crooks who get away with it,'' said Arthur
Herzog, who wrote ``Vesco: From Wall Street to Castro's Cuba _ The
Rise, Fall and Exile of the King of White-Collar Crime.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a certain charm,'' he said. ``That's why they get
away with it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-99 2236EDT &QL; 
