<SLUG> BC-REGIONAL-AIRPORTS-BOS </SLUG>
  
 RISE OF REGIONAL AIRPORTS CUTS INTO BOSTON TRAFFIC
 &HT;    (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   BOSTON _ Thanks to Southwest Airlines and a booming economy, New
England's regional airports are starting to ease some of the burden
on Boston's Logan Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Preliminary traffic projections from the Federal Aviation
Administration indicate Logan will grow more slowly than
Massachusetts Port Authority officials had expected over the next
10 to 15 years, in large part because fast-growing airports in
Manchester and near Providence are picking up the slack.
</P>
<P>
   The projections indicate Logan will handle 33.6 million
passengers in 2010, up almost 27 percent from what it handled last
year. But that is still about 4 million passengers fewer than
Massport's most conservative projection for that year.
</P>
<P>
   Logan's share of the New England air passenger market has
dropped from 69 percent to 62 percent over the past four years and
is expected to keep dropping as regional airports continue to grow.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas J. Kinton Jr., aviation director at Logan, said the
projections do not mean Logan can shelve plans for a fiercely
debated new runway, but he said they are the first signs that
regionalization is working. ``The regionalization effort was never
meant to stop Logan from growing,'' he said. ``Logan is going to
continue to grow, but at a smaller pace.''
</P>
<P>
   The FAA forecasts an annual growth rate at Logan of 2.4 percent
over the next 10 years, dropping slightly to 2.27 percent if the
projection is extended to 2015. Kinton said the forecasts mean that
in some years Logan will experience little or no growth. He also
said the forecasts take into account the development of high-speed
rail service to New York.
</P>
<P>
   Kinton credits Southwest Airlines and the booming economy for
boosting regionalization. ``It couldn't have been better timing,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Southwest launched service at T.F. Green Airport in Warwick,
R.I., in October 1996. With its low fares and strong performance
numbers, it has become the leading carrier there, ousting US
Airways from the top perch this year.
</P>
<P>
   But even more important than Southwest's rise is that US Airways
and most other airlines at Green have also grown. In other words,
Southwest has grown rapidly, but not at the expense of other
airlines operating out of Green.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic at Green has almost doubled since Southwest's arrival,
and the FAA projects 5.1 percent annual growth over the next 10
years. The forecasts project Green will handle 8 million passengers
by 2010. Airport officials say nearly half of Green's passengers
are from Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   The same scenario is unfolding in Manchester, where Southwest
launched service in June 1998. In July, the latest period for which
figures are available, Southwest carried 87,597 passengers. US
Airways remained the top carrier with 90,000 passengers, but only
with the help of its commuter business.
</P>
<P>
   For July, air traffic overall at Manchester was up 17 percent
over July 1998; for the year so far it was up 77 percent. The FAA
projects an annual growth rate of 7.2 percent at Manchester over
the next 10 years, with the airport handling 3.6 million passengers
by 2010, up from 1.9 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, it is surprising that the passenger growth at
Green and Manchester has not caused Logan's traffic to hold steady
or decline. But officials at all three airports and at Southwest
Airlines say the low fares available at Green and Manchester are
not just pulling customers away from Logan but putting more people
in airplane seats who normally would not have flown.
</P>
<P>
   The real test of regionalization may come when the economy slows
down. ``Airlines are quick to cut back at regional airports and
maintain services at more dominant airports when the economy
softens,'' Kinton said. ``If Green and Manchester can keep growing
or at least hang on to the passengers they've got, that will tell a
lot about the success of regionalization.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
