u s BC-TEN-USOPEN-ART-NYT &LR;      09-05 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-USOPEN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR PLAYERS, RAIN BECOMES A FOE AT THE OPEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
may make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ True to the warning of the tournament's in-house
radar sensors, an ill-intentioned weather system clamped down on
the U.S. Open and caused a case of vapor lock on Sunday. Dozens of
matches were delayed by showers, dozens more were postponed, and
according to the disgruntled players who actually experienced the
banana-peel conditions underfoot, their best efforts were sabotaged
by Mother Nature.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in her life, 15th-seeded Amelie Mauresmo
experienced the trauma of staring down a trio of match points
before, during and after a rain delay. She failed to survive it and
was toppled by Germany's 27th-ranked Anke Huber, 6-4, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   For the umpteenth time in her life, Mary Joe Fernandez
experienced a tennis-inflicted injury, but she blamed this one on a
slippery court and a second-set rain delay that was officially
declared an instant too late to save her. The tumble she took on
the rain-slicked Arthur Ashe Stadium destroyed her momentum,
strained her left quadriceps, and gave third-seeded Venus Williams
the extra incentive necessary to pull off a 2-6, 6-1, 6-0 comeback.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely related to the rain,'' a resigned Fernandez said of
her injury. ``As soon as it starts to drizzle, the lines get very
slippery, the court itself gets very slippery.''
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez, who chided herself for not requesting a second-set
stoppage the way she had in the first, said: ``It was too slippery.
But you know, once you get started, you want to keep playing.''
</P>
<P>
   A combination of patience and pinpoint aggression gained the
38th-ranked Fernandez the 27-minute first set, where Williams
committed 18 unforced errors. But the 19-year-old Floridian had
already begun to regroup and owned a 2-0 edge in the second set
when, with Williams serving at deuce under increasingly drizzly
skies, Fernandez fell to the court while attempting a running
backhand.
</P>
<P>
   Her left foot slipped and twisted beneath her as she fell, and
when she hit the court, she sat there immobile until a trainer was
summoned. Williams walked over to check that the injury wasn't
serious, and then went to her change-over chair to wait for
Fernandez to exit the court with her.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the middle of the point, it just started coming down much
harder; the match would have stopped after that point, but it was
in between the point where all the damage came,'' said Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Ninety minutes later, with the rain in abeyance and the court
wiped dry, their match resumed, but when Williams picked up the
pace, Fernandez couldn't follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happened,'' Fernandez said. ``Bad luck. That's the end of
it. I'm not going to overpower Venus Williams.'' Fernandez, who
also had failed to outwit Serena Williams at the French Open before
retiring with a right abductor strain, said, ``If this is the worst
thing that's going to happen to me in my lifetime, I'll take it.''
</P>
<P>
   Strafed by drizzle, the 20-year-old Mauresmo, shakier on these
hard courts than she was in her breakthrough run to the Australian
Open final, had just finished saving one match point and faced two
more when she and Anke Huber were yanked off Louis Armstrong
Stadium for a 22-minute rain break that neither of them welcomed.
</P>
<P>
   When they reconvened, Mauresmo served herself out of immediate
danger at 3-5 of the second set only to grant Huber _ the same
spoiler whose third-round ouster of eight-seeded Jana Novotna left
the Czech veteran pondering retirement _ three more match points.
Huber's latest upset left the French loser visibly irked and sent
the 24-year-old winner into the first Open quarterfinal of her
decade-long career.
</P>
<P>
   Mauresmo felt the intermittent weather interruptions undermined
her concentration.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't know if you're going to get on or not, if it's going
to rain again or not,'' Mauresmo said.
</P>
<P>
   Even Huber allowed the inclement atmosphere to aggravate her:
``I was getting really nervous. I said to myself when it was
raining, `Come on, keep quiet, concentrate, take it easy,' but
somehow I couldn't. Before the match, I just wait; that's not a big
problem. I think when the match started and you have to stop,
that's much worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Ranked a career-best sixth in the world in 1996, the year she
reached the Australian Open final, Huber termed it a coincidence
that her career, hampered last year by foot surgery and Achilles
problems, appears to have revived in tandem with Steffi Graf's
retirement. Huber said she long ago outgrew the stress that came
with being labeled the 30-year-old Graf's heir apparent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, it puts pressure on you if you're 16 and everybody is
telling you, `Second Steffi.' I won a couple matches and she won
already I don't know how many Grand Slams. It's not that easy,''
said Huber, whose topspin forehand was too much for Mauresmo to
decipher on Sunday. ``You always keep saying there's never going to
be another Steffi, maybe not the next 100 or 200 years. Everybody
still is expecting it, maybe.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost three hours later than it was supposed to, day seven
began with an abortive men's singles confrontation between
seventh-seeded Todd Martin and Sweden's oft-injured Magnus Larsson
that seemed to set a precedent for the mayhem that ensued for the
rest of the session.
</P>
<P>
   After having their patience tested for hours by the morning's
showers and on-again, off-again efforts by Arthur Ashe Stadium's
grounds crew to dry the court, fans who had spent anywhere from $41
to $366 for their day session seats booed for a common cause.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-six minutes into the match, Larsson, a three-time Open
quarterfinalist, walked off the court, a default he blamed on a
flare-up of tendinitis in his left knee. It took one set, the
81st-ranked Larsson said, for him to realize his knee didn't just
hurt _ it was collapsible as a toothpick.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who next faces ninth-seeded Greg Rusedski, a 7-5, 3-6,
6-3, 6-4 winner against Chris Woodruff, couldn't decide whether he
was happy about the 6-3 victory that fast-forwarded him into the
Round of 16 or not. ``If I had won in five long sets, then I'd much
rather have only played one,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-99 2249EDT &QL; 
