<HEADLINE>
GLEN MURRAY SIGNS WITH KINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Training camp began for the Kings on Sunday with a
pleasant surprise, the sort of upbeat news absent all of last
season.
</P>
<P>
   On the first day of practice, right wing Glen Murray signed a
new, complex contract, then joined his teammates on the ice.
</P>
<P>
   Murray's contract could last for one, two or three years. The
Kings have the option to renew the contract after each of the first
two years. The signing of the 26-year-old Murray, who earned
$675,000 last year, leaves defenseman Mattias Norstrom as the last
key unsigned King.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy to be in camp with the guys, skating and getting in
game shape,'' said Murray, who scored 16 goals last season, 15 of
them before suffering an injury to his right knee Jan.2. ``I was
going to wait until I thought (the Kings' offer) was right and
fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the structure of the contract, General Manager Dave Taylor
said, ``There's a significant upside for Glen if he performs
well.''
</P>
<P>
   According to agent Anton Thun, Murray will be paid a base salary
of $1.25 million in the first year, plus performance bonuses
ranging from $50,000 to $400,000.
</P>
<P>
   After the first year, the Kings can choose between two salaries
to pay Murray in the second year. One of the salaries is $1.375
million, below the amount projected to be the average NHL salary a
year from now. The other is $1.65 million, above the projected
average. The current average salary is $1.29 million.
</P>
<P>
   The risk for the Kings in the second year is, that if they
choose the lower figure, then opt not to renew Murray's contract
for a third year, he will become an unrestricted free agent before
the 2001-2002 season. If they renew the contract for a third year,
Murray will be paid $1.775 million in 2001-2002. Additionally,
performance bonuses could increase Murray's salary in the second
and third years to the point that he could earn around $2.5 million
in 2001-2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided to be creative to get the deal done,'' Thun said.
</P>
<P>
   New coach Andy Murray was pleased with the resolution of Glen
Murray's negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a coach, you want all the players on board,'' Andy Murray
said. ``What we need from Glen Murray is that he's the player of
two years ago and of the beginning of last year. He knows that.
He's been rewarded with a contract that acknowledges the player he
was before he was injured, not after it.''
</P>
<P>
   Tough to please
</P>
<P>
   How did his first day of practice as an NHL coach compare to his
first day a year ago at a Minnesota prep school?
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the guys, `You guys almost look as good as the kids at
Shattuck-St. Mary's did after the first practice last year,' ''
Andy Murray said.
</P>
<P>
   As for his evaluation of the Kings' practice, Murray said, ``The
execution for the very first practice was good. We looked like a
pretty good hockey team on Sept. 5.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those on the ice was newcomer Ziggy Palffy, the Kings'
most important off-season acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a pretty hard practice for the first day,'' Palffy
said. ``My legs aren't used to it. It's going to be better in a few
days.''
</P>
<P>
   Ice Dog ties
</P>
<P>
   The Kings have hired Rick Burrill as assistant trainer. Burrill
spent the last three years with the Long Beach Ice Dogs. They also
have hired Joe Horrigan as their strength coach. Horrigan has
worked extensively with the Ice Dogs the last few years.
</P>
</TEXT>
