<SLUG> BC-PROTEIN-BIOTECH-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
DNA RESEARCH HAS LED TO PROTEOMICS, THE STUDY OF PROTEINS &HT;    BY TOM ABATE
 &HT;    c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ For years, scientists have been racing to map
the human genome in order to get a complete view of the DNA
blueprint that guides the construction of every aspect of our
bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as the genome map nears completion, other researchers are
studying the essential building blocks produced by DNA: the roughly
100,000 proteins that make up every muscle, nerve and fiber in our
bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Just as gene scientists call their field genomics, protein
mappers have dubbed their study ``proteomics.'' Both efforts have
the same goal: to identify the causes and possible cures for
disease, and speed up the process of developing new drugs.
</P>
<P>
   For now, proteomics remains a fledgling discipline led by tiny
firms like privately held Ciphergen Biosystems Ltd. of Palo Alto,
which has created a new system to automate the process of analyzing
proteins. It might be years before this effort leads to new drugs,
but scientists at Ciphergen already have used their system to find
proteins that could help diagnose schizophrenia.
</P>
<P>
   Leading scientists think this new field with the funny name
could be the next big thing in biotechnology.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, I think we'll come to view proteomics as a
revolution of similar magnitude to what we're going to discover
from other big projects like the Human Genome Project,'' said Keith
Yamamoto, chairman of cellular research at the University of
California at San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   To grasp his optimism, it's necessary to understand a bit about
the body's cellular machinery. Enrique Dalmasso, chief research
scientist at Ciphergen, said it all begins in the nucleus of our
cells, with the DNA molecules that scientists liken to a blueprint.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever cells need to divide or repair themselves, they look to
DNA for instructions. DNA is a double-stranded molecule resembling
a zipper in some regards. To get the job done, DNA unzips itself
and creates a working intermediary called messenger RNA.
</P>
<P>
   If DNA is the blueprint, mRNA is the construction worker. It
uses raw materials called amino acids that are present in the
cells. Following DNA's instructions, mRNA grabs specific amino
acids, in the order laid out in the blueprint, and strings them
together like a pearl necklace. This long string of amino acids
then folds itself _ in ways scientists don't yet fully understand _
to form a protein.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the cell follows a logical process: DNA makes RNA makes
protein. In Dalmasso's construction metaphor, proteins are the
studs and beams that frame the house and the pipes and wires that
run through its the walls. In our bodies, proteins form the
muscles, ligaments, skin and hair. The enzymes that digest our
foods and regulate our moods are proteins, as are germ-killing
antibodies and the hemoglobin that carries oxygen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Proteins form the framework of the body,'' Dalmasso said.
``They are the real actors. Everything that happens in the body
happens because some sets of proteins have interacted with each
other, or provided the pathway for a nerve impulse or signal.''
</P>
<P>
   Given that proteins are vital to the body's proper functioning,
they naturally are of interest to researchers seeking to understand
disease, said Charles Craik, professor of pharmaceutical chemistry
at UCSF.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, most diseases are the manifestation of a malfunction
by some protein or set of proteins. Drugs are the molecular fixes
we throw into the cells to patch over the problems.
</P>
<P>
   As Craik said more precisely: ``Most drugs are small molecules
that hit protein receptors to achieve some desired effect.''
</P>
<P>
   Because drug development mainly is about fixing proteins, one
might wonder why scientists focused on studying DNA. Fred Cohen, a
professor of pharmacology at UCSF, said it makes sense _ in view of
the relationship between DNA and proteins, and the fact that DNA is
much easier to study.
</P>
<P>
   The latter point is easiest to explain.
</P>
<P>
   DNA is made up of four basic chemicals that repeat themselves in
a predictable pattern. That predictability has allowed scientists
to devise instruments that automatically ``read'' the genetic
pattern from a tissue sample, in the same way bar code scanners
pick prices off grocery items.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, proteins are made up of 20 different amino acids
that fold and twist according to rules scientists don't yet
understand. ``If I understand the shape of one protein, it isn't
much help in figuring out the next protein,'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   Lacking tools to automate the study of proteins, scientists have
used DNA scanners as proxies to identify proteins of particular
interest, Cohen said. It doesn't take the whole DNA molecule to
make a protein. Instead, if we imagine DNA as a long freight train,
each car in the train would be a gene. Each gene contains the
blueprint for a different protein.
</P>
<P>
   So bioscientists have followed a two-step strategy, Cohen says.
They've used high-speed DNA scanners to find genes involved in
important functions, like building heart muscles. Once these genes
have been identified, scientists do the time-consuming studies of
the proteins made by these genes _ for instance, trying to
understand the protein defects involved in heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``Studying genes has been the best way to pick the targets for
your drug-development efforts,'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   Now proteomics vendors are promising to hand scientists a new
generation of instruments that partially can automate protein
analysis in much the same way that previous generations of
instruments sped up DNA studies. No one expects protein tools to
displace the gene scanners. Instead, proteomics tools should
augment current DNA screening by making it easier to design drugs,
once interesting protein targets are found.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we've done is to put a lot of the complicated chemistry
needed to do protein analysis onto a chip,'' said Dalmasso, the
Ciphergen scientist.
</P>
<P>
   Although Ciphergen is only one of several proteomics vendors _
others include Oxford GlycoSciences of the United Kingdom and Large
Scale Biology Corp., a division of Biosource Technologies in
Vacaville _ its ProteinChip System has won the company considerable
attention.
</P>
<P>
   The process begins with the chips, thin strips of aluminum
coated with chemicals designed to grab and hold certain types of
proteins. Scientists grind up tissues they want to study to create
a protein ``soup.'' They deposit a few drops on the chip and insert
it into a device about the size of a two-drawer filing cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   This ProteinChip reader contains a laser and sophisticated scale
that work together to identify the microscopic quantities of
protein by measuring their molecular weight. Professor Bob
Vessella, a prostate cancer researcher at the Unversity of
Washington in Seattle, said that the first week his lab used the
ProteinChip reader, it completed three experiments his staff had
been working on for months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until now, protein analysis has been something of an art,''
Vessella said. First, scientists would have to isolate and purify
large batches of protein. Then, they would submit these purified
samples to a long series of tests that could be wrecked by the
slightest contamination or error. And it all took a lot of time.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, he said the chip can analyze a few drops of
protein, eliminating the need to grow large samples. The reader is
faster and more precise than current, labor-intensive methods.
</P>
<P>
   ``They haven't invented any new science,'' he said. ``But the
ability to put all that really difficult protein analysis into a
black box is really phenomenal.''
</P>
<P>
   Dalmasso said Ciphergen has sold about 50 of its ProteinChip
readers since the company was formed in 1997. Most of these
$150,000 instruments have been placed at academic labs doing basic
disease research.
</P>
<P>
   Commercial biotech firms are evaluating proteomics tools but
have not seemed in a rush to embrace this new wave.
</P>
<P>
   ``The study of genes is not going to give us all the answers,
and we know that,'' said Paul Godowski, director of molecular
biology for Genentech Inc. ``We're interested in proteomics, but I
wouldn't exactly say it was central to our research efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Paul Kelly with ING Baring Furman Selz in New York
estimates the current market for protein-analysis equipment at $500
million annually, about one-third of what is spent on genomics
instruments. Ciphergen's systems, he said, ``should become
important components'' of this protein analysis market.
</P>
<P>
   Ciphergen isn't talking yet about a public offering, though the
60-person firm clearly is headed that way. It has raised a modest
$25 million from venture backers. John Young, former chief
executive of Hewlett-Packard, is Ciphergen's chairman. William
Rich, a former pharmaceutical company executive, is its chief
executive.
</P>
<P>
   Rich is an evangelist for proteomics in general and Ciphergen in
particular. He likens the ProteinChip System to past advances in
biotechnology, like invention in the mid-1980s of polymerase chain
reaction, or PCR, the technique that allowed scientists to grow DNA
and RNA in samples large enough to study.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen, however, whether proteomics tools will be
as important as PCR or later advances, like the invention of
DNA-sequencing equipment in the late 1980s and early 1990s by firms
like Affymetrix, PE Applied Biosystems and Molecular Dynamics.
</P>
<P>
   But Cohen, the UCSF expert, said bioscience always has been
driven by tools and techniques. As far back as the invention of the
microscope some 350 years ago, medical science has been a continual
tinkering exercise that makes great leaps whenever the tinkerers
get new tools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Discovery,'' Cohen said, ``is driven by the industrialization
of fundamental molecular biology experiments.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-99 2308EDT &QL; 
