<SLUG> BC-OBIT-ROSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
E.J.B. ROSE, 89, WARTIME MILITARY ANALYST 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By NICK RAVO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   E.J.B. ``Jim'' Rose, who worked with the legendary British code
breakers at Bletchley Park during World War II, died on May 20 in
Sussex, England. He was 89.
</P>
<P>
   The advance knowledge of German plans, so laboriously deciphered
at Bletchley Park, helped Britain when it was fighting alone
against the Nazis, and Rose was head of the section that determined
the military importance of the information they received.
</P>
<P>
   Rose later became a noted journalist, a publisher and a
ground-breaking surveyor of race relations in Great Britain,
serving as director of the Survey of Race Relations. In 1969 he
published ``Color and Citizenship,'' a report on the country's
integration and immigration problems, with Nicholas Deakin.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, however, Rose was best remembered for his
exploits during World War II as an analyst of broken German
military codes and as a liaison between British cryptologists and
higher military authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Rose was at times critical of Allied intelligence reports.
According to The Daily Telegraph, he and a colleague, Alan
Pryce-Jones, visited the American general Kenneth Strong, who was
Gen. Dwight D. Eisenhower's intelligence chief, three weeks before
the costly German counterattack that became known as the Battle of
the Bulge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Strong said the Germans were losing a division a day and
wouldn't hold,'' Rose said. ``Alan was just a major, but he sat on
the edge of the general's desk and said: `My dear sir, if you
believe that, you'll believe anything.'''
</P>
<P>
   Eliot Joseph Benn Rose was born on June 7, 1909, to a well-off
Jewish family. After attending Rugby and New College, Oxford, where
he spent his spare time working with Jewish refugees in the East
End of London, Rose joined the Royal Air Force in 1939.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, Rose moved to the government's cryptology
school at Bletchley Park, where he became adept at assessing the
intelligence value of the code decrypted from the Luftwaffe, the
German air force.
</P>
<P>
   He left the RAF as a wing commander in 1948 and, after a brief
flirtation with political office, joined the staff of The Observer,
at the time an influential weekly Sunday newspaper, as literary
editor. Among his reviewers was George Orwell.
</P>
<P>
   Three years later he became the founding director of the
International Press Institute in Zurich, Switzerland, established
with the backing of the Ford Foundation with the aim of maintaining
a free press in the Cold War era.
</P>
<P>
   Rose returned to England in 1963 when he was asked by Philip
Mason, the director of the Institute of Race Relations in Great
Britain, to serve as the chairman of the survey of race relations.
</P>
<P>
   Six years later, Rose became editorial director of Westminster
Press, and in 1973 chairman of Penguin Books, where he oversaw the
company's acquisition of Viking, a publisher in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Rose was a consultant to UNICEF and served on a government
committee on education of ethnic minority children.
</P>
<P>
   He also was instrumental in the formation of the Runnymede
Trust, a race research center, and served as its chairman from 1980
to 1990.
</P>
<P>
   For his work during World War II, he was awarded the Legion of
Merit. For his work studying racism, he was appointed a Commander
of the British Empire.
</P>
<P>
   Rose, who lived in Kent, is survived by his wife, Pamela; a son,
Alan, and a daughter, Harriet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
