<SLUG> BC-BIOSCOPE-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
ANALYSTS SKEPTICAL OF STRENGTH BEHIND BIOTECH INDEX'S RECORD HIGH &HT;    By TOM ABATE
 &HT;    c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Amex biotech stock index has soared to
record highs. Wall Street, it seems, suddenly can't buy its fill of
the index's biggest firms.
</P>
<P>
   Driven by high-profile issues like Amgen, Genentech and Biogen,
the index gained another 14 points Friday (September 3) to close at
284.75, comfortably exceeding its previous peak of 256.60 in
January 1992. Chiron also has helped goose the index. Its stock
closed at a record $33.44 last week, amid speculation that Novartis
AG, the Swiss drugmaker that owns 44 percent of Chiron, wants to
acquire the rest of it.
</P>
<P>
   But the index only tracks 15 of the biggest companies, and
veteran industry watchers aren't sure the rally will lift biotech's
400 smaller players _ much less open the window for private
startups to go public.
</P>
<P>
   Richard van den Broek, a biotech analyst for Hambrecht &AMP; Quist
in New York, said that though big biotech stocks have been doing
well for the past two years, the current rally is starting to look
exceptional.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time in recent memory,'' he said, big biotech
stocks are outperforming shares of large drug companies. Van den
Broek thinks the rally isn't just confined to the big firms, but
``has also broadened out to include select, promising second- and
third-tier companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Among his favorite up-and-comers, van den Broek lists LeukoSite
Inc., a Cambridge, Mass., firm working on cancer and autoimmune
drugs; Pharmacyclics Inc., a Sunnyvale, Calif., company developing
ways to increase the potency of radiation and chemotherapy; and two
firms, Medarex of New Jersey and Abegenix of Fremont, Calif., that
are developing mice whose cells produce human antibodies, which
would form the basis for new drugs.
</P>
<P>
   But Bill Slattery, who manages Amerindo Investment Advisors'
biotech fund, is suspicious of the surge, partly because of its
timing. ``Summer is usually the slow season for biotech,'' said
Slattery, who thinks the current run is being driven by momentum
players who don't understand that biotech stocks can take five to
10 years to pay off.
</P>
<P>
   ``The seasoned life sciences investor is not buying into this
rally,'' Slattery warned. ``They're probably taking some profit.''
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco investment banker Steve Burrill is another skeptic
who thinks the current rally won't provide any lasting help for the
lagging stocks at the low end of the sector.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll have some companies that will go up on the momentum or
some bit of good scientific news,'' Burrill said. ``But if you
watch a few days or months, they'll probably come back down.''
</P>
<P>
   Burrill said he won't be ready to proclaim a broad recovery
until Wall Street warms up to biotech IPOs. ``I don't think
institutions are ready yet for a raft of new biotech offerings,''
he said. ``Their portfolios are still loaded with life sciences
plays that haven't performed up to expectation.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Morrison, a biotech consultant with Ernst &AMP; Young in Palo
Alto, Calif., is more optimistic about biotech companies using the
current momentum to go public. He notes that Vaxgen, a South San
Francisco (Calif.) firm working on AIDS vaccines, and BioMarin
Pharmaceutical, a genetic disease firm in Novato, Calif., both
completed public offerings earlier this summer _ and both still are
trading above their offering prices.
</P>
<P>
   Emboldened by their example, Oratec Interventions of Menlo Park,
Calif., filed an IPO in July to test Wall Street's appetite for a
new, minimally invasive surgical technique to repair ligaments and
other soft tissue.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least a dozen other local biotech companies are in serious
discussions with investment bankers,'' Morrison said.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean all will take the plunge. Morrison doesn't
envision a repeat of what happened after biotech bounced back from
its latest slump in June 1995, when 62 firms raised $1.7 billion
from IPOs in 13 months.
</P>
<P>
   But at least the outlook isn't as bleak as it was a year ago,
when the public markets appeared completely closed to new
offerings.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Flores, publisher of BioCentury newsletter in San Carlos,
Calif., said he'll have more good tidings to report in this week's
edition. ``Everybody thinks money for startups has dried up, but
our figures will show venture money has been a lot more plentiful
than people think,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-99 2314EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
