<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-05 23:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1880 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-OUTTAKES-COLUMN-SFCHR     09-05 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTTAKES-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
GIVING BIRTH TO A WEB STARTUP _ AND A BABY &HT;    BY STAN BUNGER AND JAN BOYD
 &HT;    c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Josh Newman, the guy who in college could always
be spotted with his dog sitting under his chair during class,
decided last year to launch a Web startup called Petstore.com. At
the same time, Newman and his wife, Martha Diepenbrock, decided to
expand their family and adopt a baby.
</P>
<P>
   As the saying goes, timing is everything _ especially when
trying to adopt or raise venture capital funding. There's also
another saying: Life can get complicated.
</P>
<P>
   About six months ago, Newman and his wife got the call _ the
birth mother of their child had gone into labor _ four hours east
of Dallas in the small town of Nacogdoches, Texas. At the same
time, Newman and his team were entering the final round of
negotiations for their initial round of funding.
</P>
<P>
   On the morning of March 9, Newman sat in the hospital maternity
ward in Nacogdoches, cell phone in hand and computer perched on his
lap. The negotiations were tense because Amazon.com had just
announced that it, too, was going to sell pet products and the
funders were nervous. They demanded one more face-to-face meeting
to be convinced that Petstore.com could compete before they would
hand over a check.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, a healthy little girl entered the world, and at 3 p.m.,
Newman turned off his electronic gear long enough to take his
family back to the hotel and catch a little nap, his new infant
daughter, Zoe, asleep on his chest. At 6 p.m., Newman drove the
four hours back to Dallas, caught a midnight flight to the San
Francisco Bay Area, landed in his office at 1 a.m., worked all
night with his team in Oakland and arrived for a 6 a.m.
presentation meeting in San Mateo, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   After the meeting, Newman jumped back into his Celica
convertible and once again headed for the airport. ``At this point,
I felt like I was in the Twilight Zone,'' said Newman. The cell
phone rang; the funders were satisfied; now the term sheet needed
to be agreed upon. Newman talked all the way onto the plane. Once
he reached Dallas, his team read the terms over the phone, Newman
approved the signing and they all celebrated the $10 million
windfall for a few seconds. Then it was off to the rental car
counter and Nacogdoches to collect his newly expanded family.
</P>
<P>
   Newman reports that Zoe is growing up happy and healthy and that
the company is growing, too, up from four to 90 employees. He's
also careful to give credit to a person largely responsible for his
success in both ventures: ``I couldn't have done this without my
wife, Martha.''
</P>
<P>
   THE BUS STOPS HERE: Technology has taken on a lot of challenges.
There's software to help the disorganized get organized, and there
are digital cameras designed to let even the fumble-fingered take
decent pictures. And then there's the Muni Railway.
</P>
<P>
   The transit system San Franciscans love to hate represents not
only a challenge, but a business opportunity for Emeryville's
NextBus Information Systems. The startup company's technology first
was deployed on Muni's 22-Fillmore trolley line. A combination of
wireless devices and software lets NextBus predict when the next
coach will roll up to a given bus stop.
</P>
<P>
   The information can be flashed onto an electronic display at bus
stops or accessed via the Internet. While the system won't
necessarily keep buses on schedule, it will at least let passengers
know how long they'll be waiting. Muni officials were pleased
enough with NextBus' performance on the 22 line that they've
awarded the company a $900,000 contract to install the system on
the entire Muni Metro streetcar fleet.
</P>
<P>
   NextBus Chief Operating Officer Jim Maresca said skeptics
abounded when the company first started touting its bus-locating
technology. ``Everybody said, `If you could actually do that, we'd
be interested in buying,''' recalled Maresca, ``but you've got to
show us you can do it first.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Maresca says NextBus is negotiating with a half-dozen other
transit systems for contracts.
</P>
<P>
   There are still some kinks to be worked out. Sometimes, a
streetside display will indicate a bus' imminent arrival when
there's no bus to be seen. And recently, an elderly man waited for
the bus at Fillmore and Sutter streets in San Francisco. When asked
if he liked the idea of knowing when the next bus would arrive, he
spun the conversation toward a discussion of user interface and
ergonomics.
</P>
<P>
   Seems the digital readout was mounted too high off the ground
for him to be able to read it.
</P>
<P>
   SEGA HAS A DREAM: Once upon a time, Sega was king of the video
game mountain. In 1993, Sega's Genesis game machine was going
strong and the company owned more than 50 percent of the market.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Nintendo and Sony's fortunes have soared, while
Sega's has plummeted. Industry analysts agree that Sega's market
share has dipped to single digits.
</P>
<P>
   And so, Thursday's (Sept. 9) scheduled North American launch of
Sega's new Dreamcast game system is a Very Big Deal for San
Francisco's Sega of America. Sega is spending $100 million on a
massive marketing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The effort already has produced such gems as a San Francisco
motorcade, in which police officers escorted a convertible carrying
somebody in a Sonic the Hedgehog costume. ``Isn't a hedgehog sort
of like a skunk?'' asked one cop.
</P>
<P>
   At the same event, dozens of young video game fans showed up in
blue paint (matching Sonic's skin tone), hoping to win free video
games and cash in on a ``dress-alike'' contest. The winners' checks
were handed out by Sega of America Senior Vice President of
Marketing Peter Moore, who appeared to be the only guy in the crowd
wearing a necktie.
</P>
<P>
   It's Moore's job to push product, and he makes a brave
prediction, saying Dreamcast will set a new entertainment-industry
record for single-day sales. ``When we looked during our research,
`The Phantom Menace' did $28.1 million in its first 24 hours,''
Moore said. ``We believe we will be somewhere in excess of $60 to
$70 million at retail that day.'' If numbers like those really
materialize on Thursday, nobody will be feeling too blue around
Sega's offices.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
