<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-BUCHANAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOWN SO LONG, BUCHANAN AND THE FALCONS DEAL WITH SUCCESS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill.)  (rk) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thirty-three years of foiled plans and churning heartache were
dissolved in one season for the Atlanta Falcons. In 1998 they won
their first division title since 1980, won the most games in
franchise history (16), scored their most points ever (511), were
unbeaten at home in the Georgia Dome (9-0) and reached their first
Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the night before the championship game, safety Eugene
Robinson was arrested on charges of soliciting a prostitute. Hours
later the Falcons were smacked, 34-19, by the Denver Broncos in
Super Bowl XXXIII.
</P>
<P>
   Way down. Way up. Way down again.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons' off-season shook out this way: Robinson was
retained, receiver Tony Martin and linebacker Cornelius Bennett
were released and star running back Jamal Anderson returned despite
trade rumors and a contract holdout.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as the Falcons prepare for their season opener on Sunday at
home against the Minnesota Vikings _ a rematch of last season's
tingling National Football Conference championship game _ the
Falcons realize they are not the same team.
</P>
<P>
   They are, they hope, a little wiser. Certainly more seasoned.
Hungry enough, they envision, for that final push over the top in
Super Bowl XXXIV. The game on Jan. 30, 2000, will be played in the
Georgia Dome.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got to the Super Bowl in the '98 season and blew up,''
linebacker Jessie Tuggle said. ``We have to distinguish that this
is the '99 season. Last year is behind us. Now we have to work
twice as hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Falcons Coach Dan Reeves said a lot must change.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the hunted now,'' Reeves said. ``We are the defending
NFC champions and the intensity is going to be greater. San
Francisco ruled our division for so long; they want it back. And we
start the season against the team we beat to get to the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, Minnesota is awfully good, but throughout this league,
who is the lesser opponent? We won some close games last year
against some teams that finished 5-11 or worse. Just a point here
or there can change everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Few Falcons know the pulse of the team like cornerback Ray
Buchanan. Like the Falcons, he was down for a long time before he
rose, glimmering.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened with Eugene did affect our team some in the
Super Bowl and there is no denying that,'' Buchanan said. ``It drew
a lot of unnecessary attention to our football team and it was a
tough situation to handle. I was up with Eugene until 3:30 that
morning until I saw his eyes begin to fall asleep. Before we went
on the field, I looked into his eyes, and he was ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw the biggest moments of a lifetime. The cameras were
flashing. The jets were flying overhead. And then we went out and
played so uncharacteristic of our season. We missed tackles. They
picked us apart on a long bomb. We didn't punch the ball in near
the goal line. We didn't make that fourth-down conversion early in
the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eugene has a chance now to grab back some of his football
legacy. We've been a franchise that's been at the bottom of the
food chain, but now we know what it's like to be at the top. The
Super Bowl can spoil you, though. When I first got to this team
three years ago, I had my mind set for patience. I looked around
the locker room and saw a bunch of studs, but guys who didn't play
like studs. There were some bad seeds. These are good times now. If
we want it enough, the stage is set for more.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan grew up near Chicago playing football at Proviso High,
which won two games and lost 36 during his prep career.
</P>
<P>
   He was switched from running back and receiver to safety at the
University of Louisville. He did not win many games in college, but
Louisville did beat Alabama in the Fiesta Bowl, and Buchanan was
the game's most valuable player. That caught the attention of pro
scouts.
</P>
<P>
   He was selected by the Indianapolis Colts in the third round of
the 1993 draft, and he played there for four seasons. He was
shuffled from safety to cornerback. And then Reeves called in 1997
and asked Buchanan, then a free agent, to come and be part of the
foundation for the new Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ray was the first move I made,'' said Reeves, who became the
Falcons' head coach on Jan. 20 of that year and signed Buchanan on
March 3. ``We had to improve our defense and we needed an
aggressive cornerback to help do it. Finding those type of corners,
ones who can cover the other team's best receiver all day and shut
them down, is very difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Before 1998, Buchanan describes himself as a ``diamond in the
rough'' on teams that struggled. Then came last season, his first
Pro Bowl season, and a spot in the Super Bowl. He sought the
cameras and the newspaper coverage, and they came to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I wore the dog collar at the Super Bowl media day, I was
saying that we were underdogs, so why not go with it?'' Buchanan
said. ``Then our fans started wearing them and it was fun. Now,
you've also got to be smart and know how to market yourself. Some
guys like Barry Sanders and Darrell Green are recognized solely for
their ability. Some guys like me have to do a little more and then
you see my ability and appreciate it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, and sometimes I get bored and just do stuff. It's my
personality. I am a confident, happy person, outgoing and
outspoken, and I like to joke and have fun. That's always been me.
But I play cornerback on the edge. I don't think of being average;
I think of being feared. I'm not the vocal type with our team,
though. I just try and make plays and let that be contagious.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan, who turns 28 later this month, is only 5 feet 10
inches and weighs 185 pounds. As he enters his seventh pro season,
he has already produced three seasons with five or more
interceptions, has started in 82 of 93 career games and has led his
team in passes defended in each of his last five seasons. He makes
big plays at big times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ray is a unique character,'' Tuggle said. ``He has endless
energy. He loves to compete. He has very quick feet, recognizes
plays and can accelerate. There are few like him in pro football at
cornerback with the exception of Deion Sanders. There is a lot of
respect here for Ray and his ability. We count on him.''
</P>
<P>
   To shut down the opponent's best receiver. To make game-swinging
plays. To be the team's conscience and inspiration. To help lead
the Falcons back to the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go out and light the spark,'' Buchanan said. ``And even if I
don't have matches to light the fire, I'll go out there with rocks
and create a fire. And it will spread.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
