<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-CAMPAIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW RACE, BUT OLD WALK ON THE BEACH FOR BRADLEY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Mo.)  (lb) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPRING LAKE, N.J. _ The storm-whipped winds had been lashing the
beach all day Sunday, driving dark clouds before them, roiling the
surf and forcing summer's last vacationers out of the water, when
former Sen. Bill Bradley stepped onto the boardwalk for an
afternoon of handshaking.
</P>
<P>
   Call it dumb luck, or call it a good omen, as Bradley did. But
at that very moment, the sun broke through the clouds in this town
south of Asbury Park, briefly warming the small crowd that had
gathered in their tank tops, swimsuits and sandals to welcome
Bradley on his annual Labor Day political pilgrimage to the beach.
</P>
<P>
   But this was no ordinary beach walk for Bradley _ who has done
this nostalgia-laced event for 19 of the last 21 years _ and so the
weather was more welcome than ever. For Bradley is running for the
Democratic nomination for president, and Sunday's stroll was a
kickoff of sorts for his national campaign. (He will make another
kickoff in his hometown of Crystal City, Mo., later this week.)
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my good luck charm,'' Bradley said, gesturing toward
the beach as if it were his home court. ``There are a lot of good
omens out there.''
</P>
<P>
   The clutch of more than 20 reporters tailing him was the largest
ever, his aides said, and included television crews from Britain.
Instead of his usual small coterie of aides, he brought several
carloads this year. And the beachgoers' enthusiasm for their
favorite-son presidential candidate seemed louder than in past
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take a french fry, Bill,'' shouted Gloria Hennessy, 64, from
Point Pleasant. ``You're the best. You're going to the White
House.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked later why she liked Bradley, who represented New Jersey in
the U.S. Senate for three terms and still lives in Montclair, Ms.
Hennessy said, ``He's honest and he played basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   But if things around him seemed somehow different than in past
years, Bradley looked and acted every bit the same. As he has on
all his beach walks, he wore the sort of informal clothes he did 30
years ago, when he was playing professional basketball for the New
York Knicks: forest-green shorts, size-13 Adidas sneakers and
orange-and-blue socks that were balling up around his ankles from
the moment he stepped out of his car.
</P>
<P>
   And if Bradley was charged up about kicking off his campaign, he
did his best to hide it. He just wandered up to people, offered his
hand without introducing himself, asked a question or two, and then
ambled off. He did not kiss any babies, except his own
grandchildren, and did not ask anyone to vote for him.
</P>
<P>
   There were a few questions to be answered, mainly from
reporters. At a brief news conference along the arcade in Point
Pleasant a few miles to the south, Bradley was asked by an English
reporter about those ``dogging questions'' concerning his being too
vague about his agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley replied that he had already offered detailed proposals
to require registration of handguns and to revamp campaign-finance
laws, and would soon be releasing more on health care, the economy
and preserving people's pensions. ``I don't feel dogged,'' he said,
adding, ``I feel like we're going out and telling the people what I
believe and what I want to do and who I am and where I came from.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-99 2342EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990905.0214 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-05 23:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1887 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-ENCEPHALITIS-660&AMP;A     09-05 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ENCEPHALITIS-660&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENCEPHALITIS THREAT MEANS INDOOR HOLIDAY FOR MANY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Loretta Sikiric was outside grilling sausages early
Saturday evening when she heard the thucka-thucka of a helicopter
flying low over her home in Whitestone, Queens. She watched it
swoop in and dump its payload: a pesticide that officials say has
mostly eliminated the mosquitoes responsible for an outbreak of St.
Louis encephalitis, a viral disease that has killed two elderly
people in Queens and may have sickened as many as 37 others.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Sikiric, 52, rushed into the house and stood with her arms
outstretched, a stricken look on her face. ``They sprayed me!'' she
announced dramatically to her daughter, Sania Recupero, before
running upstairs to take a shower. The sausages had to be thrown
out.
</P>
<P>
   Recounting the scene Sunday, Mrs. Recupero said: ``She got
scared. She was not a happy woman, let me tell you.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Sikiric was far from alone. The encephalitis outbreak,
confirmed by city officials on Friday, and the ensuing emergency
operations undertaken by the city have spread consternation across
northeastern Queens and the southeastern Bronx, residents said
Sunday, and ruined the Labor Day weekend for thousands of people.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Sunday morning, city emergency management
officials said that the spraying of pesticide by helicopter on
Friday and Saturday had been successful and that they believed the
greatest danger had passed. As of Sunday afternoon, the number of
confirmed cases of encephalitis remained at five, including the two
deaths, the same as the day before, they said.
</P>
<P>
   But in the affected areas, backyard barbecues and other
festivities were called off. Frightened families remained shuttered
indoors, with insect repellent at the ready for anyone who needed
to run essential errands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been keeping the kids in the house,'' said Steve
Lauritano, who lives in Whitestone. ``We're worried about the bugs.
We're not using our pool right now. We have been staying inside.''
</P>
<P>
   Lauritano had gone out only to pick up insect repellent. The
Mayor's Office of Emergency Management had set up a command center
in Whitestone to direct the anti-mosquito operations, and Fire
Department personnel distributed free canisters of the repellent,
part of a $115,000 supply that city officials hastily bought after
the the outbreak was confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   Jerome Hauer, the director of the emergency management office,
said Sunday that most of the adult mosquito population in
northeastern Queens had been killed. He said officials were now
focused on killing larvae to preventnew mosquitoes from developing
and were targeting abandoned tires and stagnant water that could
serve as breeding grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Hauer said the city would provide free chlorine treatments or
pesticides to residents who want to clean their swimming pools. And
he said that sanitation and transportation workers would continue
to pick up abandoned tires and remove them for shredding and
disposal.
</P>
<P>
   At Sunday's news conference, Dr. Neal Cohen, the city health
commissioner, said that all three of the people who were confirmed
to be suffering from St. Louis encephalitis remained seriously ill
and were being treated at area hospitals. Officials have declined
to reveal their names or those of the two elderly people known to
have died from the disease.
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. Cohen said all three of the remaining confirmed cases
involved residents of Queens who are over 65. The elderly and
infants are considered the most susceptible to the disease, which
originates in birds and is transmitted to humans by mosquitoes.
</P>
<P>
   At least 34 other people had exhibited some symptoms known to be
associated with St. Louis encephalitis, including fever, headaches
and stiff necks or muscles, officials said. Officials said 31
people were in hospitals and all were being monitored by the city
Health Department and officials from the federal Centers for
Disease Control and Prevention in Atlanta.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But even as officials stressed that there was minimal danger of
contracting the disease, city residents continued to express
concern throughout the day. Officials said that by Sunday afternoon
more than 7,000 people had called the city's special telephone
number with questions and concerns, and that about 300 calls an
hour were still coming in.
</P>
<P>
   City health officials said that the pesticide sprayed in the
Bronx and in Queens, malathion, posed little or no health risk to
humans. But they had urged residents to stay indoors with windows
closed and air conditioning off while the spraying was done.
</P>
</TEXT>
