<SLUG> BC-NY-JEWS-SECURITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JEWISH GROUPS TIGHTEN SECURITY FOR HIGH HOLY DAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By TINA KELLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After a year of high-profile anti-Semitic violence,
including a shooting at a Jewish community center in Los Angeles,
Jewish groups in the New York metropolitan region are planning
increased security during the approaching High Holy Days.
</P>
<P>
   Extra police patrols, private security guards and new alarms and
surveillance cameras are some of the measures that will be employed
from Rosh Hashana through Yom Kippur, a solemn 10-day period of
repentance and introspection.
</P>
<P>
   Security during the High Holy Days has been a concern for the
past 10 or 15 years, but this year, congregations are more
concerned than usual, said Abraham H. Foxman, national director of
the Anti-Defamation League of B'nai B'rith.
</P>
<P>
   At Temple Beth Chai in Hauppauge, the site of arson in August,
worshippers should see a police presence at holiday services, said
Rabbi Laurence Bazer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've asked the Police Department to have a patrol officer
here, just to relieve any fear and increase comfort,'' Bazer said.
There are no suspects in the fire, which destroyed the synagogue's
office, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Howard Buechler, head of the Dix Hills Jewish Center, a
Conservative congregation of 650 families on Long Island, said the
synagogue was installing alarm systems and enough security cameras
to provide a 360-degree view of the building. The synagogue is
hiring more off-duty police officers to provide security than in
past years, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Rosh Hashana, the Jewish New Year, begins at sundown on Friday,
and Yom Kippur, the Day of Atonement, starts the night of Sept. 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a result of Sacramento and Chicago and L.A., there's a
degree of anxiety,'' Foxman of the Anti-Defamation League said,
referring to a number of recent attacks.
</P>
<P>
   In June, three of the five synagogues in Sacramento, Calif.,
were burned in arson fires, and anti-Semitic fliers were found at
two of the sites. In Illinois, Benjamin Smith went on a shooting
rampage against blacks, Asians and Jews, killing two people over
the Fourth of July weekend, the authorities said. And a man faces
attempted murder charges in the shooting of five people, including
three children, last month at the North Valley Jewish Community
Center in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Hassid, executive director of the Jewish Community Center
on the Hudson in Tarrytown, said his group was improving its
security after the Los Angeles shootings. The suspect, Buford
Furrow, who is also accused of shooting and killing a
Filipino-American mail carrier, had called the attack ``a wake-up
call to America to kill Jews,'' the authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   The center in Tarrytown, which runs a nursery school, an
after-school program, day camps and clubs for the elderly, now has
plans for staff identification badges, entryway monitors, a panic
button that would summon the police, and a requirement that
everyone sign in.
</P>
<P>
   In upper Manhattan, a spokeswoman for the Jewish Community
Council of Washington Heights and Inwood said that the police would
patrol areas near synagogues 24 hours a day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-99 2349EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
