u a BC-MILLION-YOUTH-MARCH-N     09-05 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLION-YOUTH-MARCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACKSON RECALLS WHEN JEWS AND BLACKS MARCHED AS ONE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DAVID BARSTOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ His voice was all weary and worn out. But the church
was hushed, and it was time to talk, time to resurrect the details
of history _ those crucial moments during the great struggles of a
fading century when blacks and Jews fought together for the same
causes.
</P>
<P>
   In a robe of green so luminous that he seemed to shimmer in
Sunday's milky morning light, the Rev. Jesse Jackson recalled
Jewish lawyers who joined with Thurgood Marshall to defeat
segregation. He recalled black soldiers who liberated Jews from
German death camps. He recalled blacks and Jews who joined forces
to pass anti-lynching laws, to fight for labor rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the century ends, what should we tell our children?'' he
had asked at the outset of his sermon at Riverside Church in
northern Manhattan. Near the end of his remarks, he answered the
question. ``Tell them,'' he said in tremulous voice, ``haters will
lose.''
</P>
<P>
   When he was finished, hundreds of worshippers _ black and white
_ stood and gave him a warm ovation. Some wiped away tears. Jackson
simply beamed and raised his hand in a gesture of appreciation.
</P>
<P>
   Though he never mentioned Khallid Abdul Muhammad by name,
Jackson clearly meant to remind New Yorkers of the bonds between
blacks and Jews, bonds that had been tested in the last few weeks
by Muhammad's daily displays of anti-Semitism.
</P>
<P>
   Again on Saturday, during his second annual Million Youth March
in Harlem, Muhammad punctuated his demands for black separatism by
portraying whites and Jews as the mortal enemies of black people.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, speaking with reporters after his sermon, suggested
that the sparse crowd at Saturday's rally showed that the great
majority of blacks reject Muhammad's views and his leadership.
</P>
<P>
   But while Jackson condemned Muhammad for ``inciting'' hatred
with his inflammatory words, he also called Muhammad a ``voice of
alienation and despair,'' and he argued that people should be even
more offended by ``the realities'' of economic distress that have
helped to produce such voices.
</P>
<P>
   Citing crumbling schools, abuses by the police and the failure
of Wall Street to invest in places like Harlem, Jackson said, ``So
long as there is alienation and pain, there will be voices of
alienation and pain.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson is no stranger to the subject of the relationship
between blacks and Jews in the United States. In 1984, during his
presidential campaign, Jackson referred to Jews as ``Hymies'' and
to New York as ``Hymietown,'' for which he subsequently apologized.
In the years since, Jackson has worked to solidify relations
between blacks and Jews.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, speaking at a Jersey City, N.J., memorial for Holocaust
victims, he called for ``the sons and daughters of the Holocaust''
to find common ground ``with the grandsons and granddaughters of
slavery.'' In 1992, he assisted in arranging for a documentary film
about black GIs liberating a German concentration camp to be shown
at the Apollo Theater. Two years later, after the Anti-Defamation
League bought newspaper advertisements to publicize Muhammad's
anti-Semitic speeches, Jackson quickly denounced the remarks.
</P>
<P>
   But beyond their differing views toward Jews, Jackson and
Muhammad offer distinctly different visions for the future of
blacks in the United States. Muhammad insistently calls for blacks
to disengage from whites at all levels. On Saturday, for example,
he urged blacks to form separate schools and separate ``people's
militias,'' and he recommended against blacks marrying whites.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, by contrast, argued Sunday for blacks to finish the job
of integration, saying that it had led to huge economic and
political gains for blacks.
</P>
<P>
   Today, he said, the most important fault lines in America divide
not by race, but by economic and educational standing. To overcome
what he described as an ``opportunity gap,'' it seems only natural
for blacks and Jews, given their history of shared scars, to again
join forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a century of struggle together,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-99 2350EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
