<DOCNO> NYT19990905.0217 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-05 23:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1893 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-INTERNET-WARS-NY     09-05 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-INTERNET-WARS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: INTERNET WARS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: The word AT in parentheses has been used instead of the
symbol, which is non-transmittable to many newspaper systems.) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, Sept. 6:
</P>
<P>
   With each new technological advance, the Internet beckons as a
rich and competitive playing field for business, communication and
entertainment. One of the most promising recent innovations is
high-speed Internet access through upgraded cable television lines.
Before long, these lines are expected to offer a nearly limitless
variety of television programs, movies, music, face-to-face
telephones, commercial transactions and other interactive services.
</P>
<P>
   But that lucrative prospect has produced a battle royal in
cyberspace. It revolves around AT&AMP;T's acquisition of major cable
systems as well as its big stake in Excite(AT)Home, an Internet
service provider that would give AT&AMP;T customers access to the World
Wide Web. The fear is that by controlling both the cable and the
avenue to the Internet, AT&AMP;T can dictate where users can go and
what to buy.
</P>
<P>
   The alarms are understandable. America Online, with more than 18
million customers, has joined with other Internet companies and
consumer groups to warn that they all could get shut out if AT&AMP;T
gains an Internet stranglehold, or be forced to pay high fees to
AT&AMP;T to reach potential customers. Similar concerns have been
raised over Time Warner's plans for its cable lines.
</P>
<P>
   The critics want the Federal Communications Commission to
require AT&AMP;T and Time Warner to grant equal access to America
Online and other companies that provide Internet services. For now,
the commission has demurred, and rightly so. As William Kennard,
the FCC chairman, has said, it seems premature to impose rules on
cable Internet access to head off a problem that does not yet exist
in a market that has not yet developed. The FCC is also right to
try to block localities from imposing restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   Whether consumers will have a choice other than cable monopolies
like AT&AMP;T and Time Warner will depend on the emergence of other
high-speed technologies. Local telephone companies have begun to
upgrade their service with a technology known as digital subscriber
lines, or DSL, which could compete with cable. They might not have
acted so quickly if it were not for the threat of AT&AMP;T and Time
Warner.
</P>
<P>
   Satellite and wireless communications might also provide
consumers with another way to tap into the Internet. America Online
points out that these alternatives to cable are only in formative
stages. But the interest of consumers is served by letting all
these technologies develop and taking regulatory action only if
they fail to provide adequate competition.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet's future and its prosperity clearly depend on the
principle of maintaining open access for all competitors. This
principle has led the Justice Department to block Microsoft from
using its operating system monopoly to force consumers to use its
browser as the sole means to surf the Web.
</P>
<P>
   With 130 million users around the world, the Internet is driving
a major part of the American economy. The question now becomes
whether cable systems, which are inherently monopolistic
enterprises that traditionally belong to the companies that built
and paid for them, become so dominant that they will restrict
consumer choices in getting news, watching programs or buying
products.
</P>
<P>
   In monitoring AT&AMP;T and Time Warner as they venture more and more
into cable Internet services, the FCC should not let down its
guard. Even though cable systems are not now regulated, as
telephone lines are, the FCC should ensure competition and open
access in the future.
</P>
<P>
   For now, it is best for the FCC to wait and see how the new
world unfolds before trying to set rigid rules for it. But if AT&AMP;T
and Time Warner do not exercise some self-restraint and act like
good citizens, allowing fair access for America Online and other
Internet service providers with a legitimate service to offer, they
will find themselves subjected to demands for regulation by the FCC
and local communities. It is in their interest to preserve the open
spirit of the Internet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-05-99 2353EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990905.0218 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-05 23:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1895 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-LABOR-NYT &LR;      09-05 0531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-LABOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE LOOK OF LABOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Monday, Sept. 6:
</P>
<P>
   In 1875, a photographer named Alphonse Deriaz took a picture of
the Butchers' Festival in the Swiss town of Morges. The butchers,
26 of them, stand at attention in the town square, their aprons
swept to one side like dashing military tunics. Each man shoulders
one of the tools of his trade. Five of the butchers share a raised
platform with an enormous white-faced bullock wearing a halter and
a crown of flowers while townsfolk look down from the windows
above. What is striking here, besides the soft expression on the
bullock's face, is the very public way that each butcher identifies
himself by his labor, by his apron and bone saw and by the
fraternity, publicly attested, of fellow butchers.
</P>
<P>
   The festival this photograph preserves feels Old World to us,
utterly unlike a modern American Labor Day, which is now less a
celebration of labor than one last gasping infusion of summer's
ozone. But the police and firefighters and union members and
politicians still march together through the city streets on this
day. It would be something to see the butchers of New York marching
too, dressed as for work _ to see them and the sommeliers and the
toll takers and the men and women who build wooden water tanks and
each of the vocations that give flesh to this society marching side
by side, a society articulated, for one parade, into all its
laboring parts.
</P>
<P>
   What is Old World about the Butchers' Festival is not only the
uniforms and, perhaps, the ability to look the source of meat right
in the eye. It is the sense of lifelong calling, of a time when
going to work meant assuming, for life, an identity as binding, if
perhaps not as deranging, as Bartleby the scrivener's. The days
when men and women bore the distinguishing marks of their labor
have certainly not ended, nor will they ever end as long as the
material world is shaped in part by human muscle. But now as a
nation we seem as migratory in our vocations as we do in our
dwelling places, as ready to shift jobs as to shift cities. There
is a familiar, prevailing sense that no matter what the job, it is
probably too small to contain something as volatile and
transcendent as our latter-day identities, which are made up, we
seem to believe, of finer stuff than those of our ancestors.
</P>
<P>
   Labor is both trap and liberation, servitude and release, and it
is tempting, on Labor Day, to think of labor _ even the word itself
_ in largely historical terms, to remember photographs of
coal-darkened miners and young women huddled over sewing machines,
of factory workers looking up from the conveyor belt at the
photographer's flash. But there is nothing historical about these
labors. They are still being performed today. Where the world of
work is concerned, we dwell, even in this country, among our
ancestors.
</P>
<P>
   Some people dream of living in a world without work. But the
better dream, even on a day as relaxed as this one, is that of a
world in which for everyone who wants it the necessity of work is
tempered by a choice of labors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
