country -- if that country happens to be Italy -- Bocce is becoming
one of the hottest ways to team-build in the team-charged
atmosphere that rules Silicon Valley. (Peter DaSilva/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) LOS GATOS, Calif. -- Sept. 5, 1999 -- BOCCE-GEEK-CHIC-1,
9-5 -- Engineers from 3Com Corporation's Palm Computing division at
Campo di Bocce. Bocce, a 7,000-year-old cousin of lawn bowling best
known as the sport of old men from the old country -- if that
country happens to be Italy -- is becoming one of the hottest ways
to team-build in the team-charged atmosphere that rules Silicon
Valley. (Peter DaSilva/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- Sept. 5, 1999 -- SHAKESPEARE-DISCO, 9-5 --
Anna Wilson in ``The Donkey Show: A Midsummer Night's Disco,''
produced with the project 400 Theater Group, which opened on Aug.
18 for a six-week run at a real club, El Flamingo in New York.
Project 400 seeks to be part of the long tradition of twisting the
confines of theater, so it is through the music, rather than any
traditional form of theater, that Shakespeare's comedy about the
vagaries of love is told. (Chang W. Lee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 5, 1999 -- HERMAN-PROFILE, 9-5 --
Serving in Washington in the 1990s has sorely taxed the faith of
Alexis Herman, the labor secretary and one of the few remaining
survivors of every blessed day of the Clinton administration. Her
devotion has been shaken in recent years, but never to the point of
apostasy. ``It does cause me to go back and remember the early days
and the path I took to get here,'' she says. ``I try not to be
distracted by the cynicism and the negative climate in politics
today.'' (Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) AKRON, Ohio -- Sept. 5, 1999 -- TV-GOLF-MEDIA-2, 9-5 --
Vinny Fugett, a cameraman for CBS, lines up a camera shot as Phil
Mickelson lines up a putt at the World Golf Championships NEC
Invitational tournament. At right, Arnold Mintz, an engineer,
checks audio feeds. In the minds of many broadcast professionals,
golf is the most challenging sport to televise. Spread across
hundreds of acres and having no timeouts, a big-name golf
tournament requires more cameras, more cables, more advanced
wireless technology and more ingenuity than perhaps any event short
of the World Series or the Super Bowl. (Phil Long/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) AKRON, Ohio -- Sept. 5, 1999 -- TV-GOLF-MEDIA, 9-5 --
Steve Milton, a producer for CBS, left, watches the Tiger Woods in
the second round of the World Golf Championships NEC Invitational
tournament. At right, Arnold Mintz, an engineer, checks audio
feeds. In the minds of many broadcast professionals, golf is the
most challenging sport to televise. Spread across hundreds of acres
and having no timeouts, a big-name golf tournament requires more
cameras, more cables, more advanced wireless technology and more
ingenuity than perhaps any event short of the World Series or the
Super Bowl. (Phil Long/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- Sept. 5, 1999 -- CUSTOM-PUBLISH-MEDIA, 9-5 --
Russ Meneve, 29, an aspiring comedian, sought comic inspiration in
an issue of Joe that was shown to him at a Starbucks in Manhattan.
Sony, Philip Morris and Sears, Roebuck also underwrite custom
magazines. While advertisers like Philip Morris, Mercedes-Benz and
Starbucks used to push magazines to mention their products in the
editorial pages, they have now adopted a more sophisticated
approach, creating magazines in which they control the mix of
feature articles and product placement. (Elizabeth Lippman/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) PARSIPPANY, N.J. -- Sept. 5, 1999 --
SOFTWARE-CODE-ACCESS, 9-5 --Arjen Lenstra, a Citigroup computer
scientist, worked on the encryption project that protects financial
transactions over the Internet. The government has long restricted
the export of strong encryption, citing concerns that it might be
used to conceal messages or transactions by terrorists or drug
traffickers. ``As soon as you break something, then within a
relatively short time, many people will be able to break it,'' says
Lenstra. ``I have no doubt that within a few years it will be more
or less a triviality.'' (Dith Pran/New York Times Photo)
</P>
